<SLUG> BC-BBN--Astros-Cardinals-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Cardinals down Astros 10-9
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ST. LOUIS _ Here on the banks of the Mississippi River, they like
to boast of the largest Fourth of July weekend festival in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   And while the real fireworks aren't scheduled to go off for
another few days, those hoping to see an early display of
explosives could have gotten their fill Saturday afternoon at Busch
Stadium, where the St. Louis Cardinals outbombed the Astros in a
10-9 slugfest.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros outhomered the Cardinals 4-3 but St. Louis did more
damage with its round trippers, getting three-run homers from Mark
McGwire and Fernando Tatis _ the most telling blow of the game _ to
send the Astros to their 13th loss in 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys did a great job of swinging the bats,'' said Jeff
Bagwell, who was 3-for-5 with two home runs for the Astros. ``But
we needed to score 11 runs, and we came up short at nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really the same old story: If we pitch well, we don't
hit; if we hit, we don't pitch well. I really don't know what else
to say about it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored seven runs in the first three innings, jumping
out to a four-run lead, but by the sixth inning they were faced
with another catch-up situation.
</P>
<P>
   And while they had the potential go-ahead run on first base when
Cardinals closer Dave Veres got Chris Truby to pop out to end the
game, the outcome was fairly predictable, considering the Astros
had lost each of the previous 45 games they trailed going to the
ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell's leadoff homer started the ninth-inning threat. But in
the end, all it did was pull the Astros close enough to suffer
their 18th loss in 21 one-run games.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrating?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to answer that question anymore,'' manager Larry
Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   No answer needed; you could see it on Dierker's face and the
faces of every coach and player on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the most frustrating year of my career,'' Bagwell
said. ``It's draining for us, and I'm sure it's draining to
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros starter Octavio Dotel wasn't exactly a sight for sore
eyes, allowing seven hits and six runs on a day when the Astros
provided him plenty of extra run support.
</P>
<P>
   That would seem to be just what the doctor ordered for a pitcher
who has lost four consecutive decisions and hasn't won since May 5,
but Dotel was working with less than his best stuff.
</P>
<P>
   His fastball was about four miles per hour slower than normal
and when a pitcher relies as heavily on one pitch as Dotel does, he
can't afford to have it at less than its best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what was going on with me,'' Dotel said. ``But I
didn't have my best stuff; I know that. I just have to keep going
out there. Some day, things are going to be different for me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a bad day for Cardinals starter Garrett Stephenson,
a nine-game winner whom the Astros feasted on for 11 hits and seven
runs (six earned) in four innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, who had 15 hits in the game, including a
season-high-tying seven for extra bases, scored two runs in the
first and three more in the second to reclaim the lead after
McGwire's three-run homer in the bottom of the first.
</P>
<P>
   Back-to-back homers by Moises Alou and Richard Hidalgo increased
the Astros' lead to 7-3 in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fifth time the Astros have had back-to-back homers
this season, and Hidalgo has been involved each time. It was the
first homer since June 14 for Hidalgo, who leads the team with 21.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals pulled within a run and chased Dotel with three
runs in the fourth, then took the lead for good with four in the
sixth, three on Tatis' two-out homer off Doug Henry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our year has been like that at-bat I had against Tatis,'' said
Henry, who has allowed more home runs (nine) than anyone in the
Astros' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a pitch that wasn't even in the strike zone; he
shouldn't have even swung at that pitch, and he hits it out of the
yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Tatis missed 54 games with a groin injury before returning to
the lineup Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You keep winning and you keep winning and that's what it's all
about,'' said the Cardinals' Jim Edmonds, who doubled twice and
drove in two runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, who are on pace to lose a club-record 106 games,
dropped to 26 games below .500 and trail St. Louis by 21 games in
the National League Central.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Thompson (1-1) pitched 2 innings in relief of Stephenson to
get the win, allowing one unearned run on one hit. The save was
Veres' 16th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Slusarski (1-5) gave up two runs on two hits in two innings
of relief in taking the defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is just another example of the way the whole
stinking season has gone,'' Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it will only be half over after today's series
finale with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
