u s BC-BKN--FREEAGENTS-HNS &LR;      07-02 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--FREE </SLUG>
 AGENTS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Magic has key to free-agent sweepstakes
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
``Hi, this is Tim Duncan. I'm either on the phone right now or out
of the house, so at the tone, please leave a message.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're the Orlando Magic, please press one, and make sure
you follow that with plenty of zeroes. If you're the San Antonio
Spurs, press two, as in Twin Towers. If this is Grant Hill yo,
Grant, hit 33 and tell me what's up. If you're the Chicago Bulls,
please hang up and try again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks for calling. And have a nice payday er, day.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday marked the start of the NBA's free-agent shopping
frenzy, and for every general manager in the league it's the same
story _ Tim Duncan, when you absolutely, positively have to have
the best.
</P>
<P>
   Accept no substitutes.
</P>
<P>
   And forget about Bull markets, this is expected to be a Mouse
market _ as in Orlando, current home of Disney World and what is
hoped to be the future home of Duncan and _ in a domino effect _ a
couple of other free agents. Like Hill, who shares not only a
friendship with Duncan, but an agent (Lon Babby).
</P>
<P>
   But if Hill doesn't join the Magic, then other free agents will
jump at the opportunity to play alongside Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tracy (McGrady, of Toronto) watched the success of the Lakers
with (Shaquille) O'Neal at center, and he realizes that Tim is one
of the best centers in the game,'' said Arn Tellem, McGrady's
agent. ``I think what Tim Duncan does will set off the free-agent
process for a lot of guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what Orlando is banking on.
</P>
<P>
   But while it is interested in two or three free agents of note,
the Magic is determined to make Duncan the center of attention.
With that in mind, the Magic has invited Duncan and Grant to drop
down _ together, of course _ for a little visit. Orlando is pulling
out all the stops, and with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic learned the hard way what life is like on the other
side in 1996 when the Lakers won a high-stakes recruiting war to
land Magic center Shaquille O'Neal to a deal totaling $120 million
over seven seasons.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was just one of the big-time free agents in the class of
'96 to change teams _ joining Dikembe Mutombo (from Denver to
Atlanta) and Allan Houston (from Detroit to New York).
</P>
<P>
   Orlando hopes there is a chance for similar movement among this
year's top targets (Duncan, Hill and Eddie Jones) and some of the
budding stars as well (McGrady, Jalen Rose, Rashard Lewis, Austin
Croshere and Tim Thomas).
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how this plan works,'' said Orlando general manager
John Gabriel. ``We've worked it here, and we've had it worked
against us. I hope we'll be busy (in the free-agent wars).''
</P>
<P>
   Why not? The Magic has been busy up to this point.
</P>
<P>
   Between last June and the February trade deadline, the Magic
made 37 transactions involving 38 players, creating a little more
than $13 million in cap room. Four starters, including resident
star Penny Hardaway, were dealt from a team that made the playoffs
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Wednesday's draft-day moves, when the Magic dumped two
of its three lottery picks, along with two contracts in Corey
Maggette and Derek Strong, to get the organization $21 million
under the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando can now go out and sign two maximum-salaried free agents
from a list that includes Duncan, Hill, McGrady, Jones and Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Teams began negotiating with free agents Saturday, but they
can't sign those players until Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Had it not cleared out the extra cap room, the Magic would have
been forced to try to work out a sign-and-trade deal with at least
one of the teams that will lose one of its stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have been able to sign two free agents before, but
the sign-and-trade thing would have come into play,'' said Magic
coach Doc Rivers. ``It would have been tougher. We have the money
now to go out and get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs expect to be busy as well, most of it centering on
letting Duncan know how much he is loved by the organization. And
should Duncan re-sign with San Antonio, the Spurs will make heated
pitches to Hill, Duncan's good friend, who would have to sign for
the $2 million exception for a chance to play on a team that could
challenge the Lakers for NBA supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   So the Spurs, who can offer Duncan seven years (one more than
competing teams) and bigger annual raises (12.5 percent vs. 10
percent), are gearing up their sales pitches as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in competition with another team for Tim,'' said Gregg
Popovich, who serves as Spurs coach and general manager. ``So in
that sense, you have the same sort of feeling in your stomach as
you do before a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two seasons now _ the regular season and free
agency. They (free-agency rules) have made the summers like college
(recruiting).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that was intended, but that's the reality of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   For all teams, not just the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons are working just as hard to keep Hill in the fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about this with Grant,'' said Joe Dumars, Pistons
president of basketball operations. ``And I'm not being cocky or
anything. I've talked with him probably every day the last two
weeks. And we've talked about his little visit down South (to
Orlando).
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand and respect that he wants to check out his
options. And we'll talk when he gets back. I know it looks bad from
what everyone's saying and writing, but, right now, I have no
reason to believe that he's not going to be in training camp come
fall _ with us.''
</P>
<P>
   But will that be enough?
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte's Jones, another top free-agent prize, is going to
mull any and all offers before making a decision. The Hornets
appeared to be one of the top teams in the East until their
first-round bust against Philadelphia in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   So Jones, whose name has come up in sign-and-trade scenarios
with Miami, isn't tying himself down to Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a one-in-a-lifetime opportunity, to be in position to
choose where he wants to play,'' said Jones' agent, Leon Rose.
``That's why he's going to be deliberate, making sure he makes a
good decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones is eligible for a seven-year, $86.6 million deal with the
Hornets, or a six-year, $67.5 million contract with teams that are
at least $9 million under next year's salary cap _ Chicago and
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm going to talk to the teams that have the money
to sign me,'' Jones said. ``I've been watching what Orlando has
been doing, and it looks like they're going to be able to get three
(big free agents) now, so as a free agent you have to like that.
But I don't want to say anything more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
