<SLUG> BC-TEN--WIMBLEDON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Sampras shakes off leg injury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JODY GOLDSTEIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WIMBLEDON, England _ When a tennis player hears his opponent is
injured, he usually knows he has a great chance.
</P>
<P>
   Unless that opponent is Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, who limped through his second-round match after
suffering acute tendinitis in his ankle and shin, didn't let the
injury affect him in his third-round match Saturday, losing the
first set but coming back to beat fellow American Justin Gimelstob
2-6, 6-4, 6-2, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather play him not injured than injured,'' Gimelstob
said. ``Have you ever seen him lose injured? He's a great player.
He seems to thrive on playing injured.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras had to call for a trainer to have his left ankle and
shin massaged and taped Wednesday evening during his second-round
match. Though he was limping, he won that match against Karol
Kucera in four sets.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of several matches Sampras won while in distress, the
most notable being the 1996 U.S. Open quarterfinal meeting with
Alex Corretja, when Sampras became ill on the court yet still
pulled out the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing hurt is something I've learned to deal with over the
years,'' Sampras said. ``This is Wimbledon, this is what I play for
all year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to do everything I can to play. I'm not risking my
career to play this tournament, but I'm not 100 percent and it's
something I have to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   After the first set, it was hard to tell he was ailing. He had
little trouble running down Gimelstob's volleys. He managed
well-placed serves and passed his opponent with ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``My movement is one of my best advantages out there, and I'm
not at 100 percent, but even at 80 percent, my movement is better
than a lot of guys out here, especially on this surface,'' Sampras
said.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't the story early. He spent Thursday and Friday
icing his ankle and getting treatment from the trainers. He
benefited from the long early matches and rain delays that
postponed his match, therefore giving him an extra day of rest.
</P>
<P>
   But the rust had set in.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras double-faulted four times on his first service game,
allowing Gimelstob to break and take a 3-0 lead. He double-faulted
again on set point, giving Gimelstob an edge.
</P>
<P>
   Just as significant, Sampras didn't manage a single winner off
his groundstrokes in the opening set, the only winners being four
volleys.
</P>
<P>
   ``My racket felt like a foreign object, which doesn't happen too
often,'' Sampras said. ``This is not an easy surface to play on
when you haven't picked up a racket in 2{ days.
</P>
<P>
   ``First set, I was so rusty. Had no rhythm on my serve. But once
I got that break in the second and started to feel a little better
about my timing, my rhythm, my serve started coming on a little
bit, started to feel a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   Gimelstob could only watch as Sampras started to look like a
six-time Wimbledon champion over the next few sets. Sampras drilled
37 unreturnable serves over the final three sets and had 46
winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has intangibles,'' Gimelstob said. ``Comes up with certain
shots on the run or certain shots that would get by other guys. In
his mother's womb, I think God spent a little extra time on his
right shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, the No. 1 seed, has only one seeded player remaining in
his half of the draw. He could meet No. 9 seed Thomas Enqvist in a
quarterfinal match if he is able to get past Jonas Bjorkman.
</P>
<P>
   With no play today, Sampras again will have one day off to
rehabilitate the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sore,'' Sampras said. ``Two days off definitely helped.
Yesterday, I was praying for rain and got it, which is nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's sore and it's probably going to continue to be sore
and I just need to find a way to play on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The men's draw lost French Open champion Gustavo Kuerten, the
No. 4 seed, who fell to Alexander Popp 7-6 (6), 6-2, 6-1. Kuerten,
who was suffering from a cold, said he felt lethargic.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I played two days ago, I felt a little bit worse, with
fever,'' Kuerten said. ``I was not feeling really, really bad, just
weak. I could run, could play, but not full of energy. That's
enough to be out of a tournament like this.''
</P>
<P>
   It was enough for Popp, ranked No. 163 in the world, to
characterize the match as the best he's had.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the nicest day of my life up to now,'' Popp
said.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 Andre Agassi, who went 18 games in the fifth set against
Todd Martin on Friday, had an easier time Saturday against Jerome
Golmard for a 6-3, 6-3, 6-4 victory. No. 12 seed Patrick Rafter
also advanced.
</P>
<P>
   And No. 10 seed Mark Philippoussis prevailed in a marathon,
pulling out a 38-game fifth set to beat Sjeng Schalken 4-6, 6-3,
6-7 (7) 7-6 (4), 20-18.
</P>
<P>
   The 83 games were the most in a match at Wimbledon since 1970,
before tiebreakers were used, and the time (5 hours, 5 minutes) was
the longest since the 5:12 victory by Pancho Gonzalez over Charlie
Pasarell, 22-24, 1-6, 16-14, 6-3, 11-9 over two days in the first
round in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the training I've done paid off,'' Philippoussis said.
``I've always considered myself a fighter. That kind of match I'm
proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Philippoussis, who served 20 aces in the final set and 44
overall, was broken only once in the first set and once in the
fourth. Schalken was broken once each in the second, fourth and
fifth sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``He served unbelievable the entire match. That's why he won,''
said Schalken, who fired 30 aces in the match.
</P>
<P>
   The women's draw had no surprises. No. 5 seed Venus Williams
continued to cruise through the women's draw, beating Nathalie
Dechy 6-0, 7-6 (4).
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Lindsay Davenport posted a 6-4, 6-2 win over
Paola Suarez. No. 6 Monica Seles and No. 9 Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario
advanced to the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   Three unseeded Americans _ Jennifer Capriati, Lilia Osterloh and
Kristina Brandi _ are also in the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   The players are off today. Play will resume Monday.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
