<HEADLINE>
MERCKER EAGER TO GET BACK ON MOUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Pitcher Kent Mercker admitted he's put on
about seven or eight pounds in the past seven weeks since having a
cerebral hemorrhage on the Edison Field mound May 11. But he says
he's completely recovered and said he believes he could be pitching
in the majors in 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   That's not going to happen, but Mercker is obviously eager to
get back to pitching. He rejoined the team Saturday and plans to
remain with the team until he's ready. He had a precautionary
angiogram Friday at USC Medical Center, for peace of mind more than
anything else. Doctors have all but ruled out an aneurysm as the
cause for the hemorrhage, meaning there is virtually no risk of
another occurring.
</P>
<P>
   The good news out of his situation, Mercker says, is that he got
to hang around his Dublin, Ohio, home with his family in the spring
and summer months.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all that money I've spent on landscaping, I finally got
to see the flowers and trees with leaves on them,'' he said. ``I'm
glad I was home. If I was here I probably would have rushed. I
would have sneaked out in the hall to play catch and been right
back in the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker said the Angels training staff will treat him like a
post-concussion patient, which would include monitoring his blood
pressure while he rides an exercise bike.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Mercker's hopes to return in 10 days, manager Mike
Scioscia said: ``That's wildly optimistic, but I'm not going to say
it's not possible.''
</P>
<P>
   QUICK CAREER HIGH: Garret Anderson's home run Friday was his
22nd, a career high. He did it in less than half the season, but he
continues to say he's not trying to hit home runs. Going into
Saturday's game, eight of his last 18 hits were homers. Of
Anderson's 77 hits this season, 39 have been singles and 38 have
been for extra-bases (22 homers, 15 doubles, one triple).
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is still hitting just .241, but lately has been hitting
to the opposite field, a sign his swing might be coming around.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm over there on that side of the field, things are
going pretty good because I'm just reacting to the ball,'' Anderson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson began this season as a .300 lifetime hitter. It might
be difficult for him to reach .300 this season, but Scioscia would
like to see him get close.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know he's not a .240 hitter,'' Scioscia said. ``We'd much
rather see him hit .270 or .280 with the 110 RBI he's capable of.''
</P>
<P>
   IDLE DUO: Derrick Turnbow and Edgard Clemente haven't done much
for the Angels this season, but they're not going anywhere. Turnbow
is a Rule V draftee, meaning if the Angels wanted to send him to
the minors, they would first have to offer him back to his original
team, the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Clemente, the nephew of Hall of Famer Roberto Clemente, is out
of options, meaning if the Angels wanted to send him to the minors,
Clemente could opt for free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Turnbow, the 12th pitcher on a 12-man staff, has pitched only 11
2/3 innings in nine games this season, mostly in a mop-up role. But
he's pitched relatively well and has a 3.86 ERA. Still, Scioscia
says if not for Turnbow's Rule V restriction, he'd be pitching in a
high Single-A league this season.
</P>
<P>
   Clemente has struggled as a pinch-hitter and part-time DH. He's
hitting .182 (10 for 55), but did make a game-saving throw from
right field in Minnesota last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a tremendous amount of potential,'' Scioscia said. ``We
want to get him as many at-bats as we can, but we also have
responsibility to get production right now, and (Scott) Spiezio is
producing from the right side.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
