<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-ROCKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS' WIN STREAK HITS 8 WITH VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KERRY MURRAY  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Sparks continue to be the
WNBA's hottest team as they extended their winning streak to eight
games and defeated the Cleveland Rockers 75-67 on Saturday evening
at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   But that streak, Delisha Milton said, means nothing to the
Sparks. They're thinking playoffs and working to win as many games
as they can.
</P>
<P>
   And in some ways, coach Michael Cooper added, Los Angeles'
recent success only makes them more of a target for other teams.
</P>
<P>
   For Cleveland, the most recent team to gun after the Sparks, a
full-court pressure zone nearly stopped Los Angeles' impressive
streak, the longest run in the WNBA this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a gutsy win,'' Cooper said. ``Our defense was superb
and that was what kept us in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles outrebounded the Rockers 38-23. Both teams shot
nearly identical percentages _ Los Angeles hit 42.6 percent from
the field and Cleveland hit 42.3 _ so the true difference in the
game came down to defense and the Sparks being able to recover from
the Rockers' testy zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time in this league that I've seen a full-court
pressure zone,'' Cooper said. ``It's not so much a nuisance, but a
delay method.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland started the game with man-to-man defense but after the
Rockers' leading scorer, Eva Nemacova, left the game with a
sprained left knee six minutes into the first half, coach Dan
Hughes launched the zone to try to close a 23-12 Los Angeles lead.
</P>
<P>
   The change worked, as Cleveland immediately worked its way back
into the game with a 12-2 run and eventually took its first lead of
the game at 27-26.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are such a good transition team,'' Hughes said. ``We
wanted to slow that down.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Los Angeles was the team to enter the locker room with a
37-35 lead at half.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland came back and challenged in the second half, keeping
Los Angeles in check. With less than three minutes left, the
Rockers even came so close as to tie 64-64, but Los Angeles went on
one final run to end the game with a comfortable eight-point edge.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles was led by Lisa Leslie's 22 points and Milton's 12
boards. Chastity Melvin took over for Nemacova's absence, scoring
18 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks return to the Forum today for a 5 p.m. PDT game
against the Detroit Shockers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-00 0044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
