<HEADER>
A1032 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-CAR-PEPSI400-HNS &LR;      07-02 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PEPSI </SLUG>
 400-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Burton holds off Jarrett to claim tight Pepsi 400
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Jeff Burton held off Dale Jarrett in the
final four laps to win the Pepsi 400 Saturday night and ruin
Jarrett's hopes of making it three consecutive victories at
Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   It also reversed the results of the Daytona 500 in February when
Jarrett finished ahead of Burton to win the season-opening event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The restart at the end was tough because the best in the
business was behind me,'' said Burton, who earned his first victory
at Daytona. ``I blocked him pretty hard, but that's what you've got
to do. He was going to have to knock me out of the way to get by
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace was third, Mark Martin fourth and Ricky Rudd
finished fifth in a clean sweep for Ford drivers in front of an
estimated crowd at 170,000.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett moved up from 29th in the final 40 laps after a lug nut
problem caused him to have a 31-second pit stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we made a run at it,'' Jarrett said. ``It wasn't
three in a row, but it was close and we gained some points.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett made several attempts to move around Burton's No. 99
Exide Batteries Taurus, but Burton cut him off every time. They
went to the checkered flag with Jarrett up against Burton's bumper,
finishing .149 seconds back.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really big for our race team,'' said Burton, whose
average speed was 148.576 mph. ``Our team needed a kick in the
pants and this is it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Spencer prompted the final caution flag of the race when
he went spinning down the backstretch with seven laps to go. That
set up a four-lap shootout for the victory, with Burton in front,
Jarrett second and Dale Earnhardt third.
</P>
<P>
   But Earnhardt got shuffled back to eighth when Wallace and
Martin lined up to move Earnhardt out of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt still gained ground on Winston Cup points leader Bobby
Labonte, who finished 12th. Earnhardt is only 52 points behind
Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like Jarrett was going to lead from start to finish
Saturday after starting on the pole in the No. 88 Quality Care
Ford.
</P>
<P>
   The start of the event was as boring as it gets for
restrictor-plate racing because there wasn't a single pass for the
lead in the first 58 laps, something that never had happened in the
41-year history of the event.
</P>
<P>
   The first caution flag of the race came on lap 53 of the 180-lap
event because of debris on the track in turn 2. That bought about
the first pit stops of the race, and Wallace appeared to move up
from fifth to second as the leaders headed back on the track.
</P>
<P>
   But Wallace was penalized for speeding on pit road and forced to
go to the back of the lead lap, placing Wallace 40th for the
restart.
</P>
<P>
   The first lead change came on the restart lap when Bill Elliott
lined up with Tony Stewart, Burton and Martin to push past Jarrett
and move him to the fifth spot.
</P>
<P>
   The first accident came on lap 81 and ended the night for Terry
Labonte, Michael Waltrip and Jeremy Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip was on the outside of Labonte as the two cars passed the
start-finish line. Labonte's Kellogg's Chevrolet started to spin
backward and went into the wall, hitting hard on the driver's side
of the car. Waltrip also slid sideways down the frontstretch before
he was hit by Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte briefly lost consciousness when he hit the wall, but he
walked away on his own. The Corpus Christi native was taken to the
Halifax Medical Center for a precautionary CAT scan, which was
negative. Mayfield suffered a bruised shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   That accident brought about the second round of pit stops and
moved Ward Burton to the front on the restart at lap 90, but
Elliott moved back to the lead three laps later.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Pruett hit the wall in turn 1 to bring out the next
caution on lap 104. Jeff Burton was in front after the next rounds
of pits, but Johnny Benson passed him for the lead one lap later.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the first time Benson had led a race since he was in
front in the final laps of the Daytona 500 five months ago before
Jarrett and a line of Fords slipped past him.
</P>
<P>
   Another accident came with 46 laps to go when Mike Skinner
bumped Elliott from behind and caused Elliott's back wheels to lift
in the air as Elliott spun around and crashed hard into the wall
nose first entering turn 3.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, who had run among the leaders all night, was furious
when he climbed out of the McDonald's Ford. He pushed away a safety
official and walked up the track, pointing angrily at Skinner as
Skinner went by him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I knew why it happened,'' Elliott said. ``I got hit and
the next thing I knew is I was going head on into the wall. This
type of racing is aggravating and it gets worse as you get late in
the race because more guys take chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's crash brought the lead cars into the pits for the
final time. Jeff Burton's crew chief, Frank Stoddard, elected to
take a chance and only change the right-side tires so Burton could
gain track position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a gutsy move by Frankie, but it proved to be the right
thing to do,'' said Burton, who earned $152,450 for the victory.
``If your car isn't handling well, you will fall back in a hurry
here by only changing two tires. But our car was handling so well
that we were confident it would work.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
