<HEADER>
A1035 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-ATHLETICS-     07-02 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-ATHLETICS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHBURN PITCHES WELL IN ANGELS' WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ OK, so he's no Brian Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Cooper threw a three-hit shutout one night earlier,
Jarrod Washburn had to ``settle'' for the victory in the Angels'
7-2 win Saturday night over the Oakland A's in front of 31,696 at
Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   For six innings, though, Washburn looked as though he might top
Cooper's performance. Washburn took a no-hitter into the seventh
inning, when he gave up solo homers to Olmedo Saenz and Matt
Stairs. Stairs' homer came with two out and ended Washburn's night
after 6 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn (4-2) wasn't dominant _ he walked five and retired the
side in order only twice _ but he was effective. Like Cooper the
night before, he relied on his defense to get him through.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, I don't think his command was as sharp
as other games he's pitched,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia said.
``He worked behind (in the count) a lot. But when he got behind he
came up with some good pitches. This is what Jarrod Washburn is
about. He battled. He has tremendous poise on the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have good command, they made me throw a lot of
pitches, I didn't think I threw well at all,'' Washburn said.
</P>
<P>
   He might not have had a chance at a no-hitter even if he got
through the seventh. He made 93 pitches through six innings and was
tired by the time he came out, having made 107 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew if it was going to be a no-hitter it was going to have
to be a combined no-hitter,'' Washburn said. ``I would have fought
(coming out). but it would have been a losing battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Washburn added he didn't doubt Scioscia would have the guts to
take him out even with a no-hitter going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he would have,'' Washburn said. ``He's got a lot of
guts. I don't think he'd hesitate when it's best for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Washburn joked he thought about the no-hitter in the first
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to limit hits every game,'' he said. ``The less
hits I give up, the better outing I should have. I try to give up
no hits every game. Some guys say they're not conscious of (a
no-hitter), but I'm conscious of it the whole game.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the A's had no hits through six, they were putting
the ball in play, as Washburn had only one strikeout (he finished
with two). And he got a good defensive play in the sixth to keep
the no-hitter intact.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Benji Gil ranged to his left to backhand Randy
Velarde's grounder and make a perfect throw to first for the second
out of the inning. Washburn also got double-play grounders to end
both the second and fifth innings.
</P>
<P>
   The no-hit drama ended quickly, however, when Saenz slammed
Washburn's second pitch of the seventh inning _ his 95th pitch of
the game _ over the left-center field fence 417 feet away. Two outs
later, Stairs got his, and Washburn was replaced by Al Levine, who
pitched the final 2 1/3 innings and gave up only one hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had only eight hits, four off A's starter Ariel
Prieto (1-1), but they made them count. Mo Vaughn was the only
Angel with more than one hit, getting three singles and driving in
two runs. Bengie Molina hit a two-run homer, his second home run in
two days.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels also got help from the A's defense, which made three
errors _ two that directly led to two unearned runs.
</P>
<P>
   Because Seattle also won, the Angels remained five games out in
the AL West. But they moved to within 3 1/2 of second-place Oakland
and went four games over .500 (42-38) for only the third time this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Angels third baseman Troy Glaus went 0 for 4 with two strikeouts
and is hitless in his last 14 at-bats. It marked the first time
this season he has gone hitless in three consecutive games. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
