<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1128 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0703-COX     07-02 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0703-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rivers of Life
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Peavine Watershed Alliance is only 3 years old,
but Georgia water experts already are calling it a model for
solving the state's water pollution problems.
</P>
<P>
   To clean the Chattahoochee, you've got to prevent stuff from all
those little creeks and streams that flow into the river from ever
getting there, says Frank Carubba, a state expert in runoff
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``A local watershed effort is the foundation for everything,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   It all boils down to how water acts when natural areas are
replaced with pavement that doesn't soak up the water. The result:
Meandering creeks such as Lullwater, a tributary of Peavine Creek,
receive torrents of dirty runoff from parking lots, driveways and
rooftops. The unnatural deluge undermines the roots of trees along
creeks and destroys the banks that nourish delicate plant and
animal life.
</P>
<P>
   The Peavine Alliance started with one woman and one garden club
fed up with seeing beautiful trees and plants literally going down
the creek, says Patricia White, Peavine's founder and full-time
volunteer director.
</P>
<P>
   A 30-year resident of the Atlanta neighborhood Druid Hills,
White started noticing changes in Lullwater Creek in the mid-'70s.
Her garden club cares for a 6-acre conservation park along
Lullwater Creek, and older members remember when the creek was
small enough for them to hop across.
</P>
<P>
   Garden club pictures from the 1940s show a clear creek, no more
than a few feet across. Now Lullwater is one of the state's
``impaired'' waterways, meaning it has reached the maximum
pollution it can tolerate. It is 25 feet wide in places, due to
polluted storm water runoff, and you could drown in its roaring
brown waters after a storm. During a drought like we have now, when
there's less water in our streams, it's more important than ever to
make sure the little water we have is clean, White says.
</P>
<P>
   A watershed is a drainage area where all the water runs to a
single point, like Peavine Creek. A lot can be done in a watershed
to prevent pollution and restore natural conditions. It's all about
how things are planted and built _ street by street, house by
house, creek by creek. One of Peavine's active members, for
example, is Robert Reed, an architect who creates ``creekkeeper''
homes with gutter systems that flow into cisterns and absorbent
surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   White says it wasn't until the '90s that she and her neighbors
really understood how dramatically urban runoff was changing the
luscious environment that lends character to the Peavine
neighborhoods _ Lake Claire, Candler Park, Druid Hills and part of
Decatur. White began asking her environmental friends what a
neighborhood could do to hold onto its creeks and greenery. She
contacted Tom Schueler at the nonprofit Center for Watershed
Protection in Maryland. He warned her if she got involved in
community watershed protection, she'd never be uninvolved.
</P>
<P>
   He was right, White says with a laugh. With the help of
neighborhood leaders and a small grant from a local conservation
group, White organized a steering committee and launched the
Peavine Watershed Alliance on July 10, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no scientific expert,'' she said, ``but I'm pretty expert
at organizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, with board members representing 14
organizations, including Fernbank Museum, Paideia School, Druid
Hills Golf Club, Emory University and three local governments,
Peavine won a $250,000 grant for a watershed management plan. It
was the first professional plan for a community watershed
organization in the state.
</P>
<P>
   White is proud of the alliance's accomplishments. There are
quarterly educational workshops. In creek cleanups, members have
pulled out bedsprings, old wheels and the like. They produce
newsletters and encourage involvement of most of the nine schools
located within the watershed. Decatur High School's ``ecoteam''
monitors and tests stream quality, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Peavine also mentors four emerging watershed alliances: South
DeKalb, Rock Creek, Little River and Proctor Creek. Working with
the Georgia Adopt-a-Stream program, Peavine funded a video about
the effort, titled ``Building a Watershed Alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes plans to utilize it in pushing for a state water
management plan.
</P>
<P>
   In the final analysis, White's work isn't just about pollution
prevention and community organizing. It's about the relationship of
people to water, about ``rivers of life,'' as she puts it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
