<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1129 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-RV-LIFE0703-COX     07-02 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RV-LIFE0703-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Growing numbers of people enjoying the RV lifestyle
 &HT;    By Stephanie Allmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ When Julie Swanson's husband talked about buying a
recreational vehicle six years ago, she wasn't too excited about
the idea. The couple had never been avid travelers and they already
had a home to maintain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, nah, we didn't need anything like that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But after spending time with folks at an RV ``jamboree'' who
cooked and ate together, played games and reminisced about all the
places they'd traveled, she quickly changed her mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those people seemed to have so much fun, so we saw them
having a ball and thought, well, we needed something to do after we
got older,'' she said. ``And we've been going ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, 72-year-old Julie is the immediate past president of the
Bosque River chapter of the Good Sam RV travel club, (short for
``Good Samaritan''). Her husband, Gordon, also 72, is the Texas
state treasurer for the Good Sam Club. They spend at least one
weekend a month in their 34-foot Georgie Boy motor home and
sometimes take excursions for several weeks at a time.
</P>
<P>
   The camaraderie of RVers and free-spirited RV lifestyle that
attracted the Swansons is also helping to draw in millions of
Americans who want freedom and flexibility when they travel. The
RV-traveling population, once dominated by retired snowbirds, is
quickly becoming more diverse with the influx of baby boomers and
those with discretionary income.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 study conducted by the University of Michigan found there
were almost 10 million RVs on the road. Since 1993, RV ownership in
households headed by boomers age 45 to 54 years old had increased
by 25 percent. RV-owning boomers with families now outnumber the
traditional core market of over-55 empty-nesters, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   Affordability and flexibility in traveling attracts many people
to RVs, said Jeff Beddow, spokesperson for the Recreation Vehicle
Industry Association. A survey by the organization found that RV
travelers save an average of $1,700 per year on travel. In
addition, an RV is considered a second home by the IRS, making
interest payments tax deductible.
</P>
<P>
   But ask most RVers, be they ``full-timers'' or weekend
travelers, and they'll tell you the appeal of RV travel lies in
intangibles, such as friendships made in campgrounds and the
ability to get away at a moment's notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just like being able to go out, not having to be confined
in a hotel or a motel and having our own facilities,'' said William
Teat of Bellmead, who, with his wife Eva, has been RV-traveling for
30 years. In that time, they have owned six different RVs. Now,
they own a 30-foot ``fifth wheel'' RV that they pull behind a
one-ton pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just kind of leave your cares behind and just enjoy the
trip and the fellowship with the different RVers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Teats, like the Swansons, belong to an RV travel club and
often drive in caravans and camp with 20 to 30 other rigs, he said.
Driving vehicles as big as RVs is awkward at first, but ``it's not
too bad after you get used to it,'' he said. The travel clubs keep
in touch with CBs or cell phones and alert each other if they're
having problems.
</P>
<P>
   Once they get to a campground, they hook up to water,
electricity and sewer lines. Then, the fun and relaxation begins.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Swanson said a typical day in an RV might start with
sleeping in later than usual, cooking breakfast from foods she
either brought from home or bought at a roadside grocery store, and
then watching TV. Around lunch time, she said, campers start
visiting each other in their RVs. They go for walks or drive into a
nearby town in a car that someone has towed behind an RV. At night,
campers may have ``pot luck'' dinners, in which they all cook
different dishes and come together for dinner. They play cards or
table games inside or outside each others' RVs.
</P>
<P>
   Swanson remembers one cold night in Amarillo when she cooked a
pot of chili and invited 30 or 40 other campers over to eat and to
warm up inside her motor home. Some campgrounds have recreation
centers, tennis courts, playgrounds or swimming pools, which
attract entire families.
</P>
<P>
   If it sounds like a pretty relaxed life, it is, Swanson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just a bunch of happy wanderers, and we love to get
together,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Swansons have met some of their best friends on the road and
frequently receive invitations to visit them all over the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   RVers are typically independent, quiet, free-spirited people,
said Red Tiner, owner of Concord Trailer Park in Bellmead. He rents
spaces for about $170 a month to people who want to live in RVs.
While some call their RV their home and don't stray from the park,
others take off and travel for months at a time, he said. While
they're gone, he tends to their property. That's one of the major
advantages he sees to living in an RV full time.
</P>
<P>
   But many RV owners are reluctant to sell their homes and move
into their RVs because they don't want to give up the stability of
their lives, he said. So instead, they travel in an RV from their
home base.
</P>
<P>
   Being in an RV, though, is not unlike being at home. Most have
all the amenities of home, such as bathrooms, kitchens and
bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   There's an RV to fit virtually any lifestyle and price range,
said Jerry Harrison, manager of Mack's Camper Sales in Robinson. On
the low end are pop-up campers that sell for about $4,000. Motor
homes, which are not towed but driven from the front, can cost
several hundred thousand dollars, he said. Most RV dealers require
a down payment but will finance them over 10 or 15 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   RVs have changed and improved through the years just like homes
and cars, Harrison said. Popular now are campers or motor homes
with ``slide-out'' rooms, which expand at the touch of a button
into large living rooms or bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Other RVs have furniture that folds into the walls, making room
inside for motorcyles and other small vehicles. Many also come with
satellite and Internet hookups, he said, keeping travelers
connected to the ``outside world.''
</P>
<P>
   Owning an RV takes maintenance, even off the road, Teat said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not hard to keep, but they keep you busy doing
things,'' he said. ``There are always little things that need to be
done _ like fixing lights.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Teat is off the road, it doesn't take much for him to get
the ``itch'' to travel again, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spontaneous trips are the best,'' he said. ``That's my
favorite thing _ just getting away and going to see things. When we
do that, we just kind of play it by ear. If we see someplace we
like to stop, we just do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
