<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0703-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Student activists tend to issues big and small
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Lacy Elwood has a gripe with the media. And here's
what she's going to do about it: She's going to improve it from
within.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Read has an answer to those who gripe that ``government
is the problem.'' Stop griping, she'll say, and be a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   At this point Read and Elwood, can only claim to have been a
part of student government. The distinction is immaterial. It's all
the same thing ultimately: people taking charge of events and
making as many as possible feel in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Recently when the Texas Association of Student Councils (TASC)
convened for its annual conference, activities involving both
students were recognized. The student councils from Mart High
School, where Read just graduated, and Connally High, where Elwood
just finished up, were among four Waco-area contingents receiving
the association's sweepstakes award. The other area sweepstakes
winners were China Spring and Clifton.
</P>
<P>
   Jointly, they are answers to the age-old whine, ``What's become
of the youth of America?''
</P>
<P>
   In the year since Columbine, we've made like cicadas in the
night, strumming up fears and generating no light.
</P>
<P>
   Elwood resents the national media portrayal. She's going to
study journalism at Baylor University in hopes of doing it better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how hard it is to get a good story. (But) it seemed
like every time we turned around there was something bad to
report'' when the subject was young people.
</P>
<P>
   Those reports did not include, for instance, the effort Connally
kids exerted to raise money for a freshman girl who survived a
traffic accident that claimed another student's life.
</P>
<P>
   The student council tapped student mirth amid tragedy and held a
male ``beauty pageant'' _ the most beauteous having raised the most
money. The ``Miss CHS'' contestants rang up $2,000 in a week. In
sum, it was a statement of caring and good humor.
</P>
<P>
   Elwood, the Connally Class of 2000 salutatorian, had the unusual
experience of being student council president as a junior last
year, then served in a support role her senior year. There was a
lot do.
</P>
<P>
   The Connally student leaders got a taste of organizational rigor
as host council for the state TASC convention in Austin, bringing
into the mix the Cadet marching band, jazz band and choir. They
also hosted 500 students for a district conference.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the world-changing worth of student government isn't
in the deeds _ no one expects high schoolers to save the world _
but in the doing. It shows what's possible.
</P>
<P>
   In Mart, a student council led by Read ran up a long list of
accomplishments and in-school projects: drug education, energy
conservation on campus, a safe-prom initiative. The council also
did things for others: a Veterans Day assembly, Food for Families,
a Halloween party for Head Start.
</P>
<P>
   Read, who will attend Texas A&AMP;M this fall, said being in student
government means bucking a tide of negative impressions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once young people see they can do something they'll do it,''
she said. ``The hard thing is showing the other people in the
community how much we really do.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Read is organizing a citywide cleanup this month
for junior high and high school students, tentatively set July 29,
through First Methodist Church of Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Will she seek out a role in student government at A&AMP;M? Are an
Aggie's corpuscles maroon? (Answer: Emphatic yes.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
