<DOCNO> NYT20000702.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1144 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MODERN-SOUTH0703-COX     07-02 2156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODERN-SOUTH0703-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who's running the South?
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ Stroll the marble _ or, depending where you are,
reinforced concrete _ walls of any Southern capitol in this
turn-of-the-century year, and you will notice many things that
appear untouched by the new era.
</P>
<P>
   The past few decades have witnessed revolutionary changes in the
racial and gender makeup of Southern legislatures and the awakening
of the Republican Party in the South. A generation of Southern
governors _ often with the presidency as their ultimate goal _ have
pushed impatiently to modernize their state governments.
</P>
<P>
   But outside the chambers where an increasing share of the most
important decisions affecting the region are made, those who make
the laws and those who would have the laws made their way still
engage in a familiar mating dance. In many states, a seasoned
observer can tell you in what corner of a capitol hallway a certain
kind of deal might be cut, based on which lobbyist stands there
every day and which legislator passes by.
</P>
<P>
   ``The South has always been the region where (interest) groups
have predominated, probably because of the weakness of any
countervailing force like strong political parties,'' wrote
academics Clive Thomas and Ronald Hrebenar in an article for State
Legislatures magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the splintering of power _ between Republicans and
Democrats, blacks and whites, governors and their increasingly
independent legislatures _ appears only to have strengthened the
hands of the lobbyists. At the same time, the number of those
waiting in the halls to catch a legislator's ear has exploded all
around the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alabama is a dream state for lobbyists,'' said Milo Dakin,
whose clients include several gaming interests. The Legislature
gives itself such flexibility, he said, that there is virtually no
certainty what is going to happen from day to day _ ``an ideal
climate for a lobbyist.'' The governor no longer has a controlling
hand, and a skillful lobbyist who can influence 30 or 40 votes is
``just as likely to have a majority as anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I registered here in 1978, you could put all the
lobbyists in the Capitol on a school bus,'' Dakin said. ``Now you
couldn't get them all on an Amtrak train.''
</P>
<P>
   `NEW ECONOMY', NEW LOBBYING
</P>
<P>
   It was easy for Calvin Kytle and James MacKay to frame the
question in their landmark 1947 study, ``Who Runs Georgia?'' In
those days, Georgia Power Co., a few businesses and the state's
agricultural interests were the only players in the Legislature's
yearly power struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Decades later, the answer Kytle and MacKay came up with _ ``a
few executives in a few corporations, together with a few skilled
politicians'' _ still sufficed for much of the South. But as the
``new economy'' begins to affect the region, the old system is
beginning to mutate in interesting ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who runs North Carolina? There are a lot more answers than
there used to be,'' said Ran Coble, executive director of the North
Carolina Center for Public Policy Research.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1981, the center has polled North Carolina legislators,
Capitol reporters and lobbyists to rank the 50 most influential
lobbyists in Raleigh. It's not a fool-proof measure of political
influence. Some of the most effective lobbyists, after all, are
those who attract the least notice. But the ranking does give some
indications of how things are changing.
</P>
<P>
   There used to be more lobbyists on the list who worked
exclusively for one or two big clients, winning the favor of key
committee members and weighing in as the voice of the company when
its interests were at stake.
</P>
<P>
   These days, some of the most effective lobbyists are
free-lancers brought together temporarily to work as a team on a
specific issue. That mirrors Alabama, where it is not unusual,
according to Dakin, for a lobbyist to hire another lobbyist on a
spot contract for a day, simply to win the vote of a specific
legislator with whom that lobbyist has close ties.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer lobbyists from the old trio of tobacco, textiles and
furniture are showing up on the North Carolina list, and there are
more lobbyists for health care, hogs and homebuilders _ a
reflection of the state's changing economy.
</P>
<P>
   More public interest lobbyists and women have been ranked in
recent years, along with lobbyists representing a growing number of
new companies, such as those that have sprung up around the
Research Triangle near here. With the ``new economy,'' observed
Ferroll Guillory, director of the Southern politics program at the
University of North Carolina, has come an interest in issues _
``livability,'' sprawl, day care _ the Old Guard was not much
concerned with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that a relatively small number of companies and
the Farm Bureau carried the political weight in this state. Today,
political power is spread out over a diverse group of individuals
and organizations and companies,'' said Don Beason, a lobbyist with
several major business clients who is ranked No. 2 on the center's
list.
</P>
<P>
   This trend has been widened by the increasing complexity of the
problems state legislatures grapple with, and the devolution
movement, which over the past decade has transferred an increasing
share of responsibility back to the states.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time a few years ago, observed Bobby Kahn, chief of
staff to Gov. Roy Barnes, when a committee meeting on health care
might draw only a lobbyist for the Medical Association of Georgia.
These days, with hospitals, nursing homes, medical specialties and
public interest groups looking to their own interests, the same
meeting might draw several lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Dakin, who has lobbied in several Southern states, traces the
proliferation back to the 1970s, when California, with its auto
emissions legislation, sent a message to national corporations that
they could no longer confine their efforts at winning influence to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   MORE MONEY IN STATE POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   Simply registering to lobby in a state is likely to trigger a
barrage of letters from legislators asking for campaign donations.
Just as much as the increased costs of campaigning, the enlargement
of the donor pool appears to be contributing to the staggering
increase in the costs of politics at the state level.
</P>
<P>
   The states don't have uniform reporting procedures, and it is
much harder to get comprehensive statistics about campaign finances
at the state level than the federal. But there are strong
indications the South's capitols have witnessed an inflation in
costs that rivals Washington.
</P>
<P>
   According to a public interest group, the North Carolina Forum
for Research and Economic Education, what the average winner spent
in a North Carolina Senate race rose from $36,301 in 1994 to
$82,161 in 1996 and $110,638 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And the spending figures don't tell the entire story. Much of
the money being raised from lobbyists and their clients is going
into the coffers of powerful legislators who have weak or often no
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in the cases where their races aren't contested, they're
raising lots of money to chase away possible opponents and to
funnel money to their colleagues,'' said Bob Hall, director of
Democracy South, a public interest group based in Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   A few states have attempted to contain campaign spending at the
legislative level, but this has proved difficult. Florida, for
instance, has a $500 cap on contributions to state races, but it
allows unlimited soft money contributions to the state parties,
which in turn have great flexibility in getting money back to the
candidates. For example, soft money contributions to the Florida
Republican Party, which now controls the Legislature, jumped from
$9.9 million in 1996 to $24.3 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study by Florida Common Cause, health care
interests and the insurance industry each contributed more than
$442,000 to the two parties in the first three months of this year,
when the Legislature was about to consider a measure that affected
patients' right to sue their HMOs. The measure failed. So did
legislation affecting the sale of generic drugs, after
pharmaceutical interests contributed more than $79,000.
</P>
<P>
   The increased emphasis on political action committees and
campaign contributions does not sit well with Dakin, schooled in
the ``eyeball-to-eyeball'' approach. But, he says, ``the system
runs on revolving funds,'' and lobbyists understand they have to
open their checkbooks to play the game.
</P>
<P>
   He prefers the ``personal touch,'' which sometimes means
ordering carry-out dinner for 150 or 200 people in a committee room
without making a big deal about who picked up the tab.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing the game doesn't just mean campaign contributions.
Playing the game means being there all the time, every time,''
Dakin said.
</P>
<P>
   SHADOW SECTORS
</P>
<P>
   Along with money and personal contacts between powerful
executives, their lobbyists and the legislators, a traditional
source of power throughout the South has been the number of
employees _ and voters _ companies such as Carolina Power &AMP; Light
had in legislative districts throughout North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, Guillory observed, these local powerhouses are
being outnumbered by companies, such as EDS, which are
headquartered out of the state, or, as is the case with
Glaxo-Wellcome, out of the country. These companies do not often
leave the same deep footprint in the Capitol corridors.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one of the noticeable developments across the region is
the rise of what might be called shadow sectors: big business
interests that either can't, or choose not to, play the traditional
game of statehouse power politics.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling in Louisiana and tourism in Florida provide contrasting
examples of the effect shadow sectors can have.
</P>
<P>
   While observers detect a splintering of business interests
elsewhere, John Maginnis, who has written several books on
Louisiana politics, says the biggest change in that state's power
politics the last few years has been the unifying of business
interests under the banner of LABI, the Louisiana Association of
Business and Industry.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the business lobby hung together to defeat a proposed
oil and gas processing tax supported by Gov. Mike Foster, who
helped unify the business community to pass his tort reform
measures and has since been foiled by business in his attempt to
find new revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Oil and gas gets off the hook, Maginnis said, because the
Legislature can always hang another tax increase on casinos and
video poker. The gaming sector spent enormous political capital to
gain entrance into Louisiana, and with its revenues skyrocketing it
has little influence to prevent its becoming a cash cow for the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Louisiana's always been able to survive on other people's
money,'' Maginnis said. ``It used to be oil and gas, and now
gambling has started to fill the gap.'' But ``taxing Texans,'' as
they call it in Louisiana, only puts off the day when the state
will have to reckon with the shortcomings in its tax structure, he
contends.
</P>
<P>
   No one in Florida would describe the tourist industry as a
pushover at the Legislature, but it is subdued in the role it
plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think Disney and some of the Central Florida
entertainment attractions would run the state. But Disney is a very
low-profile corporate citizen in Tallahassee,'' said Richard
Pinsky, a lobbyist and Republican campaign consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it was directly affected, he noted, Disney didn't
flex any muscles when a proposal to tax cruise ships came up _
aware, perhaps, that the measure was going to fail anyway. But the
tourist sector also didn't speak up for itself this year, he said,
when the South Florida counties eliminated auto emissions testing,
a move that could lead to more pollution, tighter government
restrictions and fewer tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other Southern states, which have been generous in
bestowing incentives to new industries, Florida has lost a number
of businesses to Arizona and other states. That is due in part,
Pinsky believes, to tourism, which brings revenue into the state
and has little interest in attracting more industry.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the changes being felt in the Southern economy are only
slowly being reflected in terms of influence in state legislatures.
The old giants still wield considerable power _ but they do so in a
more crowded field.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question tobacco has less clout today than 30 years
ago. There's also no question they still have a lot of clout,''
Coble said of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Similar things are said about oil and gas in Louisiana and
agriculture in Florida. The old powers still ply the statehouse
halls, seeking to wield influence. But the halls are a lot more
crowded these days.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
