<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1145 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SMALL-TOWN-DIVERSITY0     07-02 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-TOWN-DIVERSITY0703-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    City seeks diversity to save small-town soul
 &HT;    By Karen Hill
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ White people in Decatur, Ga. want more black
neighbors. They also want more neighbors who are poor.
</P>
<P>
   Really.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the sentiments behind a proposed strategic plan for
the city's next decade. The report, scheduled for a vote by city
commissioners July 17, is based on comments made during a series of
public meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people at the meetings were well-to-do whites. Over
and over, they said that they want to save the ethnic and economic
diversity that gives their city its markedly off-beat beat.
</P>
<P>
   They're afraid that skyrocketing property values are forcing
low-income residents _ especially elderly African-Americans _ to
move out of Decatur because rising assessments are making their tax
bills unaffordable. They're worried that police officers and
waiters can't afford to live near where they work.
</P>
<P>
   They're willing, they say, to grant the tax breaks and denser
zonings needed for developers to build lower- and middle-income
homes and apartments. They're willing to pay for marketing programs
to bring more minority residents to the city.
</P>
<P>
   They say Decatur can't become home only to wealthy whites
because it will cost the city of 17,400 its small-town soul.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING PRICED OUT
</P>
<P>
   The average sale price of an existing home in Decatur jumped 31
percent in the past three years, from $142,781 in 1997 to $186,614
in 1999. A new home in 1997 cost $202,367 on average; in 1999, it
was 20 percent more, at $242,430.
</P>
<P>
   The price increase reflects a major societal shift. Forty years
ago, many of Decatur's white residents stampeded out to homogenous
suburbs as black people moved in.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Wilson, Decatur's first black mayor, has said that
when she moved into the then-predominantly white Oakhurst
neighborhood in 1966, she awoke the next morning to find the white
neighbors on either side of her new home gone.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Cope, a 54-year-old white Decatur native, estimated that
three-quarters of his family's friends moved while he was in high
school. ``We thought we had good friends and they were racists,''
Cope said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1960 U.S. Census showed Decatur's population was 85 percent
white and 15 percent black and other minorities. By 1990, that had
changed to 53 percent white and 47 percent black and other
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Now, according to Atlanta Regional Commission estimates,
Decatur's population is 59 percent white and 41 percent black and
other minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Decatur also has more elderly residents, on average, than either
the state or nation: 18 percent are at least 62 years old, compared
to 12 percent statewide and 15 percent nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the African-Americans who moved into Oakhurst had been
middle-class residents of Beacon Hill, a black neighborhood on
Decatur's west side. They moved when Beacon Hill was razed for a
public housing project.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they're worried that they may be about to undergo what is,
in effect, a second bout of urban renewal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain things are happening that seem very familiar,'' said
City Commissioner Kecia Cunningham, an African-American whose
constituency includes most of the city's African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to low-income constituents being unable to afford
rising assessments, Cunningham said aggressive real estate agents
are taking advantage of elderly residents who don't realize the
value of their property, convincing them to sell at prices that are
too low.
</P>
<P>
   ``And even if they do hold out, the neighbors they've had for 25
or 30 years are gone,'' Cunningham said. ``It's no longer their
community.''
</P>
<P>
   City Commissioner Jim Baskett, who represents the city at large
but lives on the south side, said he gets calls weekly from elderly
constituents, black and white, worried that they'll have to move
because they can't pay their taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Tax relief as a way to keep elderly residents, particularly
African-Americans, emerged as a theme two years ago at a series of
public roundtable discussions led by resident Jon Abercrombie.
</P>
<P>
   The roundtable group studying diversity was about half white,
half black, said Cope, who was a member. Cope said Abercrombie told
them, ``Decatur had to be big enough to protect the weakest members
of our city,'' Cope recalled. ``The middle-class and
upper-middle-class white people kept looking at each other and
nodding their heads and said, `You're right. It doesn't happen very
often, but it needs to happen here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   They knew, Cope said, that would mean shifting more of the tax
burden onto themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The strategic plan also notes that most city employees can't
afford to live in the town that employs them. First-year police
officers and teachers, for example, qualify as low-income residents
because their annual salaries are less than the $31,690 median for
80 percent of Decatur residents.
</P>
<P>
   The strategic plan recommends that city officials find ways to
include more affordable homes for city employees in future
development.GOOD INTENT VS. THE MARKET
</P>
<P>
   The report lacks specifics, but also calls for:
</P>
<P>
   Developing marketing programs to attract minority residents.
</P>
<P>
   Improving the condition and availability of rental housing.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing and publicizing tax breaks for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   If the plan is approved, it will become a guidebook for city
planners and the city manager to enact concrete programs and
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the battle between the report's good intentions and
the market forces driving Decatur's boom is a tossup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Backed up with appropriate public policy measures, then it
probably is possible,'' to encourage diversity, said Emory
University political scientist Michael Rich. ``But in the long run,
the market is a pretty powerful force.''
</P>
<P>
   If any community can put up a good fight, it would be Decatur,
where residents' starched white shirts cover tie-dye hearts and the
only frowned-upon lifestyle is one of conspicuous consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Decatur has a history of jumping off the beaten path. In the
1830s, residents of the young town turned down the chance to become
a major transportation hub, telling the Western and Atlantic
Railroad to move on to what is now downtown Atlanta. The money and
excitement simply weren't worth the noise and dust, they decided.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, residents said ``no thanks'' to shopping malls and
superstores, gambling that the small businesses and small houses
then being abandoned in favor of suburban sprawl would someday come
back in vogue.
</P>
<P>
   Decatur resident Tom Keating worries, though, that the city will
be missing the point if it focuses only on keeping a certain number
of minority residents. It's more important, he said, that minority
residents, no matter how many, be treated fairly.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-00 1453EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000702.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1146 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-STOCK-MARKET-DEBATE07     07-02 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCK-MARKET-DEBATE0703-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Opposing best sellers indicate stock market's direction
debatable
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the Nasdaq composite index dropped like a lead
dot-com from its all-time high in March, Princeton University Press
moved up the publication date of Robert J. Shiller's book by nearly
a month to April 3.
</P>
<P>
   The book is ``Irrational Exuberance,'' a scholarly and
foreboding forecast that the common stocks we love so much are
headed for a prolonged bear market over the next 10 to 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The book became a best seller and Shiller an instant celebrity,
appearing on TV and in the financial press, where he defended his
views with quiet assurance.
</P>
<P>
   His basic argument is that common stocks have risen in price to
levels that are unsupported _ and unsupportable _ by the profit
prospects of U.S. corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The other side of that argument is in the book ``Dow 36,000,''
which was published in September and also became a best seller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dow 36,000'' was authored by James K. Glassman, 53, and Kevin
A. Hassett, 38, two resident scholars of the American Enterprise
Institute, a Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Shiller's position is that investors, Wall Street
professionals as well as individuals, have been on an irrational
buying binge that, based on history's record, will inevitably come
to an end with enormous losses followed by years of minimal
returns.
</P>
<P>
   This gloomy scenario so impressed Alan Greenspan at a private
economic briefing in 1996 that the chairman of the Federal Reserve
used the now-famous term ``irrational exuberance'' in a speech that
December.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan asked if maybe the stunning run-up in stock prices
during the 1990s was not due in part to this ``irrational
exuberance.'' His comments sent stocks tumbling from Tokyo to Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Greenspan or his speech writers apparently coined
the term. Shiller, 54, says he did not use it _ until he adopted it
as the title for his book.
</P>
<P>
   Shiller uses the price-to-earnings ratio to measure the value _
or excessive value _ of stocks. The P/E measures the price of a
share of stock relative to a company's per share profit, either
looking back or looking forward. The price is sometimes expressed
as a multiple of earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, investors have paid an average of $15 for stock in
a company earning $1 a year in profits. Today, based on the
Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks, they pay almost $30 for each
$1 in profits, and have paid more.
</P>
<P>
   Shiller notes that the S&AMP;P multiple has been as low as five
times earnings in the recession of 1920-21, to a high of 44.3 times
in January of this year. The index's P/E was 32.6 in September
1929, just before the Great Crash in October, and 20.3 in August of
1987, prior to that year's crash, also in October.
</P>
<P>
   He identifies three earlier periods of excessive stock prices _
prior to the one we are in now _ and says that each time they led
to disaster for investors.
</P>
<P>
   The market lost 67 percent of its value in the 20 years
following the turn-of-the-century peak in 1901, and almost 81
percent of its value between the October 1929 crash and January
1932. In the 20 years following the January 1966 peak of the '60s
bull market, stock returns averaged less than 2 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Some event will trigger another such setback for the market,
Shiller says, pointing out that it could be any one of many causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't predict short-term moves in the stock market,'' he
says. ``Bull markets like the one we have now can go on for a long
time. But clearly we're in a nonsustainable situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Shiller's book is by common consent the most authoritative case
against long-term continuation of the bull market in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to Shiller and many other analysts who believe stocks
are overvalued and vulnerable to a fall, Glassman and Hassett in
``Dow 36,000'' argue they are a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Glassman and Hassett believe that 36,000 is where the Dow Jones
industrial average should be trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stocks are significantly undervalued, and they are rising in a
one-time-only positive `correction.' Reason requires a Dow of about
36,000,'' Glassman says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stocks were undervalued in the past because investors believed
they were riskier than they really were,'' he adds. ``Now, acting
more rationally _ that is, with less aversion to risk _ they are
bidding up the prices of stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Glassman and Hassett don't quibble with those who say that
stocks are trading at high multiples, as measured by
price-to-earnings ratios.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, they say ``so what?'' Such valuations are based on
the perceived riskiness of common stocks, when in fact stocks are
not as risky as investors fear, they contend.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the economy is in a new era that will produce the
future profits that justify the current prices of common shares.
</P>
<P>
   They deny that a stock market ``bubble'' exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``When economists talk about a bubble, what they mean is the
greater fool theory _ the idea that there's a greater fool who will
buy my stock at whatever the price,'' says Glassman.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of some individual stocks, there's no doubt that
bubbles occur. But there is some doubt that there ever has been a
bubble for the overall market, even in 1929,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dow 36,000,'' as well as ``Irrational Exuberance,'' has come
in for sharp criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Barron's columnist Gene Epstein accused Shiller of exaggerating
the current P/E by using 10 years of trailing _ backward looking _
earnings as the denominator. That submerges the big earnings surge
of recent years, Epstein says. Edward Yardeni and some other
economists argue that stocks are not as overvalued as Shiller
contends, based on projected, or forward looking, earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Glassman and Hassett are accused by critics of minimizing the
``risk factor'' of stocks too much. Bonds, the critics say, while
admittedly less rewarding than stocks, really are safer.
</P>
<P>
   Economist Paul Krugman of the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology says stocks have not appeared to be risky in the past
mainly because ``people have been very cautious about buying
stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   But if investors begin to buy stocks based on the belief that
they are without risk, he says stock valuations will swing widely
``with the slightest bit of news.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors are unyielding. They say their books are products of
extensive research and careful thought, including comments and
observations from peers.
</P>
<P>
   As for their advice to investors and potential investors, their
positions are equally clear.
</P>
<P>
   Take your stocks out of the market, says Shiller, and put the
money in bonds and cash and other assets.
</P>
<P>
   Buy more stocks, say Glassman and Hassett. If anything, most
people do not have enough stocks in their portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Still confused about who is right?
</P>
<P>
   Who isn't?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
