<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1148 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-OLDER-WORKERS0703-COX     07-02 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDER-WORKERS0703-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Retire? No way. Options abound for older workers
 &HT;    By Maria Mallory
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Miriam Dennis-Stinson taught home economics for more
than 37 years, 34 of which were in the Atlanta school system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been 38 had I not taken maternity time,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   It really doesn't matter how you calculate it. When she retired
on June 9 from Kennedy Middle School in southwest Atlanta, you
might expect that after that much time on the job, Dennis-Stinson
would, well, retire.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis-Stinson, 60, a self-proclaimed ``jill of all trades'' is
as busy as ever.
</P>
<P>
   When she's not painting the exterior of her home, laying tile in
her kitchen or installing a suspended ceiling in her basement _ all
of which are recent projects of this ardent do-it-yourselfer _ she
is honing her entrepreneurial skills as a seamstress.
</P>
<P>
   Why would a ``retiree'' spend some 11-12 hours a day making
dresses from scratch instead of lounging by a pool or hitting golf
balls?
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have some responsibilities,'' says Dennis-Stinson, who
is a mother of three, including a son still in college.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, Dennis-Stinson's in pretty good financial shape with
her pension and an annuity. And though her sewing will bring in
extra money, one of the primary reasons she still works is because
she can't imagine not working.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm a workaholic,'' she laughs while continuing to
work on a dress. ``Somebody just told me that, and I think I'm
beginning to believe it. Retire ? Probably not, knowing me.''
</P>
<P>
   Workaholic or not, Dennis-Stinson is not the only retiree
eschewing unemployment. The New Economy has produced a feisty crop
of new retirees, folks who refuse to go quietly into a state of
perpetual leisure. Some, like Dennis-Stinson, turn to new
entrepreneurial ventures. Others find new opportunities in a
different industry. Still others are beginning to land part-time
positions with their former full-time employers.
</P>
<P>
   The diversity of post-employment options for the recently
retired is a sign of the times. On average, today's retirees are
blessed with longer life expectancy than their parents and
grandparents. Their children aren't yet old enough nor large enough
as a group to replace them in the work force. And, the booming
economy has wrought a shortage of well-trained workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People delaying retirement and returning to the work force
post-retirement have helped the labor force expand at twice the
rate of the working-age population over the past four years,''
reported U.S. News &AMP; World Report in a recent cover story.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are retiring,'' says Cathy Fyock, a human
resource consultant who specializes in working with retirement-age
adults. ``But they are retiring to their next job.''
</P>
<P>
   That next job may be a hobby or favorite pursuit, such as
Dennis-Stinson's sewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Sewing) has been something I've done all along, as a
supplement to my teaching salary,'' Dennis-Stinson explains. ``I
have always sewn. I've done alterations and, especially, prom and
wedding dresses.''
</P>
<P>
   But these days, instead of an occasional frock here or there,
Dennis-Stinson is taking larger orders. Her current project is a
wedding. Not just a wedding gown, but an entire wedding party: 16
dresses, including the bride's gown and dresses for the mother of
the bride, the flower girls and 11 bridesmaids.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister called me and told me it just makes her tired
thinking about making all those dresses,'' Dennis-Stinson quips.
``It's not really a chore because I enjoy it so. I get physically
tired, but mentally, I so enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   That can-do attitude is shared by many of today's
post-retirement entrepreneurs and older workers, Fyock says.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the gift of retirement, that you can go back to work
doing your dream job and there's nothing to stop you.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``gift'' may also be the key to post-retirement longevity,
asserts Fyock, who is the author of ``UnRetirement: A Career Guide
for the Retired, the Soon-to-be Retired and the Never-want-to-be
Retired.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to a lot of older adults who say, `I thought I'd
like to play golf or garden all the time,' '' only to find those
activities unfulfilling and undesirable, Fyock says.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, doing little or nothing after retirement may actually
be hazardous to your health, Fyock adds. ``Work feeds us in many
more ways than a paycheck,'' she says. ``It's a way to stay active,
to feed the soul, to be with friends, to feel challenged, to feel
like you're giving back.''
</P>
<P>
   Fyock says she has seen anecdotal evidence that retiring without
ambitions for additional work or other productive activities may
actually hasten death.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, for a growing number of retirees, many of whom joined
their companies at an early age or took advantage of corporate
downsizing proposals, retirement can come quite early in life.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Sisk retired at age 50 last year after some 27 years with
Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. A former sales and marketing executive, Sisk
says landing a job right out of college with the apparel giant
based in his hometown of San Francisco was his first ``grown-up
job.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Sisk relocated to Atlanta to help launch a new line of
men's slacks. He met and married his wife, Helene, and then he
faced a choice: He could either move back to San Francisco for a
post the company offered him there, or he could take an early
retirement package Levi's was using to help trim its work force.
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting to move, Sisk opted for retirement, securing 91
percent of what his retirement salary at age 55 would have been, as
well as full medical and dental coverage for himself and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a window of opportunity that may not have availed itself
ever again. Those kind of enhanced retirement packages, depending
on who's at the helm of the company, (sometimes) go away,'' Sisk
says.
</P>
<P>
   Sisk left Levi Strauss in October 1999. In April, after
researching franchise opportunities, he launched Proforma Sales and
Marketing Consulting, a business solutions, commercial printing and
promotional products firm.
</P>
<P>
   Why go right back to work?
</P>
<P>
   ``First, of all I'm only 50 and that's much too young. . . .
Nobody in my family every retired at 50,'' Sisk says. ``The reason
I work, I don't want to project being lazy. I'm still mentoring my
nephews and nieces, who are still struggling. I have a nephew going
to Morris Brown (College), and I want to be an example for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Duke, a special services manager, took early retirement at
Monsanto Co. in 1991, after working there 31 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wasn't quite ready to retire,'' says Duke, now 62.
</P>
<P>
   So he became part of the global agricultural firm's phased
retirement program. ``I went from 60 hours a week of full-time work
to 30 hours when I retired, and now I work only 18 hours a week,''
says Duke, guest relations educator at Monsanto's research center
in Chesterfield, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Phased retirement, in which retired employees return to work
part time, is a growing option in corporate America, driven by a
tight labor market and the desire of baby boomers to remain active.
</P>
<P>
   ``We introduced phased retirement a decade ago because coming
out of the lean and mean era of the 1980s, we realized we needed
replacements _ and also that we had qualified, intelligent and
loyal retirees we wanted to maintain our relationship with,'' said
Liz Thien, head of Monsanto's Retiree Resource Corps.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
