hysterical about a proposed hike in postal rates. By Alex
Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   POWER-SHORTFALL (Undated) _ Whether in terms of quantity or
quality, the nation's electrical power supply is no longer up to
the task of meeting the new economy's digital needs. By Barnaby J.
Feder.
</P>
<P>
   WORLDCOM-EBBERS (Undated) _ Has Bernie Ebbers' long run reached
its end? He has build Worldcom into a global power, and the Sprint
acquisition was to have been his crowning achievement. If the
Sprint deal falls apart as expected, what then for Ebbers? (News
Analysis.) By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   ORACLE-LEADERSHIP (San Francisco) _ Who's minding the store at
Oracle? After last week's clamorous disclosure that the software
giant had paid a private investigation service to gather
information about Microsoft, followed by the abrupt resignation
Friday of the company's president, Ray Lane, Oracle now seems to be
in the day-to-day hands of a troika of executives. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ENGINEERS (Undated) _ In an effort to reward its
brightest technologists, Microsoft plans to announce on Monday that
it has created a Distinguished Engineer program, initially honoring
16 of the company's best designers. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ The New Economy column: assessing
the continuing challenges of the online grocery business, in the
wake of Webvan's deal to acquire HomeGrocer.com. By Constance L.
Hays.
</P>
<P>
   ECOMMERCE-COLUMN (Undated) _ The E-Commerce column: a new
technology enables people who visit participating Web sites to see
what personal data participating the sites are collecting. By Bob
Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
