<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, July 3:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION (Mexico City) _ Mexicans vote in the most
competitive presidential election in the country's history, a
virtual dead heat between Francisco Labastida, the candidate of the
party that has ruled Mexico for 70 years, and his challenger,
Vincente Fox. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   With sidebars.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-TREES (Jerusalem) _ Reports that workers cynically uproot
the saplings planted in ritual tree-plantings by tourists has
prompted the Jewish National Fund to suspend several workers and
set up a formal investigation. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-REFERENDUM (Kampala, Uganda) _ Early results of a
referendum on Uganda's political future showed that more than 80
percent of voters want to continue with the current no-party system
advocated by the nation's president. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-OPPOSITION (Harare, Zimbabwe) _ How a new party, the
Movement for Democratic Change, united black union activists and
white corporate executives, students and workers into a formidable
movement that shook Zimbabwe's political establishment. By Rachel
L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-ARMS (United Nations) _ Scott Ritter, the former U.N. arms
inspector who quit two years ago charging that Secretary-General
Kofi Annan and U.S. officials were undercutting efforts to disarm
Saddam Hussein, now says the Iraqis have no prohibited weapons of
any importance left. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   ALBRIGHT-LEGACY (Washington) _ How does Madeleine Albright want
to be remembered as secretary of state? As Albright zoomed from
country to country, region to region _ four hours here, 36 hours
there in nine days _ the legacy question was never far away. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   6TH-GRADE-PRESSURES (Undated) _ Sixth graders today face a
combination of pressures that their parents never encountered. With
a college degree increasingly seen as a prerequisite for a decent
life, higher education has become a preoccupation for children even
before they reach puberty. At the same time, the students face new
layers of standardized tests that judge not only what they know but
the performance of their teachers, their schools, and their towns.
A special report. By Jodi Wilgoren and Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-MOTTO (Denver) _ Close on the heels of the Supreme Court's
latest ruling against officially sponsored prayer at public school
events, the Colorado State Board of Education is expected to pass a
resolution on Thursday that encourages public schools to display
the national motto ``In God we trust.'' By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA-HIGH-SCHOOL (Undated) _ Worried that new demands that all
students meet high achievement standards are impossible to meet in
the current educational structure, Sandra Feldman, the president of
the American Federation of Teachers, plans to call for an optional
fifth year of high school at the opening of the union's biennial
convention Monday. The proposal is part of a growing sense that
``seat time'' in class should be more flexible. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   PLATFORM-WRITER-PROFILE (Washington) _ A month from reaching the
ripe old age of 25, Andrei Cherny is writing the Democratic
platform, a 20,000-word spiritual guide to the party's political
soul that dedicated Democrats will fuss and bicker over all summer.
By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded p)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ Gore can't seem to catch a break.
Last week alone, everything seemed to go wrong for him, from the
polls to the campaign finance allegations to the Nader boomlet. But
even Bush loyalists concede that Democrats should not despair _ at
least not yet. (A political memo.) By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
