<SLUG> BC-CNN-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TED TURNER PLANS $1.2 BILLION EXPANSION AND MORE CNN ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN ROBINSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Spurred by declining ratings during slow news periods,
CNN's parent, Turner Broadcasting System, announced last week a
billion-dollar expansion that included broadening the network's Web
presence.
</P>
<P>
   Turner will spend $1.2 billion the next five years to enlarge
its downtown Atlanta headquarters and build and renovate its
offices and studios elsewhere in the city. One of its new downtown
towers will house over 3,000 new employees for the online and
wireless services it plans.
</P>
<P>
   Turner's strategy is to expand the network's online presence to
include research tools and more in-depth coverage. The result would
be a wealth of information from a combination of on-air and online
sources, said Steve Heyer, chief operating officer for Turner
Broadcasting, a Time Warner subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   ``People online are looking for a broader array of easy-to-get
news and information,'' he said. ``We are a dominant player in news
online. We don't want to lose that position, so what you're seeing
is the logical extension of that commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Woelfel, president and editor in chief of CNN Interactive,
the online division, said Turner's expansion in Atlanta would lead
to CNN's availability on wireless devices and interactive
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are expanding the content, but we're also expanding a lot
in how we deliver it,'' Woelfel said.
</P>
<P>
   Turner will undoubtedly collaborate with its prospective parent
company, America Online. The AOL merger with Time Warner still
needs federal approval, but many here expect the union to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking to work with them very closely,'' Woelfel said.
``The clout that AOL has in the market is really going to help us
as we try to distribute our products and market them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Heyer said Turner's expansion plans began long before there
was talk of a merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get approval to build buildings of this scope and
scale that quickly,'' he said. ``We've had these plans in the works
for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Heyer did say, however, that the likelihood of an AOL-Time
Warner union was another reason the expansion was important for
Turner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pride ourselves on being the fastest-growing division of
Time Warner, and we'd like to keep that going inside AOL,'' he
said. ``That's hard to do, given how fast AOL is growing.''
</P>
<P>
   The expansion also affirmed Turner's commitment to Atlanta a day
before plans for the AOL-Time Warner world headquarters in
Manhattan were announced.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.2 billion expansion comprises three new office buildings,
a tourist attraction highlighting Turner's entertainment networks
and a collaboration with Omni Hotels to more than double the size
of Turner's existing hotel at CNN Center, which is managed by the
Omni chain. The buildings should be completed by 2005.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
