<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION (Mexico City) _ Mexicans vote in the most
competitive presidential election in the country's history, a
virtual dead heat between Francisco Labastida, the candidate of the
party that has ruled Mexico for 70 years, and his challenger,
Vincente Fox. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-TREES (Jerusalem) _ Reports that workers cynically uproot
the saplings planted in ritual tree-plantings by tourists has
prompted the Jewish National Fund to suspend several workers and
set up a formal investigation. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-TOURISTS (Kfar Kila) _ It was a fine, sunny Sunday and
thousands of people flocked to Lebanon's newest tourist attraction
_ a stroll along the barbed wire fence here at the new, official
border with Israel, a chance to bring the kids, pose for pictures
and videos, even throw a stone or two in the general direction of
the Israelis. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   6TH-GRADE-PRESSURES (Undated) _ Sixth graders today face a
combination of pressures that their parents never encountered. With
a college degree increasingly seen as a prerequisite for a decent
life, higher education has become a preoccupation for children even
before they reach puberty. At the same time, the students face new
layers of standardized tests that judge not only what they know but
the performance of their teachers, their schools, and their towns.
A special report. By Jodi Wilgoren and Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
