<SLUG> BC-MAGS-POSTAL-RATES-ART-960(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGAZING PUBLISHERS ENRAGED OVER POSTAL RATE PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When magazine publishers and chief executives of
media companies discuss the latest problem facing the magazine
industry, they use words like ``passion,'' ``devastation'' and
``death.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives who usually favor brevity will spend an hour in
conversation detailing the potential ``horror'' of the crisis. The
feared trauma is such that magazine publishers have been cruising
the halls of Congress for the last five months, spending millions
of dollars lobbying for relief.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a grand theme like freedom of speech or censorship
that is kicking up all the emotion. The panic involves a rate
increase the U.S. Postal Service has proposed to take effect next
year, which would raise the cost of mailing subscription copies of
magazines by 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Estimating that the rate increase will cost their industry $300
million in the next two years, magazine publishers are going _ well
_ postal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be potentially devastating for many magazines,''
said Nina B. Link, the president of the Magazine Publishers of
America.
</P>
<P>
   The Magazine Publishers of America plans to spend $10 million
this year lobbying Congress on the issue, while companies like Time
Warner, the parent company of Time Inc., have put their own
lobbyists to work on the case as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Magazine Publishers, a trade group to which more than 1,000
of the largest consumer magazines belong, has placed ads in trade
journals stating that the proposed increase is twice the average
increase the Postal Service usually proposes, is three times the
rate of inflation and is double what the Postal Service actually
needs to cover the projected costs of processing magazines.
</P>
<P>
   But economists for the Postal Service say that while the service
is willing to negotiate the proposed increase, it is not only
necessary _ it is mandated by federal law. The Postal Reform Act of
1970 mandates that every class of mail must cover its own mailing
costs.
</P>
<P>
   This latest rate proposal comes at a tense time for the
industry: newsstand sales are sinking, subscriptions are down for
many consumer magazines, and several smaller but high-profile
magazines have closed this year.
</P>
<P>
   And some publishers still remember the last time such a large
postal increase went into effect for the magazine industry _ in the
early 1970s, when the added financial burden contributed to the
demise of even some venerable publications like the old weekly
Life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small magazines are the ones that will be most devastated
because they have smaller margins,'' Link said. ``This will hurt
them the most. And it will be hard for other magazines with larger
circulations that don't have much wiggle room.''
</P>
<P>
   Link has spent a substantial part of the last five months on
Capitol Hill, pleading with members of the House and the Senate to
encourage the Postal Service to turn back the increase. She has
encouraged both Democrats and Republicans to unite in asking
William J. Henderson, the postmaster general, to reconsider the
increase.
</P>
<P>
   And Link has been joined by some of the most powerful figures in
magazine publishing: Cathleen P. Black, the president of Hearst
Magazines; Christopher M. Little, the president of the Meredith
Publishing Group, and Daniel B. Brewster, the former chief
executive of American Express Publishing who is now the chief
executive of Gruner &AMP; Jahr magazines. Link has hit Capitol Hill
with as many as 10 magazine publishers in tow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been trying to educate anyone and everyone as to why
this is so unfair and unjust and unreasonable,'' Link said. ``We
absolutely will not accept these kinds of increases. We feel the
industry has been singled out.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rate increase applies to consumer magazines that
are mailed under the bulk classification of ``periodicals.'' Rate
increases for other categories, like first-class mail, are in the
single digits. Greg Frey, a spokesman for the Postal Service, said
that the last increase _ 4.6 percent _ was proposed two years ago
and went into effect in January 1999. Link said because that
increase was so much smaller, the decision met less criticism from
the magazine industry.
</P>
<P>
   Little of Meredith said that every Meredith title would be
affected by the proposed increase, the news of which he described
as ``a bombshell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every copy of Better Homes &AMP; Gardens will be affected,'' he
said, referring to a Meredith title. ``And at Hearst every copy of
Good Housekeeping will be affected, and at Conde Nast, every copy
of Vogue.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed increase has also made strange bedfellows; two of
the most concerned crusaders against the increase are The National
Geographic Society and Playboy magazine. Both magazines depend on
subscriptions for much of their circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Of The Geographic's 8.5 million circulation, 8.2 million copies
are sent by subscription. Playboy's subscribers number 2.6 million
out of a total circulation of 3.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Sims, senior vice president for magazine publishing at
the National Geographic Society, said it cost the society 24 cents
to send a subscription issue out; the proposed increase could raise
that to about 27.6 cents an issue. At 3.6 extra cents an issue each
month for 8.2 million issues, that is an increase of $295,200 a
month in expenses for the society.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't sound like much at first,'' he said. ``But when you
when you add up the costs of print, editorial and other
distribution costs, well, pretty soon you don't have any money
left.'' He described the rate increase as ``potentially devastating
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gail Day, a senior vice president at Playboy Enterprises and the
publisher of Playboy, said, ``If this goes through, we will have to
look to other lines of our business to fund that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ashley Lyons, an economist and the manager of pricing for the
Postal Service, acknowledged that the proposed increase was a
substantial one.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are saying is that the costs of handling magazines
will go up by roughly 12.8 percent over the next three years,'' he
said, adding that the Postal Service was actively investigating
ways to reduce the increase. The postmaster general testified
before the House Postal Appropriations Subcommittee that he would
take steps to achieve $150 million in savings that would apply to
magazine handling.
</P>
<P>
   Frey of the Postal Service said that the service was not
singling out any industry and was making every effort to
incorporate cost-cutting measures proposed by the magazine
publishers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The various classes of mail must support themselves and we
cannot cross-subsidize,'' he said. ``And that is mandated by law.
For them to feel singled out or to imply that there is a conspiracy
against some of our best customers is ridiculous.'' Frey said that
additional increases in postage would be likely this year because
of recent increases in gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   But even the Postal Service's avowal to try to curb the increase
does not placate publishers like Little, who has criticized the
Postal Service as poorly managed. He said the postmaster general
had disregarded the Magazine Publishers of America's
recommendations over the last two years to keep the increase in the
single digits.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first heard of this 15 percent hike, we came in and
said, `Now wait a minute,' '' Little said. ```We have been working
with you for two years and we have been promised that the rate
increase would not be anything in the double digits, and then you
present us with a 15 percent rate increase.' That to us is just
unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   If the magazine industry and the Postal Service cannot reconcile
their differences, the magazine industry may be left with little
recourse. Link said that publishers had begun to explore other
options, like shipping magazines via non-government means like
United Parcel Service, DHL and Federal Express.
</P>
<P>
   Sims of The National Geographic said that the National
Geographic Society had broached the idea of negotiating a contract
rate with the Postal Service, such as the Society does with foreign
postal services like England's Royal Mail. But he said the U.S.
Postal Service would not negotiate individual corporate contracts.
</P>
<P>
   On June 12, Rep. Chaka Fattah, D-Md., introduced a bill in
Congress that would reduce the rate increase. Congress and the
Senate have until November to approve the new postal rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever think you'd hear so much passion about postage
rates?'' Link asked. ``It's ridiculous. I dream about it at
night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
