<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: NEW ACCOUNT ASSIGNMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., skedded earlier as NEW-AD-COLUMN) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For agencies large and small, the second half of 2000 is
beginning the same way the first half ended, with a flurry of
account assignments from advertisers in major categories like
beauty products, automobiles, dot-coms and banking.
</P>
<P>
   Estee Lauder in New York, the cosmetics and fragrance giant,
named A/R Media in New York to assist its in-house team with the
creative development of a new national campaign. It marks the first
time in several years that Lauder has sought creative direction
from outside the company.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will continue to feature Elizabeth Hurley, the
actress who serves as the public ``face'' of Lauder, in ads that
are expected to be shot by the fashion photographer Steven Meisel.
The new work is planned to start in January.
</P>
<P>
   A/R Media, headed by Alex Gonzalez and Raoul Martinez,
specializes in designer fashion advertising for apparel marketers
like Dolce &AMP; Gabbana, Missoni, Emanuel Ungaro, Valentino and
Versace.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of parallels and similarities between fashion
and beauty,'' said Donna Laveran, a spokeswoman for Lauder. ``A/R
is a name known in the fashion and beauty worlds.'' A/R was chosen
after a six-month review, she added, declining to disclose the
other participants.
</P>
<P>
   Though a budget for the campaign is not being disclosed, Lauder
spent $116.2 million last year on advertising, according to
Competitive Media Reporting in New York, which tracks ad spending.
</P>
<P>
   Bates Worldwide in New York, part of the Cordiant Communications
Group, remains the agency of record for Lauder, handling duties
like media planning and buying.
</P>
<P>
   On the automotive front, BMW of North America in Woodcliff Lake,
N.J., part of BMW AG, named Washington Daniel Advertising in
Chicago as its first agency of record for so-called diversity
marketing initiatives aimed at African-Americans and other
consumers. Billings were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The company is hoping that Washington Daniel can help ``to
extend our brand to a more diverse audience,'' said Jim McDowell,
vice president for marketing at BMW of North America. Other clients
of Washington Daniel include Anheuser-Busch and IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Fallon Minneapolis, part of the Fallon Worldwide unit of
Publicis SA, handles general market advertising for BMW.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to other account assignments, Finance.com in Long Island
City, , N.Y., a Web site offering financial and investment advice
that is part of the e-Citi operation of Citibank, named Kirshenbaum
Bond &AMP; Partners in New York to handle its first account. Spending
was estimated at $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after a review that had been narrowed to
Kirshenbaum Bond and four undisclosed agencies. Kirshenbaum Bond
handles another assignment for Citibank, the American Airlines
AAdvantage credit card program.
</P>
<P>
   Kirshenbaum Bond was also being considered in a review for the
U.S. account of Citibank, which has been handled by the New York
office of Young &AMP; Rubicam Advertising. The review for that account,
with billings estimated at $48 million, was narrowed last week to
two agencies, the daily fax edition of the trade publication
Advertising Age reported: Fallon Minneapolis and three offices of
TBWA/Chiat/Day, part of the TBWA Worldwide unit of the Omnicom
Group. Citibank is owned by Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   In another dot-com decision, MySimon.com in San Francisco, an
online comparison shopping service that is part of CNET Networks,
named Leo Burnett USA in Chicago, part of the Leo Burnett Co. unit
of the B Com3 Group, to handle its account, which had been at
Bigelo &AMP; Partners in San Francisco. Billings were estimated at $15
million.
</P>
<P>
   The MySimon.com decision came after a three-week review that had
been narrowed to Burnett and three undisclosed agencies based in
the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   And the Hibernia Corp. in New Orleans, which operates banks in
Louisiana and Texas, named Doner in Southfield, Mich., to handle
its account, which had been at Caldwell VanRiper/MARC in
Indianapolis, part of MARC USA. Billings were estimated at $15
million to $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after a review that had been narrowed to Doner
and two other agencies. One was McCann-Erickson Southwest in
Dallas, part of the McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising unit of
the McCann-Erickson World Group, which is owned by the Interpublic
Group of Cos. The other was Publicis in Dallas and New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
