<HEADLINE>
VETERAN HAITIAN MUSICIANS STRETCH TRADITIONAL RHYTHMS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JON PARELES  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A big band doesn't survive for 37 years without being
flexible. Orchestre Tropicana d'Haiti, one of Haiti's two reigning
big bands along with its older rival, Orchestre Septentrional,
celebrates its 37th birthday in August. When it performed for
dancers on the night of June 30 at Lincoln Center's Midsummer Night
Swing series, it ambled between homegrown tradition and congenial
extensions.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti shares the island of Hispaniola with the Dominican
Republic, and Orchestre Tropicana gives more than a glance over the
border. Between Haitian compas tunes, the singers switched from
Kreyol (Haitian Creole) to Spanish as the group played its own
versions of bolero, cumbia, Dominican merengue and the
stripped-down Dominican ballad style called bachata. In place of
the bachata's spiky acoustic guitar, the keyboardist used a banjo
sound. Yet Orchestre Tropicana holds on above all to the unhurried
beat of the compas. The occupation of Haiti by the United States
from 1915 to 1934 brought swing bands, and Haitians adapted the
lineup for their own dance music. Haitian big bands played compas
with a gentle beat that carried a jovial, evolving interchange of
riffs from saxophones, brasses and singers. Then, in the late 1960s
and 1970's, along came so-called minijazz bands like Tabou Combo.
Guitars took over the horn parts, and the rhythm eased toward rock
and salsa.
</P>
<P>
   Orchestre Tropicana, which is directed by Louis Jean, has not
ignored the changes. Its songs from recent decades have added
guitar licks and synthesizer lines to the round-robin of riffs. It
has also moved from songs about love and domestic troubles _ like
``Angelique,'' which complains that she always cooks the same meal
_ to songs with uplifting messages. Yet the saxophones, trumpets
and trombones have held onto their -unslick, blithely out-of-tune
dialogues, and the music remains breezy and affable.
</P>
<P>
   Orchestre Tropicana's songs get better as they grow longer. They
can seem understated, almost lackadaisical, when they start. After
a minute or two, they are unassumingly pleasant, with smoothly
crooned melodies over the clip-clopping compas beat. But after
about four minutes, something mysterious happens. New riffs keep
turning up from every section of the band. And the mesh and
colloquy of stuttering saxophones, cheerful sustained trumpets,
pearly syncopated guitar lines, calliopelike keyboard phrases and
self-effacing percussion directly insinuate themselves into feet
and hips, making dancers move without a hint of pressure. For all
its modesty, the music persists because it never wears out its
welcome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
