<HEADLINE>
NBC OFFICIAL REBUKED; MAGAZINE FOR PRO ATHLETES; CNN DEAL IN
JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Va., N.Y., Tenn., )   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Scott Sassa, the president of NBC's West Coast division, in
so much trouble with the network's management that he is about to
be fired?
</P>
<P>
   Not at all, say a wide range of senior NBC executives. The
officials were put on the defensive last week when The New York
Post published an article saying that John F. Welch Jr., the
chairman of General Electric, NBC's parent, had criticized Sassa
during a tense senior management meeting last Tuesday. The article
said that Sassa would be out in a matter of days. Dismissing the
threat to Sassa, Kassie Canter, the corporate spokeswoman for the
network said, ``The Post dredged up a six-week-old rumor.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Hollywood had been rife with rumors for many weeks of
Sassa's imminent departure _ always steadfastly and authoritatively
denied by NBC executives.
</P>
<P>
   But The Post report had its biggest fact right. NBC did have an
executive meeting last week, and Welch did have occasion to ``beat
up'' Sassa, as one executive put it, as well as some other NBC
division heads.
</P>
<P>
   Welch was unhappy with the entertainment division that Sassa
directs for not following the lead of ABC and CBS into the hot
programming trend of reality shows like ``Who Wants To Be a
Millionaire'' and ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC's president, Bob Wright, had already expressed
dissatisfaction with the division's reluctance to enter the reality
race. Last December, just after ``Millionaire'' emerged as a force
that would overwhelm prime time, Wright was voicing concern about a
then-obscure show CBS had purchased called ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Wright's anxiety, NBC still did nothing to try to buy
the rights to other reality formats being offered to the networks.
NBC's entertainment executives said they had no special budget to
buy summer programs, making it impossible to get in on the intense
bidding for shows like ``Big Brother,'' for which CBS paid $20
million and which makes its debut on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   But one senior NBC executive said, ``That didn't mean they
couldn't get `The Mole'.'' That reality show, set for January, was
snapped up by ABC. Welch also expressed concern in last week's
meeting because NBC seemed to have few promising shows lined up to
take advantage of the upcoming promotional platform of the Summer
Olympics in September. NBC's coming fall series have not received
strong advance notices.
</P>
<P>
   So while reports of Sassa's shaky status may have been the
product of some nasty efforts to undermine him, the pressure on him
is only going to increase. ``We know the fall season is crucial,''
one senior NBC entertainment division executive said. ``If we don't
have a hit or two, things could get really ugly in October.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Carter
</P>
<P>
   A New Magazine for Professional Athletes
</P>
<P>
   Do not look for Pro, a new magazine, in local stores. The
publication will be sent only to the homes of its target market:
professional athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The glossy publication, which features helpful articles on
everything from investment planning (three athletes ``show their
monetary moves'') to buying a luxury watch (``it's all in the
wrist''), is shooting for a tiny target audience of 25,000.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterly magazine, introduced in May, is circulated only to
current and recently retired American professional athletes, who
receive it free.
</P>
<P>
   While many magazines depend on revenues from advertising for a
significant portion of their budgets, Pro's publisher, Street &AMP;
Smith's, plans to rely solely on ad sales _ confident that
advertisers will jump at the opportunity for access to one of the
nation's most affluent demographic groups.
</P>
<P>
   The typical professional athlete makes far more than do doctors
or even the chief executives of major corporations. And since the
athletes that receive Pro are also usually younger than other
affluent professionals, they are less likely to be loyal to certain
brands. John Capouya, Pro's editor in chief and a former editor at
The New York Times, said part of what made the gamble surrounding
his new magazine interesting was its reliance on advertising alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We guarantee advertisers exclusive access to these people at
home,'' he said. ``That's what we think is our unique advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The first issue features advertisements for a luxury yachting
company, a home security company run by former Navy Seals and an
asset management group.
</P>
<P>
   Each issue will have sections on topics like shopping, exotic
travel, sports psychology and health. Many of the short articles
are collaborations between writers and athletes, Capouya said.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine, as Capouya states in his first letter from the
editor, will not feature any negative stories about athletes.
Instead, it will try to help athletes by providing advice,
mentoring and support, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Hopkins, a Tennessee Titans lineman who encouraged athletes
to hold open doors and sign autographs in the article he wrote for
the first issue, said: ``I don't know if helpful is the word. Let's
just say entertaining.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Kruti Trivedi
</P>
<P>
   CNN News Comes to DoCoMo Handsets
</P>
<P>
   CNN plans to announce on Monday that it has stuck a deal with
Japan's largest mobile telephone operator, NTT DoCoMo, to provide
news and other information to customers via their mobile telephone
handsets.
</P>
<P>
   The service will provide breaking news in English or Japanese to
subscribers of DoCoMo's i-mode service, a wildly popular service in
Japan that allows customers to surf customized Web sites over the
Internet. I-mode became so popular in Japan that DoCoMo recently
had to curtail sales of cellular phone handsets that offer Internet
access to ease the load on its overburdened network.
</P>
<P>
   While most Web sites on the Internet have had a hard time
charging consumers for access to content, CNN, a unit of Time
Warner, predicts that customers will be willing to pay for content
over their mobile telephones. While news headlines will be free,
users will be charged 300 yen, or $2.83, to download an entire
article. The charges will be added to customers' monthly telephone
bills.
</P>
<P>
   The service is being offered through CNN Mobile, a CNN unit that
has formed similar alliances with other mobile telephone operators
internationally. The information delivered over the service comes
mostly from CNN's Web site, CNN.com.
</P>
<P>
   The CNN/i-mode service could serve as a model of sorts for other
mobile Internet access services, because of DoCoMo's network, which
can deliver data at much higher speeds than most other current
mobile telephone networks.
</P>
<P>
   The service will be promoted through CNN Interactive and CNN
International and could eventually be marketed through America
Online, if AOL's acquisition of Time Warner is completed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Andrew Ross Sorkin
</P>
</TEXT>
