<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CONFIDENT ARMSTRONG EXPECTS A FIGHT IN A RACE WITH NEW DYNAMICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDUN, France _ Looking relaxed and sounding unruffled, saying
that his form is good but needs some improvement, Lance Armstrong
predicted a tough Tour de France. ``It'll be a good fight,'' he
said solemnly, then broke into a smile, as if he knew a secret. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he does. Perhaps, though, it's not really a secret. ``I
like my own chances,'' he finally said. He squared his jaw and
waited for a contradiction _ a dare that was hard to accept.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong is no longer in the overall leader's yellow jersey
that he wore for two weeks last summer. He finished second to David
Millar of Cofidis as the 87th edition of the race began Saturday,
and Millar retained the yellow jersey Sunday after finishing 17th
in the 120-mile race from Futuroscope to Loudun. Tom Steels of
Mapei won the opening stage in 4 hours 46 minutes 8 seconds.
Armstrong was 37th, in the same time as Steels, and and is second
over all, trailing Millar by only four seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Millar is, as Armstrong described him, ``a good guy and a good
friend,'' but Armstrong has a long memory. When the new leader of
the Tour came up to him at the starting line in Futuroscope Sunday
morning and proudly showed him his yellow jersey, yellow helmet and
yellow shorts, Armstrong said, ``One thing wrong.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What's that?'' Millar asked. Armstrong pointed to the Cofidis
team name on the shorts. That was the employer who Armstrong feels
betrayed him by trying to reduce his salary and then terminate his
contract when he was stricken with testicular cancer four years
ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yellow jersey or not, Armstrong, the leader of the United States
Postal Service team, is wearing No. 1 on his back because of his
victory in the Tour last year and he is, as the French sports
newspaper l'Equipe anointed him Saturday, Le Boss. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His strength has been evident in races this spring and his
motivation is, as always, sky high. He is riding, he says, not only
``to prove that a cancer survivor can win this bike race, the
hardest sporting event in the world,'' but also to gain the respect
he feels some riders begrudge him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why, he was asked in an interview, after his clearcut triumph
last year do so many people say this is an open race and then list
seven, eight and nine candidates for victory? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that started with those guys who weren't here last
year,'' Armstrong replied, naming Marco Pantani, the Italian who
won the Tour in 1998, and Jan Ullrich, the German who won in 1997.
``Pantani and Ullrich perhaps didn't respect the race last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Pantani missed last year's race after failing a drug test;
Ullrich was injured. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's all history, it doesn't matter,'' the 28-year-old
Texan said. ``We're all here now, everybody's here, and I think
everybody will have the ambition to go to the finish. That's the
way I prefer it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody was to get an injury or crash or mysteriously pull
out, I would be disappointed. If it was a Pantani or an Ullrich _ a
big favorite _ I would be disappointed because if they're not
there, inevitably somebody says, `Well, Pantani wasn't there.' Or
`Well, but.' So this is better. We're all here, let's go, we'll
find out.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong leaned back in his chair, poured a glass of water and
went on: ``It's hard this year. It's a totally different race from
last year, not that it wasn't hard then. But being the defending
champion, being that the course is a lot harder this year, being
that all the others are back, there are totally different
dynamics. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that there's no time trial before the mountains
changes a lot.'' In the first long individual time trial last year,
Armstrong won easily, hammering the morale of his rivals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the psychological factor, he was talking tactics.
``You can't have a cushion this year and let guys get away _ no,
you can't do that,'' he said. ``Everybody can be a threat unless
they have a poor team trial,'' which will be held Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong looks fit, perhaps a bit under his usual weight of 165
pounds.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As the defending champion, I know I'm a marked man,'' he said,
``but this Tour should be a little easier than last year's because
I'm one more year away from cancer.'' After diagnosis, surgery and
three months of chemotherapy in 1996, Armstrong returned to the
sport in 1998 and to the Tour in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``To sum it up, I'm a little less nervous than I was last year,
I'm confident about my team and comfortable about my condition.
Plus I have the experience of winning the Tour.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is he stronger than last year? After a long pause, Armstrong
answered: ``Probably yes. That's normal with age and the further
away I get from my illness. It's normal that my body is still
recovering from that period but at the same time I am getting older
and more experienced. I should be stronger. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have to work hard. I don't like to train, I'm lazy.''
He allowed himself a mischievous grin. ``No, actually I thrive on
training, it's fun to me. I prefer it to racing.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Training pays a lot less than racing, he was told. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Not if you win the one race a year,'' he replied. ``It's too
bad, but that's the way it is. The Tour is so big.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
