<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Monday, July 3. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION (Mexico City) _ Mexicans vote in the most
competitive presidential election in the country's history, a
virtual dead heat between Francisco Labastida, the candidate of the
party that has ruled Mexico for 70 years, and his challenger,
Vincente Fox. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WOLVES-PROTECT (Undated) _ The federal government is
preparing to announce that the gray wolf, which was once nearly
shot, trapped and poisoned out of existence in the lower 48 states,
is abundant enough in a few places that it no longer uniformly
needs the strict protection afforded the country's most endangered
species. By Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-TREES (Jerusalem) _ Reports that workers cynically uproot
the saplings planted in ritual tree-plantings by tourists has
prompted the Jewish National Fund to suspend several workers and
set up a formal investigation. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-TOURISTS (Kfar Kila, Lebanon) _ It was a fine, sunny
Sunday and thousands of people flocked to Lebanon's newest tourist
attraction _ a stroll along the barbed wire fence here at the new,
official border with Israel, a chance to bring the kids, pose for
pictures and videos, and even throw a stone or two in the general
direction of the Israelis. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   HARRY-POTTER-FRENZY (Los Angeles) _ This coming weekend, when
the latest Harry Potter novel, ``Harry Potter and the Goblet of
Fire,'' officially goes on sale, at least 9,000 Federal Express
trucks will be deployed around the nation on that morning by the
Internet retail giant Amazon.com to help deliver 250,000 presold
copies of the fantasy novel. The newest ``Harry Potter'' is a
752-page book and will be published simultaneously in the United
States and Britain with a first printing of 3.8 million copies in
America, a record. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   6TH-GRADE-PRESSURES (Undated) _ Sixth graders today face a
combination of pressures that their parents never encountered. With
a college degree increasingly seen as a prerequisite for a decent
life, higher education has become a preoccupation for children even
before they reach puberty. At the same time, the students face new
layers of standardized tests that judge not only what they know but
the performance of their teachers, their schools, and their towns.
A special report. By Jodi Wilgoren and Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   OPSAIL-UNDERDOG (New York) _ OpSail 2000 promises to be full of
awe-inspiring tall ships. And then there is Ukraine's official, if
utterly unfunded, representative: Bat'kivshchyna, a 90-foot
metal-hulled fishing trawler dipped in cement and topped with two
masts. Its captain, Dmytro Biriukovich, never doubted for a second
that the ship would make it to New York, not when the ship ran
aground on the Dnepr River a few days into the trip and lost a big
chunk of her keel. Or when storms in the Mediterranean shredded the
mainsail. Or when they lost their satellite phone service somewhere
around Spain, or their radio gave out in the Atlantic, setting off
an oceanwide search. By Andy Newman.
</P>
</TEXT>
