<HEADER>
A1207 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILMS-JULYFOURTH-NYT &LR;      07-02 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS-JULYFOURTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STORM' OUTFLANKS `PATRIOT' AT BOX OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
  By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Despite predictions of a neck-and-neck race for the
Independence Day weekend box office between a pair of big-studio
behemoths, it turned out to be not much of a race at all. ``The
Perfect Storm'' blew away ``The Patriot,'' earning an estimated
$41.7 million since its Friday opening, compared with $21.6 million
for its rival, a Revolutionary War epic.
</P>
<P>
   The third major opening of the weekend, the family-oriented
``Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle,'' registered barely a blip,
earning just $6.6 million and ending up in fifth place behind the
animated ``Chicken Run,'' with $12.8 million, and the Jim Carrey
comedy ``Me, Myself and Irene,'' with $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday weekend shakedown was of particular importance in
Hollywood this year because the summer movie season, which runs
from Memorial Day to Labor Day, had been in a slump in recent
weeks, at least compared with last summer's record-setting pace.
Many were hoping that strong showings by the holiday films would
power a strong second half for the summer, traditionally the most
lucrative moviegoing period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall the box office is up for the first time in three
weeks, and that's good,'' said Paul Dergarabedian, chairman of
Exhibitor Relations, a Los Angeles company that monitors box-office
performance. ``This was a pivotal weekend for the summer because
with that slump we were in, we really needed a weekend to bring us
out of the doldrums.''
</P>
<P>
   The top 12 movies earned an estimated $121.7 million over the
three days ending Sunday, up 5.3 percent from last year's total for
the same period. The rise comes after three consecutive weekends in
which the box office fell around 20 percent compared with the same
weekends last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely good news, because it means that audiences are
excited about the movies that were playing this weekend,''
Dergarabedian said.
</P>
<P>
   But whether this weekend's rise will be strong enough to
resuscitate the summer box office remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, hopefully, the pictures will hold on,'' said Tom Sherak,
longtime distribution chief for 20th Century Fox. ``These pictures
just need to hold on so the exhibition world can get a little more
healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the weekend provided spectacular news for Warner
Brothers and its ``Perfect Storm,'' which exceeded most
expectations and provided the largest three-day opening in the
studio's history and the biggest openings ever for its director,
Wolfgang Petersen, and its star, George Clooney. It was also the
third highest-grossing Fourth of July release in history, behind
1997's ``Men in Black,'' with $51.1 million, and 1996's
``Independence Day,'' with $50.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dominated the weekend, making almost double the
second-place film,'' said Dan Fellman, president of distribution at
Warner Brothers. ``And we still have two big days before the
holiday is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellman credited Petersen's direction and the spectacular
special-effects by Industrial Light and Magic with making the
difference, as well as the studio's advertising campaign, nearly
ubiquitous in recent weeks, showing a fishing boat dwarfed by a
huge wall of water. Of special importance, he said, was the film's
PG-13 rating, which expanded the potential audience. ``The
Patriot'' is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   As with ``The Patriot,'' the audience that turned out for ``The
Perfect Storm'' was primarily those over 25. But Petersen's sea
adventure, based on the best-selling book by Sebastian Junger about
a devastating 1991 storm and its effect on a boat crew of
Massachusetts fishermen, drew an audience that was slightly skewed
toward women, about 53 percent female and 47 percent male.
</P>
<P>
   If the film can now begin to attract more young people, who make
up the bulk of the summer movie audience, it stands a good chance
of becoming the second $200-million film of the summer, after
``Mission:Impossible 2,'' which opened over the Memorial Day
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be around $75 million for our first week and certainly
have $100 million in 14 days or less,'' Fellman said. ``It
certainly has the potential to be a $200 million movie.''
</P>
<P>
   This was also a very good weekend for DreamWorks, which added
400 screens for its critically praised ``Chicken Run'' and saw only
a 27 percent decline on its second weekend, indicating that the
film is also enjoying strong word of mouth. By comparison, Fox's
``Me, Myself and Irene'' saw a 50 percent drop-off in its second
weekend and, despite the star power of Carrey, ended up finishing
behind ``Chicken Run.''
</P>
<P>
   The weekend box office figures are based on actual ticket sales
from Friday and Saturday and estimates by each of the studios of
Sunday ticket sales. Final figures for the weekend will be made
public on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia Pictures was putting the best spin possible on the
opening weekend for ``The Patriot,'' a film that many expected to
end up in first place, largely on the drawing power of its star,
Mel Gibson, and the track record of its director, Roland Emmerich.
But its R-rating and a running time of 2 hours 40 minutes may have
worked against it, as well as an aversion among young moviegoers to
period pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patriot'' opened on Wednesday, hoping to take maximum
advantage of this year's long holiday weekend, with the Fourth
falling on a Tuesday. Instead, the studio estimated the film would
finish its first week with about $43 million, only slightly more
than ``Perfect Storm'' made in its first three days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we played a bit more adult than we had anticipated,
because of the ratings and the subject matter,'' said Jeff Blake,
Columbia's head of distribution. ``We didn't play like an R-rated
action film. Now we have to do what we have to do to become the
best-holding movie of the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   But Blake said the exit polls were strong, and ``The Patriot''
saw a 25 percent rise in ticket sales from Friday to Saturday, so
there are hopes that the movie will still do very well. ``Though
perhaps it will be more in a long run way,'' he said. ``I think we
have a wonderful chance to be the adult film of the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gordon, one of the film's producers, said that he had
always anticipated such an opening, since the film's main audience
is older and less inclined to run out and see something on its
first weekend. He pointed to other recent films, including ``Saving
Private Ryan,'' which he also produced, as having similar openings
yet going on to extremely lucrative runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a great thing to crow about,'' Gordon said. ``Oh,
we won the weekend.' But I'd rather look at the great business the
weekend held for everybody. We're not in competition with anybody.
There's room for several good pictures.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
