<HEADER>
A1210 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-SOC-U.S.-WOMEN-1600(2     07-02 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-U.S.-WOMEN-1600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SOME CAREFUL PRUNING, THE U.S. WOMEN'S TEAM REGROWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
  FOXBORO, Mass. _ Euphoria over winning the 1999 Women's World Cup
was quickly tempered for the Americans by a coaching change and a
contract dispute with the United States Soccer Federation. What had
seemed certain was no longer certain. Invincibility was replaced by
insecurity.
<TEXT>
<P>
   April Heinrichs, one of the early stars of the women's national
team, replaced Tony DiCicco as coach in January and bluntly told
the veterans, ``I don't care if you've played in three World Cups,
if I feel you are past your peak, I will release you.'' In her
first game as coach, she did not start the captain, Carla Overbeck,
or midfielder Michelle Akers, considered the greatest player ever
in the women's game. ``Are you putting me out to pasture?'' a
perplexed Akers asked Heinrichs.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, the coach cut five veterans who were not contending for
starting positions.
</P>
<P>
   Had she been hired by the federation to clean house?
</P>
<P>
   ``We had gone through this huge ugly brawl over the contract and
all we had been hearing was, `They don't want you guys anymore, you
create too many problems,''' the co-captain Julie Foudy said. ``We
were like, `Is she listening to them, does she believe that, did
they pick her because of that?' We didn't think so, but I don't
think she understood how nervous we were about that.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, the American women will face Brazil in a
rematch of the World Cup semifinal here in the championship match
of the Gold Cup at Foxboro Stadium. The teams also played to a 0-0
tie in a Gold Cup group match last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the early fears were unfounded. Heinrichs said
she never intended to do any clear-cutting of the American roster,
just some necessary pruning. Fifteen of the 18 members of the 2000
Olympic team are expected to be players from the World Cup team.
And Heinrichs has become widely popular for her competitiveness and
for her encouragement of the players to be creative and take risks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Americans face difficult questions as they attempt to
repeat as Olympic champions at the 2000 Games in Sydney, Australia,
in September: Can they survive a difficult draw that features their
toughest rivals, Norway and China, in the first two matches? Can
they win on the road after winning the 1996 Olympics and the 1999
World Cup at home? Can they compensate for injuries that have
affected the spine of their defense _ Akers (shoulder surgery),
Overbeck (knee surgery) and goalkeeper Briana Scurry (shin
splints)? Can they remain focused on soccer while also enjoying the
endorsement and public-appearance bounty of a World Cup victory?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympics are going to be our biggest challenge,'' Foudy
said. ``There are a lot of people tugging at the team, so many
demands. It's been a major topic of conversation. It requires that
much more focus, that much more dedication and commitment to
saying, `No, I can't do this.' If it's not going to help you in
September, say no now. This is the last time we'll all be together.
We want to go out with a bang, not with regrets. Everyone asks if
we'll be complacent, but that's not us. We've worked harder this
year than we ever have.''
</P>
<P>
   A year after the World Cup, attendance has inevitably dropped at
the national team's matches, but Foudy said people still frequently
approached the players in airports and high-fived them and
congratulated them on the victory. ``I'm amazed at the depth of
people we've reached, from Midwesterners who never watched a soccer
match to Nascar-type guys,'' she said. ``I think it's going to have
a big impact on kids for years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   With her exultant, jersey-removing celebration at the conclusion
of the penalty-kick shootout against China in the World Cup, Brandi
Chastain has entered the national lexicon as an answer on ``Who
Wants to be a Millionaire'' and a question to the finalists in the
Junior Miss America pageant. The pageant contestants criticized
Chastain, but she said she had no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not unhappy I did it,'' she said. ``It was a liberating
moment for myself and I hope it was a liberating experience for
other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Five reserves from the World Cup team have been dropped from the
pool of Olympic players _ goalkeepers Saskia Webber and Tracy
Ducar, midfielder Tiffany Roberts, forward Danielle Fotopoulos and,
most notably, midfielder Tisha Venturini, who scored two goals on
four shots in the World Cup. Of the younger players brought in, the
most significant has been goalkeeper Siri Mullinix, who has started
in Scurry's absence and has performed assertively in patroling the
penalty area and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got depth at every position that we've never had
before,'' said Heinrichs, who coached the past four years at the
University of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Scurry, Overbeck and Akers are expected back with the team this
month, but Akers remains the biggest question mark. At 34, she
continues to suffer from chronic fatigue syndrome and is recovering
from surgery to repair a dislocated shoulder. She has not played
with the team since the World Cup, and Lorrie Fair has assumed her
spot in defensive midfield.
</P>
<P>
   Elite players can take significant time off and still retain
their skills, Heinrichs said, which Akers has done in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our hope that she can do that again,'' Heinrichs said.
``On the other hand, she battles chronic fatigue and she hasn't
been with the team in 11 months. That's like Steve Young taking a
year off and jumping back in in the middle of the season when the
49ers are 6-5 and making a playoff run. That's a concern. But
Michelle certainly has a presence just being on the field. There's
value in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Her shoulder surgery in April was complicated by a fracture and
nerve damage, Akers said. She will not be completely healed for the
Olympics but will be healthy enough to play, she said. Akers also
struggled to regain her energy after the World Cup and even
considered retirement in early April. In a way, the shoulder
surgery restored her motivation, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel the fire is back,'' Akers said. ``I've trained my fanny
off. My health is good. I'm confident that, if given the chance to
play in, I can be a starter for the team.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Apprehension about Heinrichs as coach began to dissolve in
March, when the team traveled to a tournament in Portugal.
Heinrichs got to know the players, they got to know her. The day
before the final against Norway, she had the team play an amusing
game of soccer golf, complete with props and a team manager who
carried a tray of sparkling water around the course as if she were
a waiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony was great,'' defender Kate Sobrero said of DiCicco, who
led the team to victory in the 1996 Olympics and the 1999 World
Cup. ``He took this team farther than anyone ever had. But change
makes you better. It's good to have April. She wants you to take
risks and gives you the freedom to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinrichs, who is 36 and a native of Littleton, Colo., is a
seminal figure in American soccer, the first woman elected to the
sport's national hall of fame. She was captain of the American team
that won the inaugural Women's World Cup in China in 1991, playing
forward with Akers and Carin Gabarra in an alignment known as the
triple-edged sword, fronting a relentless attack that outscored the
opposition 74 goals to 5 during qualifying and the final round of
the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``April set the foundation for this team,'' Foudy said. ``All
the principles we live by _ the work rate, the mentality, the
teamwork, all the things that have made us successful _ stem from
her days as captain.''
</P>
<P>
   Anson Dorrance, who recruited Heinrichs to the University of
North Carolina and later made her captain of the national team,
frequently tells the story of how Heinrichs upset the upperclass
players at Carolina with her ferocious play as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you going to do about April?'' one player asked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clone her?'' he thought to himself.
</P>
<P>
   She became a star by racing through cultural red lights that
hindered women from being overly aggressive on the soccer field and
by dispelling the conventional wisdom that women had difficulty
competing against friends for fear of destroying their personal
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was driven to compete, driven to want to win, and the
consequences never occurred to me,'' Heinrichs said. ``I didn't
feel constricted by social norms or constrained by criticism. In
fact, I felt the opposite. I felt my acceptance as a person came
through my athleticism. It wasn't until I was 22 or 23 that I
separated my athletic identity from my personal identity and
realized they weren't tied in.''
</P>
<P>
   Foudy, who played four seasons with Heinrichs on the national
team, said she had never met so competitive a person.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were on the road, on one of our first trips, and we were
playing Pictionary,'' Foudy said. ``I was on her team, and she was
screaming: `Draw faster! What is it you're drawing, I can't tell!'
She was intent on winning this freaking game as if her life
depended on it. On the field, I knew what she was like, but this
was a whole new level. Obsessed with winning Pictionary.''
</P>
<P>
   It is in this aggressive image that Heinrichs wants to mold the
national team for its run at an Olympic gold medal, bringing an
attacking style that she likens to the Phi Slama Jama days of
basketball at the University of Houston. It was the way the
Americans played during her own days on the national team.
</P>
<P>
   ``At practice, we used to pick teams and play, and my first pick
would always be April,'' Foudy said. ``I didn't care if she had two
broken legs, a straight jacket, crutches, I'd take her first. Even
if she couldn't play, she'd be on the sidelines screaming to get
everyone going.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
