<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, July 3, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A complex of thunderstorms will ignite across the eastern Great
Lakes Monday morning as a jet stream disturbance intercepts a humid
air mass. These storms will then march east, nearing the Northeast
and Middle Atlantic seaboards around dusk. Some of the storms have
damaging winds, but the most disruptive character of the storms
will be heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeast will be partly sunny and humid. As the sun heats
the ground, ascending currents of moistened air will cause
billowing clouds to form, some of which will produce thunderstorms.
Storms will be most numerous in south Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Humid air streaming north from the Gulf of Mexico will fuel
afternoon thunderstorms over the western Plains while cool and
unsettled weather affects the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: THUNDERSTORM RHYTHMS
</P>
<P>
   Before dawn on Sunday, strong thunderstorms erupted in
Minnesota. Unlike many thunderstorms, these were not energized by
solar heating. The key to these storms were the rhythms of the
moisture-laden wind a half-mile above the ground. During the day,
turbulent motions mixing the lower part of the atmosphere cause the
5000-foot winds to be slowed by friction. When the sun's energy is
lost, a shallower layer is mixed, allowing the 5000-foot winds to
be unfettered by friction. These faster winds were able to supply
the moisture vital to the night storms.
</P>
</TEXT>
