<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION _ MEXICO CITY _ Mexicans went to the polls
Sunday for a historic presidential election that could end the
71-year reign of the Institutional Revolutionary Party. (Ferriss,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Polls close at 7 p.m. EDT. An initial story should move
about 8 p.m. EDT, with a first update around 10 p.m. EDT and later
updates as warranted.
</P>
<P>
   No meaningful returns are expected Sunday night. Exit polls will
be released Sunday evening, but their reliability is in doubt. It
is likely that the Cox story will focus on turnout and how that
could affect the result, and whether
</P>
<P>
   the vote was conducted in a free and fair manner.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ELECTION-BORDER _ CIUDAD JUAREZ, Mexico _ Reaction from this
border city as Mexicans come back across the border to vote.
Developing. (Harmon, Austin American-Statesman). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move in advance on the NYT Wire.
</P>
<P>
   ATTN EDs: In order to move an early version of the story, we
will try to line up companies doing credible exit polling for the
outcome. But an official tally of 40 percent is not expected until
midnight EDT.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CARTER _ MEXICO CITY _ The Institutional Revolutionary
Party's long history of political dominance has both advantages and
disadvantages in Mexico's election, former President Jimmy Carter
said in a one-on-one interview as he
</P>
<P>
   visited polling places Sunday. Carter acknowledged that PRI
officials were using the government's powers to pressure voters,
but said the party's long record also left it vulnerable to the
people's dissatisfactions. (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moving about 6 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TERRACE-COLLAPSE - The parties had just started warming up when
the music stopped at 4:45 p.m. Saturday. A terrace overlooking Lake
Erie at the Lonz Winery, crowded with over 100 people, collapsed in
an instant, 18 feet into an old wine cellar, killing one Columbus
man and sending at least 75 people to the hospital. ``They came
running up and said, 'Stop playing, the terrace just collapsed,' ``
said Larry Read, who has played the piano for revelers at the
winery for 12 years. (Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   MODERN-SOUTH _ RALEIGH, N.C. _ Stroll the marble _ or, depending
where you are, reinforced concrete _ walls of any Southern capitol
in this turn-of-the-century year, and you will notice many things
that appear untouched by the new era. The past few decades have
witnessed revolutionary changes in the racial and gender makeup of
Southern legislatures and the awakening of the Republican Party in
the South. A generation of Southern governors _ often with the
presidency as their ultimate goal _ have pushed impatiently to
modernize their state governments. (Baxter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SHARKS _ MOBILE, Ala. _Two men were attacked and one lost an
arm. A few days later, a tour boat was rammed. Shark phobia is
building on the Gulf Coast. Some experts blame the drought. We talk
with scientists, coastal residents and possibly one of the victims
for a Fourth of July boo story. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SOLARMAX _ The northern lights, including rare red colored
auroras, have been seen as far south as the Carolinas. In Alaska
and Greenland, radio frequencies used by aviators and mariners have
been hit by sudden fadeouts. NASA, worried that unusual heating of
the Earth's atmosphere was dragging down its space station, had to
use the space shuttle to boost it to a higher altitude. It's the
summer of the hyperactive sun, Cycle 23. Every 11 years or so, the
storms that rage across the surface of the sun reach a frenzied
peak, flinging charged particles and hot gases into space with
predictable _ and sometimes unpredictable _ consequences for the
increasingly wired world on the third rock from the sun. ``Solar
activity is expected to peak in the next month or two,'' says
Ernest Hildner, director of the government's space weather center
in Colorado. ``Every cycle is different, but there is no question
that our society is more vulnerable now than it ever has been.''
With great color pix. Two charts. And web addresses. (Toner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SMALL-TOWN-DIVERSITY _ ATLANTA _ White people in Decatur, Ga.
want more black neighbors. They also want more neighbors who are
poor. Really. Those are the sentiments behind a proposed strategic
plan for the city's next decade. The report, scheduled for a vote
by city commissioners July 17, is based on comments made during a
series of public meetings. Most of the people at the meetings were
well-to-do whites. Over and over, they said that they want to save
the ethnic and economic diversity that gives their city its
markedly off-beat beat. (Hill, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KID-LAWYER _ Having just seen his client convicted, the young
lawyer left the courtroom and walked into yet another body blow. A
stern-faced juror in the hallway told him, ``We thought you could
have done more work. You stumbled sometimes.'' ``Well,'' sighed the
blond-haired lawyer, ``It's my first jury trial.'' Joshua Earwood
isn't smooth yet. But that's not surprising. A few weeks ago he was
a law clerk in the Bartow County courthouse, assisting the judges,
digging into case law, at times feeling like the office gofer
wearing a ``Junior Lawyer'' badge. (Schneider, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   WORKFORCE-DIVERSITY _ ATLANTA _ Georgia Gulf's management looks
different from its Atlanta peers: More than 40 percent of the
chemical company's 187 managers are black. No other Atlanta-based
company that provided data on the racial makeup of its work force
to the Journal-Constitution comes close in terms of management
diversity. The nearest is the Cotton States group of companies,
which includes Cotton States Life Insurance. A quarter of the
group's managers are black. (McNaughton, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OLDER-WORKERS _ ATLANTA _ Miriam Dennis-Stinson taught home
economics for more than 37 years, 34 of which were in the Atlanta
school system. ``It would have been 38 had I not taken maternity
time,'' she says. It really doesn't matter how you calculate it.
When she retired on June 9 from Kennedy Middle School in southwest
Atlanta, you might expect that after that much time on the job,
Dennis-Stinson would, well, retire. Hardly. Dennis-Stinson, 60, a
self-proclaimed ``jill of all trades'' is as busy as ever. When
she's not painting the exterior of her home, laying tile in her
kitchen or installing a suspended ceiling in her basement _ all of
which are recent projects of this ardent do-it-yourselfer _ she is
honing her entrepreneurial skills as a seamstress. (Mallory,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   STOCK-MARKET-DEBATE _ ATLANTA _ When the Nasdaq composite index
dropped like a lead dot-com from its all-time high in March,
Princeton University Press moved up the publication date of Robert
J. Shiller's book by nearly a month to April 3. The book is
``Irrational Exuberance,'' a scholarly and foreboding forecast that
the common stocks we love so much are headed for a prolonged bear
market over the next 10 to 20 years. The book became a best seller
and Shiller an instant celebrity, appearing on TV and in the
financial press, where he defended his views with quiet assurance.
His basic argument is that common stocks have risen in price to
levels that are unsupported _ and unsupportable _ by the profit
prospects of U.S. corporations. The other side of that argument is
another book, ``Dow 36,000,'' which was published in September and
also became a best seller. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Lacy Elwood has a gripe with the
media. And here's what she's going to do about it: She's going to
improve it from within. Lauren Read has an answer to those who
gripe that ``government is the problem.'' Stop griping, she'll say,
and be a part of it. (Young, Waco Tribune-Herald.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ The Peavine Watershed Alliance is only
3 years old, but Georgia water experts already are calling it a
model for solving the state's water pollution problems. To clean
the Chattahoochee, you've got to prevent stuff from all those
little creeks and streams that flow into the river from ever
getting there, says Frank Carubba, a state expert in runoff
pollution. ``A local watershed effort is the foundation for
everything,'' he says. (Ezzard, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   GLOUCESTER _ GLOUCESTER, Mass. _ This time around, the people of
Gloucester are praying for a big wave _ of tourists. Many in this
small and rugged blue-collar fishing town are hoping to cash in on
``The Perfect Storm.'' There's The Perfect Tour, a quick escorted
venture through the town depicted in both the best-selling book and
George Clooney's new film, the Perfect T-Shirt and a bold, if not
perfect, new sign for one of the town's best-known entities, The
Gorton's Fisherman. Pegged to the opening weekend of the big summer
movie. (Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WIZARD-OZ _ Turner Classic Movies is putting up an unusual
showing of ``The Wizard of Oz'' on Monday. It will be uncut with no
commercials. What's unique: PINK FLOYD's ``Dark Side of the Moon,''
on the SAP channel. The phenomenon, in which the entire album seems
to perfectly fit with scenes in the movie, can be emulated by those
whose cable carriers aren't carrying the SAP channel by getting
your copy of ``Dark Side...,'' ready and unpausing the disc as the
MGM lion roars for a third time. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLES
</P>
<P>
   RV-LIFE _ WACO, Texas _ When Julie Swanson's husband talked
about buying a recreational vehicle six years ago, she wasn't too
excited about the idea. The couple had never been avid travelers
and they already had a home to maintain. ``I thought, nah, we
didn't need anything like that,'' she said. But after spending time
with folks at an RV ``jamboree'' who cooked and ate together,
played games and reminisced about all the places they'd traveled,
she quickly changed her mind. (Allmon, Waco Tribune Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   TENNIS-FASHION - Luv 'em, or hate 'em, those clingy little
dresses that some of the top young stars of women's tennis are
wearing at Wimbledon probably won't be overwhelming a court near
you, but you may see one here or there. Those who closely follow
the game, and monitor the on-court fashions of the Williams sisters
(Venus and Serena) and Anna Kournikova, say most women wouldn't
dare wearing the equivalent of an oversized tank top during a
match. And the supply of such outfits isn't that great anyway.
(Walton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   BBO-VLADIMIR _ A feature on Montreal outfielder Vladimir
Guerrero, one of the biggest stars in baseball you've never heard
of. He's fourth in All-Star voting and will be a starter if Sammy
Sosa is traded to an AL team before the game. (Schlabach, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TOUR DE FRANCE
</P>
<P>
