<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBRIGHT-LEGACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADELEINE ALBRIGHT: HER ISSUES AND HER LEGACY
</HEADLINE>
  By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ How does Madeleine Albright want to be remembered
as secretary of state? As Albright zoomed from country to country,
region to region _ four hours here, 36 hours there in nine days _
the legacy question was never far away.
</P>
<P>
   Part of her mark in history will be as the first woman to hold
the post, a role she relishes. In Seoul, South Korea, last week,
she emerged from her plane in citrus yellow, a bold look she said
was intended as a metaphor for President Kim Dae Jung's ``sunshine
policy'' with North Korea. In Berlin, she was not too shy to tell
an audience that she was grateful for cosmetics to help disguise
her exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   Albright has also taken on issues that others may have
considered too soft, like the empowerment of women in developing
countries and Internet literacy in nations under dictatorships.
</P>
<P>
   But as Albright traveled from Beijing to Seoul and on to Warsaw
in late June, with an interlude in the Middle East and a drive
through the Brandenburg Gate, it was clear that, in the last six
months of her term, she wants to concentrate on her vision of
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Democracy, she said in Warsaw, was her ``lodestar.'' And to
emphasize the message, she intends to stay on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're going to do is keep traveling around the world and
have 36-hour days, so six months is nine months,'' she told
reporters as her plane headed home last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   She has already visited 82 countries since she took office in
January 1997, a record for any secretary of state. She plans two
trips to Asia this month, and perhaps another in the fall,
including a possible stop in Nepal, where she has never been.
</P>
<P>
   Albright says her travel shows how the job of secretary of state
has changed since the end of the Cold War. Her predecessors, she
says, concentrated largely on the Soviet Union and the Middle East.
Since then, there has been an explosion of new countries _ 189 in
the United Nations at last count.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, foreign policy issues, Albright likes to say, have
expanded beyond traditional questions of arms control and balance
of power to international business corruption and illegal
immigration. She feels obliged, she suggests, to push U.S.
interests to new corners of the world. And for Albright, a child of
Central Europe whose Czechoslovak parents fled the Communists and
arrived in the United States in 1949 to begin a new life, the
nurturing of democracy is a prime interest. (As she bounced from
culture to culture on this latest trip, she appeared most at home
chatting into the late evening over coffee in Warsaw's old town).
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of her stay in Poland was a conference that
pulled together 107 democracies. But the gathering _ born very much
of Albright's guiding hand _ revealed undertones of resentment at
American hegemony.
</P>
<P>
   This was most stridently expressed by France, which refused to
sign the closing statement. But there were criticisms elsewhere,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Roth, the executive director of Human Rights Watch in
New York, whose organization was present in Warsaw, says the
promotion of democracy by the United States is useful but is done
in such a way that it ``fuels growing hostility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is increasingly viewed as a government that
preaches to the rest of the world but is unwilling to be bound by
international standards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Albright's efforts, Washington has failed to sign U.N.
accords on an international criminal court or on the control of
land mines _ largely because the administration and Congress want
to make American military personnel immune from international laws
imposed on others, and Albright failed to beat out the Pentagon in
internal administration debates.
</P>
<P>
   Albright seems to believe that she does best abroad, riding
imperial motorcades and speaking unchallenged from a broad variety
of venues. There, she is away from the political sniping of
Congress and day-to-day management from the National Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   She finished this last tour of the world in Berlin with a speech
on democracy in the Balkans, which dealt with Serbia as a last
holdout of repression.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary began her term rebuking the harshest of dictators,
Saddam Hussein. She was one of the strongest advocates within the
administration for military strikes and economic sanctions against
him, but the Iraqi leader remains in power.
</P>
<P>
   Since then _ before, during and after last year's Kosovo war _
she has paid much attention to another repressive leader, President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia. A year after the NATO air
campaign, he, too, remains in power _ much to the evident
disappointment of Albright.
</P>
<P>
   In Berlin, she reiterated that Milosevic belongs in The Hague,
home of an international tribunal that indicted him on charges of
war crimes. ``If Milosevic cared at all about the rule of law,''
she added, ``he would turn himself over to The Hague.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he will go,'' she said as she headed home, offering
no clear scheme to achieve that goal beyond what she called a
combination of people working inside and outside Serbia, and her
opinion that his government is increasingly brittle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patience is what is necessary,'' she said. ``The calendar is
not what we're looking at.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright is keenly aware of her own calendar, however. She was
asked whether the Balkans, which have consumed much of her time,
would remain a top priority for the next administration. ``It
depends on who gets elected,'' she replied, adding, ``No matter
where I am, we're not going to forget them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
