<HEADER>
A1218 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NOTEBOO     07-02 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAFTER LIKES HIS CHANCES WITH A REPAIRED SHOULDER  
 THE SERIOUSNESS OF MCENROE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ During a long winter, there were moments
when Patrick Rafter's surgically repaired shoulder deceived him.
After arthroscopic surgery in October to repair a tear in his
rotator cuff, he went through a series of optimistic strides that
were routinely dashed by a setback.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't sure, but perhaps the tennis career was over for
Rafter, the two-time U.S. Open winner with the screaming-teen
following. Rafter thought that if this season was too much of a
struggle, he might retire. But after all the rehabilitation, and
all the time he was forced to confront his tennis mortality, Rafter
has snapped back to life. When play resumes on Monday at Wimbledon,
the 12th-seeded Rafter will face Thomas Johansson in the Round of
16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize I have a chance here again,'' Rafter said. ``Now,
I'm starting to play good tennis again. The shoulder's fine. Makes
me excited to be out here. I still haven't had a big five-setter,
yet. Not that I want one, but it still really hasn't been tested
out. But I'm confident it will be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not so sure after his surgery. Just over a year ago,
Rafter began to feel the pain creep into his shoulder during the
French Open. It worsened at Wimbledon as he advanced to the
semifinals. By the United States Open, it was unbearable, and he
withdrew in the fifth set of his first-round match. But after
toiling through rehabilitation, he feels confident in wielding his
big serve. Still, in the back of his mind, there is a clock
ticking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just pretty happy out here doing what I'm doing and trying
to enjoy the most of it right now,'' the 27-year old Australian
said. ``There's no guarantee the shoulder will be ready or fit in
three years, so I'm doing everything I can, all the strength work.
I'm at the gym all the time. I have a lot of other little exercises
I have to do every day. If I can continue that, then hopefully I
can get through another couple years.'' headline  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In one of the more intriguing matches on Monday, the resilient
Jennifer Capriati will play the second-seeded Lindsay Davenport in
the Round of 16. They represent just two of the Americans who have
survived the women's draw.
</P>
<P>
   After failing to fare well at the French Open, the American
women are dominating Wimbledon. The list also includes Venus and
Serena Williams, Monica Seles, Lisa Raymond, Kristina Brandi and
Lilia Osterloh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been really great,'' Davenport said. ``There is always a
level of players, it seems, that always get forgotten because
they're not at the top, like Osterloh, Brandi and even Raymond to a
certain point. So it's been a very good tournament. It's nice to
see everyone still around here.''
</P>
<P>
   THE SERIOUS MCENROE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the day of rest at Wimbledon, John McEnroe and Bjorn Borg
stirred up echoes from the past when they played in a charity event
Sunday. In 1980, Borg defeated McEnroe for the Wimbledon title
after an epic fourth-set tie-breaker. Sunday, McEnroe used his deft
touch to come away with a 6-3, 7-6 (5) victory. Typical McEnroe, he
yelled out, ``You can't be serious,'' when the referee delayed
suspending the match because of a 15-minute drizzle.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-00 1807EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
