<DOCNO> NYT20000702.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1221 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TV-LOCALNEWS-MEDIA-2T     07-02 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LOCALNEWS-MEDIA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CHICAGO, TV NEWS GOES BACK TO BASICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Something strange has happened to the 10 p.m. newscast on
Chicago's Channel 2, WBBM-TV.
</P>
<P>
   It was in February that the health correspondent, Dr. Michael
Breen, stopped doing nightly health reports with titles like
``Potentially Deadly Fruit'' (grapefruit) and ``The Secret to a
Good Sex Life'' (exercise), to focus on topics like risks
associated with early prostate cancer screening (unnecessary
treatment). And the weatherman, Steve Baskerville, toned down his
chatty banter in favor of shorter meteorological reports.
</P>
<P>
   One night last month, when the other local newscasts opened with
live reports from a neighborhood where the power had briefly gone
out, WBBM devoted most of its early minutes to an accord between
the Environmental Protection Agency and chemical manufacturers,
limiting the use of a dangerous insecticide.
</P>
<P>
   And last Wednesday, when the other 10 p.m. programs led with
stories about a nonfatal shooting of an off-duty police officer and
Elian Gonzalez's return to Cuba, the Channel 2 newscast began with
a lengthy report on the day's Supreme Court decisions, including
one to strike down a law banning a controversial form of abortion.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the management at WBBM-TV has thrown out the local
news playbook of pizazz and sensationalism used at TV stations
throughout the country and replaced it with an on-air clinic in
no-frills journalism.
</P>
<P>
   And if there is a gimmick in all of this, it is that there is no
gimmick. For Channel 2, the CBS-owned station in Chicago, the
restructured news program represents not so much a bold move in
journalism as an attempt to increase revenue and crawl out of last
place in its local news market.
</P>
<P>
   But it also casts the national spotlight once again on Chicago,
the third-largest television market in the country _ where Jerry
Springer, Siskel and Ebert and Oprah Winfrey were made famous. The
no-gimmicks strategy is being studied across the nation by news
directors and station managers, who have sought ways to stem the
loss of viewers of their own local news programs, which can account
for as much as a third of a station's advertising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Some reasons for dwindling local news audiences are obvious:
with 24-hour news channels and information available over the
Internet at any time, the news market has simply become more
competitive. Yet there is a growing sense in local TV news that
another factor behind the ratings decline is a perception among
viewers that the newscasts have been gradually dumbed down.
</P>
<P>
   The people who devised the new 10 p.m. model at WBBM, where
ratings for the late evening news have plunged 70 percent since the
late 1980's and are far behind its competitors' on the NBC and ABC
stations, share that view. They set about developing a new 10 p.m.
program last year with an eye toward righting what they saw as the
wrongs of local TV journalism, hoping to prove that higher-quality
news would draw a higher-quality audience _ better educated, more
affluent _ worth more to advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it is unclear if the experiment is working. Although the
program's ratings rose initially, they later dropped. But whether
their effort succeeds or fails, the station's journalists say the
reward has been in the journey, which has involved heavy doses of
journalistic soul-searching about local TV news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we had lost our way, and we disappointed a lot of
people who counted on us,'' Carol Marin, the program's anchor, said
in an interview at her Chicago office. ``We stopped telling you
things that were particularly important and started just telling
you anything that we thought maybe offered you a little bit of eye
candy.''
</P>
<P>
   Marin, 51, said she believed that the quality of local news had
deteriorated gradually in recent decades. As entertainment
programming costs went up, news became a comparatively stronger
profit generator for station managers, who with the help of
consultants devised stunts and gimmicks to draw viewers.
</P>
<P>
   One such stunt, in fact, led Marin to leave her previous job, in
1997, as the lead anchor at WMAQ, Chicago's NBC station. In what
she considered a clear ploy to lure viewers, WMAQ hired Jerry
Springer, host of the daytime talk show, as an on-air commentator
for the newscast she co-anchored. After nearly 20 years at the
station, she quit in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Marin moved to WBBM, initially as a part-time correspondent
focusing on investigative pieces not only for the local news, but
also for the CBS network's new prime-time magazine show ``Public
Eye with Bryant Gumbel.'' She said at the time that she had sworn
off anchoring for good.
</P>
<P>
   But when the ratings for WBBM's late evening news program
slipped even further in May 1999, the station manager, Hank Price,
persuaded Marin to take the 10 p.m. anchor slot by promising that
she would be able to shape the local program as she saw fit.
</P>
<P>
   It was an offer she could not refuse. Along with station
executives and news department staffers, Marin set about devising a
wholly new 10 p.m. broadcast. She convened dozens of meetings over
six months in which they debated how news should be defined and how
it should be conveyed to viewers. The meetings became almost like
group therapy sessions, according to station staff members.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the group concluded that the conventional local news
format long used for Channel 2's late evening newscast was
unacceptable. So they decided that the revised 10 o'clock news
would not follow any rigid formula.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were questions that we asked like, `What do viewers want
from weather?''' said Pat Costello, the new WBBM news director.
``If there's the threat of a big storm, they want to know
everything. Otherwise, they want to know `How hot? How cold?' and
`What's it going to be like for the next five days?'''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Baskerville, the weatherman, was told to shorten his reports,
although he was assured they would grow in length and prominence in
cases of severe weather. Tim Weigel, the sportscaster, was given
similar orders.
</P>
<P>
   Another philosophical question arose: If an abandoned warehouse
is burning brightly near the highway, making for great photography,
but no one is hurt and traffic has not been affected, is it a
story? Maybe, Marin said. But, she added, ``You don't stick a
reporter out there in front of it, eight hours later, and say,
`There was an unbelievable fire here earlier today where nobody got
hurt and nothing was lost.'''
</P>
<P>
   Breen, the health reporter, and staff members agreed that the
nightly health reports were among the worst offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd say, `Coming up: The fruit that kills you,''' Breen
recalled. ``And, it would be, `grapefruit _ if you combine it with
certain medications.''' The solution, they agreed, was for Breen to
present reports less frequently but on weightier issues.
</P>
<P>
   The team also decided the station would produce longer stories
and pass over those considered inconsequential. And any banter
between personalities that was not spontaneous was out, as were
plugs for sponsors or network shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among the things that I said I couldn't ever do again,'' Marin
said, ``is to say, `Meet the real guy behind tonight's movie.'''
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, there would be no closing shots of animals _ or,
as the staff mantra had it, ``no water-skiing squirrels.''
</P>
<P>
   On paper, at least, it was a completely new format for
television news. And Price signed off on the plan. With CBS so far
back in third place, there was nothing to lose. And here was a
program he could sell to advertisers as being geared to a more
upscale, sophisticated crowd. The sales staff did just that,
executives said, lifting the rate for a 30-second spot nearly 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   When the revamped format was introduced on Feb. 7, Marin, as a
lone female anchor, stood in marked contrast to the rival network
affiliates' male-female anchor teams. Her competitors led their
newscasts with stories about a water main break earlier that day in
downtown Chicago. Marin's newscast all but ignored it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she opened with a report about the deposed city
treasurer, Miriam Santons, who had spoken that day with reporters
for the first time since a judge had reversed her conviction on
charges of fraud and attempted extortion.
</P>
<P>
   For the first month, viewer reaction was positive. According to
Nielsen Media Research, the television ratings service, the program
was watched in 214,700 homes in February, a sweeps month in which
stations closely gauge ratings to set advertising rates. But while
the audience was 5 percent larger than it had been a year earlier,
viewership was still far smaller than for the 10 p.m. news programs
on ABC (474,295 households) and NBC (349,563).
</P>
<P>
   Yet, while there was a falloff among older viewers of Marin's
program, its audience of people between 25 and 54 _ who matter most
to the advertisers that sponsor news _ increased 33 percent over
the year-earlier period. And viewership among more affluent viewers
was also up for February.
</P>
<P>
   The ratings upturn seemed to be temporary, however. During the
May sweeps period, the program's viewership declined 13 percent in
total households, compared with the prior May, and was down by 25
percent among viewers in the 25-to-54 age range, according to
Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
   The WBBM approach has come under fire from some media critics
and, not surprisingly, from competitors, who have taken to calling
it ``PBS on CBS.'' One of the newscast's more prominent critics is
Bill Kurtis, a former WBBM anchor who is now host of
``Investigative Reports'' on the A&AMP;E cable network.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Kurtis criticized the program for failing to
report all of the news of the day. ``I think they made a mistake,''
he said. ``You have to cover the news or you're a talk show.''
</P>
<P>
   At WBBM, Price said he intended to stay with the format adopted
for Marin's 10 p.m. program, which, he said, still needed time to
catch on with viewers.
</P>
<P>
   And it seems the people who matter, the people who buy ads, are
willing to stick with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really holding out,'' said Ross S. Currie, local broadcast
director of the Chicago branch of TN Media, a media buying firm.
``I really think 'BBM will come around.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Currie said he expected the ratings to go up soon, with
some help from CBS' new hit program in prime time: ``Survivor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
