<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIDOWS-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WIDOWS': SOME LAUGHS, BUT LEAVES AN EMPTY FEELING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By DAVID DeWITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Four husband-hunting women. Three wife-seeking men.
Guess who is going to be disappointed?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dance on Widows' Row'' is a comic yarn about a group of
North Carolina neighbors who have bad luck with husbands. Their men
keep dying. The widows are glad to have the pensions, but they miss
the companionship and hate the gossip that keeps their street off
limits to the town's menfolk.
</P>
<P>
   Magnolia (Barbara Montgomery) has had enough. She invites some
bachelors _ ``I did my homework. Ain't a dog in the bunch'' _ to
join her and her fellow widows at her home for a romance-sparking
party.
</P>
<P>
   Cupid shows up. So does the Grim Reaper. That makes the lusty
widows sly suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dance on Widows' Row'' is a mild farce, and it drew plenty
of hoots and hollers at the performance I saw. But between each
hoot and holler were anxious moments spent waiting for the next
laugh. The cast seemed most anxious of all, because when they
couldn't play to the audience, they didn't have much to do.
</P>
<P>
   The production is directed by its playwright, Samm-Art Williams,
who has earned respect for plays like ``Home.'' The old-fashioned
style of ``Widows' Row'' has its place, and it's good to see comic
parts for older actors. But it's uncomfortable to watch mature
performers make leering faces and Viagra jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' production, by the New Federal Theater at the Henry
Street Settlement's Harry De Jur Playhouse doesn't offer enough
character to fill out its caricatures. Elizabeth Van Dyke offers
the broadest and least substantial performance as Annie, the
churchgoer who becomes a temptress. She and sometimes the rest of
the cast seem to flaunt the production's loud, empty feel.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Thomas and especially Jack Landron commit to the play's
comic heights, Elain Graham has moments with an entertaining bite,
and Montgomery anchors the action well when the play is allowed to
relax. But that's not often, because it is desperate to yuk it up
and hope the audience is paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   Felix E. Cochren's naturalistic set, Evelyn Nelson's more
extreme costumes and Shirley Prendergast's cool lighting combine
for a mixed effect that doesn't help the production.
</P>
<P>
   At moments, the widows of this play seem destined to discover a
sort of woman-affirming unity, but those moments are unfortunately
too fleeting.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE DANCE ON WIDOWS' ROW' Written and directed by Samm-Art
Williams; production stage manager, Jacqui Casto; set by Felix E.
Cochren; lighting by Shirley Prendergast; costumes by Evelyn
Nelson; sound by Sean O'Halloran; technical director, Green Turtle
Productions; property mistress, Ebony Loney. Presented by the New
Federal Theater, Woodie King Jr., producing director. At the Harry
De Jur Playhouse, 466 Grand St., Lower East Side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   With: Barbara Montgomery (Magnolia Ellis), Marie Thomas (Simone
Jackson), Elizabeth Van Dyke (Annie Talbot), Elain Graham (Lois
Miller), Adam Wade (Deacon Hudson), Jack Landron (Newly Benson) and
Ed Wheeler (Randolph Spears).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
