u e BC-DANCE-REVIEW-ABT-NYT     07-02 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-REVIEW-ABT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO EXAMPLES REVEAL THE GLORY OF PURE CLASSICAL BALLET
</HEADLINE>
 By JENNIFER DUNNING  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``La Bayadere'' was created in 1877. ``Theme and
Variations'' came seven decades later. But the two works are at
heart shining examples of the great glory of pure classical ballet.
And the dancers of American Ballet Theater communicated that truth
with joyous clarity in performances at the Metropolitan Opera House
in New York on Thursday and Friday nights respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Paloma Herrera offered an interestingly double-faceted portrait
of Nikiya, the frail young temple dancer whose doomed love for the
warrior Solor forms the narrative of ``La Bayadere.'' Herrera's
pliant torso subtly suggested Indian classical dancing, each soft
twist and tilt registering love, sorrow and anger in Marius
Petipa's tale of exotic India, glowingly restaged by Natalia
Makarova.
</P>
<P>
   In the famous Kingdom of the Shades pas de deux in the second
act, Herrera became a grand ballerina. Stretched tall, she surged
authoritatively through the scene's fast turns and balances, though
her occasional snapping finishes distracted from the flow of her
dancing. The redoubtable Julio Bocca was her Solor, with Gillian
Murphy icy and powerful as the treacherous Gamzatti.
</P>
<P>
   This has been Bocca's season. The purity and infectious
excitement of his dancing promise to linger long in the memory, as
once again he stepped into a role vacated by an injured dancer,
this time Angel Corella. Special praise must go to the corps in the
second act, whose dancing rightly embodied Baudelaire's ``luxe,
calme et volupte.'' Herman Cornejo stood out for the welcome
fluency he brought to the hard-dancing Bronze Idol. David Lamarche
conducted the Minkus score, performed with enjoyable panache.
</P>
<P>
   Joaquin De Luz is often cast as rapscallion characters whose
cheekiness sometimes conceals the considerable technical demands of
the choreography. De Luz got his chance at elegance in a role debut
as the lead male in ``Theme and Variations,'' George Balanchine's
glittering, sweeping reinvention of Petipa's classicism. A little
short in height for such a part, De Luz seemed to grow in stature
as he negotiated challenges like a fiendish-looking series of air
turns with ease and solemn grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley Tuttle brought an unexpected but welcome warmth to her
impressively danced ballerina role. Ermanno Florio conducted the
Tchaikovsky score.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
