<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. INVESTIGATING ADVISER TO KAZAKHSTAN
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors are investigating whether an American trade
consultant funneled millions of dollars in payments from major oil
companies like Phillips Petroleum and Mobil to Kazakhstan officials
who are his clients, according to a Justice Department document.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Justice Department asked Swiss authorities for
help in investigating the financial activities of James Giffen, a
prominent consultant for trade deals in Russia and former Soviet
republics.
</P>
<P>
   3 EXECUTIVES TO LEAD ORACLE DAY TO DAY
</P>
<P>
   After the abrupt resignation of Oracle Corp.'s president,
Raymond Lane, the day-to-day operation of the company is now in the
hands of three executives: Gary Bloom, 38, Oracle's top marketer
and executive vice president; Jeffrey Henley, 54, the chief
financial officer; and Safra Catz, 38, a former investment banker,
now an executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE GROCERS STILL FACE HURDLES
</P>
<P>
   The announcement last week that Webvan had agreed to pay $1.2
billion for HomeGrocer.com showed that online grocers are realizing
that there is strength through scale but that significant kinks in
the business continue to present big challenges to its long-term
viability.
</P>
<P>
   NETEASE DAMPENS SPIRITS IN CHINA
</P>
<P>
   The poor debut on Friday of the Chinese Internet company
Netease.com _ whose American depository receipts opened at $15.50
but fell to $12.125 on Nasdaq _ has sent shudders through China's
Internet entrepreneurs, who see an overseas listing as their only
hope.
</P>
<P>
   TWO MORE POINTS IN WEB PRIVACY DEBATE
</P>
<P>
   When the online privacy debate peaked earlier this year, the
watchwords were ``notice'' and ``choice.'' Consumer groups demanded
that online advertising companies give consumers more notice when
tracking their behavior and give them the choice to avoid such
tracking. But two other principles have received scant air time:
giving consumers ``access'' to data collected on them and providing
them with the ``security'' that the data is kept private.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT HONORS ITS ENGINEERS
</P>
<P>
   To reward its brightest technologists, Microsoft plans to
announce a distinguished engineer program on Monday, initially
honoring 16 of the company's best software designers.
</P>
<P>
   CNN BROADENS ONLINE PRESENCE
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by declining ratings during slow news periods, CNN's
parent company, Turner Broadcasting System, announced last week
that it would broaden the network's online presence to include
research tools and more in-depth coverage. The result would be a
wealth of information from a combination of on-air and online
sources. Turner will spend $1.2 billion the next five years to
enlarge its downtown Atlanta headquarters and build and renovate
parts of offices and studios elsewhere in the city.
</P>
<P>
   TELEFONICA BOLSTERS CONTROL OF UNITS
</P>
<P>
   Telefonica, Spain's largest phone operator, has increased
control of its Argentine and Brazilian units after most investors
swapped stock in the units for the company's shares.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. MARKETS CLOSE EARLY MONDAY
</P>
<P>
   The stock market and other financial markets in the United
States will close at 1 p.m. Monday and will be closed Tuesday in
observance of the Fourth of July. Most overseas markets, however,
will be open both days. U.S. markets will reopen on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
