<HEADER>
A1227 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WORLDCOM-EBBERS-2TAKE     07-02 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDCOM-EBBERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: WORLDCOM AND SPRINT LOOK FOR WAYS TO SAVE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most telecommunications experts may see the $115 billion
WorldCom-Sprint merger as having one foot in the grave, but the
companies are not yet ready to declare it dead.
</P>
<P>
   At least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Some people at both WorldCom Inc. and the Sprint Corp. contend
that the deal can be salvaged, despite opposition from regulators
on both sides of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say that it is not 100 percent locked and clearly
over,'' one person close to the companies said over the weekend.
``Over the next few days it will become more clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials from both companies have declined to comment, while
they weigh their options. Reached over the weekend, John Sidgmore,
WorldCom's vice chairman, would say only: ``I believe the company
will be successful with or without Sprint. We have more options
than people think.''
</P>
<P>
   One impetus for keeping the merger on life support may be the
desire of Bernard Ebbers, WorldCom's 58-year-old chief executive,
to make the merger the capstone achievement of the acquisition
strategy he has used for nearly two decades to build WorldCom into
an international power. Otherwise, Ebbers would be left to
contemplate how the deal's rejection by antitrust officials in
Washington and Brussels was the result of the very modus operandi
that brought him so close to the pinnacle.
</P>
<P>
   But the merger die-hards may be unable to prevail, at least
partly because some executives at the two companies differ sharply
on just how they would handle the regulatory challenges.
</P>
<P>
   After the European Commission's top antitrust official said last
Monday he opposed the deal on grounds that it would give WorldCom
too much control of Internet traffic, the companies withdrew the
merger proposal in Europe _ though reserving the option to
re-introduce it in the future. Last Tuesday, the U.S. Justice
Department filed a suit to block the merger, saying it would place
too much of the nation's long-distance market in WorldCom's hands.
</P>
<P>
   The Sprint merger hold-outs are inclined to try fighting the
Justice Department in court, according to people close to the
companies. But WorldCom, contending that a court battle would take
too long to be effective no matter the outcome, is said to be
willing to accede to the Justice Department's demand _ that it sell
Sprint's long-distance and local phone operations, as well as
Sprint's Internet business. That would still give WorldCom what it
wants most: Sprint's extensive wireless network.
</P>
<P>
   But Sprint opposes such a drastic dismembering, which is why
many analysts predict that it may end up seeking a merger partner
that would keep the company largely intact. ``I think they'll be
speaking German soon,'' said Eric Strumingher, a communications
analyst at PaineWebber. He was referring to the German
communications giant Deutsche Telekom's well-known interest in
Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, WorldCom would have trouble promising regulators
that it would dismantle Sprint until it knew how much money the
various units would fetch. And under its deal with Sprint, WorldCom
is constrained from talking to outside companies about splitting
Sprint into pieces.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Ebbers have said in recent days that if the
Sprint deal had gone smoothly, he might have considered it his swan
song, the final act of a spectacular career that would have let him
leave the stage on his own terms. But besides being a
communications titan, Ebbers is also known as a combative, ornery
man _ an executive who would almost certainly not want to go out on
a busted Sprint deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, if we had closed the deal and everything had worked out
perfectly and the stock was at 90 or 100 then maybe he would
leave,'' one person close to WorldCom said over the weekend. ``But
he wouldn't want to go out without things being tied up.
</P>
<P>
   If there is one thing Ebbers has always cared about, it is his
company's stock price. After rising robustly for most of the 1990s,
WorldCom's stock has languished since last year, closing Friday at
$45.875, up $1.8125.
</P>
<P>
   So analysts and people close to the company said Ebbers was
quite likely to take a dramatic step to raise his company's share
price, whether or not the Sprint deal was saved. The most likely
move, according to people close to the company, would be a sale of
most or all of WorldCom's consumer long-distance business, second
in the nation only to AT&AMP;T's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bernie does one thing for sure, which is show Wall
Street that he's really working for the shareholder,'' said
Strumingher, the analyst. ``It's been now almost a year where his
stock has underperformed dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Before acquiring MCI in 1998, WorldCom was hardly in the
consumer business at all. And these days, the consumer
long-distance industry, with its incessant price wars, is often
less profitable than serving business customers.
</P>
<P>
   Because consumers, unlike business customers, do not sign
long-term contracts, the consumer side of the industry can also be
far more volatile. That is why many institutional money managers
are currently wary of investing in companies that have a big
presence in the consumer long-distance business _ a wariness that
has also deflated AT&AMP;T's stock.
</P>
<P>
   So by spinning off all or part of its consumer long-distance
business, WorldCom could boost its growth and, at least as
important, increase the stability and predictability of its
financial results. Of course, regulatory constraints might limit
the pool of potential buyers, since neither AT&AMP;T or any of the Bell
companies would be likely to receive approval to buy WorldCom's
consumer long-distance business even if they wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves at least two likely options for dispatching the
consumer business, according to analysts and people close to
WorldCom. The first is a complete sale of the consumer subscribers
to a financial buyer like Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co., Forstmann
Little &AMP; Co., or Hicks, Muse, Tate &AMP; Furst Inc. WorldCom would
become a wholesale supplier to that unit, providing the network
operation but shedding the marketing costs. One of the buyout
companies could enjoy billions of dollars in cash flow from the
unit, and as a private company it could ignore the stock market's
distaste for the consumer long-distance business.
</P>
<P>
   Another, even more intriguing possibility, would be a sale of a
big stake in the consumer long-distance business to a
consumer-oriented company that could market the service more
efficiently than WorldCom does now. One person close to WorldCom
mentioned, ``people like Disney, Microsoft or AOL'' as potential
partners. The same person, who asked that he not be identified,
estimated that the chance of WorldCom's announcing some sort of
consumer long-distance spin-off in the next six months or so at
between 50 and 80 percent, no matter the fate of the Sprint deal.
</P>
<P>
   Even if such a spin-off becomes the consolation prize of an
aborted Sprint merger, Ebbers would still have to make peace with
the realization that his hard-bargain approach to the
communications industry might have finally caught up with him.
</P>
<P>
   A big reason that the Justice Department has balked at the
WorldCom-Sprint deal is because Ebbers left a bad taste in
regulators' mouths the last time they approved one of his big deals
_ the acquisition of MCI two years ago. In that case, Ebbers agreed
to sell MCI's Internet business to Cable &AMP; Wireless PLC.
</P>
<P>
   But afterward, Cable &AMP; Wireless contended that WorldCom did not
transfer all of the customers and assets that their deal specified.
At least as important, in the United States, Cable &AMP; Wireless was
also left in the position of buying capacity on WorldCom's
fiber-optic network to connect the MCI Internet switches. That made
it very difficult for Cable &AMP; Wireless to make money on the MCI
Internet operation.
</P>
<P>
   For WorldCom, driving a bargain so hard that it almost looked
unfair was just business as usual. It was the style that had made
WorldCom and it was why investors have generally loved Ebbers.
</P>
<P>
   But the regulators were not favorably impressed. And so Ebbers
had no good will waiting for him when his lawyers went back to the
same regulatory agencies last fall seeking approval for the Sprint
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's live by the sword, die by the sword,'' Strumingher said.
``WorldCom has a take-no-prisoners approach, which has rewarded
shareholders handsomely over the years. But that approach is not
without risks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
