<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE THINGS YOU CAN'T LIVE WITHOUT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Designer  &UR; Phillip Bloch &LR; , who created a necklace-length key
chain that Los Angeles magazine says is worn by  &UR; Jenna Elfman &LR; ,
 &UR; Lauren Holly &LR;  and  &UR; Courtney Love &LR; , said his epiphany came one day
when he was stuck in traffic. ``Here I was in DKNY this and Prada
that,'' he told the magazine, ``and I've got this crappy key chain.
I was like, `Why don't I get some beautiful fabrics and make my
own?'''
</P>
<P>
   - If you're pondering the difficulties of wearing plastic shoes
downtown, designer  &UR; Isabel Toledo  &LR; has an answer. ``New York is
dirty,'' she told the New York Observer. ``My flip-flops are men's
size 12. It's like taking my own floor around with me.''
</P>
<P>
   - In a story about nouveau baby necessities such as $18 bottles
of shampoo, the Wall Street Journal describes a product made by a
woman in rural Minnesota:  &UR; Heidi Kluzak &LR; 's ``Rejuvenating Massage &AMP;
Bath Oil'' is purported to allow ``the baby to rejuvenate for
another day of exploration and growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the New York Times says that wealthy parents are
wondering how to bring up their children. ``Do I have to fly coach
so my son will not alienate other kids?'' asked the parent of one
young braggart.
</P>
<P>
   - New Line Cinema, which is making a movie based on  &UR; J.R.R. &LR; 
 &UR; Tolkien &LR; 's ``The Lord of the Rings,'' has signed a contract with
Marvel's Toy Biz to create action figures and accessories, dolls,
remote-control toys, collectible marbles and accessories,
electronic and nonelectronic plush flying toys and LCD watches. New
Line also has signed with Sideshow Toy for a similar line of
products related to the rerelease of the movie ``This Is Spinal
Tap.'' Company officials said they got the idea from successful
``Austin Powers'' merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the journal Use Less Stuff, described herein
previously, is going out of business, partly because it's been so
successful and it costs too much to produce and distribute.
</P>
<P>
   - Stuff magazine says the first pizza ever delivered was to
 &UR; Queen Margherita  &LR; of Naples, in 1889. And  &UR; Richard Reynolds &LR; , just
back from Rome, says that opposite the Spanish Steps, tucked next
to the Caffe Greco once favored by the likes of  &LR;  Keats &LR; , is a huge
Foot Locker store. Reynolds found this even more disturbing than
the McDonald's sign in front of the Vatican Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, inside the museum, there's a new reminder of
non-infallibility. When  &UR; William Hynes &LR;  _ former academic vice
president of St. Mary's College in Moraga, now president of St.
Norbert College in De Pere, Wis. _ took his family there to see the
Sistine Chapel, he noticed new escalators, ramps, cafeteria and
halls. The greatest change, he said, was visible next to the museum
exit: a big yellow suggestion box.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Ben Affleck &LR;  told the Times of London that he and  &UR; Matt &LR; 
 &UR; Damon &LR;  are writing a story together about a pair of drug abuse
counselors in Boston. Affleck will play the lead, he said, and
Damon will ``play the more comic supporting role. More Mercutio,
you know what I mean?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Betsy Bozdech &LR;  overheard it at the recent Novato Art and Wine
Festival: ``Their Web site sucks! It's from, like, 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Karen Juster Holt &LR;  has found a use for the sample CDs that
come tucked into magazines as free offers. Hung from the branches
of the black-cherry tree in front of her Benicia house, the shiny
discs keep hungry birds away.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Eric Brizee &LR;  drove down Gough Street behind a car with a
consular license plate and an ``Alien on Board'' bumper sticker and
is wondering if there's a delegation in town he doesn't know
about. &UR; Saul Feldman &LR;  saw a San Francisco car with a sticker that
asked, ``What if the hokey pokey  &LR; is  &LR; what it's all about?'' And
 &UR; J.P. Murphy III &LR;  saw one near Crystal Springs Road that said,
``Visualize Grilled Cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   - The country's first Karaoke Spin class _ singing on bikes _ is
held once a week at Crunch L.A., reports Fitness magazine. At one
recent session, says Fitness,  &UR; Tori Spelling &LR; ,  &UR; Fabio  &LR; and
 &UR; Jeanne Tripplehorn &LR;  were watching ``with eyes wide and jaws
dropped.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I resent being likened to this Neanderthal. Rocker is being
called rotten 'cause he's ignorant and I've been called rotten for
being informed. I am deeply hurt to be compared to your
mouth-breathing national numbskull.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; -  &LR;   &LR; Former Sex Pistol  &UR; Johnny Rotten &LR; ,  &LR; host of the eYada.com
chat show ``Rotten Radio,'' when the New York Post ran a picture of
Atlanta Braves pitcher &UR; John Rocker &LR;  with the headline ``Johnny
Rotten.''
</P>
