<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ECOMMERCE-COLUMN-2TAK     07-02 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOMMERCE-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE: PRINCIPLES OF CONSUMER PRIVACY ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the online privacy debate reached its peak earlier this
year, the watchwords were ``notice'' and ``choice.'' Consumer
groups demanded that online advertising companies like DoubleClick
give consumers more notice when tracking their behavior, and give
them the choice to avoid such tracking.
</P>
<P>
   But there are two other core privacy principles: giving
consumers ``access'' to data collected on them and providing them
with the ``security'' that the data is kept private.
</P>
<P>
   The first two terms continue to be volleyed back-and-forth by
legislators scoring points in this year's campaign, but the latter
two have received scant air time.
</P>
<P>
   That may change, as companies have begun heeding the call of
privacy advocates to increase access to profiling data.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is, the techniques of the companies that offer
solutions on data access may actually run afoul of some privacy
groups. The resulting conflict could shift the debate to a new
front and make strange bedfellows of privacy advocates and the
advertising networks and other companies that have until now been
their prime targets.
</P>
<P>
   Access has been a sleeper issue primarily because it is so
complex. It seems obvious that consumers should be able to check
the files that others keep on them and to change anything that is
wrong. But articulating the boundaries of such a policy is no easy
task.
</P>
<P>
   Should businesses give consumers access to transactions made
years ago, data that the company has on a computer tape sitting in
the back of a storage closet? Should they be forced to spend
millions of dollars updating their computer systems so consumers
can see and change that information? And what right do consumers
have to data that is collected not about them, per se, but on the
computers they share with others at work or at home?
</P>
<P>
   These questions have led advertising networks like DoubleClick
and Engage, among others, which gather information on users
anonymously, to hold off on giving users access to data.
</P>
<P>
   Still, recent steps within the industry suggest that some
companies are heeding the call for access.
</P>
<P>
   One such company is BeFree, which, among other things,
distributes software that helps online businesses tailor their
content to the user's interest. This so-called personalization
software has become increasingly common among e-commerce companies
this year, as they vie to improve their profit margins by showing
customers merchandise they are more likely to buy.
</P>
<P>
   This software also raises privacy issues, as it relies on
tracking a user's behavior on a site, or a group of sites, to
determine a consumer's buying preferences. As with other companies
that track user activities, BeFree inserts a ``cookie,'' or a
number within a small text file, on the user's hard drive, to track
activity.
</P>
<P>
   BeFree says it requires the sites that use the software to
inform customers how it works, and give them a way to opt out of
the tracking. The company also goes one step further, by giving
users access to the information gathered on them.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, on SuperGo.com, a bicycle store, users can click
on a link within the site's privacy statement and go to another
site set up by BeFree, which then discloses information compiled
about the user's behavior on SuperGo. Later this year, when BeFree
tracks user activity across multiple sites, it will disclose the
user's information from all the sites on one page.
</P>
<P>
   To authenticate the identity of the user who asks for his online
dossier, BeFree checks the user's cookie number, then retrieves
only the browsing and purchasing information associated with that
cookie.
</P>
<P>
   Notably, BeFree does not have full control over how that
information is displayed. At the moment, for example, SuperGo
customers can view only the stock numbers of the products they
looked at or purchased. Steven Laff, who designed the SuperGo site,
said the company would translate those numbers to text soon.
</P>
<P>
   Laff said that giving consumers access to data gathered on them
was a common sense approach. ``It's a nice, respectful thing to
do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Executives of other companies facing the same access questions
said the BeFree approach was flawed. Daniel J. Jaye, co-founder of
Engage, an online advertising company that tracks consumers
anonymously, said BeFree ``may be well-intentioned, but it could
lead to a security breach.'' Jaye said the technique jeopardized
users' privacy, because it could disclose their information to
someone else who uses the same computer.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if a person visited the SuperGo site while at work,
an employer or a co-worker could sit at the same computer and see
that a person used it to shop for bikes, or easily view that
person's BeFree profile.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Shen, policy analyst for the Electronic Privacy
Information Center, and a critic of companies like Engage that
track online users, said: ``I actually agree with Dan on this one.
You don't want that information to end up in the wrong hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas A. Gerace, BeFree's co-founder, said he considered that
argument when developing the software, but added that when two or
more people used the same computer, Web browser software allowed
users to control their information by erasing cookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The user just has to be conscious about how they're using the
machine,'' Gerace said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the access issue is less problematic when companies
gather information, usually offline, that includes a person's
identity.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike companies that only track users online anonymously _ and
therefore have no way to ensure that they are disclosing profile
information to the right person _ companies that track personally
identifiable information have alternatives. Because these
businesses usually have an address to go along with a name, they
can simply send a letter with the information requested, or send a
log-in and password so the consumer can view the information
online.
</P>
<P>
   Axciom Corp., which sells information on tens of millions of
U.S. households, allows users to get access to their information by
sending a letter and $5 to the company. More important, Axciom
released technology last year that allows companies with vast
amounts of consumer data to sift through it quickly and present it
for review or editing by consumers or a sales staff.
</P>
<P>
   The technology, dubbed AbiliTec, solves one aspect of the access
issue for companies that collect data on consumers from several
sources _ for instance, through mail order operations, retail
stores or the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Such companies often contend that it would be too burdensome to
offer consumers access to personal data, because it would be
technologically impossible to compile that data in one place
quickly and efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   AbiliTec and competing products may make it easier for companies
to do that, but such technology is not inexpensive. One Axciom
executive said it could cost a large retailer that sells through a
traditional store, a catalog and the Web more than a million
dollars to implement.
</P>
<P>
   Other solutions to the access problem are coming to market, as
well. ECustomers.com, for instance, has developed technology that
will soon allow e-tailers to use data about a person's offline
shopping habits to tailor their display of merchandise for
consumers who sign up for the ECustomers service. Like BeFree,
ECustomers plans to allow consumers to have access to the data it
compiles on them, by mailing a log-in number and password. If the
consumer's address matches the one ECustomers has on file, the
consumer's identity is all but assured.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, for companies that continue to collect data
anonymously to preserve users' privacy _ but that do not want to
follow BeFree's example _ there are few, if any, technological
solutions to the access problem. ``We very much support the notion
of access,'' said Jaye of Engage, which places ads on Web sites
based on a user's online activity. ``But we can't do it securely.
It's kind of a devil-if-you-do, devil-if-you-don't situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-00 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
