<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-PLATFORM-WRITER-PROFI     07-02 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLATFORM-WRITER-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 24, A VETERAN OF DEMOCRATIC POLITICS, FROM VACUUM TO PLATFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ So how did you spend the summer after seventh
grade?
</P>
<P>
   Mowing lawns? Rereading ``Born Free'' at summer school? Andrei
Cherny had grander plans for his vacation.
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1988, and he had recently read Theodore H. White's
``The Making of the President, 1960.'' No comic books for this
pre-teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by that portrait of John F. Kennedy, Cherny volunteered
to work on the Los Angeles campaign of another Massachusetts-bred,
Harvard-trained candidate for president, Michael Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   A skeptical campaign official asked what he would like to work
on. ``Foreign policy,'' 12-year-old Andrei confidently replied. The
official offered a vacuum cleaner instead. By fall, he had
graduated from doing floors to stuffing envelopes and answering
phones.
</P>
<P>
   But from that modest beginning came more precocious things. By
his senior year at Harvard, Cherny was writing speeches for
President Clinton. A week after graduation, he became a senior
speech writer for Vice President Al Gore. At 23, he edited a
big-thought magazine for the Democratic Leadership Council, the
party's leading centrist organization. And at 24, he wrote a book
describing the politics of the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a month from reaching the ripe old age of 25, Cherny is
writing the Democratic platform, a 20,000-word spiritual guide to
the party's political soul that dedicated Democrats will fuss and
bicker over all summer, whether or not voters pay any attention to
it in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are a lot of people who really do look at the
platform,'' Cherny said. ``Perhaps especially in this day and age,
it's an important way of saying: here's what the Democratic Party
stands for, here's what we've done and what we're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   As platform director, Cherny joins the ranks of other platform
writers with silky prose and grand ideas who later became leading
policy makers within the party. In 1984, it was Susan Estrich, who
managed the 1988 Dukakis campaign. In 1992, it was Bruce Reed, now
a top domestic policy adviser to Clinton. And in 1996, it was Reed
and Elaine Kamarck, who is now policy director for the Gore
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As any of those people could tell you, platform writing is its
own special art form. The prose must be pithy, elegant and
inspiring. And the wording must deftly skip across the ideological
minefields that have surrounded Democratic and Republican platforms
of the past.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when Sen. Edward M. &UR;  &LR; Kennedy challenged President
Jimmy Carter in 1980, a combative Kennedy team _ which included the
mayor of Cincinnati, Jerry Springer _ produced 25 minority reports
on the platform. Things got so testy that a Kennedy adviser named
Paul Tully nearly came to blows with a Carter delegate named Mario
Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   This year, after former Sen. Bill Bradley yielded early in the
primaries, the struggle within the party is much quieter. To be
sure, gay rights activists, environmentalists and union leaders are
laboring behind the scenes to insert pet phrases into Cherny's
draft. But the process, he insists, has been remarkably consensual
and free of acrimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly trade is one place where there's been some debate,''
he said. ``But it's not like you have these groups at each other's
throats. You have the single goal of winning in November.''
</P>
<P>
   A gentle platform process would befit Cherny's unassuming style.
Lanky and soft-spoken, he fills his spare time, what little there
is, with history books, films and, he confesses, ``junk TV'' shows
like ``Ally McBeal'' and ``Friends.'' In his cluttered office at
the Democratic National Committee, a photograph of his favorite
scholar-writer-politician, Winston Churchill, sternly stares down
from the white wall.
</P>
<P>
   The older of two sons born to immigrants from Czechoslovakia,
Cherny was raised in the Valley Village section of Los Angeles, a
heavily minority, working-class community. His father, a school
teacher, and his mother, a psychotherapist, are proud of his
achievements, he says, but not overly awed by the company he keeps.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still expect me to pick up my socks and wash the dishes
when I'm home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cherny first caught the eye of Democratic heavyweights during
his senior year at Harvard, when Donald Baer, then the White House
communications director, read an article he had written for the
student newspaper, The Crimson, analyzing President Clinton's
landslide victory of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Baer showed the article to the president, who liked it so much
he made it required reading for his cabinet and cribbed a sentence
from it for his second inaugural address. ``We need a new
government for a new century, a government humble enough not to try
to solve all our problems for us but strong enough to give us the
tools to solve our problems for ourselves,'' the line went.
</P>
<P>
   Baer commissioned Cherny to write speeches for Clinton during
Cherny's final semester at Harvard. After graduation, Cherny moved
to Washington to write for Gore, an author and former reporter whom
Cherny found to be a perfectionist about language.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would bring him drafts, he'd sit down and change every
word, and then some,'' Cherny said. ``In the end, they were his
speeches.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Cherny returned to California where he managed to
work as a part-time policy adviser to the speaker of the state
Assembly while attending Boalt Hall, the law school at Berkeley,
and writing a book. The book, ``The Next Deal,'' will be published
by Basic Books this winter.
</P>
<P>
   And what if there is a Gore administration? Cherny says he wants
to return to California, finish law school and become a criminal
prosecutor. ``When the convention approves the platform, my job is
done,'' he said. But the hesitation in his voice suggested that he
senses this will not be his last job in Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
