<SLUG> BC-TENNIS-FASHION0703-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Most women content to leave those skimpy tennis dresses to
Wimbledon stars
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Luv 'em, or hate 'em, those clingy little dresses that
some of the top young stars of women's tennis are wearing at
Wimbledon probably won't be overwhelming a court near you, though
you may see one here or there.
</P>
<P>
   Those who closely follow the game, and monitor the on-court
fashions of the Williams sisters (Venus and Serena) and Anna
Kournikova, say most women wouldn't dare wear the equivalent of an
oversized tank top during a match. And the supply of such outfits
isn't that great anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't as many of those dresses available as there are
(skirt and top) separates,'' said Howard Matthews, owner of the
Tennis Menace shop in Duluth, Ga. ``We do carry some things that
would look nice on a perfect body, but there aren't too many women
like that around. Most people who play recreationally have a little
extra weight here or an unwanted bulge there, and they want to
cover it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova and the Williamses have been wearing revealing tennis
dresses emblazoned with the logos of Adidas, Puma or Nike at
Wimbledon, which runs through Sunday. But, as Matthews maintains,
``Those are sneaker companies that mainly make those clothes for
the players for the exposure it'll bring to their brands. Most
stores don't carry much of it, or any at all, because (sneaker
makers) don't have extensive collections or wide enough
distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Prince, a major manufacturer of tennis equipment and apparel,
offers only two dress styles out of about 50 outfits for women in
its latest catalog. ``From what I gather, we're pretty much where
the industry is,'' said Sandy Connelly, production manager for
Prince Apparel. ``The market isn't asking for a whole lot more
dresses.''
</P>
<P>
   Buying separates, Connelly added, ``gives you more wardrobe
flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Dukes Wilburn of Lithonia, Ga., a 10-year veteran of ALTA
(Atlanta Ladies Tennis Association) league play, said she had to
search long and hard to find a dress similar to one she saw Venus
Williams wearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see how I'd look in it,'' said the 33-year-old
investment manager, who eventually found two among a small
selection at Phipps Plaza's Nike Town. ``I was concerned that they
would be tacky because they're so tight. But they actually fit
pretty well, because of the way the undergarments are sewn into the
dresses.''
</P>
<P>
   Has dressing like the Williams sisters improved her game any?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could say it has,'' Wilburn sighed. ``But at least I
look good.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
