<HEADER>
A1238 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-WIZARD-0Z0703-COX     07-02 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIZARD-0Z0703-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Somewhere over the rainbow there's dark side of the moon
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no place like home.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dorothy Gale,
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wizard of Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Home, home again/
</P>
<P>
   I like to be here when I can.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Roger Waters,
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dark Side of the Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how or when the legend began, the one that goes
like this: If you play Pink Floyd's ``Dark Side of the Moon'' while
watching ``The Wizard of Oz,'' the music and the movie appear to be
in sync, at times startlingly so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark Side's'' songs change with the movie's scenes, offering
emotional underscoring and sometimes even specific connections.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of quick examples:
</P>
<P>
   When Dorothy's house is being spun by the tornado, the CD plays
the celestial scatting of ``The Great Gig in the Sky,'' which
sounds like it was written for the scene. As soon as Dorothy opens
the door to Oz and the film dramatically switches from black and
white to color, the CD switches at precisely that moment from
``Gig'' to ``Money.''
</P>
<P>
   The lyric ``black and blue'' (on the song ``Us and Them'') is
sung just as the camera pans between the Wicked Witch of the West
(in black) and Dorothy (in blue). Then the line ``And who knows
which is which?'' corresponds to a cut between the Wicked Witch and
Glinda the Good Witch.
</P>
<P>
   And folks who have spent vast amounts of time poring over these
coincidences list dozens of them, including the obvious connection
that ``Dark Side'' has a rainbow on its cover.
</P>
<P>
   To help people further explore the synchronicity (or maybe just
to offer up a really cool marketing gimmick), Turner Classic Movies
will air ``The Wizard of Oz'' at 11 tonight with ``Dark Side'' on
the SAP (Second Audio Program) feed. The cable channel also will
air ``Oz'' at 8 tonight (without ``Dark Side''), the first time
it's been on TV without commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything to this or is it all just the ravings of
addled adolescents staying up too late while ingesting too many
chemicals and frequently saying, ``Whoa, dude?''
</P>
<P>
   I cued ``Dark Side'' to ``Wizard'' (you have to start the CD
precisely on the third roar of the MGM lion) and there really are a
handful of times when the music and the film work together
magically, as if the movie (on mute) is a silent classic and ``Dark
Side'' is the score.
</P>
<P>
   But there are long passages where the music has nothing to do
with the film and the whole thing seems to be an exercise in the
power of suggestion more than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   That's also the conclusion of The Straight Dope, the reliably
skeptical newspaper column and website, which studied the
``synchronicity'' in May and concluded: ``This really isn't all
that different from receiving a psychic reading or looking at your
horoscope. You see the things that match and ignore those that
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to the ``Whoa, dude'' contingent, though, which is
convinced that Roger Waters, Floyd's lyricist and the guiding light
of ``Dark Side,'' arranged the whole thing as some sort of cosmic
in-joke. Waters reportedly has refused to comment on the hubbub,
but Alan Parsons, the album's producer who had a major hand in
arranging its complex sound effects (and, thus, its timing), has
denied any deliberate connection.
</P>
<P>
   As an underground legend, the Floyd/Oz link has spread and grown
since roughly the mid '90s, meaning it's lasted much longer than
the pop-cultural myth it most resembles, the ``Paul is Dead''
mania, circa 1969. That one came up fast and furious, then
sputtered. The Internet, which has been a major tool in spreading
the Floyd/Oz word, doesn't just move these things faster; it can
give them longer life. What it can't give them is truth.
</P>
<P>
   HOW DOES IT WORK?
</P>
<P>
   The Second Audio Program (SAP) is available on many newer TV
sets that are hooked to cable or satellite. You can access it
through your remote control, usually by pressing an audio or menu
button and following the prompts. The procedure may not be
available on some remotes.
</P>
<P>
   Media One will carry the SAP signal for Turner Classic Movie's
special airing of ``The Wizard of Oz'' as will DIRECTV (satellite).
</P>
<P>
   If you can't get the SAP, cue ``The Dark Side of the Moon'' in
your CD player and hit pause before it begins. When the MGM logo
comes on at the start of ``Oz,'' wait for the third roar of Leo the
Lion. On the third roar, hit play to start the CD.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
