<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1244 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-TREES-ART-NYT &LR;      07-02 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-TREES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TREE GROWS IN ISRAEL _ OR DOES IT? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Armed with a spade, a $10 pine sapling and a
videocamera, Marvin Stabler of Richboro, Pa., descended a terraced
dirt path Sunday to take part in an age-old ritual for Jewish
tourists: planting a tree in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Sweating in the noon sun, Stabler hacked at the rocky soil of
his chosen patch of Holy Land, wondering aloud if there was not
``someone you could pay to do it for you.'' His family, who came
here for his daughter Gabrielle's bat mitzvah, urged him to do his
imitation of his grandfather while he dug.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oy vay! Oy gevalt!'' he said, using a thick Yiddish accent, to
the great amusement of two boys from Alabama who wore ``Super Jew''
T-shirts. ``This has got to be a first _ me digging!''
</P>
<P>
   Though no agronomist, Stabler could look around him and tell
that this hillside in Jerusalem was not the most fertile ground. So
it came as no shock to him to learn that most of the saplings
planted by his family would not survive.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is a fact not advertised by the sponsoring agency, the
Jewish National Fund. In fact, six of every 10 trees planted at the
hilly, arid, unirrigated site here die, a fund spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week an Israeli tabloid created a commotion when it ran an
investigative article, ``The Great Tree Fraud,'' suggesting that
workers cynically uproot the saplings planted by tourists to make
way for the next day's busloads.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper, Maariv, printed three photographs taken from the
same vantage point on two consecutive days in late June. One showed
tourists busy at work surrounded by dozens of freshly planted
trees, the second showed the same site nude but pockmarked,
supposedly on the next morning, and the third revealed a nearby
pile of uprooted saplings.
</P>
<P>
   Many Israelis said life was imitating art. The tree-planting
ritual, a deeply rooted phenomenon in the culture of the Jewish
diaspora, has long been the subject of satirists. A well-known
Israeli film, ``Salah Shabati,'' features a scene in which the
dedication plaque at the entrance to a forest is changed when one
group of American Jewish benefactors leaves and another arrives to
see ``their'' trees.
</P>
<P>
   But Jewish National Fund officials were not amused. Late last
week, the fund suspended several workers, and Sunday it established
a public investigation committee headed by a former judge.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they would be horrified to learn that the charges
were true, but that if they were, they would represent an isolated
case of malfeasance. In a statement prepared by a public relations
firm in New York, the fund defended its good intentions and
declared that it would file a libel suit against Maariv for
maligning the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Established in 1901 in Switzerland to purchase land in
Palestine, the Jewish National Fund is the second-largest landowner
in Israel, after the government. Its tree-planting program long
epitomized the Zionist enterprise in its ambition to make the
desert bloom.
</P>
<P>
   ``JNF views its afforestation program as its crowning
achievement and respects each and every planter,'' the statement
from the fund said. ``Many tourists who years earlier had planted
saplings have returned to visit the section where they planted
their trees. These tourists have expressed to us in moving letters,
which we preserve and treasure, their excitement in seeing the
saplings that have grown into mature trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the fund's spokeswoman here, Orly Doron, acknowledges
that many saplings planted at the Jerusalem site are routinely
removed by workers because they do not survive. That does not take
away from the program's track record, she said: Eighty thousand
trees are successfully planted by tourists every year, out of 2.5
million planted by the Jewish National Fund.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not a point that the fund's literature or
representatives make clear to the tourists who pay $10 to honor or
memorialize a relative with a tree in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is that the experience itself means so
much to people, and that their contribution helps support the
enterprise _ $50 million worth of plantation a year,'' said Doron.
``If Orly Doron pays $10 to plant a tree, and then it dies, and a
worker takes it out and plants a new one, that is not the important
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by Sunday's crowd at the planting site near Hadassah-Ein
Kerem Hospital, that is indeed the tourists' sentiment. All the
same, they said they found it a little silly that the reality was
not made clearer to them.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Swerdlin from Atlanta spent a substantial chunk of time
not only planting her sapling but landscaping it with the bounteous
rocks in the area. It was clear that she had bonded with the flimsy
little tree. And like many thousands of tourists before her, she
chose to believe that it would grow to be a mighty pine, her
personal, hands-on contribution to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Her 18-year-old son, Ryan, said, ``If 40 percent are going to
survive, that's all right for us.'' Still, he looked disappointed
to learn the Jewish National Fund's statistics.
</P>
<P>
   At other planting sites, outside Jerusalem, in better soil, the
survival rate is much higher _ close to 95 percent. But the the
convenient Hadassah-Ein Kerem site is the most popular.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Arnold M. Goodman, the leader of their congregation in
Georgia, called over a worker with a green garden hose to bless the
Swerdlins' tree with water. Without knowing anything about the
Maariv article, Goodman said, ``Chances are, they pull them out and
plant them again when the next group shows up.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he winced. ``Oh, don't write that down,'' he said.
``They'll take away my rabbinical credentials.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``Write that even if they do pull them out, the
JNF will prosper. And it's a great activity. The average youngster
who comes here has very little experience with dirt. It gives them
a sense of what the pioneers did.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the fund has been battling criticism that goes much
deeper than that published in Maariv, part of which suggests that
Israel might be better off if the pine saplings did not take root.
</P>
<P>
   In a petition to the High Court, the Union for Environmental
Defense has challenged the Jewish National Fund's method of
operations, contending that the organization is subject to only
minimal governmental and public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   The group has also criticized the fund's forestry practices,
from its supposed overreliance on highly flammable pine trees to
accusations that it overuses toxic herbicides and that it has used
controlled burning to eliminate unwanted brush.
</P>
<P>
   Doron, the spokeswoman, dismisses such criticism by attacking
the environmentalists. ``They are very radical,'' she said. ``This
is a group that says everything that is not natural is wrong. For
example, foresting is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Philip Warburg, the environmental group's deputy
director, said, ``The JNF should get out of the business of
maligning others and look inward in a constructive manner at
forestry practices that have gone unquestioned for too long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
