<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1254 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-02 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BILLIE, BENNY AND THE DUKE 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Listen. Those sounds you hear are the first faint glorious notes
from the film ``Jazz,'' Ken Burns' wonderful 10-part, 19-hour
exploration of this nation's greatest music. The documentary will
debut on PBS in January, but last week I got an early look at some
excerpts and they're amazing.
</P>
<P>
   I once asked Dizzy Gillespie how close he had really been to
Charlie Parker. He replied, ``How close are two coats of paint?''
</P>
<P>
   That's how I feel about the relationship between this country
and the astonishing variety of music that we call jazz. Jazz is
more than a musical reflection of America _ it is the embodiment in
music of the quintessentially American idea of free and talented
and diverse individuals working, playing, frequently fighting, but
most of all improvising together to come up with something
beautiful and great. It is the truest artistic expression of who we
are.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Burns has captured this on film.
</P>
<P>
   Burns himself, in a telephone conversation a few days ago, said:
``I think it's the best thing I've ever done. I've never said that
before in any of my interviews. Ever.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jazz'' is the third part of the trilogy of American life that
Burns began 16 years ago when he started work on his acclaimed
``Civil War'' series. The second part was the epic 18 1/2-hour
``Baseball'' documentary.
</P>
<P>
   For once, a film about jazz does not give the music short
shrift. The music is abundant and it's thrilling. But there is also
much more. With remarkable footage _ 2,000 archival film clips and
another 2,400 still photos _ ``Jazz'' carries the viewer on a
spellbinding tour of the personalities and the venues (the
speakeasies, the smoke-filled clubs, the ballrooms, the concert
halls) that gave us this extraordinary music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jazz is the story of the 20th century,'' said Burns. ``It's an
unusually objective witness to what we've been through _ two world
wars, massive dislocations in the Depression, the ever-present
question of race, that is to say, minstrelsy and Jim Crow and
lynchings and all of that. And it's about sex, the way men and
women talk to one another, the mating call of America. And it's
about drugs and their terrible cost. But mostly it's about these
terribly courageous men and women who created art on the spot _
something the rest of us can only dream of.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the people you meet on this 19-hour tour are, in the words
of the narrator:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The pampered son of middle-class parents who turned a whole
orchestra of extraordinary musicians into his own personal
instrument, wrote nearly 2,000 pieces for it to play, and in the
process became America's greatest composer.'' (That would be Duke
Ellington.)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A Russian-Jewish immigrant's boy from the Chicago slums who
was taught the clarinet just to keep him out of trouble, but who
grew up to teach a whole country how to dance.'' (Benny Goodman.)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The troubled daughter of a Baltimore housemaid whose
distinctive style of singing transcended the limitations of her own
voice and routinely transformed mediocre music into great art.''
(Billie Holiday.)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The son of a pullman chef from Kansas City, Mo., who came to
New York to launch a musical revolution, proudly led it for a time,
and then destroyed himself at 34.'' (Charlie Parker.)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The fatherless waif from the streets of New Orleans whose
unrivaled genius helped turn jazz into a soloist's art (and) who
influenced every singer, every instrumentalist, every artist who
came after him.'' (Louis Armstrong.)
</P>
<P>
   There is a moment in the film when the actor Ossie Davis
describes walking in on Louis Armstrong unexpectedly and seeing
``the saddest expression I've ever seen on a man's face.'' And
there is a moment when Dave Brubeck, reminiscing on camera, is
suddenly overcome by an ancient and horrible memory, and he breaks
down and begins to weep.
</P>
<P>
   With taste, and with his own sure and unerring artistic touch,
Burns guides us through this sacred cultural terrain. No one has
ever put jazz on film better than Ken Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Kudos must go to PBS and to the folks who carry the General
Motors ``Mark of Excellence'' banner for sponsoring this important
work. I seldom look forward to January. But this is different. This
is really special.
</P>
</TEXT>
