<HEADER>
A1255 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CYC-TOUR-MAIN0704-COX     07-02 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-MAIN0704-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SBy Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FUTUROSCOPE, France _ For much of their 194-mile trek through
the rich farmland of the Loire Valley on Sunday afternoon, the
riders of the Tour de France _ the peloton as its called in cycling
lingo _ were content to stay basically intact.
</P>
<P>
   Two riders, France's Jacky Durand and the Netherlands' Erik
Dekker, made an early break to pick up valuable bonus seconds at
certain sprint stages, but the two gradually fell back, with Dekker
seeking medical attention for a cramp and Durand simply growing
leg-weary. Several others made solo dashes, but just as quickly as
they charged forward, they came back to the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as the group reached the final stretch into Loudun, the
bravest of the group, the sport's top sprinters, readied for one
final push.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 194 miles and four hours and 45 minutes after the group
left Futuroscope, there was a photo finish to decide the victor.
Tom Steels _ teeth clinched, and his bicycle wobbling from side to
side as he furiously pumped the pedals for more speed _ got to the
finish line just ahead of Australia's Stuart O'Grady. During his
final push over about 1 1/2 miles, Steels averaged more than 39
miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the last-second flurry, the results of the second
stage had little effect on the overall standings.
</P>
<P>
   David Millar, a 23-year-old Scotsman and the lone rider from
Great Britain competing in the Tour, remained in first place
overall, despite finishing 17th Sunday. Millar, the winner of
Saturday's stage one prologue, has an overall time of 5 hours, 5
minutes and 9 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Four seconds behind in second place was Austin's Lance
Armstrong, the defending Tour champion. Armstrong, riding
conservatively, finished 38th.
</P>
<P>
   France's Laurent Jalabert remained in third, 15 seconds behind
Millar and 11 behind Armstrong. Jan Ullrich, the 1997 champion, was
fourth, 16 seconds behind the leader.
</P>
<P>
   Millar finished third Sunday at the third intermediary sprint
and picked up two bonus seconds, which allowed him to pad his
minimal margin over Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong stayed near the front of the peloton but away from the
kamikaze sprinters. His focus wasn't to win this flat stage or even
come close. Rather, he wanted to stay out of trouble and steer
clear of a crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who ride for the overall lead don't particularly get
into the first week,'' Armstrong said. ``You can absolutely lose
the Tour de France in this first week. Nobody's going to win it the
first week, but you can lose it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, our strategy is to stay out of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Trouble almost sidetracked Tyler Hamilton, one of Armstrong's
most valuable teammates. Hamilton crashed about one-quarter into
the race, but was able to get back on his bike with only slight
scrapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened in an instant,'' Hamilton said. ``The peloton was
going really fast. There was some sort of contact toward the front,
somebody laid on the brakes really hard and it had a domino effect
on the rest of the peloton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy to get off the pavement and get on my bike. It
could have been a lot worse. Lance was right beside me. It could
have just as easily been him. A crash like that, it's just like a
lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's conditions were a bit windy, but most of the stage was
completed under slightly overcast skies with temperatures in the
low 70s. All the riders returned to their hotels near Futuroscope,
although today's stage starts in Loudun, about 25 miles away, and
continues on to Nantes, in western France near the Atlantic coast.
</P>
<P>
   The stage victory was Steels' eighth since 1998. At 28, he is
one of the top sprinters in the world and one of his sport's most
volatile competitors. Yet he also knows that even with his win
Sunday, he was unlikely to unseat Millar as the overall leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a chance I could catch Millar because Cofidis
(Millar's team) was too good,'' Steels said.
</P>
<P>
   Millar, the son of a Royal Air Force pilot, continues to remain
the big story in the international media, although the time trial
specialist is not expected to keep his overall lead once the Tour
leaves its flatter stages. In fact, the Cofidis team controlled the
peloton so well Sunday that they were able to keep the major
sprinters from kicking up the pace.
</P>
<P>
   Millar's eight teammates set up in a line in front of him, with
one rider each at his right and left. This way, the volatility of
the peloton would not cause him to crash.
</P>
<P>
   The Cofidis riders peeled away with about three miles to go and
allowed the sprinters from Mapei, Credit Agricole and Telekom to
finally take over the stage, setting up Steels' spectacular finish.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
