<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-OPPOSITION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMBABWE HAS A FRESH POPULIST BREEZE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ There were buses to hire, fliers to post,
people to rally. The country's newest opposition party was about to
be set in motion in Rufaro Stadium and time was running out.
</P>
<P>
   The new party had no slogan, no logo and no access to the
television or radio controlled by the government it hoped to
topple. ``We were all anxious,'' recalled Grace Kwinjeh, a member
of the party's executive board. ``We were asking ourselves, `How do
we get people there? How do we get the information out?'''
</P>
<P>
   But to the surprise of many onlookers, thousands flocked to the
township stadium for that first rally last September. And within
nine months, the new party, the Movement for Democratic Change, had
united black union activists and white corporate executives,
students and workers into a formidable movement that shook the
political establishment.
</P>
<P>
   In the elections on June 24 and 25, voters here loosened
President Robert Mugabe's grip on parliament by electing opposition
party members to more than a third of the seats. Mugabe's governing
party kept its majority, but for the first time in more than a
decade, it lost its authority to change the Constitution
unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
   By almost any measure, the success of the Movement for
Democratic Change is astounding. And its rapid rise to power
reflects its attentiveness to the frustrations of urban voters at a
time when Mugabe and his party, who have ruled this country for 20
years, seemed detached from the needs of ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Tsvangirai, 48, the leader of the Movement for Democratic
Change, promised to improve the economy, race relations and the
prospects for young people, a message that appealed to a nation
experiencing an economic crisis, a generation shift and an
increasing sense of alienation among whites.
</P>
<P>
   He put young people in prominent positions and adopted slogans
that borrowed from popular township slang. He referred to whites as
his ``cousins'' and offered them leadership roles in the party. And
he emphasized over and over again that his party intended to find a
way to reduce unemployment and skyrocketing inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But Mugabe, 76, who was considered a hero for fighting to end
decades of white minority rule here and a master of the art of
politics, never seemed to notice that the nation was changing under
his feet.
</P>
<P>
   He focused on the redistribution of white-owned farms to
landless blacks in a country that was increasingly urban and
preoccupied with joblessness and falling wages.
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized the history of the liberation struggle when about
a third of the population now consists of young people who were
either children in 1980, when majority rule was won, or were born
shortly after. ( Mugabe helped lead the battle against white rule
that led to this country's first democratic elections twenty years
ago.)
</P>
<P>
   He attacked the tiny white minority, which still controls much
of the economy, and shook them out of political hibernation. It
was, in large measure, Mugabe's inflammatory racial rhetoric and
his support of violent invasions of white-owned farms that
persuaded many whites to bankroll the new opposition party.
</P>
<P>
   And last year, while inflation was soaring and civil servants
were struggling to feed their families, Mugabe gave his cabinet
members salary increases of up to 182 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It is not that Zimbabwe has never had opposition parties. The
party of Joshua Nkomo, the prominent nationalist, won 20 seats in
parliament in 1980 before it was absorbed by Mugabe's party in
1987.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the governing party, the Zimbabwe African National
Union-Patriotic Front, has controlled all but three seats in
Parliament. And voters became so apathetic that only about 10
percent voted in the local elections last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``People got tired of a one-party state, but they were never
really accorded an alternative,'' said Alfred Nhema, the chairman
of political science at the University of Zimbabwe. ``And then, the
MDC comes along as a real alternative.'' Tsvangirai, the country's
most important union leader, already had a strong record of
challenging the government. He brought the nation to a halt in 1997
with a general strike. And he led the battle for higher wages and
lower taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition candidates also appealed to the public. They were
teachers, butchers, lawyers and students who lacked political
experience but understood ordinary hardships and were willing to
risk their lives for change.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, at least 26 people were killed, most of
them opposition party supporters. But the opposition candidates
fought on, even though they lacked access to government-controlled
news media or public financing, which supports established parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I screwed up my courage,'' said Benni Tumbare Mutasa, 44, a
newly elected member of Parliament who runs a butcher shop and was
attacked by supporters of Mugabe. ``It was high risk, but sometimes
risks are worth taking.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, nearly 60 percent of registered voters turned out
for the election. And when it was all over, the new opposition
party had claimed 57 seats and Mugabe's party had won 62.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened by their unprecedented showing, the opposition did
not hesitate to turn their slingshots on the giant of Zimbabwean
politics, Mugabe. And Tsvangirai announced that he would run for
president in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the end of Robert Mugabe,'' Tsvangirai said. ``The
sooner they start planning his retirement the better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
