</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGANDA-REFERENDUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UGANDANS STAY WITH ONE-PARTY SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ Voters in Uganda overwhelmingly endorsed the
nation's ``no-party'' political system, according to final results
released Sunday, though only half of registered voters went to the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the leaders of Uganda and neighboring Rwanda
met over the weekend to defuse tensions over one of the problems
that has most troubled Ugandans _ Uganda's role in the fighting in
Congo. Last month, Rwanda and Uganda, nominally fighting on the
same side, clashed for the third time in the Congolese city of
Kisangani. At least 600 people died, aid groups say, most of them
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, as the final votes in the referendum were tallied,
presidents Yoweri Museveni of Uganda and Paul Kagame of Rwanda
issued a joint statement calling for renewed respect for the
cease-fire between their countries and, more broadly, in Congo
itself.
</P>
<P>
   The two nations have been close allies, both fighting to
overthrow the government of the Congolese president, Laurent
Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting in Congo is unpopular in Uganda, and opponents of
Museveni had used the issue against him in the referendum on
whether to retain the current no-party state or to return to a
multiparty political system.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, 88 percent of Uganda's voters still favored
Museveni's no-party system, while 9 percent wanted a return to
traditional political parties. The balance, from voting on
Thursday, were voided ballots.
</P>
<P>
   The turnout, however, was just 51 percent. As results trickled
in over the last three days, opposition leaders said that the low
turnout proved the success of a boycott they had organized and
indicated widespread discontent with Museveni. In 1996, the last
presidential race, three quarters of the voters went to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was, in many ways, a referendum on the popularity of
Museveni, who strongly opposes the return of more than one party.
</P>
<P>
   In campaign appearances around the country, he argued that
parties merely divide Uganda by tribe and religion and gave rise to
the dictators Idi Amin and Milton Obote in the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In Uganda, political parties may exist in name only. Parties may
not hold conventions or rallies or field candidates for office.
Instead, all political activity takes place within what is known as
the Movement, a national umbrella political organization to which,
in theory, all candidates and voters belong.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of a multiple-party electoral system and government
say the Movement violates their freedom of association. They also
argue that Uganda is fast becoming a one-party state with Museveni,
in power since 1986, having inordinate power.
</P>
<P>
   That concern was echoed by a group of industrialized nations _
including the United States and many European nations _ which had
contributed $4.5 million for the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The group of donors emphasizes the importance of ensuring that
the Movement system does not evolve into a de facto one-party
state,'' officials of those nations said in a statement released
Saturday. ``Experience shows that such development would not be in
the interest of transparent and accountable government in Uganda.''
</P>
<P>
   In August 1998, both Rwanda and Uganda helped start a rebellion
against President Kabila of Congo, backing three competing rebel
groups at various times.
</P>
<P>
   On Kabila's side, Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia have joined in
the fighting. Last summer, Uganda and Rwanda turned on each other
in the northeastern city of Kisangani _ and they have now clashed
three times, all but destroying their once-close relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The two nations had vowed to leave Kisangani, to make way for
U.N. peacekeepers. But it was only after the latest round of
fighting between Uganda and Rwanda, which drew criticism from the
United Nations as well as the United States, that the two nations
actually withdrew their troops from Kisangani. Both still have
troops inside Congo.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement, the two nations ``reaffirmed their commitment
to a demilitarization of the city of Kisangani and called on other
parties to the cease-fire agreement to reciprocate and not take
advantage of Rwanda and Uganda's withdrawal from Kisangani.''
</P>
</TEXT>
