<HEADER>
A1262 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CYC-TOUR-SIDE0703-COX     07-02 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-SIDE0703-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Media frenzy
 &HT;    Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lance Armstrong has made no secret of his distaste for
certain French publications since several French newspapers accused
him last year of using performance-enhancing drugs during his Tour
win.
</P>
<P>
   The innuendo hasn't stopped this year. It's simply taken another
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the Tour started, the newspaper L'Equipe, an
all-sports daily, wrote a story that said Armstrong has gotten so
money-hungry he is asking to get paid to give interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, to insinuate that I ask for money for interviews
is absurd,'' Armstrong said. ``But then, some things that are
written in certain publications are absurd. Interviews are free.
Appearances, personal endorsements, commercials _ they cost
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Stapleton, Armstrong's Austin-based agent, said that his
client is set to make $7 million this year, $5 million of which is
coming from endorsements. None of Armstrong's salary is being paid
by the media.
</P>
<P>
   TOUR BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   16: The number of opening Tour road stages won by riders from
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   25.2: The average speed (mph) of stage two winner Tom Steels.
</P>
<P>
   36: The number of French cyclists still riding in this year's
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   1968: The last year a sprinting specialist (Jan Janssen) won the
overall Tour.
</P>
<P>
   2,120: The number of miles remaining until the finish line in
Paris on July 23.
</P>
<P>
   JAUNTY JACKY
</P>
<P>
   A French rider did not win a Tour stage last year for the first
time in 83 years.
</P>
<P>
   Jacky Durand, though, tried to give his country something to
cheer about on Sunday. Durand, a 32-year-old who rides for the
Belgium team, Lotto-Mobistar, led the second stage for 70 miles.
</P>
<P>
   With his head wrapped in a red and blue kerchief to honor his
homeland, Durand got plenty of TV time as he built a lead of more
than four minutes. But he faded back into the peloton with about 50
miles to go.
</P>
<P>
   Durand is known as a rider who seeks attention. He has won three
Tour stages in his career and had the distinction of finishing last
in the 1999 Tour. Yet despite finishing 144th, Durand was selected
as ``Most Competitive Rider'' of the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVELOGUE
</P>
<P>
   Although the peloton actually rode 120.2 miles Sunday afternoon,
the riders didn't get that far from the initial starting line in
Futuroscope. The cyclists rode around Poitiers, starting northeast
of the city and continuing in a counterclockwise loop until they
headed north and then slightly west to Loudun, which is about a
30-minute drive via car from Poitiers. Loudun, nestled in the Loire
Valley, is known for the ancient cave dwellings of
Candes-Saint-Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Just to the north of Loudun lies the historic village of Chinon.
Those who saw the movie ``Joan of Arc,'' starring Ingrid Bergman,
might recognize this quaint town, known now for producing red wine.
Five hundred and seventy-one years ago, Joan of Arc, the
self-proclaimed messenger of God, sought out French King Charles
VII to ask him for an army. The seat of the French government
stayed here until 1450.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE DE JOUR
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a funny thing happen to me. First, I was stung by a bee.
I saw him on my leg and swatted him off. Then, there was a
spectator right in my line, trying to take my picture. I still had
the stinger in my leg when I finished. . . . It's an amazing scene
here at the Tour, unlike anything I have ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Austin's Chann McRae, who competes for the Italian team,
Mapei.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
