<HEADER>
A1264 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-N     07-02 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE, CLEMENS AND THE YANKEES SHED SOME ANXIETY 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ David Justice did not bring an entourage
when he joined the Yankees. He seems more like a kid switching to a
new grade school, genial but quiet among new teammates. Justice
noticed that almost all of the Yankees have the cuffs of their
pants set just above the ankles, and before Sunday's game, Justice
had his pants adjusted as well.
</P>
<P>
   The conformity that matters most, however, will be in his run
production, and Justice had his first hit with the Yankees Sunday
and drove in two runs as they completed a turbulent 13-game trip by
beating Tampa Bay, 5-2. Roger Clemens was activated from the
disabled list and pitched efficiently and effectively, allowing
three hits, two walks and a run over seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   When they last played at home on June 18 they were five games
over .500 and a half-game behind the first-place Red Sox. They are
now four games over .500, at 40-36, and one game behind the Toronto
Blue Jays in the American League East. But they are a different
team, jettisoning Jim Leyritz, Ricky Ledee and Todd Erdos over the
last two weeks and adding infielder Jose Vizcaino, pitcher Ben Ford
and Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Justice said it was exciting being with a new team after
Sunday's game, ``and it's scary sometimes, no matter where you
go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in a comfort zone; I've been in the same type of
routine for the past three and a half years,'' he said. ``It's just
a matter of basically getting into another one.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice went hitless in his first two days with the Yankees, and
he admitted to being somewhat anxious, even at age 34, trying to
get that first hit for his new team, trying to fit in. He changed
his socks but put on his underwear backward, a mistake pointed out
by new teammate Felix Jose; Justice laughed along and decided to
keep it that way, just to see how it worked.
</P>
<P>
   And it worked well. Justice pulled a single to right-center in
the second inning, driving home Bernie Williams with the first run,
and with the bases loaded in the third, he hit a sharp grounder to
first, enabling Derek Jeter to cross the plate with the Yankees'
third run. ``He's a legitimate hitter and he is going to be a good
guy in big situations,'' said Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager.
</P>
<P>
   There was no telling how much run support Clemens would need, if
he would even last five innings. He went on the disabled list 18
days ago after straining his right groin muscle and spent most that
time training at the Yankees' facility in Tampa, Fla. Clemens
tracked the Yankees, feeling frustrated when they struggled. He
would see George Steinbrenner, who hit him with a good-natured
verbal jab, telling him he was needed back in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens seemed particularly anxious before Sunday's game,
teammates said, stalking through the clubhouse purposefully, no one
saying anything to him, giving him personal space. The pitcher
``walks around like Alfred Hitchcock'' in the clubhouse, Torre
said. ``He's in the movie, but nobody's supposed to know about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He went to the bullpen to warm up about 10 minutes before he
usually does, to get loose and to see how the muscles around his
legs felt, and to have a little extra time just in case he required
a little extra wrapping.
</P>
<P>
   But Clemens felt great, threw hard and threw lots of strikes,
his pace steady from pitch to pitch, his mechanics smooth and
steady. Clemens usually averages about 18 pitches an inning, and
Sunday, he needed only 87 over seven innings, an average of 12 an
inning. ``Maybe this two week stint on the disabled list helped
more than just physically,'' said Torre. ``It helped him to
organize his thoughts and then get ready to pitch. Sunday he seemed
like he was very focused and very aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' outing marked the seventh time in the 13 games on this
trip that the Yankees got a good pitching effort, and they won six
of those seven games. The Yankees won the first two games of the
13-game trip, and the last two games.
</P>
<P>
   Torre felt a rebirth of energy in his players Saturday, right
after Jorge Posada was involved in a fight with Tampa Bay's Bobby
Smith. Immediately after play resumed, Derek Jeter made a diving
play to his left, and it was as if that intensity carried over into
Sunday's game. Scott Brosius, the third baseman, made three nice
plays, and Bernie Williams and Shane Spencer both had running
catches, and Clemens was focused, working fast.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' rotation had been in shambles because of injury,
but now four-fifths of the rotation is intact _ Clemens and Orlando
Hernandez, David Cone and Andy Pettitte in line; Ramiro Mendoza is
the only sidelined starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been looking to put something together,'' said Torre.
``Hopefully, this will start us into a good streak.''
</P>
</TEXT>
