u e BC-GLOUCESTER0703-COX     07-02 1684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOUCESTER0703-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Massachusetts fishing town finds Clooney movie perfect
opportunity to put itself on map
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLOUCESTER, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   To shamelessly use the most overused adjective here these days,
this particular morning is beginning to look perfect. The sun is
peeking from behind long white clouds, and dew is giving luster to
the bright yellow snapdragons and multicolored pansies in tiny
gardens dotting this small, 377-year-old harbor town on the rocky
Cape Ann coast 33 miles northeast of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It's the last day of what local officials have dubbed ``The
Perfect Month,'' which culminated with the debut of ``The Perfect
Storm,'' Warner Bros.' $100 million movie starring George Clooney
and Mark Wahlberg. The film, partly shot in Gloucester last year,
is based on Sebastian Junger's immensely popular nonfiction best
seller about the tragic loss of the Gloucester-based swordfishing
boat Andrea Gail, which in October 1991 sailed head on with its
crew of six into three ferocious weather systems that collided in
the Atlantic Ocean, churning up 100-foot waves and creating one of
the worst storms in recorded history.
</P>
<P>
   Along historic, red-bricked Main Street, shop owners are
embracing the town's connection to Hollywood's latest hoped-for
summer blockbuster. W.E. Blanchard Jeweler's storefront window
boasts that its trinkets make ``The Perfect Gifts.'' There's ``The
Perfect Cut'' (diamond-studded jewelry), ``The Perfect Storm
Ornament'' (chrome- or brass-plated Christmas tree decorations
priced from $34.95 to $49.95), and watches described as ``The
Perfect Timing.'' Nearby, at Cormorant Gloucester, staffers have
taken a life-size stand-up of a smiling George Clooney, dressed it
in a yellow rain hat, white T-shirt and starry night-scene tie, and
placed it with the store's linens in a claw-foot bathtub.
</P>
<P>
   All this salesmanship irritates some who live here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's being used in the wrong way,'' says Melissa Bach, 34. ``I
get so angry I can't be eloquent on it. This is a story about six
people who died. It's called 'Perfect' only because it couldn't get
any worse than it was at sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Bach is owner and operator of The Perfect Tour, a $15-per-person
guided walking venture along the harbor she started three years ago
in which she talks both about the making of the film and local
fishing history (more than 10,000 Gloucester fishermen have died at
sea since the 1600s). She says she called Junger and asked
permission to use the word ``perfect'' with her tour. ``I wanted to
be respectful,'' she says. ``Anyway, storm and tour kind of sound
alike. And they share a vowel.''
</P>
<P>
   Bach's movie-and-fishing tour is indicative of major change
brewing in Gloucester (most often pronounced ``Glosta'' by
long-time locals). Many in this port of 30,000 see the 1997 book
and especially the new film spurring tourism to all-time highs.
Others cling to the centuries-old fishing tradition that has been
the town's lifeblood.
</P>
<P>
   The fish industry has been taking a severe beating. In the last
six years; some 1,000 fishing jobs have reportedly been lost
(tourism employment, including hugely popular whale watching
excursions, now overpowers fishing). Locals talk about a struggle
with alcoholism among fishermen. Rogers Street alone once held 32
bars, Bach says. ``It's a hard-drinking town.'' Gorton's, the
frozen seafood food giant here since 1849, now uses much more
Alaskan pollock than seafood caught off Cape Ann.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fish here is just not hot right now,'' says Steve Dunn, 37, a
buyer for Captain Marden's Seafoods. He's inside the Gloucester
Seafood Display Auction with about a dozen other buyers clad mostly
in T-shirts and jeans from various regional firms. Gathered for the
five-day-a-week, 6 a.m. fish auction, they sit in plastic maroon
armchairs in a large, high-ceiling conference room with headsets
and cell phones, bidding on yellowtail, lobsters, skatewings and
other catches brought in overnight from vessels like the Star Dust,
Captain Dutch and Sasquatch. Prices reach $1.51 a pound for this
day's catch of nearly 9 tons of large cod.
</P>
<P>
   Auctioneer Gus ``Butch'' Maniscalo, a short, burly and tattooed
gusto of 53 who punctuates each highest bid with his trademark
verbal flourish, ``You bought 'em,'' says the town's fishermen talk
quite a bit about ``The Perfect Storm'' and what it might bring.
Maybe tourism will benefit, he concedes, but ``it doesn't help the
fishing part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the media is fueling ``The Perfect Storm'' mania. The
Associated Press, USA Today and many others have written about a
potential tourism boom here that could be overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``What will happen with the movie is really anybody's guess,''
says Mike Costello, executive director of the Cape Ann Chamber of
Commerce. ``People have already been coming to Gloucester to visit
for the last couple of centuries (upwards of 100,000 tourists
arrive each year). There's probably been some small impact from the
book and filming. It's a little more difficult getting around on
the streets. But is that 'The Perfect Storm' or the results of a
nice day?''
</P>
<P>
   He says the area's collection of small motels and inns was well
into the summer season and operating at 90 percent occupancy before
the movie opened. ``From this period on, all the major
accommodations are already booked. There are lots of weddings in
August and September and those have to be done a couple of years in
advance.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every tourist and not even those aware of the Hollywood
tie-in ride in to catch the ``Perfect Storm'' wave. ``My son just
read the book but we've come today to meet friends and visit,''
says Joann McEnerney, 52, of Philadelphia. She's sure they'll see
the movie at some point but have no plans to scour the town for
memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Mayer and Elaina Carruth, of Cleveland, however, have
obtained a marriage license and plan to wed next weekend inside the
Crow's Nest, the one-time rowdy Gloucester bar depicted with great
fanfare in the book and film.
</P>
<P>
   The epicenter of the ``Perfect Storm'' migration, the Crow's
Nest is beginning to shed some of its rough, hard-drinking image.
On any given day, a small but steady stream of tourists in shorts
and T-shirts gingerly walk into the joint to sit on leather stools
next to the often unshaven, rough-skinned locals at the wooden bar
and dip plastic spoons into small lunchtime bowls of creamy chowder
spattered with squares of potato and bits of plump, juicy clams for
$3.50.
</P>
<P>
   It's here at the Nest with its single pool table, dart boards
and Keno machines that Bobby Shatford, the fisherman played by Mark
Wahlberg in the movie, hung out. Shatford lived in a small rented
room with stark white walls, a TV and shag carpet upstairs above
the bar (it now costs $35 a night). Wahlberg stayed there with
Shatford's brother weeks before filming to better understand
Bobby's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of dreams staying there,'' says Wahlberg, who
returned last week with Clooney and director Wolfgang Petersen for
a special screening of the movie in nearby Danvers to benefit The
Gloucester Fund, a confab of charities serving the port. ``I dreamt
about water and fishing and the town. It's the closest I've come to
a real-life family while making a movie. I wanted my portrayal to
be sensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   At least three busloads of Gloucester citizens traveled to
Danvers for the screening. While many praised the film, they also
found it hard to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was speechless,'' says Michelle Talisman, 40, an extra in
the movie's recreation of the memorial service for the Andrea Gail
fishermen. ``It's going to take a while for the magnitude of it to
sink in. At the end of the movie the audience was pretty quiet and
somber. I bumped into a friend at the after-party and she said, 'I
feel like I just went to a funeral.'''
</P>
<P>
   Petersen, who also directed ``Das Boot'' and ``Air Force One,''
says he wanted the movie to accurately depict the hard life of a
fisherman. ``We want moviegoers to think (the next time they eat
out) what's behind the piece of swordfish on their plate.''
</P>
<P>
   There is much of the town's history that moviegoers won't learn
from the film. It's the place that inspired Rudyard Kipling to
write ``Captains Courageous.'' Nineteenth century artists Fitz Hugh
Lane and Winslow Homer painted here. The Cape Ann Historical Museum
includes several of Lane's harborscapes as well as an 1812 British
red coat, the only surviving example in the United States of an
enlisted man's uniform from the period. The Gloucester Town Hall,
built in 1870, with its creaky wooden floors, boasts past
appearances by Buffalo Bill and P.T. Barnum.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, a steady stream of Portuguese fishermen,
Italians, Brazilians and Cambodians have diversified the
population. A spattering of Italian bakeries downtown sell
melt-in-your-mouth Sicilian pastry and cookies, including pinoli,
farfaletti and baci di dama. In 1892, the Portuguese constructed
Our Lady of Good Voyage Church, rebuilt in 1915 after a fire. Its
sanctuary displays nearly two dozen elaborate wooden ship replicas,
carved at sea by local sailors.
</P>
<P>
   While ``The Perfect Storm'' hasn't fully overrun the town, its
presence is everywhere. Near the harbor, Joe's Bike Shop has become
Joe's Perfect Bike Shop. Another store has used blue wrapping paper
and a 2-foot-long boat in its window display to re-create the
film's ubiquitous poster, depicting the Andrea Gail riding the
movie's monstrous 100-foot wave. Through July 23, Leslie Harrell
Dillen, 53, a local who worked as an extra in ``The Perfect
Storm,'' is putting on her comedy play ``George and Me,'' about her
repeated failed attempts to talk to Clooney on the set.
</P>
<P>
   But at Valentino's Pan-Baked Pizza at the far west end of Main
Street there is perhaps the most perfect respite from everything
``Perfect Storm.'' To attract passers-by, its outdoor sound system
is blaring music.
</P>
<P>
   It's the theme from ``The Godfather.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
