<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1271 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-GIANTS-BROWN-NYT &LR;      07-02 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-BROWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS REVISE THEIR OFFENSIVE LINE FOR MORE COHESION 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cruel, swirling wind at Giants Stadium, the harsh winters
and a desire to be linked forever to their Super Bowl past has
meant that the Giants in recent years have remained a pounding,
simplistic offensive team. Coach Jim Fassel has labored at
loosening that fixation, tossing in more multiple formations and
shifting tight ends and four-receiver sets. More screens and draws
and trickery. But what the San Francisco 49ers perfected in the
last 20 years on offense and what the St. Louis Rams exuded last
season in winning the Super Bowl has escaped the Giants. We are
talking speed and explosiveness, big plays and points and crispness
on offense.
</P>
<P>
   A personality. A presence.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants simply have not had either, and last season, with a
7-9 record, their offense nearly swallowed them whole. There has
long been a testy air among the Giants' offensive and defensive
players, a feeling that the defense rules and the offense sleeps.
Finger-pointing emerged last season. The Giants' offense needed an
infusion of talent and confidence. For Fassel and the team to be
ready for the 2000 season, changes were required. And the Giants
started at their core.
</P>
<P>
   They will line up this fall with four changes on the offensive
line. Only right guard Ron Stone returns at the same position. This
is like dumping the engine in a car or painting a white house a
bold red. The building has been gutted. The smoke is clearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not something that happens every year in the NFL
because consistency on your offensive line is supposed to be a
football requirement for success,'' Stone said last month as the
Giants concluded their last minicamp before training camp begins
later this month. ``We've got four changes on the line, and I don't
know how you would perceive that. I guess last year we all needed
to factor more as a group and obviously we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of last season it was Romen Oben at left tackle, Luke
Petitgout at left guard, Brian Williams at center, Stone at right
guard and Scott Gragg at right tackle. The lineup this season is
Lomas Brown, Glenn Parker, Dusty Zeigler, Stone and Petitgout, with
the first three players arriving as free agents.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' offensive line has been symptomatic of the offense.
It would routinely engage in false starts. It was short on grit and
fight. Often when things went wrong, the linemen would stroll off
the field, heads down and defeated. It was a troublesome signature
for an offense on which the leading rusher for the entire season
(Joe Montgomery) gained only 348 yards. That was a focal point for
a team that scored only 299 points; in comparison, the Rams'
league-leading total was 526.
</P>
<P>
   Lomas Brown could play a pivotal role in changing that.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive linemen have rarely been glamorous, but the left
tackle position is the jewel among common stones. For a
right-handed quarterback, the left tackle protects a blind side.
The left tackle should be a player bred for battle. And that is
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   He is a rarity: a 37-year-old player who is a seven-time Pro
Bowler and who is entering his 16th pro season. Brown, whom Detroit
selected as the sixth player over all in the 1985 draft, blocked
for Barry Sanders during 11 seasons with the Lions. In the last
four seasons, Brown spent three in Arizona and last season in
Cleveland. He is 6 feet 4 inches and weighed 305 pounds as a rookie
in '85, weighed 275 when he arrived in Arizona in '96 and weighs
280 now. He has had one surgery _ a knee scoped in 1989 _ in his
pro career. He is a marvel at that age and experienced at his
position. A player of striking wisdom, desire and character.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever Lomas Brown has been, teammates have sought him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nearly everywhere I've been guys have asked me to be their
union representative,'' Brown said. ``They come to me with personal
problems, financial problems, family problems. It's flattering. But
now I am trying to focus more on me. I've been through a divorce.
I've had problems with my daughters. Who do I turn to for my
problems? Well, I'm turning to me. I am under the microscope now.
I'm in the media capital of the world with a team that is asking me
to help give this line and this offense some personality and
presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``On our schedule this year I've got ends Bruce Smith of
Washington twice, Simeon Rice of Arizona twice, Greg Ellis of
Dallas twice. We play Tennessee and I'll see Jevon Kearse. I'll get
Cleveland's Courtney Brown, and he was the No. 1 pick in the entire
draft this year. I've got some work to do. This is an opportunity
for me, a make or break year. I get a chance to really project my
name out there. If I ball, if I shut down some people and we win, a
lot of things can happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never won a championship in high school, college or the
pros. Maybe this is the year I win a championship in the pros, in
my 16th year. This could be so very lovely.''
</P>
<P>
   Or it could all collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Will the aged veterans Brown and Parker, a four-time Super Bowl
player with the Bills who is 34 and in his 11th year, last the
entire season? Have the Giants added enough speed and scoring
ability at the skill positions? Will quarterback Kerry Collins
glow?
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the league has evolved, the key positions on your
offense are the skill-position people, at quarterback, running back
and receiver,'' said Jim McNally, the Giants' offensive-line coach.
``I don't think you can win with duds on the offensive line, but
you can win with average guys there. We're hoping this group will
far surpass that. Lomas gives us experience and leadership. He
knows how to play the left tackle position. He may not be like he
was in his third year or so in the league, but he has played
against a number of players and does not get rattled in games when
those fast ends come off the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been in the league 22 years and had the chance to coach
Anthony Munoz at left tackle. I have seen the good times and the
bad times for players and teams. You come to work every day and do
your job and hope that injuries won't be a big factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone said of Brown: ``Lomas is like a coach. I give to him and
I take from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown was told by the Giants' coaches that they wanted him to
show the other linemen how to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have some dogs up there on the line,'' Brown said.
``When I look at linemen, I look at build and temperament. I think
we have some of that. And with Ron Dayne running the ball, he
provides the force like an extra lineman. I call him R.D. There is
only one Barry Sanders, but R.D. has some of that Barry mystique.
He's got some quick feet on him. We've got the receivers and the
quarterback. We should be a scoring offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are counting on Lomas Brown to provide a lift. To
help give the team a face lift on offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the type of player that even downfield I am there to pick
up my running back after a tackle,'' Brown said. ``At practice and
in games, I want guys whenever they get tired and feel like they
can't push any further to look over at me. I think they'll find me
doing the right things.''
</P>
<P>
   Helping to provide more Giants offensive personality and
presence. A welcome change. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
