<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1273 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-6TH-GRADE-PRESSURES-A     07-02 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-6TH-GRADE-PRESSURES-ART-1190(4TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN IN SIXTH-GRADE, THE PRESSURE IS ON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Calif, N.C., Mass., Fla., Wis., Nev., Ariz., Mont.
Utah, Hawaii)  A Special Report.(EDS: First take can stand alone as an abridged
version. See also 6TH-GRADE-SOCIAL-PRESSURE)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT9 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JODI WILGOREN and JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lauriston Nunes takes sample SATs as if he was taking batting
practice, signing onto a Web site with practice questions a few
afternoons a week from his home near Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Chanel Meanor regularly startles awake past midnight, fretting
about overlapping assignments at her Silicon Valley school.
``Sometimes I'll wake up thinking something's due the next day,''
she said, ``and it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   After a Duke University basketball game a few months ago, Max
Mashore's father introduced him to a university admissions officer,
who told Max to take Spanish rather than Latin and sign up for
calculus as soon as possible at his school in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   These students have one thing in common: They are in
sixth-grade.
</P>
<P>
   On top of the timeless complications of being 12 years old, an
age of bubbling hormones and anti-authority stirrings,
sixth-graders today face a combination of pressures that their
parents never encountered.
</P>
<P>
   To understand how the country's continuing educational make-over
and the pace of U.S. society are transforming the lives of
students, The New York Times conducted round-table discussions over
the past six months with 221 sixth-graders, youngsters on the
bridge between childhood and adolescence. The conversations took
place at 21 schools _ public and private, cutthroat and coddling _
in 11 states and the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The interviews showed that with a college degree increasingly
seen as a prerequisite for a decent life _ and admission to
prestigious universities more competitive than ever _ higher
education has become a preoccupation for children even before they
reach puberty. At the same time, the students face new layers of
standardized tests that judge not only what they know _ and whether
they should be promoted _ but the performance of their teachers,
their schools and their towns.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about the future of the nation's economy, U.S.
educators have over the past decade imported pages from the strict
curriculums of Asian schools and Europe's elite academies, imposing
the rigor and seriousness of high school on the lower grades.
Though the United States has surpassed its competitors
economically, public dissatisfaction with the preparation of U.S.
workers remains, heightening the hurdles for students.
</P>
<P>
   In this era of earlier and higher expectations, most of the
students interviewed said they were driven to excel by parents who
had seized on test scores and early college readiness as new
benchmarks for success.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the students suffer tension headaches and bouts of
anxiety, raising questions about the costs of growing up quickly.
But a number of the students embraced this intense focus on the
future, saying it gave more meaning and direction to their lives
than idle hours in front of the television.
</P>
<P>
   They drink in the challenges like a first sip of coffee, a
tantalizing if slightly bitter taste of adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to strive for stuff that I know I can't achieve right
now,'' said Yesenia Mendez, 13, of Boston. ``I read harder books
that I can't understand right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesenia attends the Academy of the Pacific Rim, a three-year-old
charter school that has adopted some Asian educational principles _
children take martial arts for gym, clean their own classrooms and
are often rewarded or disciplined as a group for an individual's
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stay in school longer than my mother goes to work
sometimes,'' Yesenia said of the 210-day calendar of classes
stretching from 8:05 a.m. to 4:10 p.m. ``I feel like I need to get
paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Though New York City's prestigious private schools are well
known for their pressure-cooker atmosphere, the interviews show
that similar stresses pervade students' lives regardless of
geography or socioeconomic station. In fact, students at the
nation's most expensive academies seemed among those most at ease,
perhaps confident that their course in life was assured.
</P>
<P>
   The level of anxiety prevalent in sixth-grade lunchrooms
appeared almost to grow in proportion to a school's distance from
the ivory towers of the Northeast. Middle-class children in
cookie-cutter subdivisions say they fear that attending no-name
local universities will consign them to mediocrity, while minority
students and those living in poverty are scrambling to prepare
themselves for any college, a path pursued by few of their
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   In affluent Newton, Mass., and suburban Orlando, Fla., children
are already drawing road maps to follow their parents' footsteps
into the Ivy League; in the hardscrabble neighborhoods of Milwaukee
and New York, there are also sixth &UR; - &LR; graders fixated on Harvard and
Yale as their ticket to surpass relatives who never finished high
school.
</P>
<P>
   At a Muslim school in Atlanta, just as at a Jewish school in Las
Vegas, preteen-age overachievers sweat even fractional fluctuations
in grade-point average. From Nogales, Ariz., on the Mexican border,
to East Palo Alto, Calif., a ghetto bordering the mansions of
Silicon Valley, tutors and resume-padding activities have
supplanted after-school play dates.
</P>
<P>
   That means 10 more years of hated piano lessons for Lucy
McDaniel, 12, whose mother tells her that music improves math
scores. ``I barely even get to go outside when I get home,'' said
Lucy, who attends the Westminster Schools in Atlanta, where tuition
is more than $12,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   As sixth-graders confront these challenges, they also worry that
the school shootings they see on television will invade their own
classrooms, and they are saddled with new responsibilities in
families overwhelmed by dual careers or damaged by divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Even educators are confounded by this precarious age. In some
districts, sixth-grade is elementary school's finale, with recess
and classrooms as comforting as warm milk; Elsewhere, it is the
opening act of middle school, where sixth-graders switch rooms for
every subject and fumble with locker combinations while jostled by
eighth-graders topping 6 feet.
</P>
<P>
   No matter the setting, the sixth-grade curriculum is changing,
too, as teachers and parents push higher-level material like
geometry and geology, a trickle-down effect from high schools,
where enrollment in college-level advanced placement courses has
doubled over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too much going on in sixth-grade,'' said Nora Farley,
12, of Pleasantville, N.Y., in Westchester County. ``It's all being
crammed in your brain. It's too much to take.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are sizable pockets of students at private and
public schools who say they feel little pressure in their lives,
and who have given no thought to college. But it was only at a
one-room schoolhouse in Montana that the sixth-graders _ both of
them _ seemed confused by the very notion of pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Most schools were more like Mantua Elementary in Fairfax County,
Va., where the county requires a one-time class lesson on stress _
and how to deal with it _ for every sixth-grader.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to childhood?'' asked Ellen S. Schoetzau, 45,
Mantua's principal. ``The pressures on children are much greater
now than when I was teaching _ certainly than when I was in
school.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   THE VIEW: `IS THERE A BETTER SCHOOL THAN HARVARD?'
</P>
<P>
   One new chain of thought that runs nearly unbroken through
today's sixth-grade classrooms is the belief that a college degree
_ particularly a parchment from someplace with a pedigree _ comes
with a passkey to the good life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just see education as the way to get rich,'' said Keenan
Robinson, 12, the son of a tax appraiser and a secretary from
DeKalb County, Ga., outside Atlanta. ``You can't get a
multimillion-dollar entertainment company by being a bum on the
street.''
</P>
<P>
   Keenan, who used to live in New York, wants to attend St. John's
University in Queens, N.Y. ``That's all that runs through my
mind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With applications to four-year colleges, especially the most
selective, increasing every year, the intense competition over
admission is filtering all the way down to sixth-grade.
</P>
<P>
   Students like Keenan are not just ruminating about colleges;
they are researching them. In Las Vegas, Nogales, Atlanta and
Milwaukee, among other places, sixth-graders reported surfing
college home pages on the Web _ some with an eye on future majors,
others seeking scholarship opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really thinking so much about which college,'' said
Chelsea Hammack, 12, whose father is a Las Vegas police officer and
whose mother works in a casino. ``It's more, what am I going to do
when I get there?
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in a while me and my parents talk about what I'm going to
take for my subject that could help me with the job I want to do,''
said Chelsea, an aspiring writer (``fiction, short stories,
mostly''). ``I want to take something I'm interested in, but not
something that's so easy I won't learn anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea has been using the Web to compare Brigham Young
University in Utah with a college in Hawaii. ``I'm sort of split
between the two,'' she said. ``I'm actually thinking of going to
UNLV for a year to get a better chance of getting into a good
school.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why Lauriston Nunes, the 12-year-old Atlanta boy who
drills himself on the SATs, keeps going back to the Web site of the
College Board, www.collegeboard.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first few times I went there, I got every question
right,'' he said. ``It makes me feel smart. It lets me know that I
can do more than what I have to do right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Lauriston is already experimenting with a kind of higher
education: a school for models, Sundays from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. ``I
like being on stage,'' he said. ``I like seeing people clap for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   For other students, particularly those with older siblings,
weekend activities include leafing through college guidebooks _ or
even visiting campuses. Kristen Summerall is getting advice from
her sister, a high school junior.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's going to Spelman, I wanted to go to Harvard,'' said
Kristen, 12, a 4.0 student at Stephenson Middle School outside
Atlanta. ``Then I was like, `Is there a school better than
Harvard?' She was like, `Its initials are MIT.' It's in Michigan or
something.
</P>
<P>
   ``The farthest I've ever been is Virginia,'' she added. ``I want
to see more of the United States. When I was little, I used to tell
my parents I wanted to leave the United States and go to school in
Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   Some children are clearly self-motivated, but more often the
prod is a parent or grandparent _ whose success in life has set an
example that students want to follow, or whose failures the
children hope to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Max Mashore's pilgrimages to Duke, his dad's alma mater, began
in second-grade. Max went to a basketball camp at Duke last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole year I've been thinking about college,'' said Max,
a B student at Sidwell Friends school in Washington who was wearing
his Duke sweatshirt, as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to go to some small college in the middle of
Maine or something.'' he said. ``I heard someone say once, `C is
community college, B is state college, A is Ivy League school.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rahel Haile, 12, of the Ethical Culture Fieldston School in the
Bronx, said her parents, immigrants from Eritrea, were determined
that she achieve more than they have. Rahel's father, a grocery
store manager, went to Rutgers, but that ``isn't the best
college,'' Rahel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since third- and fifth-grade, I used to think I wanted to go
to Harvard, Harvard, Harvard,'' she said. ``I was looking at
Harvard. I don't want to sound harsh, but Harvard was just too
preppy for me. I'd rather go to NYU.''
</P>
<P>
   One might expect students at Fieldston, a feeder school to the
Ivy League, to have a college focus _ though perhaps not at age 12.
But what is striking is the nervous attention to college admission
_ fed by misinformation _ in schools elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Sixth-graders in suburban Washington, Las Vegas, Nogales and
East Palo Alto all believe, mistakenly, that colleges will examine
elementary school transcripts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go to Stanford, they might look at your records and see
if you've been bad,'' said Tuuta Tuipulotu, 11, who is worried that
his one-day suspension at his northern California school, for
fighting, might result in a rejection letter.
</P>
<P>
   For the college class of 2010, it seems, it is never too early
to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Ivy League schools, my dad always says that to get
into them, it's like a race,'' said Joshua Bordin, 12, the son of a
Pleasantville businessman and nursery school teacher. ``Let's say
we could put the whole grade in a race. People have to fall. People
have to stop to tie a shoe. But if you keep getting good grades,
you race and race to the top.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE TESTS: `I'M WORRIED IF I'LL GET HELD BACK'
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, it is AIMS. In Massachusetts, MCAS. Florida has the
FCAT. Virginia, the SOL. In East Palo Alto, there is the SAT-9 and
the R-SAT. Las Vegas spells it out: Terra Nova, which greets
sixth-graders just a month after they arrive at middle school.
</P>
<P>
   They are the standardized tests beloved by politicians, business
leaders and those who call themselves education reformers, and they
have sixth-graders nationwide chewing on their No. 2 pencils. The
tests are part of a concerted effort to elevate achievement,
leaving students far more worried than their predecessors that poor
marks could land them in remedial classes, in summer school or even
back to suffer sixth-grade all over again next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can feel the pressure,'' said Mark A. Valenzuela, the
principal of Desert Shadows Middle School in Nogales, ``from
teachers, administrators, parents, older siblings _ from older
students in the school.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be two years before Nogales sixth-graders face the new
state tests, the Arizona Instrument to Measure Standards, and four
years before they take a math exam required for a high school
diploma. Still, Valenzuela convened an assembly this spring to tell
sixth-graders, many of them the children of truckers and
distributors in the tomato industry, that their homework today is
critical to their AIMS performance.
</P>
<P>
   To Ben Larriva, 11, such warnings echo the daily mantra from his
teachers: ``This will be on the AIMS test.'' Ben, whose parents
unplug his computer if he slips off the honor roll, is warily
watching his brother's experience in eighth-grade. ``He can't keep
up,'' Ben said.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure is more immediate at the Menlo Oaks School, where
the have-nots of Silicon Valley must pass a standardized state test
in three subjects to be promoted and take the Ravenswood Stanford
Achievement Tests, a set of district exams, for three days each
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I take a test, I get nervous,'' said Jeremiah
Sagote, 11, the son of a truck mechanic and a store clerk from
Samoa. ``Not like a spelling test _ I don't get nervous on those.
Like the R-SAT test. I'm worried if I'll get held back.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeremiah's expression of concern about promotion was repeated by
sixth-graders across the country. And, with scores published in
local newspapers, students in several districts said they were also
anxious about what the tests meant for the teachers they love (or
hate).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sometimes the teachers have the tendency to stress
them out,'' said Clara Rice, the principal at Menlo Oaks. ``Because
the teachers will look bad if the students don't do well. Their
jobs are on the line. The principal's job. And the
superintendent's.''
</P>
<P>
   Private schools are not immune, either. At Fieldston,
sixth-graders have been taking standardized tests since
kindergarten, and they were frazzled by a recent math exam.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 30 minutes to do this test, which means we had like a
minute and five seconds to do each problem,'' Joseph DeJesus, 12,
said. ``Most of those problems took two to three minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocky Russo, 12, another Fieldston student, said he felt as if
he was being used. ``You think they could come up with a better way
to figure out if the teachers are doing their jobs correctly,''
Rocky said.
</P>
<P>
   In Fairfax County, students expressed frustration that a test on
Virginia history had squeezed other educational activities out of
the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to have an archaeological dig, make artifacts
and bury them, and another class would dig them up, and it would be
really cool,'' said Monica Kumar, 11, a student at Mantua
Elementary.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Monica's class spent two weeks reviewing for Virginia's
Standards of Learning test. ``The teachers stuck note cards from
every single event _ from when Jamestown was founded to Arthur Ashe
winning tennis tournaments _ they put them all around the walls,''
said Meredith Keller, 12, a classmate.
</P>
<P>
   With stakes so high, grades now count more than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a B on a homework assignment,'' said Julia Cohen of
Newton, Mass., a Boston suburb known for its stellar schools. ``It,
like, ruined it. I couldn't say I'd gotten all A's. Everyone was
making fun of me.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to get A's, then you might as well get them
all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, many families have devised intricate incentive
plans borrowed from corporate America and pegged to even the most
mundane assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Lipinski of San Carlos, Calif., used to write one-sentence
responses to homework questions. Then his mother, an emergency
medical technician, started paying him 2 cents per word. Now, Jon
says he can pull down ``6 bucks'' an essay. His mother also pays 10
cents for every page he reads, and Jon says he is owed $44.
</P>
<P>
   At Sidwell Friends, where Chelsea Clinton is an alumna, Cameron
Pastrick is striving to reach a B average by employing tutors four
afternoons a week. To stay focused while doing her homework, she
uses an egg timer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom's always like, I can't get you any more tutors, unless
you want one Friday and Saturday and Sunday,'' said Cameron, who
has had tutors since third-grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom went here. Whenever I bring home, like, a C, she's
like, `When I was your age, I got an A,''' Cameron said. ``I keep
telling them this, and they say, `We don't pressure you, we
encourage you.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
