<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1276 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TERRACE-COLLAPSE0703-     07-02 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRACE-COLLAPSE0703-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Early reports indicate structural problems caused terrace
collapse with 1 dead, 75 injured
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLE BASS ISLAND, Ohio _ The parties had just started warming
up when the music stopped at 4:45 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A terrace overlooking Lake Erie at the Lonz Winery, crowded with
about 100 people, collapsed in an instant, falling 18 feet into an
old wine cellar and killing one Columbus man. At least 75 people
were hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary report indicates a structural problem, rather than
overloading, caused the collapse, said Ottowa County Sheriff Craig
Emahiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``An engineer got a quick look last night and said it looked
like a failed beam,'' Emahiser said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Reighard, 29, of Columbus was dead at the scene when
paramedics arrived, after crossing about four miles of water by
boat and helicopter to get to the island.
</P>
<P>
   About 25 people remained hospitalized Sunday, most in stable or
serious condition, at hospitals in Port Clinton, Sandusky, Toledo
and Cleveland. One was in critical but stable condition at St.
Vincent Medical Center in Toledo, according to Ottawa County
Sheriff Craig Emahiser. Names and hometowns of the injured were not
available at press time.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday police tape ringed the winery as detectives and civil
engineers looked for a cause of the accident, the worst in the
popular recreational area since the landmark Beer Barrel restaurant
burned to the ground in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Police investigators picked their way through giant chunks of
concrete, twisted metal, dust and dirt in the cellar, out of sight
of onlookers watching from the land and boats. The cellar
underneath the 20- by 25-foot terrace was empty except for some old
wine casks.
</P>
<P>
   The Lonz winery was originally constructed in 1870 and was
remodeled, with the addition of the terrace overlooking Lake Erie
in the 1960s, according to Put-In-Bay Police Chief Jim Lang.
</P>
<P>
   In the moments before the accident, people were singing the
Three Dog Night song, ``Joy to the World,'' said piano player Larry
Read. He was taking a break from the piano, turning it over to
Darrell Wallace of Columbus, when the terrace collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came running up and said, 'Stop playing, the terrace just
collapsed,''' said Read, who has played the piano for revelers at
the winery for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked down and there was this big hole,'' Read said. ``The
people down there seemed to be moving in slow motion. There was
blood everywhere. It was absolutely silent.''
</P>
<P>
   Read said that Lonz management and staff and patrons started a
line passing water and ice to the injured. A staff member made the
911 call. By the time emergency crews arrived 10 minutes later,
patrons had pulled the victims free of the debris in the cellar,
said Put-in-Bay Fire Chief Mark Wilhelm.
</P>
<P>
   Middle Bass Island has just one ambulance and no hospital.
Rescue crews were called in from Toledo and other areas to help.
The most seriously wounded were flown to St. Vincent Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Jet Express, which normally ferries people to Put-In-Bay on
South Bass Island, diverted its course to Middle Bass to help
evacuate the less seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were lots of broken bones,'' said Jet Express Captain
Joe Lamb.
</P>
<P>
   After emergency squads removed the last of the victims, Read
said the 70 to 80 customers who stayed and helped all stood and
recited the Lord's Prayer late into the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing you can say is to be thankful everyone wasn't
killed,'' Read said.
</P>
<P>
   A man, who asked not to be named, said that five of his friends
were injured. ``Four are still in the hospital, one is very
serious,'' he said. He said his friends injuries included a
fractured eye socket, pierced lung and kidney, broken ribs and a
broken pelvis.
</P>
<P>
   The 120-acre Lonz Winery, owned by Paramount Distilleries Inc.,
has been closed indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
