<HEADER>
A1277 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-6TH-GRADE-PRESSURES-A     07-02 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-6TH-GRADE-PRESSURES-ART-4THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: encourage you.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE OUTSIDE FORCES: `SOMEONE'S PROBABLY GOING TO BRING A GUN TO
SCHOOL.'
</P>
<P>
   As high academic expectations hang over their young lives, this
year's sixth-graders have been distracted by outside forces that
did not buffet their predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Five months after the massacre at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo., Mia Grill stayed home from the first day at
Molasky Middle School in Las Vegas. She was nervous that it would
prove more violent than her elementary school because the pupils
were older.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom, she said not to worry,'' said Mia, 12, whose parents
sell tile. ``I'm still worried. Sooner or later, someone's probably
going to bring a gun to school.''
</P>
<P>
   In the New York borough of Queens, Christopher Bennett's mind
sometimes fills with doomsday scenarios as he moves through the
hallways of Public School 21, a tan-brick box of an elementary
school crammed with Eastern European and Asian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we do a silent meeting after lunch,'' said Chris, 11, ``I
always look at the door and imagine someone big and dressed all in
black coming through.''
</P>
<P>
   For others, though, the classroom is a respite from home lives
rendered turbulent by parents' work schedules or divorce.
</P>
<P>
   A cog in an increasingly mobile work force, Suzannah Mullen's
mother has been shuttled through four states in recent years, often
starting new jobs before her family can catch up. Suzannah, 11, and
her older sister stayed with their father in the Orlando suburbs
this spring while her mother, a human resources administrator,
commuted to Charlotte, N.C. ``Sometimes, I kind of search my house
for my mom and it's like, `Oh, she's in North Carolina,''' Suzannah
said.
</P>
<P>
   Joaquin Vega lives with his mother in Milwaukee, but said he
might as well live alone. While Joaquin likes the DVD player and
big-screen television paid for by his mother's job at a car
dealership, he said those gifts ``can't pay for the time she's
gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like her to help me with my homework,'' Joaquin said,
adding that he has never met his father. ``If we have teacher
conferences, she can't come. I was on the basketball team. I got
first place, and she couldn't come to the ceremony.''
</P>
<P>
   Kayleigh Wittman, 12, of Altamonte Springs, Fla., who is also a
child of divorce, gets a fat monthly allowance of $110 _ but she
said that had to cover all her expenses, from shampoo to school
supplies to tithing and saving for college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I write down how much money I use, and what I use it on,'' she
said. When Kayleigh worried aloud about paying for her future
education, saying she expects no further subsidy from her family, a
classmate seated nearby wondered, ``Why don't you just save all
your money for college?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because,'' Kayleigh said, ``I have to pay for lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   THE TOLL: SLEEPING BRINGS HER ONLY STRESS-FREE TIME
</P>
<P>
   At Mantua Elementary, a red-brick school a few miles down a
wooded road from Prosperity Avenue in Fairfax, Va., stress is part
of the curriculum: the county mandates a lesson on the subject for
every sixth-grade class.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent session, Suzzette Rodriguez's students easily
defined the word. ``A thought or something that you think about
that causes strain on your mind,'' Matt Wong explained. ``On your
body, too. Say you have a big test coming up. Your body stiffens.''
</P>
<P>
   But, echoing some educators, Jenny Drenkard said, ``A little bit
of stress is probably actually good for you. You shouldn't be so
laid-back that nothing matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Ranking the stresses in their lives on work sheets, most of the
students placed school difficulties and divorced parents highest.
(One boy offered a write-in candidate: ``Girls in general.'') When
talking in groups about their most stressful situations, every
cluster of children picked tests. As for the side effects, they
listed headaches, queasiness, anger, depression, insomnia,
exhaustion, lack of appetite and butterflies in the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   At the San Carlos Charter Learning Center, an alternative public
school in the Silicon Valley that does not use letter grades, many
of the 15 students interviewed, including Chanel Meanor, said they
had at least two bouts of sleeplessness a month because of pending
schoolwork.
</P>
<P>
   A coast away in Atlanta, John Hobart said that while baseball
was ``probably my favorite thing in the world to do,'' he had so
much homework this year that ``I get really excited when I don't
have practice because I can relax.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sonia Dahliwal, a student at Teague Middle School in
Altamonte Springs, Fla., is so desperate to get into the English
class for gifted students that it is starting to show. ``As you can
see I don't like eating,'' Sonia, 13, said with a sour face. ``I
have better things to do than put stuff in my mouth and chew.''
</P>
<P>
   At Oaklands Elementary in Prince George's County, Md., Calisa
Carter just dreams, every day, about being back in fifth-grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time that I don't feel stressed out is nighttime,''
she said, ``when I'm sleeping.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as Calisa yearns for the past, other sixth-graders are
already looking beyond the summer to the fall _ and the pressures
next year will bring.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Park, 12, of Queens, recently toured her new junior high
school, No. 185, near the elementary school that has been her
security blanket, P.S. 21. ``I heard a group of people there
saying, `I can't wait till Freshman Friday,''' she said. ``I think
they beat you up.''
</P>
<P>
   For many, the new school year will be filled with firsts:
foreign language instruction, math and English classes sifted by
students' academic abilities and junior varsity athletic tryouts.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bartomioli, 12, plans to play football, which means he
will be required to attend practice daily until dusk even though he
is very likely to warm the bench behind the bigger boys on the
roster. He is already worried about starting his homework _ sure to
be heavier _ three hours later than he did this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard seventh-grade is the hardest grade,'' Michael said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
