u s BC-BBO-VLADIMIR0703-COX     07-02 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VLADIMIR0703-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The invisible superstar
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He shares an apartment with his brother and mother,
spends hours playing video games in the clubhouse and seems
invisible to most of America.
</P>
<P>
   But Braves fans should learn this week what most French-speaking
Canadians already know: Montreal Expos outfielder Vladimir Guerrero
might be the best player in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the future superstar of this game,'' Chicago Cubs first
baseman Mark Grace said. ``He's the total package. He's a fabulous
right fielder, he's got a strong arm, and he's got great speed.
There's not one weakness in his game.''
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero, 24, enters this week's four-game series at Turner
Field among the National League leaders in nearly every offensive
category. Through 77 games, he is hitting .365 with 22 homers and
68 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe God reached out with a finger and touched him and
said, `You are a baseball player,' '' Expos outfielder Rondell
White said. ``He's blessed. God gave him everything to be a
baseball player. He's the best in the game _ by far.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Guerrero has played his first three seasons in the majors
in relative obscurity. He is the superstar television forgot as the
Expos aren't scheduled for any national telecasts in the U.S. this
season. Even the English-speaking citizens of Montreal are left to
watch only highlights of him _ the Expos don't have a local
television broadcast that comes with play-by-play in English.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero's inability to speak English and his natural shyness
have added to his obscurity. He speaks only Spanish and is
reluctant to be interviewed by the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Seattle when Ken Griffey Jr. first came into the
majors,'' Expos general manager Jim Beattie said, ``and they said
the same thing about Junior. They thought he was being overlooked
because he played in the northwest corner of the country and no one
ever saw him play. (Vladimir) will get his. Eventually, everyone
will know who he is, just like Griffey.''
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero is one of nine children raised on a farm in the
Dominican Republic. His father was a farmer and his mother a
housewife, until she moved to Montreal to join Guerrero and his
brother Wilton, an infielder for the Expos.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Guerrero dropped out of school before he was a teenager
and became a fisherman. At 16, he was invited to an extended tryout
by the Dodgers, who had signed Wilton two years earlier and another
older brother, Albino, before that. But Vladimir was sent home
after only eight weeks into the team's Dominican academy.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero got another tryout with the Rangers in 1992, but their
scouts reached the same conclusion as the Dodgers _ he was a slow
player with too long of a swing.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Ferreira, a Latin America scout for the Expos, gave
Guerrero another chance in February 1993 when he invited the
17-year-old to a tryout with 25 other players.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero hitched a ride on the back of a motorcycle and borrowed
spikes that didn't match, stuffing a sock into a shoe that was too
big. He pulled his hamstring after only one at-bat, but Ferreira
still gave him a $2,000 signing bonus and a minor-league contract.
</P>
<P>
   Ferreira might have been the first to notice Guerrero's
free-swinging hitting skills, which now have teammates and
opponents shaking their heads in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got tremendous plate coverage, both inside and outside,''
Cubs pitcher Rick Aguilera said. ``You think you've got a ball far
enough inside or far enough off the plate and he still seems to get
the bat on it. It's pretty incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't pitch around him,'' Grace said. ``If you think
you've thrown the ball a foot outside, he whacks it. If you throw
it neck-high, he whacks it. I've never seen anything like it. He's
an amazing hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in his second full season in the majors, Guerrero
became only the fourth player in history to hit more than 30 home
runs and drive in more than 130 runs twice before the age of 24.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents also are impressed with his arm, which some have
called the strongest in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Vladimir is in the game, you've got to be careful on the
bases,'' Cubs outfielder Sammy Sosa said. ``He has a rocket.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6 feet 3 and 205 pounds, Guerrero also has a tremendously
long stride and good speed. But he's still learning how to steal
bases and needs to improve his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like his durability,'' Expos manager Felipe Alou said. ``He
shows up every day to play nine innings. He's a good late-inning
hitter. I know from when I played there are players who do get
tired. But he gets better as the game progresses, and he gets
better as the season progresses.''
</P>
<P>
   The Expos are betting that Guerrero improves as his career
progresses. But unlike Andres Galarraga, Larry Walker and Pedro
Martinez, who were all traded by the Expos before the prime of
their careers, the team is adamant that it'll keep Guerrero, who
has three years left on a five-year, $28 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's for real,'' Alou said. ``At this age, I haven't had
anybody better. Before a player like him is let go, the team itself
will go. If a guy like that is going to be moved, you might as well
pack the last baseball and the last fungo and move the whole
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
