<HEADLINE>
SOME THINGS ABOUT SIXTH-GRADE HAVEN'T CHANGED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ga., Va., Ariz., Md., Fla.)  (With 6TH-GRADE-PRESSURES)  
 By JACQUES STEINBERG and JODI WILGOREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raychelle Burwell and this boy were going out. They did not
actually go anywhere, of course. Just talked on the phone, passed
notes in class. Locked eyes. Held hands.
</P>
<P>
   But all their friends at the Academy of the Pacific Rim, a
charter school in the Hyde Park section of Boston, thought they
should kiss. On the lips. ``They pressured me so much,'' Raychelle
recalled. ``I was like, `No, no. ...'''
</P>
<P>
   Then one day Raychelle's sixth-grade class found itself alone in
the room, waiting for the teacher. She was out of excuses. Their
mouths met.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you know, the teacher walked in the classroom,''
Raychelle said, horrified even in the retelling. The 13-year-old
girl landed in front of the principal, who called her grandmother.
``I broke up,'' Raychelle said, ``because I figured he was bad
luck.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the more familiar pressures of sixth-grade, the
backdrop against which the new stresses from standardized tests and
college competition are set.
</P>
<P>
   There are raging hormones and new responsibilities, the fading
of old friendships and the unspoken formation of cliques. All of a
sudden, appearance counts. Girls are trying on bras, some getting
their periods. Boys, meanwhile, eagerly await promised growth
spurts. Peer pressure, whether to smoke or to cheat _ or just to
fit in _ is ubiquitous.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not a baby anymore,'' said Ebony Rosser, 12, a student
at Stephenson Middle School in DeKalb County, Ga., outside Atlanta.
``You're getting more experiences. Nobody's going to take you by
the hand.''
</P>
<P>
   They are reluctant romantics. On the one hand, sixth &UR; - &LR; graders
long for the simplicity of kindergarten, when, as Meredith Keller
of Fairfax County, Va., put it, the only thing anyone fought over
was who got the green crayon. At the same time, they are newly
curious about each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``You walk down the hall, you see couples everywhere,'' Diane
Robles, 11, said of her middle school, Desert Shadows, on the
border with Mexico in Nogales, Ariz. Diane has even heard about a
relationship between a sixth-grader and an eighth-grader.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about to go very far,'' she said. ``Then they broke
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Boy-girl parties have begun, and truth or dare is alive and
well. In Queens, students were worried that on a coming school trip
to Hot Skates, a Long Island roller rink, you could not skate
without a date.
</P>
<P>
   The first French kiss, however awkward, remains a sixth-grade
institution _ but not for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had somebody,'' lamented Sean Ellis, Diane's
classmate at Desert Shadows.
</P>
<P>
   The budding relationships, such as they are, sometimes poison
longtime friendships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Patrick and Suzy's case,'' said Toni Grdovic, 12, who
attends Public School 21 in Flushing, Queens. ``They've been going
out for four months. And I think Tiffany did something with
Patrick.'' One morning before the bell, the girls hurled curses,
and a school security guard had to break things up. ``People were
screaming `Jerry, Jerry,' as if it was `The Jerry Springer Show,'''
Toni recalled.
</P>
<P>
   In sixth-grade, popularity is a varsity sport.
</P>
<P>
   At Oaklands Elementary in Prince George's County, Md., the boys
rate the girls, 1 to 10, and the 9s and 10s rule the school. It is
mostly about looks, but sense of humor counts. Elsewhere, the rich
kids with their Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch shirts are in charge. The
smartest students, once admired, begin their descent into geekdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's dorks and there's cool people,'' said Matthew
Goldstein, 12, of Teague Middle School in Altamonte Springs, Fla.,
outside Orlando. ``Before it was just you're friends with
whoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey Carmen's eyes were sad behind her glasses as she talked
about being picked on and left out. ``It's so difficult not being
popular,'' said Lindsey, an Oaklands student. ``It's one of the
most depressing things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sort of learning,'' Lindsey continued, ``that if they
don't like me the way I am, they can find their own friends.''
</P>
</TEXT>
