<HEADER>
A1281 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-KID-LAWYER0703-COX     07-02 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KID-LAWYER0703-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rookie appointed in high-profile case
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Having just seen his client convicted, the young
lawyer left the courtroom and walked into yet another body blow.
</P>
<P>
   A stern-faced juror in the hallway told him: ``We thought you
could have done more work. You stumbled sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' sighed the blond-haired lawyer, ``it's my first jury
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Earwood isn't smooth yet. But that's not surprising. A
few weeks ago he was a law clerk in the Bartow County courthouse,
assisting the judges, digging into case law, at times feeling like
the office gofer wearing a ``Junior Lawyer'' badge.
</P>
<P>
   Then suddenly the 26-year-old had his own office in the
Cartersville, Ga. law firm of Harris and Helton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was strange,'' said Earwood, sitting behind his desk,
wearing the lawyer's standard _ a blue pinstripe suit. ``On Friday
I was a law clerk and then on Monday I was trying cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Young, inexperienced, still crafting a courtroom style, Earwood
knows he is not a defendant's dream attorney. ``I'm a work in
progress,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd ``Bo'' Riddle knows it too. Riddle's 14-year-old son,
Thomas, has been charged with murder as an adult in the May 21
shooting of another boy. After the Riddle family saw they could not
afford a lawyer, the court appointed Earwood to represent the
eighth-grader, at no cost to them. Bo Riddle had hoped he could pay
a law firm out of his own pocket, thinking they would work harder
for his son. Now he is not only getting a public defender, but a
rookie.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Bo Riddle has been pleasantly surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's called me and gone over quite a few things,'' Riddle
said. ``He does seem to have an interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Earwood, for his part, is taking great care with the
high-profile case, bouncing ideas off the firm's senior lawyers,
talking it over with his wife, weathering some sleepless nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure I'm scared. I don't want to make a mistake,'' said
Earwood of his first big case. ``There's a lot at stake for
Thomas.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot at stake for Earwood, as well. If he wins, he
could score some hot-shot credentials. A failure, though, would be
long remembered.
</P>
<P>
   In their first meeting, Thomas Riddle told his lawyer that the
shooting was just an accident, that all the boys were playing with
the gun, that he didn't mean to kill 13-year-old Michael Wilbanks.
``He said that over and over - It was an accident,'' recalled
Earwood.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas remains locked up. Earwood's attempt at obtaining an
affordable bail failed; the judge set bond at $100,000. For the
next few weeks, the case remains in limbo while the district
attorney and judge decide whether to bump it down to juvenile
court, where the penalties drop significantly.
</P>
<P>
   But the media attention continues. Fresh into the big leagues,
Earwood has seen his face on the nightly news, his name under
banner headlines. Just the other day the news program ``20/20''
called him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's stressful,'' he said. But he prides himself on keeping
his cool. Not one to deliver podium-pounding closing arguments, he
believes a jury should be reasoned with, that when you lose your
head in court, you lose, period.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true for anything,'' he said. ``Most mistakes occur
when people get too emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a philosophy that has served him well.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a department store manager, the even-tempered middle
child of three boys grew up in a small town in northwest North
Carolina, not far from the mountains. In Fairview, there were no
traffic lights, and his television had only two channels.
</P>
<P>
   So he loves to talk; ``If anything, I tend to ramble,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing college as an economics major with a B average, he had
no plans for the future. But he'd always had a good memory, and the
ability to rise to an occasion. A friend was taking the entrance
test for law school and urged his soft-spoken buddy to give it a
shot. Earwood did, and did well. His friend choose another career
path.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating the University of Georgia Law School, Earwood
landed the job as a law clerk in the Bartow County courthouse.
While most law school grads head straight into private practice,
his unusual job choice has paid off. After two years of hustling
around this three-story courthouse - running down some court brief
for this judge, fetching a law book for another - he has earned the
good graces of the stewards who run this place.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just fit right in,'' said Melissa Walker, a judge's
secretary who acknowledged that when it comes to the fledgling law
clerks, ``I just sort of mother these folks.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, as Earwood strolls the hallways in a crisp blue suit
carrying his brown leather attache case, court deputy Bob Cauley
teases him, the secretaries make sure he has all his paperwork, and
the judges _ well, he keeps feeling like he's trying cases in front
of his dad.
</P>
<P>
   Earwood's first appearance before a jury was assisting on a case
a month ago in which a man was accused of fondling a child. The man
had denied every allegation to the police, only to finish by saying
that he did indeed touch the girl. To police, that's pretty much a
confession on a silver platter. But Earwood and his fellow attorney
argued that the touching was not intended to satisfy any sexual
desire. The jury set the man free.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pretty shocked,'' Earwood said.``It just goes to show,
you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   This latest trial - the one in which the juror gave him a piece
of his mind - didn't fare as well. For the first time, Earwood was
on his own, presenting the entire case to a jury. He defended an
accused child molester, Charles Hudson, a 45-year-old man with
intense look and a habit of mumbling when he speaks. The biggest
hurdle was the videotaped police interviews with the two little
girls. The oldest, a frail-voiced 8 year old, cried as she pointed
out the places she had been touched.
</P>
<P>
   He may not get jittery, but Earwood gets nervous. While waiting
for the jury to render a decision in the fondling case, he sat in
the hallway across from the courtroom. Each time the door opened,
he was startled.
</P>
<P>
   But even these seemingly empty hours were not wasted. An older
attorney came over and passed on a tidbit of local lawyerly advice:
A courthouse secretary meets her old friends for lunch at Wendy's.
These women know everything about everybody in Cartersville. ``So
just bring your list of prospective jurors down to Wendy's,`` he
said, ``and they'll give you the rundown on every one of those
people.''
</P>
<P>
   As the jury returned to the courtroom, he watched whether any
glanced at the defendant. That's a trick he learned as a clerk
watching some 60 jury trials. If the jurors avoid the gaze of the
defendant, there's a good chance they've found him guilty.
</P>
<P>
   A few jurors stole some quick glances. The jury foreman
announced they had found the man guilty of three of the six charges
of child molestation.
</P>
<P>
   Outside in the sunlight, Earwood talked about the criticism from
the juror.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did stumble,'' he said. ``I know I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Thinking out loud, he wondered what else he might have done.
Maybe he should have focused more on one of the defendant's
excuses. But that probably wouldn't have mattered, he said,
considering the girl's tears.
</P>
<P>
   Learning to lose can be tough for a lawyer. But Earwood has
adopted a remarkably patient, if not forbearing, attitude toward
himself as he comes of age as an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take a while,'' he added, ``before I'm smooth.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
