</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRY-POTTER-FRENZY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRENZIED WEEKEND LIES AHEAD FOR FOURTH BOOK IN HARRY POTTER
SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., name Sage-EL in last graf is CQ) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Planes gliding over beaches on Long Island and the
Jersey Shore as well as in Los Angeles, Chicago and Hilton Head,
S.C., will carry banners this coming Saturday reading, ```Harry
Potter and the Goblet of Fire.' Read it Now!''
</P>
<P>
   At least 9,000 Federal Express trucks will be deployed around
the nation on that morning by Amazon.com to help deliver 250,000
presold copies of the fantasy novel.
</P>
<P>
   The Jumbotron screen in Times Square will herald the birth of
the fourth book in the hugely successful Harry Potter series about
an orphaned boy with wizard powers.
</P>
<P>
   And the staff at the Blue Marble bookshop in Fort Thomas, Ky.,
will dress up like wizards and witches and begin doling out
cinnamon oatmeal from a black cauldron at 6 a.m. to waiting
families. Compared with hundreds of other bookstores around the
nation, that's late. By all accounts there will be tens of
thousands of sleepless children and parents _ perhaps many more _
showing up in bookstores late Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   At 12:01 a.m. Saturday, when the novel by the author of the
series, J.K. Rowling, officially goes on sale, small independent
bookshops and selected stores in chains like Borders are opening
their doors to Harry Potter theme parties with magic shows, costume
parties featuring characters from the book, stuffed and even live
owls, who are messengers in the novels, and at the Tattered Cover
bookstore in Denver, a brew of ginger ale and apple juice on dry
ice to imitate Harry's favorite butter bee.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are frenzied out there about this book,'' said Richard
Klein, owner with his brother, Bob, of the Book Revue in
Huntington, N.Y., one of the biggest independent bookstores in the
region. This Long Island shop already has an unusually high number
of copies of the book reserved _ 500 _ and the staff will unpack
hundreds of others just after midnight during a children's party at
the store. ``I have never seen anything like this,'' Richard Klein
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has anyone else in the publishing business.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first ``Harry Potter'' was published by Scholastic in
the United States in 1998, the series by Rowling has sold nearly 21
million copies, including the paperback of the first novel, ``Harry
Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone.'' The other novels are ``Harry
Potter and the Chamber of Secrets'' and ``Harry Potter and the
Prisoner of Azkaban.'' The newest ``Harry Potter,'' a 752-page
book, will be published simultaneously in the United States and
Britain with a first printing of 3.8 million copies in America, a
record. The books have been translated into 35 languages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The anticipation is beyond anything we imagined,'' said
Michael Jacobs, a senior vice president at Scholastic and the
executive in charge of marketing. ``The book has crossed over and
is now being read by adults now as well as children. The
anticipation has allowed us to have the biggest first printing in
the history of trade publishing.''
</P>
<P>
   The anticipation has also led to even more bruised relations
between bookstores and their main competitor, Internet retailers
like Amazon.com, which was allowed to essentially break the embargo
and open book crates on Friday to ship them by Federal Express.
</P>
<P>
   More important, beyond the promotion and hoopla generated by
Scholastic, the book and its accompanying huge audio sale by Random
House's Listening Library has led, say various booksellers, to a
remarkable resurgence of interest in books among children in
elementary and middle schools who have previously ignored reading
in favor of the Internet, video games and watching television.
</P>
<P>
   What is fueling the instant success of the new book is a shrewd
campaign by Scholastic _ and, for that matter, Rowling, who is
involved in the marketing _ to keep everything about it secret
including the plot and the title. It was only after the title was
printed in the British press that Scholastic acknowledged it. In
keeping the book embargoed and under military-style secrecy,
Scholastic drew even more attention to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each book has just ratcheted up the anticipation for the next
one,'' said Jacobs of Scholastic. ``We wanted very much to have a
specific on-sale date. We felt we could build anticipation to a
certain frenzy. As soon as kids finished book three, they were
waiting for the next one. If there was one date, we knew we could
drive a lot of the anticipation, the advanced sales and give
booksellers a chance to promote it.''
</P>
<P>
   And they have. At the Politics and Prose bookstore in
Washington, Susan Dexter, who works in the children's department,
said many parents had told her that they were showing up with their
children at midnight on Friday to buy the book. ``The more I hear,
the more I know there's going to be a crowd,'' said Dexter, who
recalled the visit of Rowling for a book-signing in the late
afternoon last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``People started lining up early in the morning,'' she said.
``It was like a Rolling Stones concert.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-00 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
