<DOCNO> NYT20000702.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT &LR;      07-02 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' STANDING DOES NOT CHANGE BUT THEIR ATTITUDE DOES 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mets will meet the Atlanta Braves in less than
three weeks, and perhaps by then the standing will have changed.
The Braves won Sunday at Shea Stadium, 10-2, to split the four-game
series and maintain their two-game lead over the Mets in the
National League East.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there is an important difference in the way the Mets
now see their biggest rival. In future meetings, Mike Piazza is
certain, the Mets will not press. These games are not so much about
the Braves, he said, as they are about the Mets themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what happened is, we just felt like it didn't really
matter who we were playing,'' Piazza said. ``I don't think we
really saw them as the Braves or the `Team of the '90s' or anything
like that. We saw ourselves as playing good baseball. Whatever way
you want to take it, that's a positive thing for us.''
</P>
<P>
   There were not many positives Sunday for the Mets, who were
humbled by Tom Glavine. Mets starter Glendon Rusch allowed 13 hits
and seven runs. The best thing that happened for the Mets was
probably when John Rocker boarded the Braves' team bus and left
Shea. One and all were relieved to be done with that story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to deal with a lot of nonsense that wasn't part of the
game at all,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine said. ``And the game
came to the forefront.''
</P>
<P>
   It did, with a boost from Friday's dramatic Mets victory in
which they scored 10 runs in the eighth inning, although Sunday's
game offered the least for fans to savor.
</P>
<P>
   After Melvin Mora reached base in the first by bunting for a
leadoff single, he tried to advance two bases on a weakly hit
comebacker. Glavine tossed to Andres Galarraga at first base for
one out before Galarraga fired to third to get Mora easily. The
shortstop, who figures to be the Mets' leadoff hitter the rest of
the season, is daring on the bases and was running on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way I play,'' Mora said. ``My job is to try to take
the other team out of concentration. Every time I hit a single, I
have to make it a double.''
</P>
<P>
   But this time, Mora's effort backfired. Instead of having a
runner at second, one out and the middle of the order coming up in
the inning in which Glavine is usually most vulnerable, the Mets
had two outs and the bases empty.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine retired Edgardo Alfonzo on a groundout, and the Atlanta
pitcher permitted only one single and one walk over the next five
innings. Piazza and Todd Zeile hit consecutive home runs in the
seventh, but those were the only runs allowed by Glavine (8-5). He
pitched seven innings, allowing five hits and one walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of pitchers that wish they could do what he
does, and they can't,'' Mets third baseman Robin Ventura said.
``That's a credit to him. It just shows you don't have to have a
98-mile-per-hour fastball to get people out.''
</P>
<P>
   The comparison between Glavine and Rusch is irresistible, and
when Rusch, the Mets' left-hander, is pitching well, his teammates
often note their similarities. Rusch (6-6) said he tries to model
himself after Glavine by throwing down and away consistently.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves were crowding the plate on Rusch, trying to take
away the outside pitch, and Rusch said he was probably too
conscious of that. He tried to come inside more than usual, to back
the Braves hitters off, but he left a few balls over the middle and
paid for it.
</P>
<P>
   With one out and runners at second and third in the second
inning, Rusch gave up a sacrifice fly to Walt Weiss and the Braves
led, 1-0. That began a stretch of five pitches that ended with the
Braves leading by 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Lockhart swung at the first pitch and grounded a single to
right, scoring a run. Glavine lined a single to left, also on the
first pitch. Rusch threw a ball to Quilvio Veras, then gave up a
two-run double to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were aggressive early in the count,'' said Rusch, who did
not issue a walk. ``I think they knew that I'm going to be around
the plate and throwing strikes, and they tried to get pitches early
in the count so they didn't have to chase a pitch with two strikes.
They're a good, veteran team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves handed their lead to Glavine _ a good, veteran
pitcher _ and the Mets knew he would probably not let it go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glavine, when he's ahead out there, is very difficult to have
a big inning against when he's on,'' Zeile said. ``His first-inning
E.R.A. is high, and after that, it's down to microscopic numbers.
The further the game goes, the better chance he has to keep his
team in there.''
</P>
<P>
   It all might have been different if Derek Bell had held on to a
liner by Reggie Sanders in the second, before the scoring started.
Bell dove to his right and gloved the ball, but it popped out when
he hit the ground. Bell said he joked with the umpires that the
ground cannot cause a fumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you give me that?'' Bell asked.
</P>
<P>
   They could not, of course. The Mets do not get many gifts when
they play the Braves. For now, they are pleased to be right where
they were before this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically speaking, a split here is OK,'' Zeile said.
``It's not maybe what we would have loved, but given the types of
games we had, it's OK I think we can live with that and move
forward from here.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-00 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
