<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKER-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKER GETS CREDIT FOR RELIEVING SECURITY WORRIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Rocker appeared in only one of the four games
with the Mets at Shea Stadium _ the first one _ and one of his
teammates thought that was the perfect outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 300 media people here and he pitches Thursday night
and half the people aren't here the next day,'' said Tom Glavine,
the veteran starter. ``That alleviated a lot of it. I don't think
the fans here are going to give up on it. And that's fine. If the
fans want to do their things, we expect that. But I think a lot of
the extra emphasis that was put on this situation died down after
John pitched Thursday night.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker would have been called into Friday night's game, an 11-8
Mets victory, but a callus on his left thumb broke open, and he did
not pitch the rest of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be an ongoing process,'' Glavine said of the
attention Rocker receives from members of the news media. ``This is
going to be an all-year situation. We want to make it a better
situation for us to concentrate on what we should be concentrating
on, and that's baseball. Hopefully, he'll realize that.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, his teammates hope Rocker will keep his thoughts
to himself the rest of the season and not stir the controversy
again, as he did a few weeks ago when he berated the Sports
Illustrated reporter who quoted Rocker's views on gays, foreigners,
unwed mothers and members of minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker did make an on-field appearance Sunday, warming up left
fielder Reggie Sanders in the eighth inning, tossing a ball back
and forth while a stadium security guard stood behind him and
several police officers hovered outside the door to the visitors'
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   When Rocker was finished, he flipped the ball into the stands in
the left-field corner. Members of the crowd chanted, ``Throw it
back,'' and a fan fired a ball on to the field. It missed Rocker
and skipped across the outfield grass.
</P>
<P>
   The police arrested Gregory Sweeney, 25, of the Prospect Heights
section of Brooklyn, and charged him with reckless endangerment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the arrest, Major League Baseball officials were pleased
that no serious incidents arose during the series. Kevin Hallinan,
baseball's security chief, said that he and his expanded staff kept
an inning-by-inning checklist to make sure they covered all
possible danger points. In addition, he said, his staff members
maintained what he called an area of control, from the bullpen to
the dugout, ``to make sure if he was in that area, we would have
things under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallinan said New York City police had been prepared to ring the
field after the games, but found that maneuver unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made that decision every night,'' he said. ``They were
lined up ready to go if necessary. But they didn't have to because
the crowd was great. There's so much to be said about New York
fans. They were terrific. They took the high ground.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-00 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
