<DOCNO> NYT20000702.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1300 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-HOUSE-FORMER-INCUMBEN     07-02 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-FORMER-INCUMBENTS-ART-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER INCUMBENTS BACK ON THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ky., Calif., N.J.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALD KNOB, Ky. _ Scotty Baesler hates fund-raising. Driving all
day on the campaign trail wears him out. He's never had a real
passion for writing legislation. And when he worked in Washington a
few years ago, he longed for the weekends to return to his
sprawling 250-acre farm near here.
</P>
<P>
   So why is the 58-year-old former three-term Democratic
congressman, fresh from a bout with prostate cancer, running hard
to win back his old job on Capitol Hill?
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss it, and I miss setting the agenda,'' drawled Baesler,
after greeting old friends and wolfing down a ham-and-cheese
sandwich at Wright's Grocery in this tiny hamlet that's barely a
curve in the road. ``Democrats need six more folks to take back
control, and I want to be one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ernie Fletcher, the freshman Republican who holds the seat
Baesler gave up two years ago to run a failed Senate bid, has
another theory: ``It's clear this is a fallback position for him.
Scotty's getting a reputation for being a perennial candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   In the battle for control of Congress, three of the most hotly
contested House races this year involve former incumbents who quit
to run unsuccessfully for other offices, and are now trying to
reclaim their old seats.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Baesler's bid here, Jane Harman, a former three-term
Democrat, is challenging Rep. Steven Kuykendall, a freshman
Republican, in California. And in New Jersey, Republican Richard
Zimmer is trying to recapture the seat he relinquished in 1996, now
held by Democratic Rep. Rush Holt.
</P>
<P>
   With Republicans clinging to a narrow six-seat margin in the
House, one or two of these tight races could spell the difference
between serving in the majority or serving in the minority. To
entice the former members, party leaders have promised to restore
their House seniority, dangled prized committee assignments and
recruited state officials to beg them to return.
</P>
<P>
   And for good reason. The powers of incumbency, including paid
government staff and free mail, are so potent that defeating a
sitting member of Congress has become almost impossible. In 1998,
98 percent of all incumbents seeking re-election won their races,
and only once in the last quarter century has the re-election rate
dipped below 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But in races pitting incumbents against former incumbents, the
odds for challengers jump sharply because they are often as well
known and well financed as the sitting members. Moreover, of all
incumbents, freshmen are the most vulnerable because they often
have not yet built reputations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Former incumbents know how to raise money, they know their
districts as well as anybody and they've been winners before,''
said Rep. Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I., chairman of his party's
Congressional Campaign Committee. ``They're more sophisticated than
your average candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep, Thomas Davis III, R-Va., chairman of the National
Republican Campaign Committee, agreed but warned of a potential
pitfall: ``If they left a seat for another job, they're saying they
didn't like that job.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaping back into the fray of electoral politics was not an easy
choice for any of this year's comeback candidates.
</P>
<P>
   After losing a Democratic primary for governor two years ago,
Harman settled into an intellectually stimulating life teaching
public policy at University of California at Los Angeles. She spent
more time with her husband and teen-age children. She took up golf.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when Gov. Gray Davis and party elders came calling, offering
her plum seats on the commerce and intelligence committees, and the
chance to help put Democrats back in charge, she said she couldn't
resist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of life in the Congress stinks,'' said Harman,
recalling the red-eye flights from the West Coast, late work nights
and partisanship that has only worsened since she left.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other side of the ledger is the future of public policy
in this country. And I'm a policy addict.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign wars were also far from Zimmer's mind. Since losing a
bitter Senate race in 1996 to then-Rep. Robert Torricelli, Zimmer
has practiced law, taught politics at Princeton's Woodrow Wilson
School of Public and International Affairs, and spent time at his
farm in Hunterdon County.
</P>
<P>
   But two years ago, after Holt upset Rep. Mike Pappas, a
Republican, Zimmer said that Speaker Dennis Hastert and Republican
leaders in New Jersey urged him to run again. ``Denny told me that
control of the House was on a razor's edge,'' said Zimmer, who
defeated Pappas this month in a primary of former incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans see Holt's seat as one of their top priorities, and
each candidate expects to raise about $2.5 million in one of the
most expensive races. ``It's going to be difficult because Rush is
a bright, hard-working candidate,'' said Zimmer, a social moderate
who supports gun control and abortion rights. ``But I have a record
of being effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Back here in the rolling bluegrass country of central Kentucky,
Baesler and Fletcher offer a contrast in styles. Baesler, a former
University of Kentucky basketball star and mayor of Lexington for a
decade, has a country-boy manner and homespun humor. His favorite
jibe at Fletcher is that ``Ernie is all hat and no cattle.''
Baesler is so frugal that he slept on a cot in his Washington
office when he served in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher, 47, is a family doctor and former Air Force fighter
pilot with a polished presence. He concedes that Baesler is
well-known in the community, but more for what he did as mayor in
the 1980's than as a congressman in the 1990s. ``Folks see Scotty
as a fish out of water up here,'' Fletcher said.
</P>
<P>
   That's just a taste of the sniping in a rematch of a 1996 race
that Baesler won by 12 points. Even Baesler doesn't put much stock
in that margin. Fletcher was barely known and poorly financed then.
Now, he has built strong ties in his district and is amassing a
$1.5 million for his campaign. Baesler said he expected to raise
the same.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``You cannot imagine how nasty it's going to be or how expensive
it's going to be,'' Baesler told a $200-a-person reception in the
Governor's Mansion in Frankfort.
</P>
<P>
   The race has already taken a few weird twists. The state's
largest physicians group has supported a tobacco farmer (Baesler)
over a doctor (Fletcher). The doctors are angry at Fletcher because
he opposes the patients' bill of rights in Congress, but Fletcher
has the backing of cigarette manufacturers, whom Baesler has
criticized for buying foreign tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Baesler is a fiscal conservative who supports gun control and
abortion rights, two issues that Fletcher strongly opposes. The
National Rifle Association and religious conservatives have vowed
to defeat Baesler. Each side has traded radio ads, with a
television bombardment expected later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The election outcome will likely turn on rural areas like this.
Step inside Wright's Grocery, where Ronald Wright, the store's
61-year-old owner, recalls when Baesler made sure that Wright's
brother, stricken with leukemia, received his Social Security
checks on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I asked him for something and he helped,'' said
Wright. ``I'm going to vote for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
