<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOODIE WINS FIRST TITLE ON LPGA TOUR BY TWO STROKES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABSECON, N.J. _ Taking a two-shot lead into Sunday's final round
of the ShopRite LPGA Classic, Janice Moodie of Scotland remarked
that she had been ``chopping at the door'' on the tour without much
success.
</P>
<P>
   The door broke wide open Sunday afternoon when Moodie fended off
pursuit from a group of golfers, including Juli Inkster, and
captured her first tour victory. She shot two-under-par 69 in a
round that included three birdies and a bogey for a total of
10-under 203, winning $165,000 and leading the field each day.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Moodie won by two shots over Pat Hurst, who shot
64 to tie the lowest round of the final day, and Grace Park, who
had a 67.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday's victory in the $1.1 million tournament, the
richest 54-hole event on the LPGA tour, Moodie's best result in her
three years on tour was three second-place finishes.
</P>
<P>
   She gained her first victory by refusing to buckle when Inkster
tied her for the lead early in the round.
</P>
<P>
   After Inkster birdied the first hole and Moodie bogeyed the
second to bring about a three-way tie that included Hurst, Moodie
responded with consecutive birdies on the third and fourth hole and
never trailed after that. She had birdies in the 4-foot range at
Nos. 8 and 9 that put her ahead by two shots.
</P>
<P>
   Inkster, last week's winner of the McDonald's LPGA Championship
and twice the victor in this tournament, had bogeys on the fifth
and seventh holes. Moodie reached 10-under at the turn and had a
pleasant walk the rest of the way on the 6,051-yard Bay Course of
the Seaview Marriott resort.
</P>
<P>
   Her putter and short game were outstanding. She made a 4-foot
par saver at No. 10 and 6-footer at the next hole after blowing a
birdie attempt past a tough pin placement. Moodie also made par
savers in the 3- to 5-foot range at Nos. 13, 15 and 16. She pumped
her fist every time she made a putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I putted solidly the last eight or nine holes to save par,''
Moodie said. ``I just decided to ride with it. It was fantastic
walking up on 18 and getting that kind of reception by the crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Inkster shot 70 and finished tied for fourth along with Michelle
Estill (68) and Vickie Odegard (70), who made the cut for only the
second time in her 16 events this season.
</P>
<P>
   Hurst, who won this year at the Electrolux USA Championship,
started the day at one-under, but birdies in five of the first
seven holes applied pressure on Moodie.
</P>
<P>
   The 64 by Hurst, the rookie of the year in 1995 after a
successful amateur career, was her best round of the year and tied
for lowest in the last round of this event, which celebrated its
15th anniversary. She had eight birdies and just one bogey, on the
second hole, the most difficult one on the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you told me at the start of the day I would finish in the
top 10 I would have been happy,'' Hurst said. ``To finish second is
really a bonus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
