<SLUG> BC-GEN-CYBERSPORTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIN SCULLY IS CERTIFIED CYBERSURFER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He works on a custom-made computer at his home
office, takes a laptop with him on the road and has access to more
Web-friendly hardware at the Dodger Stadium press box.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 72-year-old Vin Scully calls himself ``Internet dumb.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, he understates his abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Four seasons ago, the Hall of Fame broadcaster started using the
Net as part of his research. He actually started Web surfing before
stats-driven partner Ross Porter broke down and joined the club.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to believe, but Scully, the master storyteller who
seemingly wouldn't need to even touch a mouse, has found a way to
use the Net to give him more material.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily, I don't have an addictive personality because I could
see going in there for information and never coming out,'' Scully
said before a recent Dodger game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not hooked. But it does come in handy. I can get on there
and in 10 minutes get as much as would usually take two hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure this generation of announcers are the best informed
because of the Internet. When I started (in 1950), I'd walk into
the booth and the statistician would give me a yellow pad with the
lineup and next to that would be the player's average, his home
runs and RBI. And that's it. Not any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Platt, the Dodgers' Webmaster of the team's official site
(www.dodgers.com), has been Scully's Internet tutor from the
beginning, but it took some coaxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had been preparing the same way for 47 years and he said he
had it down pat,'' said Platt.
</P>
<P>
   But on Opening Day, 1997, the Dodgers were playing the Phillies.
Platt went to a few sites and printed out about 30 pages of
information on the opposing team within five minutes, then handed
the information to Scully. He was very impressed.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Platt was at Scully's home, hooking him up with a
computer and DSL line, then showing him how create bookmarks at all
the major sports sites in addition to Fastball.com and newspaper
Web sites across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, Scully asked Platt for a laptop to take on the
road. Scully finds that he uses it more to research teams the
Dodgers don't often play _ such as Seattle, this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's very computer savvy now,'' said Platt. ``It's
testament to Vin's desire to always want to keep on top of things.
It's been a valuable tool for him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
