<HEADER>
A1304 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SHARKS0703-COX     07-02 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARKS0703-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sharks not eating into tourism
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PENSACOLA BEACH, Fla. _ Wanda Boshers and her family arrived on
the sugar-white sands after an 8-hour drive from Nashville. As the
emerald-green water washed gently ashore, a wave of apprehension
swept over Boshers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always got into the ocean,'' said the 39-year-old
homemaker. ``But I'm not anymore. I'm not going to get ate up by no
shark. I'm keeping my arms and my legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not getting in it _ and neither are my babies,'' she said,
motioning toward her kids, 2-year-old Brandon and 5-year-old
Amber.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite two nearby shark attacks within the last month, marine
experts say the waters of the Gulf Coast are no more dangerous than
usual _ good news for beaches reliant on tourist revenue from the
Fourth of July weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a better chance of winning the Florida Lottery than
getting attacked by a shark,'' said George Burgess, director of the
International Shark Attack File at the University of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Even Chuck Anderson agrees. He didn't hit the jackpot _ but a
bull shark ate part of his right arm June 9.
</P>
<P>
   While training for a series of summer triathlons, the
44-year-old assistant principal from south Alabama bumped into a
shark as he swam in the waters off Gulf Shores near the
Alabama-Florida line.
</P>
<P>
   Based on teeth marks left on Anderson, biologists estimate the
shark weighed 300 pounds and stretched more than 7 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's training partner, Richard Watley, also was bitten but
suffered lesser injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Warming up at 6:38 a.m., Anderson splashed past pier pilings
destroyed by a hurricane. He bumped into something. A log, maybe a
school of fish, he thought. He peered under the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see that fin coming at you and think, `Oh, shoot,' ''
Anderson recounted over the weekend. ``They tell you when a dog
chases you to holler, No! No! Well, I did that out of instinct and
thought, `Stupid, he can't hear you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson pushed off the shark's snout. He yelled to warn Watley
and another triathlete. On the first of three passes, the shark bit
the fingers off Anderson's right hand. The shark pushed the former
football coach to the bottom, 10 feet under water.
</P>
<P>
   On its final attack, the shark chomped down on Anderson's arm.
The bull shark pushed Anderson onto a sandbar, 15 yards from shore.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling on the sand and shallow water, the shark slowed its
advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually broke my own arm off,'' Anderson said. ``I heard
the snap of it. He was gnashing back and forth, like in the
``Jaws'' movie. Once it had broken off in his mouth, I made a
beeline for the shore.'' He'll have more surgery in about two
months, but he's kept his sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a Timex in his belly so when they do a commercial
about it I want my share of the royalties,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Four days after Anderson and Watley were attacked, another bull
shark partially ripped the rear swim platform on a 22-foot pleasure
boat motoring west of Pensacola Beach. The boaters yelled at
swimmers to leave. Another bull shark beached itself 60 miles east
of Pensacola about the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of the attacks has made the rounds at the beach. But
tourists are undeterred.
</P>
<P>
   Inflatable dragons, pink water wings and silver air mattresses
bob on the waves with happy passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had heard about it but it didn't bother me. Most shark
attacks are overblown anyway,'' Alan Thompson, a 32-year-old sales
manager from Houston, said before paddling a rental kayak into the
Gulf with his toddler son.
</P>
<P>
   For the profitable Fourth of July weekend, the 1,200 hotel rooms
on Pensacola Beach are 99 percent booked, according to the chamber
of commerce. Nearly 60,000 people are expected to cross the bridge
from the mainland Tuesday for a day of frolic and a night of
fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Pensacola Beach lifeguard Wes Holstman said his crew sees sharks
nearly every day from their salmon-colored wooden towers. Guards
see dark shark outlines cruise 40 to 50 yards from the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The locals know there are sharks out there,'' Holstman said.
``They're everywhere. Chances are real slim they'll attack. There's
some dispute whether shark sightings are more numerous than in
previous years.
</P>
<P>
   Drought in the Southeast may be luring sharks closer to shore.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of rain diminishes fresh water flow from rivers to the
Gulf. Water closer to shore is saltier than normal, meaning fish _
and sharks _ that prefer the salt of deeper waters can swim closer
to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement patrols, however, note no increase in shark
reports.
</P>
<P>
   Every year throughout the world, there are an average of 75
shark attacks, said Burgess, the marine expert. Of those, only
about 10 are fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Burgess said bull and tiger sharks are plentiful in the Gulf.
They're dangerous because their teeth ``have serrations like a
steak knife'' so they can carve up their prey.
</P>
<P>
   Villainous personalties popularized in ``Jaws,'' however, are
inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `Jaws' movies were outstanding entertainment but
scientific flops,'' Burgess said. ``Sharks don't hold grudges. They
don't usually go after humans because they're not regular prey
items. There's no vendetta held by sharks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, remember as we use the sea, there's no guarantee that
it's going to be safe. It's not like the YMCA pool in Atlanta. It's
a wilderness. It's no different than going for a hike in the Rocky
Mountains and considering bears or going to the Serengeti Plain and
encountering a pride of lions. The ocean has its predators.''
</P>
<P>
   It's something Anderson considered every time he trained for a
triathlon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I got in the Gulf, it still took five or 10 minutes
to get over the apprehension,'' Anderson said. ``It's like walking
across the street. You do it every day of your life and you know
someone could make a mistake and run you down. You just never think
it's going to be you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do anything wrong. I was just out swimming in his
house and he happened to bump into me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-00 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
