<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-SURVIVORS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIAN RESCUERS FIND 10 PEOPLE THREE DAYS AFTER FERRY SINKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: No Byline) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ After nearly three days spent clinging to
floating debris, 10 survivors were rescued on Sunday after a
passenger ferry crammed with nearly 500 people sank off an
Indonesian island last week, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The survivors, the only people found so far, were recovered in
waters off tiny Karakelong islet, about 125 miles northeast of
Manado, the port city where rescue operations were based.
</P>
<P>
   The six men and four women were exhausted, dehydrated and
sunburned, said Udiyanto, the chief of the National Search and
Rescue Agency's monitoring center in Manado, in North Sulawesi
Province.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were clinging to debris from the ship, and only some of
them were wearing life jackets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers also removed the body of one passenger who was part of
the survivor group but later died, Udiyanto said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 480 other passengers are still missing, and the
survivors said they feared that the rest must have gone down with
the ferry and drowned, according to Udiyanto.
</P>
<P>
   The survivors said the wooden hulled boat capsized on Thursday
afternoon after its captain radioed that it was taking on water in
a storm off the island of Sulawesi, about 1,440 miles northeast of
Indonesia's capital, Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   The rescue ship picked up the survivors more than 60 miles north
of where contact with the ferry, the Cahaya Bahari, was lost, and
nearly 75 miles from shore.
</P>
<P>
   Navy ships steamed north Sunday evening toward the southern
Philippines hoping to find more survivors when rescue operations
resumed at daybreak Monday, said an official at the sea
communications monitoring center in Manado.
</P>
<P>
   The scores of relatives who have gathered at the Manado airport
awaiting news of the ferry were stricken on Sunday by the
confirmation that the ferry had actually sunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now, we had been praying that the ship was still
afloat,'' John Girobus, whose mother was on board, told the
Associated Press. ``Now we know it has sunk and only a few people
have been rescued.''
</P>
<P>
   The ferry had set sail on Wednesday from the far eastern Maluku
islands with 492 passengers and crew, most of whom were refugees
fleeing fighting between Muslims and Christians.
</P>
<P>
   The ferry was licensed to carry about 250 passengers, Indonesian
search and rescue officials said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   More than 2,500 people have died in an 18-month sectarian war
that prompted President Abdurrahman Wahid of Indonesia to declare a
civil emergency there a week ago. In addition, tens of thousands of
homes, buildings and places of worship have been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Military and police units have been unable or unwilling to stop
the violence, and in some cases have joined the fighting, depending
on their religious affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   About 290 passengers aboard the Cahaya Bahari were Christians
who had survived an attack by Muslims on June 19 on the main island
of Halmahera.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 180 people were killed in that attack, the worst
massacre of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300,000 others have fled their homes since January
1999, prompting fears of a humanitarian disaster and prompting
calls from Washington and the Vatican for the Jakarta government to
stop the violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
