r s BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-L     07-02 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF THE WALL: SHAQ A HIT WITH JONATHAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He sat on the sidelines with a cast on his left leg, the result
of a car accident the week before that killed his mother.
</P>
<P>
   But 12-year-old Jonathan Perez of Ventura, Calif., didn't want
to miss seeing Shaquille O'Neal on Thursday at the opening of his
Slam Basketball Camp for kids at Cal Lutheran University in
Thousand Oaks, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   When Shaq saw Perez, he pulled him aside and asked how he was
coping. Then he gave him a ride in his silver Lincoln Navigator _
one with a big ``S'' for Superman on the front grill and a vanity
plate that read MNOVSTL (translation: Man of Steel).
</P>
<P>
   Shaq also promised to send Perez a laptop computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was amazing,'' the boy said. ``I was so nervous. But when
he asked about my cast, I knew he was a real nice person.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaq said it was what the Thousand Oaks camp was all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to put a smile of the faces of these kids,'' he said.
...
</P>
<P>
   -- It's not too often a draft pick of a defending NBA
championship team has a shot at starting, but Mark Madsen truly
does. ...
</P>
<P>
   -- The Clippers do have a fine team. They should go in as
favorites to win the Pac-10. ...
</P>
<P>
   -- Nike will start sellin' a new line of foot protection called
Nike Shock. Here's the sticker shock: They run $150 a pair, with or
without feet in them. ...
</P>
<P>
   -- Whenever Todd Hollandsworth isn't playing, the Dodgers'
hitter in the leadoff spot often has a batting average lower than
the starting pitcher that night. ...
</P>
<P>
   -- Arizona wants Sammy Sosa ...
</P>
<P>
   -- If Robin Yount wasn't a Hall of Fame baseball player, he'd
want to be a Hall of Fame race car driver.
</P>
<P>
   The former Taft High and Milwaukee Brewers star, a co-owner of
P1 Racing on the Toyota-Atlantic series, said he ``always had more
of a passion for motorsports. ... I just didn't do it as well as
baseball.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   -- Waive the five-year waiting period and put Ila Borders in
Cooperstown this year. ...
</P>
<P>
   -- The 15-team Women's Professional Football League opens its
season Oct. 14. Closest team to this locale is the Colorado
Valkyries, which has no coach, stadium or start date for training
camp. ...
</P>
<P>
   -- Attention Sparks: More than 300 gays and lesbians took
advantage of a ``Pride Night'' promotion put on by the WNBA's
Seattle franchise on Friday night. ...
</P>
<P>
   -- Darva Conger or Dana Carvey? ...
</P>
<P>
   -- Seriously, how can anyone enjoy the performance by Robert De
Niro in ``Raging Bull'' after witnessing what he's done to his
career in the new Rocky and Bullwinkle flick? ...
</P>
<P>
   -- Roger Clemens' demand to be traded to a contender should
start ... right about now. ...
</P>
<P>
   -- They can break down the genetic code but they can't figure
out that the molecular structure of today's players is the real
reason why baseballs are leaving the stadium at the speed of light.
...
</P>
<P>
   -- Biggest scam going is companies that sell 147 versions of one
team's hat. ...
</P>
<P>
   -- A handmade sign at Shea Stadium was supposed to read: ``How
do you spell ignorant? R-O-C-K-E-R.'' But it had one of the words
misspelled. ``Ingnorant.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings to mind a quote attributed to Albert Einstein:
``Only two things are infinite: the universe and human stupidity.
And I'm not sure about the former.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tom Hoffarth can be reached at (818) 713-3661 or sptmediaaol.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
