<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-HARTFORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEGAY TAKES HARTFORD OPEN FOR SECOND CONSECUTIVE VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROMWELL, Conn. _ Notah Begay III accomplished something Sunday
that not even his former Stanford teammate Tiger Woods has done
this year on the PGA Tour. With a dramatic 23-foot birdie putt at
the 18th hole, Begay won the Greater Hartford Open to become the
first player to win tournaments in consecutive weeks this year.
Woods has won five over all and two consecutive starts, but none in
back-to-back weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It was Begay's fourth victory in less than two years on the PGA
Tour and followed his one-stroke triumph a week ago at the St. Jude
Classic in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   It was only appropriate that Begay, 27, whose four-under-par 64
Sunday gave him a 20-under-par 260 overall, a record for the
Tournament Players' Club at River Highlands course, would close out
his victory with a dazzling putt after Mark Calcavecchia had left
his 25-foot birdie attempt short by a foot. Begay's putter had been
a wondrous club throughout his round Sunday as he drained birdie
putts from 10 feet to his 23-footer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the highest of the high and the lowest of the low,''
said Begay, the only American Indian on the PGA Tour. ``To win two
tournaments in my first year on the tour last year and now two this
year _ that's been the high. The lowest of the low was the DUI
arrest and the week in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a reference to Begay's arrest in his hometown of
Albuquerque, N.M., in January and a subsequent seven-day jail
sentence on a drunken-driving charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an uphill battle, and it's made me play with a lot
of spirit,'' said Begay, who played at No. 1, ahead of Woods, when
Stanford won the National Collegiate Athletic Association title in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-year-old Calcavecchia, the winner of nine PGA Tour events
and five international tournaments, including the 1989 British
Open, finished at 68. He had entered the final round three strokes
ahead of Begay, but Begay drew even with his fourth birdie at No.
7. Calcavecchia then fell behind by two strokes when he missed a
four-foot putt at No. 11 for a bogey and Begay knocked down a
20-foot birdie putt at No. 12.
</P>
<P>
   But Calcavecchia, playing with Begay, made up those two shots
when he eagled the 296-yard par-4 16th hole, which he drove with a
3-wood and then sank a 4-foot putt for an eagle. That put both
players even at 19 under par.
</P>
<P>
   After parring the 17th hole, both Begay and Calcavecchia pulled
their tee shots into a fairway bunker 171 feet from the 18th green.
But both recovered by drilling 7-irons to the green. Calcavecchia
then lagged his 25-foot putt short. Begay, putting right-handed _
he is the only player on the PGA Tour who putts from both sides,
depending on the lie _ then rolled in his 23-footer for his sixth
birdie of the day and for a victory worth $504,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in complete control today, and I played a very
well-rounded professional golf round,'' he said. ``And that last
putt was perfect _ it had perfect speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention perfect direction.
</P>
<P>
   Calcavecchia, who has not won since 1998, said he was
disappointed. ``But I don't feel I lost the tournament; he won
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Triplett, who fired a course-record 61 Saturday, shot a 67
to finish in third at 264.
</P>
<P>
   When Begay was asked if he would go for a third straight victory
next week in the Western Open _ something that has not been done
since Woods won three successive events last November _ he said,
``No, I'm going to Wimbledon to watch some guys play on the
grass.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've got to keep the Stanford streak going,'' he said,
adding that Woods ``won the U.S. Open and now I've won the last two
weeks, so he's got to win next week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
