<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-TRIPPI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIPPI SHOWS BREAKAWAY SPEED IN VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Trippi, the horse named for a onetime football star
who could run with breakaway speed, showed once more that he also
could run with breakaway speed when he rocketed past older
sprinters Sunday and swept the Tom Fool Handicap at Belmont Park by
4{ lengths.
</P>
<P>
   It was the sixth victory in seven starts this year for the
3-year-old son of End Sweep, his only loss coming when he finished
11th in the Kentucky Derby. After that, he came back to win the
Riva Ridge by nine lengths, and in the Tom Fool he dominated five
older horses with widening speed all the way.
</P>
<P>
   Among the rivals chasing him were two sons of Storm Cat: the
long-shot Cornish Snow and, another length back in third, Sailor's
Warning. And in fourth place came the second favorite, the
6-year-old Brutally Frank, making his 55th start after finishing
first or second in his previous seven races.
</P>
<P>
   Trippi, named for the Georgia running back Charley Trippi, is
owned by Cot Campbell's Dogwood Stable and trained by Todd
Pletcher. He also had a hot jockey aboard, Jerry Bailey, who won
his fourth race of the day in five starts and padded his lead in
the standing to 52 winners in 131 starts.
</P>
<P>
   The horses set some blazing fractions, too, dashing the first
quarter-mile in 22 seconds and the first half in 44 2/5 seconds.
And they completed the seven furlongs in 1:21 3/5, making Trippi 4
for 4 at the distance and 5 for 5 with Bailey in the saddle. They
were no surprise: Trippi paid $3.90 for a $2 bet to win, and went
home with $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't race as a 2-year-old because he had a virus in April
and then some shin problems in the fall,'' Pletcher said. ``But
he's getting bigger and stronger with each passing month.'' And
Bailey said, ``He's only 3, but he's got a lot of talent.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 94th running of the Astoria, a sprint for 2-year-old
fillies, most of the sprinting was done by Raging Fever, who poured
it on for an 11\-length romp in a field of only four. At the
finish, they were spread out from here to there, with Rose Bay
second by 3 lengths over Best Mate, who had more than 9 on Zealous
Z.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hennig, who trains Raging Fever, scratched his other star
juvenile filly, With Ability, and kept both undefeated in four
starts. ``It's nice to keep With Ability in the barn and be
represented like this,'' he said in something of an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   Raging Fever, a daughter of Storm Cat owned by Edward P. Evans,
ran the five and a half furlongs in 1:04 1/5 and paid $2.20 as the
favorite.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
