<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PROBES AMERICAN OIL CONSULTANT'S ROLE IN PAYMENTS TO KAZAKH
OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal prosecutors are investigating whether an
American trade consultant funneled millions of dollars in payments
from major oil companies to Kazakhstan officials who are his
clients, according to a Justice Department document.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Justice Department asked Swiss authorities for
help in investigating the financial activities of James Giffen, a
consultant for trade deals in Russia and the former Soviet
republics.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, Giffen has been an important adviser to
President Nursultan Nazarbayev of Kazakhstan, a role that has taken
on larger significance in recent talks between the oil-rich Central
Asian nation and the world's major energy companies. The inquiry
also comes as the United States, Russia and Iran are competing to
win Kazakh approval for oil export routes for the country's oil
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department suspects Giffen of depositing $60 million
in payments from units of major oil companies like Phillips
Petroleum, Amoco Corp. and Mobil Corp., into Swiss bank accounts on
behalf of Nazarbayev, as well as other Kazakh officials and their
families.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say the money was then funneled to the officials
through shell companies in Switzerland and the British Virgin
Islands. The transfers took place between March 1997 and September
1998 and may have violated the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act as
well as racketeering statutes, the document said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giffen was the intermediary in these transfers and used the
Mercator Corp., which he controls, to facilitate these transfers,''
according to a 17-page Justice Department document, signed by John
Harris, the acting director of the criminal division's
international affairs office.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department did not say whether the oil companies
themselves were also possible targets of the investigation, which
was first reported on Friday night on the Web site of The Wall
Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Giffen was traveling abroad Sunday and was not available for
comment. But Mark MacDougall, a lawyer at Akin, Gump, Strauss,
Hauer &AMP; Feld in Washington, who is representing Giffen, said he had
not been notified by the Justice Department of any inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mercator Corp. has had a long-standing official relationship
with the Republic of Kazakhstan and its emerging oil industry,''
MacDougall said in a statement. ``Although these transactions are
complicated, they have been documented in great detail and closed
with full disclosure to everyone involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Messages left at the Kazakh Embassy were not returned Sunday,
and no one answered at the Kazakh Consulate in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Nazarbayev has been president of Kazahkstan since the huge but
sparsely populated former Soviet republic of 16.8 million people
gained independence in 1991. Under Nazarbayev's semiauthoritarian
rule, Kazakhstan has sought to exploit its large oil reserves to
build an economy independent from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, a consortium of nine foreign energy companies found
oil in a huge Caspian Sea field and began drilling to determine how
much exists. Nazarbayev was so optimistic at the time that he
predicted the field, called Kashagan, would help Kazakhstan export
as much oil as Saudi Arabia by 2015 _ 8 million barrels a day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-00 2059EDT &QL; 
