<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ENGINEERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT TO REWARD ITS BEST AND BRIGHTEST ENGINEERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an effort to reward its brightest technologists, Microsoft
plans to announce Monday that it has created a Distinguished
Engineer program, initially honoring 16 of the company's best
designers.
</P>
<P>
   Similar programs are already in place at Cisco Systems, IBM, Sun
Microsystems and Xerox as a way to reward engineers and scientists
who might otherwise leave research and development jobs for
management positions with greater financial rewards.
</P>
<P>
   In an electronic mail message sent to Microsoft employees on
Friday, the Microsoft chief executive, Steven A. Ballmer, wrote,
``These appointments underscore Microsoft's commitment to our
technical people as key partners in the leadership of the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   The position entitles the Microsoft researchers to a financial
reward package that is similar to that received by the company's
vice presidents, said Deborah Willingham, the company's vice
president for human resources. ``We were trying to be sure that
great technical people know that they have the opportunity to
achieve the recognition that vice presidents receive inside the
company,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The company will add approximately four or five employees to the
list each year, she added.
</P>
<P>
   For Charles Thacker, a former Xerox and Digital Equipment
engineer who joined Microsoft three years ago and is now involved
in the company's effort to develop a tablet-like computer, the
program will have little effect on his day-to-day work activities.
</P>
<P>
   He said the program will principally be of value because it will
chart a path for technical employees at the company, which now has
a work force of more than 38,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It demonstrates to the technical people that you can stay on
the technical ladder,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Thacker, who is the co-inventor of the Ethernet
office networking technology, those to be named Distinguished
Engineers include Butler Lampson, Charles Simonyi, Jim Gray and
David Cutler. All are well-known scientists and engineers who have
helped the company pursue advanced computer technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Cutler, for example, came from Digital Equipment to lead a team
at Microsoft that developed the Windows NT operating system,
beginning in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The others who received appointments as Distinguished Engineers
are Mark Lucovsky, Wael Bahaa-El-Din, Anders Hejlsberg, Antoine
Leblond, Suryanarayanan Raman, Darryl Rubin, Brad Lovering, Lou
Perazzoli, Michael Toutonghi, Peter Spiro and Mohsen Al-Ghosein.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
