<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ENID NEMY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After 25 years, my husband and I, who live in
Houston, decided to treat ourselves to a visit to New York. We made
reservations at the Plaza, packed our clothes and drove north. The
World Trade Center was looming on the horizon when I realized I was
still in travel jeans. ``I can't go into the Plaza dressed like
this,'' I wailed. My obliging husband steered into a service
station. I grabbed an overnight bag, darted into the restroom,
ripped off jeans and sneakers, donned navy suit, silk blouse,
heels.
</P>
<P>
   Later, we pulled up at the hotel's front entrance. As my husband
negotiated with liveried doormen, I pushed my way through the door
into the lobby, as elegant as I remembered it. Violin music wafted
from the Palm Court. The guests? Attired in jeans and cutoffs, they
looked more like delegates to a hobo convention than visitors to an
expensive hotel. The only person who was properly dressed was a man
with a badge pinned to his blazer pocket. Hurrying over, he thrust
an envelope at me and snapped, ``Take this to the manager's office
and then, for heaven's sake, go get your name tag.'' _ PAULINE M.
DELANEY
</P>
<P>
   POEM: MONDAY MORNING UNDERGROUND &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Every Monday it's the same old thing
</P>
<P>
   A race to the subways where the seat is king.
</P>
<P>
   Gulp down some coffee ... start on the way
</P>
<P>
   Everyone's equal ... we're commuters today!
</P>
<P>
   Hit the sidewalks with a steady stride
</P>
<P>
   Meld into the masses and stride side by side.
</P>
<P>
   Into the subways we charge with the pack
</P>
<P>
   The express train's coming . . . we race to the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Step aside and let them off!''
</P>
<P>
   The conductor commands with a snort and a cough.
</P>
<P>
   Then like a river that's over its banks
</P>
<P>
   We burst through the doors, grab a seat and give thanks.
</P>
<P>
   Usually accorded the swift or the bold
</P>
<P>
   A seat is a prize more precious than gold.
</P>
<P>
   _ JAMES A. WICHT
</P>
<P>
   BOOKSELLER'S ERRAND OF MERCY
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sterling received a frantic call from a cousin at St.
Vincent's Hospital. She asked for a particular inspirational book
to read before her operation, scheduled for that afternoon. Barnes
&AMP; Noble at Sixth Avenue and 21st Street had the book but delivery
wasn't possible that quickly. When the circumstances were
explained, the saleswoman said she lived near St. Vincent's and
would deliver the book herself on her way home. Sterling explained
that that, unfortunately, would be too late, at which point the
saleswoman said she would telephone the hospital and read some of
the book to the patient. She spent the next half-hour doing just
that. When Sterling's cousin returned to her room after surgery,
the book was awaiting her, together with a second book on the same
topic, inscribed from her new friend and a group of her Barnes &AMP;
Noble colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   SHOWING ON BROADWAY
</P>
<P>
   Fran Blazer got two shows for the price of one last month. She
was well ahead of curtain time for her Broadway show and stopped at
the corner of 45th Street where Broadway crosses Seventh Avenue. It
was early evening and in the middle of the intersection, a man was
on one knee, proposing to his girlfriend. That accomplished,
obviously with an acceptance, he placed a ring on her finger and
kissed her. A mounted policeman passing by stopped traffic and
another police officer on foot took the couple's camera and snapped
their picture. The happy couple then went on their way, Blazer went
on to her show, the policeman trotted off and traffic resumed. The
whole thing took place within the space of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   DUCK ROAMS GREENWICH VILLAGE
</P>
<P>
   Wolf Chanoff, my 2-year-old godson, and I first spotted the duck
the morning after a rainstorm in mid-June. He was standing on the
corner of 11th Street and Greenwich Avenue. He was not really a
very pretty duck, and he didn't do very much, like quack and waddle
_ which was the least Wolf was expecting from a real duck _ but
people seemed to go gaga over him. It was early on a work day, but
the duck gathered a concerned crowd. Bread crumbs were offered,
water was fetched, calls were made. Meanwhile passers-by would stop
and seemingly keep vigil as if the idea of spending time with the
duck before he was captured was important. Or they would just hang
out with the duck, kind of communing with nature. Wildlife at large
in the West Village.
</P>
<P>
   The duck, clearly an urban creature, then moved to Washington
Street between Bank and Perry. Wolf saves the soft inside of his
morning bagel to feed him; he's not the only one. The neighborhood
seems to be bonding over this duck. We discuss where he might have
come from, how he got here and why he stays, as well as what he's
eating and what will become of him. Every day there are missions
where the duck is officially stalked with a big net. This happens
while we watch, knowing it's best for the duck if he gets caught,
but fretting that the rescuers will be successful and take him
uptown to Central Park. Every time the duck escapes the net and
manages to fly away, there's a kind of silent cheer. Wolf shrieks,
``Duck, fly away.'' And I do myself, of course.
</P>
<P>
   _ LYNDA LEE BURKE
</P>
<P>
   GROWING GROCERIES
</P>
<P>
   Ronee Roffe is reconciled to the fact that her 3 1/2-year-old
granddaughter, Rebecca, will probably never be a farmer. Rebecca
and her father recently went out to the family's tiny patch of
green to plant seedlings. That evening, on the phone, Roffe asked
Rebecca what she had done that day. ``We were outside planting,''
she replied. ``What did you plant?'' Roffe asked. ``Groceries,''
Rebecca said.
</P>
<P>
   REMEMBERING BUTTONS
</P>
<P>
   One more button story: After my family migrated to this country
in 1938, one of my first jobs was working in a button factory _
dipping buttons. To supplement the family income, I took home
``homework.'' On steamy summer nights, the family went up to the
roof, equipped with a floor lamp with a long extension cord to be
plugged in at our apartment. Then we dipped buttons. The more
buttons we dipped, the more money we made. The buttons were white
and one part of the button was held between your fingers and the
bottom part was dipped in various colors of paint to achieve a
two-tone effect. The most memorable buttons were white with a
stamped red emblem we made for the New York World's Fair in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   _ RUTH AWNER
</P>
</TEXT>
