<HEADER>
A1322 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MEXICO-ELECTION0703-C     07-02 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION0703-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Voters in Mexico hoping for change
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CIUDAD JUAREZ, Chihuahua _ Standing in a sun-baked parking lot
next to this border city's main bus terminal, Art and Claudia
Sotomayor spent their Sunday morning in what would be a failed
attempt to help choose Mexico's next president.
</P>
<P>
   They had left their home in El Paso, where they moved five years
ago for a better life, at 9 a.m. Sunday. Three hours later, simple
math told them they were too late: more than a thousand people were
in line ahead of them; the polling place had just 750 ballots.
</P>
<P>
   But like virtually everyone else in the snaking line _ mostly
Mexican citizens from somewhere else, drawn to Juarez or El Paso
for better-paying jobs _ they would not leave until the last ballot
was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing you are seeing here is a lot of people wanting to
change the government,'' said Art Sotomayor, 28, who works as a
quality manager for one of the booming assembly plants, or
maquiladoras, that have sprouted in El Paso and Juarez. ``We're
going to stay until they say it's over. I tried.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard-fought presidential race had ignited Mexicans'
imagination as the frontrunners _ Francisco Labastida of the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) and Vicente Fox of the
right-leaning National Action Party (PAN) _ finished their
campaigns running neck-and-neck in opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   In Juarez, roughly 750,000 registered voters filed into 1,379
polling places, each with 750 ballots. But only three of those were
so-called ``special'' polling places that accepted ``transitory''
voters casting ballots away from the district where they were
registered.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico does not allow absentee voting for its estimated 10
million citizens living in the United States and other countries.
Thousands were expected to make the trip across the border to vote
Sunday, but the fact that only 64 special polling places had been
placed along the border was expected to blunt their impact.
</P>
<P>
   At the bus terminal, the first voters arrived at 5:30 a.m., two
and a half hours before the polls opened, and waited up to five
hours to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of Mexicans in El Paso who want to come and
vote,'' Art Sotomayor said. ``There's a lot of people who want to
change things in this government, but you cannot because you can't
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   LIMITED POLLING SITES
</P>
<P>
   Under Mexican election law, up to 15 special election sites
could have been placed in Juarez _ enough to handle 11,250 voters.
But an agreement between the political parties left this city of
more than 1 million with just three sites. The sites closed by
early afternoon when their 2,250 ballots were gone.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Javier Gonzalez, a PAN representative who monitored
polling places Sunday, said his party agreed to limit the number of
special polling places to reduce the chance of fraud by people
using fake voter cards. Regular polling places, unlike the special
locations, check voters against a list of people registered in that
district.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to give the people from out of town the opportunity to
vote, but we don't trust the (PRI),'' Javier said.
</P>
<P>
   Across town at another special polling place, this one at a
graffiti-stained school with barred windows, a line that began with
50 people at 7:30 a.m. had swelled to more than 600 three hours
later. As the stacks of ballots dwindled, Hector Sandoval stood
patiently for his turn to cast a vote he hoped would change the
course of his country's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the young people want a change,'' said Sandoval, a
21-year-old student at the University of Texas-El Paso who was born
in Austin and has dual citizenship. ``Mexico is tired of corruption
with impunity, of fraud, of economic crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Those at the end of the line, which stretched for three blocks,
knew they had probably come for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know we're going to change the country with our vote, and
that's why I think they didn't want to expand the number of
ballots,'' said Emilio Lacedelli, 43, a native of Guanajuato state
who works in El Paso. ``Seven hundred and fifty ballots is
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Farther back in line, Servando Torres, 34, talked about leaving
his wife and three children in Oaxaca, a state in southern Mexico,
more than a year ago to look for work in Juarez. He sees them every
six months. Now he wanted to send a message to the government he
blames for Oaxaca's chronic poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want more of the same promises and promises,'' Torres
said. ``It's beautiful (in Oaxaca) but there's no work. My family
is disintegrating because of this, and it's the goverment's
fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the school, four election workers wrote down the name and
voter number of each person, handed them paper ballots, and pointed
them to a plastic voting stall with folding legs that could
accommodate two voters at a time.
</P>
<P>
   After marking their ballots, voters dropped them in the
appropriate boxes _ one for president, one for the Senate, one for
Congress _ before a worker punched a hole in their voter card and
marked their right thumb with indelible ink to discourage repeat
voting.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, tempers grew shorter in the sun. Inside, the
``president'' of the voting place, a volunteer named Adan Gamez
Tremillo, patiently listened to complaints about the snail's pace
and the hundreds of people baking outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be mad because there's not enough ballots,''
said Gamez, a baby-faced 27-year-old engineer at a Juarez
maquiladora. ``But there's nothing we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
