u i BC-MEXICO-BORDER-NYT &LR;      07-02 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BORDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICANS FROM THE U.S. LINE UP TO VOTE IN TIJUANA 
</HEADLINE>
   (With MEXICO-ELECTION)  
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIJUANA, Mexico _ They began arriving before dawn, crossing
south over the border in cars and pickup trucks and small caravans,
with an unusual degree of optimism in their hearts and their voter
registration cards in their wallets.
</P>
<P>
   They were Mexicans who live in the United States returning to
elect a new president, drawn by the possibility that the somewhat
paradoxically named Institutional Revolutionary Party would lose
the presidency for the first time since it was founded 71 years
ago. Since Mexico does not have absentee ballots, they had to come
from as far away as San Francisco, Washington and Chicago to cast
their ballots at special polling places for out-of-district voters
that were set up here and in several other cities along the
2,000-mile border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want change,'' said Ramiro Ramirez, a 48-year-old
mechanic from Fontana, Calif., who arrived late Saturday night to
ensure that he would get a good spot in line at one of the special
polling sites Sunday. Ramirez, who left his home state of Michoacan
for the United States as a child, said he had made the trip Sunday
because he is thinking of his own future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all left because of the same problems,'' he said. ``But I
would like to go back someday. And if the government changes, if
things get better, if there's work, I will return.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time his turn came here, at 9 this morning, to pick up a
paper ballot, fill it out in a cardboard booth behind a plastic
curtain that said ``The Vote is Free and Secret,'' and stuff the
folded ballot into a cardboard box with a clear plastic window on
each side, roughly 250 people were waiting behind him, many of them
from California as well.
</P>
<P>
   Their polling place, outside an all-night drugstore, was one of
15 in Tijuana where Mexicans away from home could vote. They wore
cowboy hats and Dallas Cowboys hats, pearl-buttoned shirts and Hard
Rock Cafe T-shirts, cowboy boots and Air Jordans. They came, they
said, out of a belief that this year's election would be different
from those in the past that were tainted by fraud. An opposition
candidate, Vicente Fox Quesada, was virtually tied in the polls
with the nominee of the governing party, Francisco Labastida Ochoa.
</P>
<P>
   The vote is to be counted for the first time by an autonomous
group, the Federal Elections Institute, rather than by a branch of
the government controlled by the governing party. And many Mexicans
north of the border were the targets of advertising and even
campaign stops by the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think change is really possible this time,'' said Gabriel
Castellanos, 26, who arrived here at 6:30 a.m. after driving down
from Huntington Beach, Calif., with his wife, Miriam Sanchez, 19,
to vote for Fox. ``The government was pressured to hold elections
that everyone can believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   Fausto Soriano, 60, who came from San Francisco with four
friends to vote for Fox, said, ``I think this will be a cleaner
election.''
</P>
<P>
   The election dominated Tijuana this weekend. There were the long
lines at polling places and the influx of voters from north of the
border, and most striking of all, there was no drinking allowed.
The government imposed a dry law until after the elections.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a switch for a place that began its rapid growth,
from a village to a city of 1.5 million people, during Prohibition,
when Californians made this a favorite place for a boozy weekend
getaway.
</P>
<P>
   Without the usual rowdy revelry, the voters stood out even more
than usual. The great fear expressed among them was that there
would not be enough ballots to go around; an old voting-law reform,
aimed at preventing fraud by ballot-stuffing, limits the number of
ballots at each polling place to 750.
</P>
<P>
   With only 15 sites in Tijuana where people could vote away from
home, the maximum number of ballots available to them here would be
11,250. And some of those would be cast by people who live in
Mexico _ soldiers, business travelers, people who moved but had not
registered their new addresses.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Jacqueline Vargas, 26, set her alarm clock at home
in Garden Grove, Calif., for 3:40 a.m. She was so worried about
oversleeping that she awakened on her own at 2:30. Vargas, who left
her home in Monterrey four years ago for a marketing job in the
United States, said she had followed the campaign online.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I graduated from the university, my aim was to move
abroad as soon as I could,'' she said. ``I didn't like the
situation either politically or economically. I didn't see much
future for myself there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans living in the United States were assiduously courted
for their votes this year for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The democratic process of Mexico is finally permeating north
of the border, making us Mexican citizens aware of what's happening
politically in our country,'' said Luis Pelayo, the president of
the Hispanic Council in Chicago, who helped organize several
caravans to cross the Texas border.
</P>
<P>
   Of the estimated 10 million Mexicans who live in the United
States, 1.5 million are believed to be eligible to vote. No one
expected that many people to cross the border to vote _ in fact,
fewer than 75,000 ballots were available at the special polling
sites.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mexicans living in the United States were wooed not only
for their votes but for their influence. Many of them still hold
sway in the villages they left behind and with the families they
support with money each month. By some estimates, Mexicans abroad
send $7 billion home each year. They like to point out that this
makes them Mexico's third highest source of income, after petroleum
and tourism.
</P>
<P>
   When Vargas called home, she said, she was disappointed when her
father told her that he would vote for the governing party. ``He
just told me, `They've done so much for us,''' she said. ``I
couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a sore point among many Mexicans in the United States
that Mexico lacks an absentee ballot. A bill that would have
created one stalled last year in the Mexican Senate, which is
controlled by the governing party.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Ross Pineda, who lives in Chicago and is taking the unusual
step of running for the Mexican Congress this year to represent the
interests of Mexicans abroad, wrote a book on the issue called
``Vote Without Borders,'' to call for an absentee ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legally we are Mexican citizens; we have the right to vote, we
love Mexico, we have families there that we sustain,'' Ross said.
``We are not asking for any special privilege.
</P>
<P>
   But without the absentee ballot, many Mexicans living north of
the border simply took to the road. ``Look at this,'' said Hector
Alvarado, 45, a Cardenas supporter from Maywood, Calif., pointing
to a line of Mexicans from the United States that stretched nearly
an entire city block here. ``This isn't a rock concert or a
football match. These are people who want to vote.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
