<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1326 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-RURAL-VOTES-NY     07-02 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-RURAL-VOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ANXIOUS VIGIL IN MEXICO'S POLITICAL TRENCHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MEXICO-ELECTION, MEXICO-BORDER) 
 By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORIZABA, Mexico _ Deep in the trenches of Sunday's elections,
Gerardo Mellado served his party as a sort of 911 operator, manning
a two-way radio that crackled with calls for help from the rural
communities in the mountains that surround this city of 120,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   The elections were expected to be the freest, most transparent
political contests in Mexican history. And Mellado, of the
opposition National Action Party, known as PAN, aimed to protect
each ballot cast for his side from the kind of chicanery that many
say has helped to keep the ruling Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI, in power since 1929.
</P>
<P>
   ``I copy, I copy,'' Mellado told a caller from Mariano Escobedo,
a farming village. ``They are letting people vote without the
proper credentials? I am sending a lawyer with a videocamera right
away. Do you copy?''
</P>
<P>
   In the contest between the PAN candidate for president, Vicente
Fox, and the candidate for the PRI, Francisco Labastida, some of
the most ferocious conflicts have arisen in places like this,
situated at the western edge of the state of Veracruz. Most of the
cities in this state, including Orizaba, have PAN mayors. But due
to the steadfast support for the PRI in the rural communities, the
governor of Veracruz, Miguel Aleman, is a member of the PRI, as are
most members of the state's congressional delegation.
</P>
<P>
   For Fox and the PAN's candidates for Congress to win Veracruz _
the state with the third-highest number of eligible voters in
Mexico _ workers like Mellado focused on safeguarding their party's
small, but growing, rural support.
</P>
<P>
   ``The votes out there will mean the difference between winning
and losing for us,'' said Francisco Briseno Cortes, who is
president of the PAN in Orizaba. ``The PRI still has a lot of ways
to try to manipulate the people out there, because they are
isolated and afraid. So we have to make sure we watch over the
brave minority who support us.''
</P>
<P>
   Local leaders of the PRI, like Rudolfo Freeman, were just as
determined not to lose any of the territory that has been one of
their party's bastions of power _ the poor, little-educated
communities that live mostly on their crops and on government
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the PAN governs has not convinced the people in the
countryside,'' Freeman said, before hopping into a car full of PRI
campaign workers to go and monitor rural polling places. ``We are
going to win, and we are going to win by more votes than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many polls opened at least half an hour later than
scheduled, voting around Orizaba proceeded without any significant
disturbances reported. Over the radio, PAN and PRI officials
exchanged numerous accusations of coercion and manipulation of
voters, but when pressed for proof neither side had any to offer.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks prior to the election, however, the campaigns had
been explosive. Just over a week ago, the mayor of Orizaba, a
surgeon and PAN member named Angel Escudero, seized a truckload of
4,500 sheets of metal sent to the city by the PRI governor, Aleman.
The metal, marked for the attention of the ruling party's candidate
for Congress, was to be distributed to poor farmers for mending
their ramshackle homes.
</P>
<P>
   PRI officials called the delivery ``a coincidence.'' Escudero,
65, said: ``It was a crime. We had always known the PRI used
government supplies to try to buy votes, but now we had proof.''
</P>
<P>
   After Escudero intercepted the metal, local PRI leaders led
protests that shut down the city hall for two days. Demonstrators
threw eggs at the windows of Escudero's small hospital and another
angry mob tried to enter his home.
</P>
<P>
   Another heated clash erupted just hours before the polls were to
open Sunday over whether PAN members with radios and cameras had a
right to keep watch on the trucking company of a PRI candidate the
opposition suspected of shipping food and building materials to
poor farmers.
</P>
<P>
   By the time polls opened, officials in both parties had taken up
positions in even the farthest election outposts.
</P>
<P>
   Some 300,000 people live in the communities of brightly painted
concrete block houses _ known to residents by the color of their
exteriors rather than by addresses _ outside Orizaba and at the
base of the tallest volcano in Mexico. They are mostly farmers, who
grow flowers, potatoes and corn on a few acres. A few residents
work from home as butchers or seamstresses, or operating taco
stands or minimarkets. Most of those interviewed said they earned
less than $4 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Almost unanimously, they complain about living in poverty and
about feeling abandoned by the government _ except at election
time. In a sign of the growing popularity of opposition parties,
many of them expressed desires for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents have supported the PRI as long as I have been
alive, and we live in the same misery as always,'' said Alvaro
Gonzalez, 24, a member of the PAN who hopes to run for mayor of
Mariano Escobedo later this year. ``Most of us make just enough to
eat. So when our children say they want to go study at a
university, we know that such things are impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 400 residents of Mariano Escobedo started election day
at church, where the Rev. Ruben Gomez told the congregants that
their votes were worth much more than the bread, clothes or
construction materials they had been offered.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Luis Quijano, a 32-year-old potato farmer, said he would
vote for the PAN. In front of the church, he pointed to a simple
block of a building with no windows and a collapsed roof. That, he
said, was where his two children went to school. He said he had
paid _ in vain _ at least $15 over the last six months to local
officials to help repair it.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what promises the PRI will make, I will not vote for
them,'' he added. ``They cannot deceive me anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   There seemed to be more support for the PRI a few miles away, in
La Perla. Many people leaving the polls said they supported the
ruling party. And Adrian Esteban Jimenez, the local mayor, was not
ashamed to say that government assistance was key.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a flat tire on my truck, and a friend came to help
me,'' he said, ``then I am obligated to help that friend when they
ask me, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Pablo Duran had walked six hours to vote in La Perla, and was
still unsure whom he would pick. He said he was frustrated by the
lack of technical support from the government to poor farmers like
him. Yet he was unconvinced that life would change if he voted
against the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people are talking about change,'' he said. ``But I do
not know if change is going to be good or bad. What if I vote for
change and our lives get worse?''
</P>
</TEXT>
