<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1327 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SOLARMAX0703-COX     07-02 1484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLARMAX0703-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hyperactive sun disrupts high-tech Earth
 &HT;    By Mike Toner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The northern lights, including rare, red colored
auroras, have been seen as far south as Alabama. In Alaska and
Greenland, radio frequencies used by aviators and mariners have
suffered sudden fadeouts. NASA, worried that unusual heating of the
Earth's atmosphere was dragging down its space station, had to use
the space shuttle to boost it to a higher altitude.
</P>
<P>
   It is the summer of the hyperactive sun, solar maximum, Cycle
23. Every 11 years, the storms that rage across the superheated
surface of the sun reach a peak, flinging charged particles and hot
gases into space with predictable _ and sometimes unpredictable _
effects on the wired world that inhabits the third rock from the
sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Solar activity is likely to peak in the next month or two,''
says Ernest Hildner, director of the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration Space Environment center in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``But every cycle is different,'' Hildner says. ``We never know
for sure what's going to happen, but we do know for certain that,
with our growing dependence on satellites and wireless
communication, we are more vulnerable to this kind of activity than
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   When solar activity last reach its peak 11 years ago, fewer than
a million cell phones were used in the United States. Today, more
than 40 million are used. Back then, one million pagers were in
circulation. Today, 50 million are out there. And high above the
earth's protective atmosphere, exposed to the vagaries of the
storms on the sun, more than 600 commercial and military satellites
now provide the world with telephone service, television,
navigation, and weather reports.
</P>
<P>
   As July begins, more than 160 sunspots _ dark areas of
turbulence that provide a general indicator of what's happening
deeper inside the sun _ pimple the face of the sun. At the last
solar minimum in 1996, there were virtually none.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a scale from zero to nine, we've moved into the sevens,''
says David Speich, a solar physicist at the Space Environment
Center in Boulder, Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Activity is likely to continue _ perhaps even increase _ over
the next few months. Potentially disruptive activity often
continues for a year or two after the peak.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Earth has avoided any major effects from the sun's
sporadic eruptions, which can unleash the power of a million 100
megaton bomb. But what is merely a modest blip of energy on the
surface of the sun can have major effects on Earth, even across 93
million miles of space.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, for instance, a large prominence erupted on the
northwest edge of the sun, flinging a billion ton cloud of
electrified hydrogen gas _ known to scientists as a coronal mass
ejection _ off into space at a million miles an hour. Earth was
nowhere in its path, so the event was of interest only to solar
physicists.
</P>
<P>
   But Earth was in the path of two major solar flares on June 6 _
one of the few to be rated a maximum as Class X flare this year.
Because the burst of energy and billions of tons of electrified gas
took more than two days to reach the Earth, satellite operators
were able to take precautions to protect their satellites. Short
wave radio transmissions were disrupted for an hour or so, but no
other major effects were reported.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the sun's effects are predicted. On April 6, a brief,
but intense geomagnetic storm send a surge of current rippling
through the New England power grid. Because it was brief, there
were no serious power outages.
</P>
<P>
   But electric utilities are watching the situation closely this
summer. With demand for power already straining capacity, any major
disruption could have far reaching effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because they are closer to the Earth's north magnetic pole,
the utilities in New England and Canada are most likely to be
directly effected by one of these geomagenetic storms,'' says Bill
Feero, former head of the Electric Power Research Institute's
Sunburst project, which tracks the effects of solar disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that the national grid is now so tightly tied,
that there is always the danger that if we lose a piece of it in,
say New England, we could be in danger of losing the whole thing.
If one of these hits, it will find our weak spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Utilities got a taste of what can happen during the last solar
maximum. On March 13, 1989, a magnetic storm triggered by a huge
solar flare disrupted the entire Hydro-Quebec electrical system,
knocking out power to six million customers and damaging electrical
transformers as far south as New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Hydro-Quebec has spent over $1 billion since then to prevent a
recurrence of the problem. Oak Ridge National Laboratory in
Tennessee has estimated that a slightly larger solar-induced outage
could cost the U.S. economy up to $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Disruptive space weather is blamed for about 150 malfunctions,
mostly minor ones, of government satellites a year. So far, no
major failures have been linked to fast moving, highly energetic
particles, ``killer electrons,'' unleashed by this year's solar
storms.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of even a single satellite, however, can have
far-reaching effects. When an unknown problem _ space debris, an
internal failure, or perhaps solar activity _ knocked out
PanAmSat's Galaxy IV communications satellite in 1998, it
interrupted network television feeds and more than half the
country's pagers.
</P>
<P>
   The risk of being ``fried'' by high-energy electronic isn't the
only risk that satellites face. As ultraviolet radiation increases
with the solar maximum, it heats the highest, thinnest layers of
the Earth's atmosphere, which puffs up like a balloon.
</P>
<P>
   As the atmosphere inflates, it exerts increased drag on orbiting
satellites, which eventually must be boosted to a higher altitude.
In May, the space shuttle was used to raise the orbit of the space
station, which had been slipping lower about two miles a week, by
27 miles _ enough to keep it safely circling the globe for several
months in spite of the denser upper atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's failure to anticipate the effect led to the premature of
its Skylab space station. Launched it 1973, it was supposed to stay
aloft until the 1980s. But increased drag caused by solar activity,
led to its premature rentry in 1979, raining 100 tons of debris
over the Indian Ocean and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   When astronauts take up permanent residence on the space
station, accurate forecasts of solar eruptions, which are
accompanied by potentially harmful increases in gamma and X-ray
radiation. On several occasions, NASA has rescheduled space walks
to avoid having its astronauts outside during such an event.
</P>
<P>
   In June, researchers announced a new model of solar activity,
used to predict the June 6 flares, will make it possible, for the
first time, to narrow the expected time when the gas cloud will
strike the earth to within a half day _ a big improvement over the
best previous estimates or two to five days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new model will greatly benefit people who operate systems
affected by space storms,'' says Dr. Natchimuthuk Gopalswamy,
senior research associate the National Academy of Sciences. ``It
will allow operators of sensitive systems to take protective action
at the proper time and minimize the unproductive time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The magnetic signatures of sunspots can tell us which ones are
most likely to develop,'' says David Hathaway, a solar physicist at
the Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Alabama. ``But it's
a little like trying to predict tornadoes. We recognize which
thunderstorms are apt to produce a tornado, but we still can't tell
ahead of time where or when it will strike.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists would also like to know what _ if any _ effect the
solar cycle has on Earth's weather. This year, for instance, saw
the warmest spring on record in the United States and a summer
drought that shows no signs of abating, but most researchers say
it's probably only a coincidence that it's happening during the
peak of solar activity.
</P>
<P>
   Longer term variations in the earth's climate, however, may be
linked to the solar cycle. Europe's unusually cool ``year without
summer'' in the 17th Century, for instance, coincided with a period
of extremely low sunspot activity -- and many researchers have
found hints of 11-year and 22-year fluctuations in climate that may
reflect the ebb and flow of activity on the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Read more about solar maximum on the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   Forecasts from NOAA's Space Environment Center
</P>
<P>
   http://www.sec.noaa.gov
</P>
<P>
   Real-time images from NASA's Solar and Heliospheric Observatory
</P>
<P>
   http://sohowww.nascom.nasa.gov/data/latestimages.html
</P>
<P>
   The Space Weather Bureau
</P>
<P>
   http://www.SpaceWeather.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
