<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1330 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-1STLD     07-02 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-870(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN TV NETWORKS PREDICT CHALLENGER WILL WIN BY WIDE MARGIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Adds overall polling results showing Fox ahead. Expands from
earlier version.)  
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Courted by a familiar but tainted dynasty yet
tempted by the prospect of historic change, Mexican voters turned
out massively Sunday to determine whether to jettison the party
that has dominated their country for 71 years.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after the polls closed, the two major national
television networks, and the newspaper Reforma said Vicente Fox,
the main opposition challenger, was leading over Francisco
Labastida of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida of the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, was
battling to become president and perpetuate his party's rule, the
longest in the world, against the challenge from Fox of the
National Action Party, a rough-spoken rancher who appealed to
Mexicans to opt for something different.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the results of surveys based on interviews with voters as
they left the balloting places all over Mexico, Televisa, the
largest television network, predicted at 8 p.m. that Fox would win
an upset triumph by a strong margin. In the survey, conducted by
the firm Consulta/Mitofksy, Mexico was divided into five regions,
and Fox was leading in four. In the Mexico City area, with the
largest number of voters of the five, Fox beat Labastida by 43 to
30 percent, and in northwestern Mexico he won by 49 to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment from either Fox or the PRI. A
preliminary official tally, based on actual returns, was not
expected until later Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Across Mexico, eager voters lined up before the polling stations
opened at 8 a.m. and often waited for hours in punishing heat. In
the most open elections ever held here, the balloting was generally
orderly but marred in several states by alleged pressure on voters
from the governing party _ which has a history of fraud _ and
disorganization that blocked many thousands of people from casting
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   After a fierce campaign that filled the television and other
media as never before, many voters said Sunday that they made their
decision only in recent days, suggesting that the undecided, who
were as much as 19 percent of the total in the most recent polls,
would determine the day.
</P>
<P>
   In many neighborhoods that long were PRI strongholds and among
working class Mexicans who were its most loyal followers, one theme
was recurrent: Mexico had to do something different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a change, and I have been asking myself, when
is it going to happen?'' said Gustavo Sanchez, a 32-year-old auto
mechanic in Ecatepec, a huge proletarian suburb of Mexico City
where the PRI was once invincible. ``Our leaders need to know that
if they don't do the job right, we're going to get rid of them.''
</P>
<P>
   At mid-afternoon, Jose Woldenberg, the president of the Federal
Elections Institute that is running the election, reported that
only 13 of 113,423 polling places nationwide failed to open because
of organizational problems, a historical record.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the presidential race, Mexicans also voted to renew the
Senate, with 128 seats, and all 500 seats in the congress, and to
elect two state governors and the mayor of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Based on surveys conducted by the polling firm Mitofsky
International with voters as they left the polls, Televisa, the
largest national television network, reported that Fox's party
crushed the PRI in the governor's race in central state of Morelos,
by 57 percent to 29 percent. The last campaign polls had showed
that the race was tied.
</P>
<P>
   Televisa's early polls also showed that Andres Manuel Lopez,
from the leftist Party of the Democratic Revolution, was _ as
expected _ ahead in the contest for Mexico City mayor. The trend
was going much more heavily against PRI than expected in that
election.
</P>
<P>
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the leftist candidate in the presidential
contest, refused to unite with Fox in the battle to oust the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo, voting in a public school near his
official residence, said, ``There's strong participation, a lot of
enthusiasm and great calm throughout the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Things were not calm, however, in the main square of the city of
Puebla, in central Mexico, where thousands of people lined up for
long hours at a special polling place set up for Mexicans who were
not in their home towns on election day.
</P>
<P>
   Before the polls opened, hundreds of army soldiers and
policemen, mostly in civilian clothes, crowded to the front of the
line at the one special station for out-of-town voters in Puebla's
crowded plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Since the special station had only 750 ballots to be cast, many
voters realized, after waiting for hours in line, that they were
not going to be able to vote. As the line stretched for six blocks
out of the plaza, angry and frustrated people began to suspect that
the PRI was pulling one of the election tricks for which it was
notorious in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fraud! Fraud!'' the voters chanted as tensions mounted, ebbed
and mounted again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the PRI again,'' said Maria Guadalupe Corona Moreno, a
28-year-old manager of a textile factory from the state of
Guanajuato who was in Puebla on business. ``I've been waiting to
cast my vote for years,'' she said, waving her voter card, ``and
now it turns out this is just a piece of trash.''
</P>
<P>
   PRI voters in Puebla were also furious about being left out.
``Where is the democracy?'' said Maria Teresa Inclan Perez, who
said she supported the governing party.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The special polling stations were set up for Mexicans who would
not appear on local rolls because they went to vote in places
different from where they registered. In regular polling places,
Mexicans were given ballots after matching their voter card with a
photograph against a list that included both their names and
pictures. However, because of restrictions in the campaign laws,
only 715 special polling places were set up nationwide, with only
750 ballots each.
</P>
<P>
   In Iztapalapa, a vast working class borough of Mexico City,
dozens of policemen pushed into the front of the line at one
special polling place. The situation grew tense as voters behind
them realized that they were probably being squeezed out of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   There were reports from four states of registered voters whose
names did not appear on lists where they were supposed to, who were
sent to special stations. The lines were so long they never got to
vote.
</P>
<P>
   The results of Televisa's polls were confirmed by similar
surveys by TV Azteca, the other national network.
</P>
<P>
   The voting Sunday was monitored by no less than 38,433 Mexican
observers and 860 foreigners. Everywhere they went, observers found
voters thrilled about being part of what felt like a bona fide
democratic exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was saying that this time their vote really
matters,'' said Pamela S. Falk, a law professor from the City
University of New York. ``They have a sense that it has been a
very, very long time since they have been able to say what they
wanted at the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   PRI leaders had promised that the party's vast machine would be
in full gear, with 2.5 million party followers working to deliver
its voters to the polls. But the power of the PRI apparatus was not
much in evidence nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   In the state of Yucatan, state elections officials reported that
some voters who had taken handouts from the PRI ahead of the
election were showing their ballots to PRI poll watchers to prove
that they fulfilled their part of the deal. State government
employees were campaigning for the PRI outside the polling station
in some rural Yucatan towns.
</P>
<P>
   By and large the voters did not express support directly for Fox
or any other particular candidate. They spoke of a longing for
something other than the government the PRI has given them, a
regime which depressed workers' salaries for three decades and was
repeatedly involved in scandals in which it squandered or ran off
with the taxpayers' money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks to me like the people have come out because they want
a change,'' said Ana Maria Mosqueda, 38, a secretary who was an
elections observer on behalf of a national teachers union, which
has been a bastion of the PRI. She made it clear that her PRI
sympathies had waned. ``We want to be treated better, and we can
make it happen today, one grain of sand at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   In many places the election split families in two, with the
older generation sticking with the PRI and the younger people going
for the opposition. Husbands and wives differed as well.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Luis Caballero Rivas, an office worker who is 39, said he
chose Labastida because ``we need someone who will help us.'' But
as they emerged from a polling station in Ecatepec, his wife,
Gabriela Alcazar, piped up to contradict him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time to change,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the state of Chiapas, followers of the Zapatista rebels
burned the voting stations in two tiny rural communities, and
rebels wearing ski masks set up roadblocks to stop PRI followers
from voting in the town of Altamirano. The actions came even though
the Zapatista leader who calls himself Subcomandante Marcos, had
said the Zapatistas would not obstruct the election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
