<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR MONDAY JULY 3
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Monday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-OLD-THEATERS-ART-3TAKES-NYT (moved Thursday, June 22)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, June 22
about historic theaters misstated the history of Ford's Theater in
Washington. The building was not torn down after the assassination
of President Abraham Lincoln. It was gutted and the interior became
office space in the 1930's, but the walls were left standing. A
restoration of the theater began in 1965, based on photographs
taken by Mathew Brady, and the new Ford's opened in 1968. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
