<HEADER>
A1345 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-DNC-PROTESTERS-2Takes     07-02 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-PROTESTERS-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS ORGANIZE FOR DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETH BARRETT  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES _ The Democratic National Convention in August
could become the first party presidential nomination in more than
two decades overshadowed by street protests.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the 1968 Democratic National Convention in Chicago has
any protest movement been strong enough to attract the 50,000 or
more expected for Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   This new millennium movement has drawn disparate groups together
under a single ``big tent'' in just eight months, drawn by a
general concern for what they see social, economic and political
injustice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very interesting social movement that while reminiscent
of the 1960s, is also very distinct,'' said Margaret Levi,
professor of political science at the University of Washington in
Seattle, where the movement was born last December during the World
Trade Organization conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a movement that while very young is growing, changing and
consolidating. The networks are wider; the links stronger and
deeper. The protesters now have the capacity to convey their
messages in more sophisticated ways.''
</P>
<P>
   After Seattle and the protests at April's International Monetary
Fund summit in Washington, D.C., the conventions this summer in
Philadelphia and especially Los Angeles will test the alliance's
strength, and the public's receptivity to its message, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of energy is congealing here in Los Angeles around a lot
of the same issues raised at WTO and IMF,'' said Shawn McDougal,
who works for a Quaker-based organization in northwest Pasadena and
is volunteering to help organize the summer's protests.
</P>
<P>
   The L.A. protests are being coordinated by the umbrella group
D2KLA, whose leaders are among the country's most seasoned, many of
them coming out of leadership in labor, environmental, peace and
justice movements.
</P>
<P>
   A nucleus of about 200 are now putting together a logistics
framework for what's anticipated by police, protesters and city
officials to be an unprecedented number of demonstrations, street
marches, festivities and civil disobedience actions Aug. 14-17.
</P>
<P>
   They will be in the national spotlight, judged both for their
message and behavior. Los Angeles already is wary with LAPD and
Secret Service warnings that a small faction intends to engage in
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are out to demonstrate that there are other ways to make
things work,'' said Lisa Fithian, 39, whose says her job is to draw
maximum attention to the movement's goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are out to demonstrate that there are other ways to make
things work. This is direct democracy. We believe our strength and
our unity will be forged in the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Convention organizers say they are trying to accommodate the
protesters as much as security will allow and don't want their
candidate, Al Gore, to be upstaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the real news will be made inside the convention hall
as Vice President Gore talks about his agenda for progress and
prosperity to the country,'' said DNC Committee spokesman Peter
Ragone.
</P>
<P>
   The debate in D2KLA now is how best to use the streets of Los
Angeles to create images that will be beamed around the world on
Web sites, and via satellite from an independent media center to be
set up near Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   As in Seattle, the Direct Action Network _ one of D2KLA's
splinter groups _ will lead small teams in intentional, nonviolent
civil disobedience.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters know they may be arrested, and they train for
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all kinds of direct actions from blockades (of
buildings, like police stations), to banner hangs, where people
climb a high structure and hang a banner. We don't have money for
advertising like corporations do, so it's free advertising,'' said
Direct Action organizer McDougal.
</P>
<P>
   Within the movement, there have been debates over what the role
of violence and property destruction should be, if any.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the political systems that forces people to work two
or three jobs; look at people harassed by the police,'' Fithian
said. ``That's spiritual and emotional violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Direct Action's official position is that property destruction
sends the wrong message, and leaders have drawn up guidelines
encouraging all groups to refrain from violence, to carry no
weapons, to avoid drugs and alcohol, and to only destroy barricades
that are erected to interfere with free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing we want to emphasize is that since people will
do civil disobedience, we want to ground it in nonviolence so that
it doesn't come to a confrontation,'' said Kevin Rudiger, a
26-year-old University of California, Los Angeles graduate student
from Simi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say they have given the guidelines to local
anarchists. In Seattle, black-hooded anarchists were blamed for
much of the $10 million in downtown property damage.
</P>
<P>
   They blame police for the destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The LAPD is putting out the threats of violent, chemical
terrorism and they're all unsubstantiated,'' Rudiger said.
``There's no credible reason that will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Police Department spokesman Cmdr. David Kalish said
the police only react to unlawful activities.
</P>
<P>
   (2nd take to come)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
