u i BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-BOS &LR;      07-02 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXIT POLLS INDICATE MEXICAN POLITICAL UPHEAVAL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ National exit polls gave opposition presidential
candidate Vicente Fox Quesada a surprisingly wide lead Sunday
night, and Mexico appeared to be on the verge of ending more than
seven decades of one-party rule after a closely fought and
scrutinized election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Although official results were not available, several exit polls
released after the end of voting Sunday night, showed Fox, the
boot-wearing, tart-tongued candidate of the opposition center-right
National Action Party holding a lead of 5 to 9 percentage point
over Francisco Labastida Ochoa, candidate of the governing
Institutional Revolutionary Party, which has ruled since 1929.
</P>
<P>
   The historic vote was a referendum on the country's willingness
to change and a test of its recently strengthened democratic
institutions after decades of corruption-filled voting. Turnout
among the country's 59 million registered voters was
extraordinarily heavy, but official estimates were not available.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a sense of commitment and obligation among
people voting today that we've never seen before in Mexico,'' said
Carlos Monsivais, a prominent writer who cast his vote for a
center-left coalition led by former Mexico City mayor Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas. ``We've seen enthusiasm for voting here before, but never
the kind of discipline that we've had this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters had six candidates to choose from, but much of the
attention focused on Labastida, a former interior minister, and
Fox, the former Guanajuato state governor. Cardenas, son of a
legendary president, was a distant third, according to the exit
polls.
</P>
<P>
   Both leading parties and candidates claimed victory soon after
polls closed. Leaders of the coalition led by the National Action
Party, or PAN, said their exit polls showed Fox the winner by 6
percentage points. Labastida and the leaders of the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, insisted they had won by the same
margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time, we can't yet confirm officially that we've
won,'' Fox told a room packed with supporters Sunday night. ``But
the exit polls have given us a large enough margin that we can
present ourselves to the Mexican people.''
</P>
<P>
   Voting generally appeared to be calm at most of the country's
113,000 voting places, although there were sporadic reports of
logistical problems and some accounts of vote tampering.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best organized process legally that we've seen in
Mexico,'' said former US president Jimmy Carter, one of more than
10,000 Mexican and foreign observers who monitored the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The loudest and most frequent complaints from voters were a lack
of ballots, particularly at the special precincts located along the
US-Mexico border and in the capital, where residents could cast
ballots outside their home districts. By law, each special polling
place was supplied with 750 ballots, but most of them were swamped
with voters, whose numbers often exceeded 2,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a right to vote and am being told that I can't because
they've run out of ballots,'' said Irma Luengo, 55, while standing
in the middle of an angry crowd at a special polling site at an old
Olympic facility in southern Mexico City. ``Is this by accident or
a plan to keep some of us from voting? I have my suspicions.''
</P>
<P>
   Some precincts in the capital and southern Chiapas state lacked
enough ballots, forcing some resident to wait up to four hours to
cast their vote. Another polling place in the city of Toluca was
forced to close temporarily because a swarm of bees stung 40
people.
</P>
<P>
   In other areas of the country, there were reports by some
international observers of party representatives interfering with
voters as they cast their ballots. In some outlying areas as well
as in suburban Mexico City, some members of the ruling PRI were
spotted taking voters' ballots and placing them into the boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not supposed to be handling ballots in any way,
because it could influence voters,'' said Eric Olson, Mexican
program director for the Washington Office on Latin America, who
witnessed some of these activities in the capital suburb of Valle
de Chalco. ``These kinds of incidents are going to be magnified if
the election is close.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters streamed to the polls all day with an unusual air of
seriousness about them. Many of them expressed confidence that, for
the first time, they were making a free choice and that their votes
would be counted fairly by the Federal Electoral Institute, an
independent agency created four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had many changes for more democracy here and that makes
me feel better about my vote,'' said Julia Gregorio, a housewife in
the middle class town of Atizapan in Mexico state, who supported
the ruling party. ``Even if another party wins, I think we've come
a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Sunday's vote appeared to answer the question of
whether to defang the political party that has ruled since its
creation in 1929, shortly after the end of the Mexican revolution.
The PRI has never lost a presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   For generations of Mexicans, the PRI has been both hero and
villain. It nationalized key industries, built hospitals, schools
and roads and built strong economic ties with other countries.
</P>
<P>
   But the party and its heavy-handed tactics has also symbolized
Mexico's deep problems, like the widening gap between rich and
poor, rampant corruption and election fraud.
</P>
<P>
   For those reasons, and mounting frustration, Mexicans have
gradually grown more accustomed to the presence of opposition
parties, particluarly over the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   PAN was founded in 1938 by conservative Catholics but gained
little influence at first. The party began accumulating victories
for mayoralties and governorships in northern Mexico beginning in
the mid-1980s. Meanwhile, a major defection from the PRI in 1989
created a third major party, the center-left Party of the
Democratic Revolution, led by Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition parties won a majority of congressional seats for the
first time in 1997, the year that Cardenas was elected as the first
opposition mayor of the capital. Opposition parties now control
governorships in a dozen of Mexico's 31 states.
</P>
<P>
   But past presidential elections have always belonged to the PRI,
mostly because the party has benefited from its massive national
vote-gathering machine, its links to government resources and
because it has managed to divide opposition votes between the PAN
and PRD.
</P>
<P>
   Some specialists said that no matter who won the elections, the
vote was a turning point for Mexico, where increased competition
among political parties combined with the stronger electoral
institutions would likely lead to more responsive governments
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a hero in all of this, it's the Mexican people,''
said Richard Warren, director of the Latin American Studies Center
at St. Joseph's University in Philadelphia. ``They've struggled
hard for years for a better political process, and they recognize
that this is an important step to make.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
