r a BC-DNC-PROTESTERS-2ndTak     07-02 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-PROTESTERS-2ndTake-LADN </SLUG>
  
LOS ANGELES: unlawful activities.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Levi said from a strategic point of view, there are a lot of
different opinions on the effectiveness of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't support it, but it does bring media attention, and
sometimes leads to other voices being heard,'' she said. ``People
will hear about the violence, but then may begin to wonder about
the other 40,000 or so people who aren't violent, and what they
have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Fithian added: ``Will we shut down anything? Maybe we will and
maybe we won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers insist they don't want shut down the conventions as
they did the WTO and IMF. Rather, it's to protest the two-party
system as exclusive, nonresponsive and ultimately undemocratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're deeply concerned that democracy is for sale to the
highest bidder,'' Rudiger said. ``There will be plenty of $10,000
dinners. So instead of being left out entirely, we'll be in the
streets.''
</P>
<P>
   The groups will have some central oversight and coordination
through what's known as the Action Spokes Council. The council, in
theory, discusses plans, but it's up to ``affinity groups'' who
share common interests, to carry them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our belief is that people need to take action on their own, to
speak in their own voices,'' Fithian said.
</P>
<P>
   Rudiger, the UCLA urban planning graduate student, said
``Decentralization lets people feel good about the process, that
decisions aren't coming down from somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Next weekend, a training session is planned, organizers said. In
addition to going over tactics for dealing with police _ including
whether to go limp or follow instructions if arrested _ the
protesters will make up street skits, and make giant puppets and
other artwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we're fighting back against is how even our public
spaces have been taken over by corporations,'' McDougal, the
nonprofit worker, said. ``We think taking over the streets in a
festive mood is really important.''
</P>
<P>
   Fithian offered slogans for their beliefs: ``People and planet
over profits'' and ``Human needs over corporate greed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have the same goal: to create a more just and peaceful
world, and to expose how the political system is not accountable to
the people.''
</P>
<P>
   D2KLA is arranging to meet housing, transportation, medical and
other needs. By August, the protesters will have a communication
nerve center planned in Patriotic Hall at Figueroa and 18th streets
near Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Each day will feature a protest theme, with groups affiliated
with that theme encouraged to showcase their concerns with signs,
songs and puppets.
</P>
<P>
   The themes include racial and gender inequality, injustice in
the criminal justice system, global economic injustice,
anti-militarism, and more.
</P>
<P>
   A candlelight vigil will culminate the protests Aug. 17 to
coincide with Gore's anticipated acceptance of the Democratic
nomination for president.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a final plea, Fithian said, ``for domestic and global
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
