<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1355 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-360VIEW-VIDEO-SFCHRON     07-02 1665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-360VIEW-VIDEO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 INTERNET VIDEO TECHNOLOGY DISPLAYS WHOLE PICTURE  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Watching a football game on television is an
incomplete experience: You get limited views, all controlled by an
unseen director.
</P>
<P>
   But imagine watching the same game using immersive 360-degree
Internet technology, being able to watch the wide receiver grab a
pass by his fingertips and then turning to view the fans in the
stands hugging each other. You could even look up to see the blimp
flying overhead.
</P>
<P>
   A picture may be worth a thousand words, but two Bay Area
companies believe a 360-degree picture could be worth millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is 21st century video,'' said Ted Driscoll,
chief executive and president of Be Here Inc. of Cupertino, Calif.
``It's a whole new medium, participatory video.''
</P>
<P>
   Be Here and San Ramon, Calif.'s International Pictures Corp., or
iPIX, are the leading proponents of 360-degree video technology,
which lets Internet users to simultaneously select the angle or
viewpoint of a still photo or a moving video.
</P>
<P>
   The video technology has caught the eyes of such noted
filmmakers as Ron Howard and Steven Spielberg, as well as the
Discovery Channel, Fox Sports Net and even eBay.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said there are more reasons 360-degree video won't
turn in to another fad like 3-D movies, where audiences had to wear
special clunky glasses.
</P>
<P>
   IPIX, which ranked No. 4 on The Chronicle 500's list of
fastest-growing companies by percentage of sales, is already
changing the face of online real estate. With a computer and a
modem, homebuyers can explore a house without stepping out the
door.
</P>
<P>
   For example, ZipRealty.com lets homebuyers look at several still
views of the house taken with an iPIX camera, using a mouse to move
the view of the picture in any direction _ right, left, up and
down.
</P>
<P>
   They can also zoom in or out, and thousands of homebuyers can
look at the same photo of the living room at the same time, but
choose different views, such as a close-up of the fireplace or the
bay view windows.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, media companies are also looking to cash in on this
new technology by looking at how ``immersive'' Web casts of
ballgames, concerts and other live events can drive traffic to
their sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The immersive images have a definite practical purpose,'' said
Lia Schubert, Internet imaging analyst with InfoTrends Research
Group Inc., a Boston firm that tracks digital imaging trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the advent of e-commerce, companies, individuals, rock
bands and sports teams are looking to reach a wider audience
through the Web and need to do that visually,'' she said.
``Immersive imaging provides a very rich and interactive way for
these companies to actually get Internet-viewing customers
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking 360-degree video one step further is the groundbreaking
four-minute film ``The New Arrival,'' which made its debut in May
at the Cannes Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Using Be Here's 360-degree technology, New York independent film
director Amy Talkington tells the story of a ``new arrival'' at a
retirement home. Be Here's camera plays the title character, which
enables viewers to jump into the role. Although the story line is
predetermined, Be Here's technology allows the audience to direct
the view.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really natural way to tell stories on the Internet,''
Talkington said. ``All my filmmaker friends who have seen the short
seem really excited about working in a new medium.''
</P>
<P>
   The film has been streamed about 100,000 times so far on
AtomFilms.com, the Seattle Web site that offers short films and
animated features. AtomFilms is running a contest among its 1
million registered members to come up with the best idea for the
next 360-degree video. The site plans to debut more original
immersive productions later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Also getting into the act are entertainers Ellen Degeneres and
Anne Heche, who are posting weekly immersive Web casts of their
``Ellen: The Americana Tour'' through August 4 at  &LR; www.ellenz.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Moving even one more step further, Be Here and Fox Sports Net
stationed cameras atop the two neutral corner posts of the boxing
ring during the June 18 fight in Las Vegas between Hector Camacho
Jr. and Manard Reed.
</P>
<P>
   No longer at the mercy of an unseen television director calling
the shots, the test showed how Internet viewers could control the
view and pan the stands for screaming fans, then pan back in time
to watch Camacho knock Reed to the canvas right below the camera.
</P>
<P>
   Although the boxing match wasn't Webcast to the public, Fox
Sports said the test should lead to live Webcasts of sporting
events in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Technology from Be Here, which has Intel, Phillips and Kodak as
investors, was used to Webcast activities during Super Bowl XXXIV,
the NFL draft and cable network ESPN's X Games.
</P>
<P>
   Providers of broadband access also stand to benefit. Driscoll
said 360-degree video will bring the content that will push sales
of high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our belief is people will not pay for broadband just so they
can load Yahoo in two seconds,'' Driscoll said.
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll said other markets, such as security and day care, may
also find use for 360-degree video technology. ``You can pop this
magic periscope anywhere in the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have developed technology that operates with the
same premise, that a specially designed camera lens can capture one
seamless 360-degree image. Other companies, like Enroute Inc. of
Palo Alto, have introduced immersive video that uses software to
stitch together multiple shots.
</P>
<P>
   Be Here's technology is the only one that supports live
streaming video, although it does not capture the top and bottom of
a picture or scene. Driscoll said Be Here's camera lens captures an
image that looks like a doughnut, cutting unneeded parts of a scene
that would otherwise take up bandwidth.
</P>
<P>
   So far, iPIX technology, originally developed for NASA, cannot
be used to stream live video on the Internet. But it does afford a
full 360-by-360-degree view so a user can, for example, look at
both the ceiling and floor of a room.
</P>
<P>
   Both iPIX and Be Here have developed fist-size lenses and
software that capture 360-degree images for digital cameras, and
the lens sizes could shrink in the future.
</P>
<P>
   While the privately held Be Here has concentrated on
entertainment and sports, financial analyst Andrew Wilcox said iPIX
already has a solid business foundation because of its firm
foothold in online real estate.
</P>
<P>
   The publicly traded iPIX, which earlier this year moved into new
offices in San Ramon, last month signed a $12.25 million deal with
Cendant Corp., parent company of real estate giants Coldwell
Banker, ERA and Century 21, to use iPIX's ``virtual tours'' service
for 360-degree photos of homes for sale.
</P>
<P>
   IPIX also sells tour packages, offering a national network of
about 700 photographers who can take a series of immersive photos
of a home or hotel room for a client. The most popular package,
which includes four 360-degree shots, sells for $100, said iPIX
Executive Vice President Don Strickland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's visual content that drives e-commerce,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cendant agreed to buy 350,000 virtual tours. It was the most
lucrative deal for iPIX, which posted sales of $12.52 million in
1999, about 16,000 percent more than the year before. The company
reported first quarter 2000 revenue of $8.3 million, but a net loss
of $36.9 million that included charges from a merger with virtual
home tour provider bamboo.com of Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   Wilcox, of J.P. Morgan Securities Inc., projects iPIX revenues
to hit about $68.8 million this year and $177 million in 2001. The
company is expecting to be profitable in mid-2001.
</P>
<P>
   Wilcox said iPIX has a virtual lock on the online real estate
market, to the point where iPIX's immersive photos are fast
becoming a requirement for online home listings. But with an
estimated 7 million to 8 million existing home sale listings
already online, iPIX has only scratched the surface of revenue
opportunities in real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to see iPIX virtual tours as a standard in real
estate in two or three years,'' Wilcox said. ``It's becoming
addictive technology. Once you have the ability to pan around back
and forth, when you don't have it, you feel like you're missing
something.''
</P>
<P>
   The company signed a deal with eBay in April to allow eBay
members to use iPIX's technology to add 360-degree photos with
their online auction listings.
</P>
<P>
   And like Be Here, iPIX is focusing on immersive video.
</P>
<P>
   In April, iPIX signed a deal with digital entertainment company
POP.com of Glendale to produce interactive short films for the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   That was significant because POP.com is a collaboration of
Imagine Entertainment, co-founded by director Ron Howard, and
DreamWorks SKG, founded by entertainment industry legends Steven
Spielberg, Jeffrey Katzenberg and David Geffen and funded by
Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen's Vulcan Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance ``will enable us to create unique and fresh online
entertainment, which will be fun for us as filmmakers and should
provide an exciting interactive experience for our viewers,''
Howard said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, not enough households have high-speed
Internet connections to make immersive film and other forms of
entertainment commercially viable, said InfoTrends analyst Lia
Schubert.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit early for it now, but (iPIX) will be in
position when the bandwidth is there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although iPIX is the leader in immersive imaging, it remains to
be seen which technology may be more pervasive in the future, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a consumer standpoint, they don't care about underlying
technology,'' she said. ``They just want to know if it's cool or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
