<HEADLINE>
GROUP DRIVES LONG DISTANCE TO WITNESS MEXICO ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ADRIANA TORREZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MATAMOROS, Mexico _ When Alfredo Castaneda of Dallas asked why a
Matamoros resident was allowed to vote in a polling place that was
supposed to be off limits to him, the representative of Mexico's
Federal Electoral Institute ordered him and the media out.
</P>
<P>
   Castaneda said that exchange illustrates why he and other
independent observers were needed as witnesses to Sunday's voting
in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to safeguard the vote of the Mexican coming from
abroad,'' Castaneda said, noting that special voting booths along
the border had only 750 ballots each reserved for the use of those
coming home from abroad to vote. ``If somebody else uses his
ballot, he's left without a vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the special polling places for Mexicans from abroad
were in Matamoros, meaning they had 2,250 votes in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Although Castaneda holds dual citizenship and as such was not
eligible to vote in the election, his desire to help fight fraud at
polling places was so strong that he and two other colleagues drove
nine hours from Dallas just to be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an historic election,'' he said. ``The whole world is
paying attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Castaneda, Eduardo Banda and Gregorio Ibanez were organizers of
a caravan that was to have brought Mexican citizens from the
Dallas-Fort Worth area to the border to vote, but no one showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people didn't come because there was a lot of
misinformation on the number of ballots available in the special
voting booths,'' Castaneda said. ``Many canceled at the last minute
because they (mistakenly) believed that only 50 of the 750 ballots
at booths were (for) voters outside their electoral district.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds lined up at the municipal plaza before 8 a.m.,
concerned that they wouldn't get a ballot unless they arrived
early. Among them were dozens of Mexican citizens who live in the
United States, most from cities such as Houston and Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here for change,'' said Jorge Gomez, 31, of Houston.
Originally from the Mexican state of Sonora, Gomez and five friends
and family members drove six hours to cast their vote for Vicente
Fox of the National Action Party, who was leading in early poll
results.
</P>
<P>
   Hector and Margarita Miranda of Brownsville also said a desire
for change drew them across the border early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons we left Mexico was because of the
government,'' said Margarita Miranda, referring to the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, also known as PRI, which has
governed the country for 71 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair that they continue to stay in power,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hector Miranda was disappointed that only 750 ballots
were allotted, he grudgingly acknowledged that the limited number
of ballots was also a safeguard against fraud by not leaving a
large number of unused ballots that could easily be stolen or
manipulated.
</P>
<P>
   Some did not get to vote because ballots ran out.
</P>
<P>
   Castaneda said that's just the type of thing he and his
colleagues hope to improve. ``The government never expects a large
turnout from Mexicans living in the U.S.,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``Mexicans abroad are going to play a large role
because we love our country, we love our culture and now we are
more informed.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
