<SLUG> BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE UNSEEN SOFTENS A METS' LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Baseball is a numbers game: batting averages, earned
run averages, games ahead, games behind. Monday morning, the
numbers show that, for all the excitement of a wild four-game
series that was framed by waves of police officers, the Mets still
trail the Braves by two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way,'' Mike Piazza said after Sunday's 10-2 shellacking
by Atlanta at Shea Stadium, ``it was a wash. But there was a lot of
excitement for the fans and players. I'm glad it's behind us. But
we're where we were coming into the series.''
</P>
<P>
   Are they really?
</P>
<P>
   As players spoke after Sunday's game, there was the distinct
sense _ from each team's hard-core veterans _ that numbers don't
begin to tell the story of this rivalry or this race. That the
distance that separates these two teams can no longer be measured
by games, but by intangibles.
</P>
<P>
   As Derek Bell, the Mets' right fielder, left the clubhouse
Sunday, he was asked if he thought Atlanta's two-game lead was as
daunting now as it was on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no,'' Bell said. ``We showed today that we're not
going anywhere, that we're going to keep coming at them.''
</P>
<P>
   When the series opened, the 31-year-old Bell cautioned that the
season was like a war, with long months of ebbs and flows. What
mattered was surviving the war and winning the crucial playoff
battles in October.
</P>
<P>
   What mattered less were personal streaks, and Bell had two of
those stopped Sunday. His 12-game hitting streak was snapped and
his team record of scoring at least one run in 11 straight games
came to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said that in the long view of a baseball season, streaks
can be restarted and losses can be absorbed. The important thing is
that the Mets had introduced an element of doubt to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed Atlanta that we can play with them,'' Bell said.
``We showed them that we can score runs off their pitchers. They
know we're here and that we're not moving.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were defeated Thursday, staged one of the greatest
comebacks in franchise history Friday, and walloped Greg Maddux on
Saturday. Sunday, they were victimized by Tom Glavine, who pitched
one of his best games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But back-to-back home runs by Mike Piazza and Todd Zeile _
despite coming in a losing effort _ were yet more signals that the
older-sibling/younger-sibling relationship between Atlanta and the
Mets had changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people only look at numbers,'' Zeile said about the
standing. ``We came in the series two games behind and we're still
two games behind. But if you take anything out of this, it's that
we don't have that same feeling of the Braves being invincible.''
</P>
<P>
   There was an unusual sense of relief in the Atlanta clubhouse.
Glavine, surrounded by a flock of news media representatives, said
he was simply happy that he gave his team a chance to win. Someone
asked if the split with New York helped Atlanta reaffirm its
position as the dominant team in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that we need affirmation of who we are,'' Glavine
said. ``But to split this series and go home is nice from a
psychological standpoint. But even if we lost three out of four, we
wouldn't have panicked about that, either.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a series of lessons. Glendon Rusch, the Mets'
26-year-old starter, was battered Sunday. The Braves, sobered by
two consecutive defeats, attacked Rusch from the beginning and
never let up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were aggressive,'' Rusch said. ``When they saw a pitch to
hit, they went after it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rusch, the youngster, watched the veteran Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't give in _ that's one thing I learned from him today.
He didn't give in. He gave up some hits, but he kept coming back.
It was good for me to see that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets should also be buoyed by the fact that the Braves have
to pull around the added weight of a silly young relief pitcher who
can't leave well enough alone. John Rocker has painted a unerasable
bull's-eye on Atlanta's collective back. While reaction to Rocker
boiled over in New York, his attitude has offended millions of
people nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The bad blood will follow the Braves for the next three months.
Sunday, Rocker went out onto the field before the eighth inning and
warmed up the left fielder. When the warm-up was over, Rocker
tossed the ball into the stands. The fan who caught it threw it
back _ fortunately, not hard; fortunately, not at Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   You can argue that the Braves had escaped once again after the
Mets had them cornered. But the Mets' miracle on Friday and the
pummeling on Saturday served notice that the escape routes are
disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Bell said Sunday: ``We've got a serious window of
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   How much space separates Atlanta from the Mets? Baseball is a
game of numbers, but this race is one of intangibles. A two-game
lead doesn't begin to tell the story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
