</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SENIORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRWIN TAKES SENIOR OPEN WITH ANOTHER 65 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL ARKUSH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, Pa. _ Hale Irwin turned 55 years old last month,
which is about the age at which golfers on the Senior PGA Tour are
supposed to begin their decline. They are supposed to hit a wall as
their younger peers to take over.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin must be an exception. Instead of hitting a wall, he shot a
second consecutive six-under 65 at Saucon Valley Country Club
Sunday to capture his second U.S. Senior Open championship in three
years, outdueling the overnight leader, Bruce Fleisher, by three
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to an early blunder from Fleisher, Irwin wasted no time
in overcoming a two-stroke deficit. He birdied the par-5 first
hole, converting a 6-foot putt, as Fleisher, going for the green in
two, pushed his 3-wood approach from 270 yards into a bunker on the
right. With a tree in his way, Fleisher was unable to get his third
shot on the green, leading to a bogey and a tone-setting, two-shot
swing. Three holes later, Irwin made another birdie, the first of
three straight, to seize a lead he never relinquished. He finished
at 17-under 267.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a stupid play,'' conceded Fleisher. ``I felt if I could
put some heat on him early, things may work the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin appreciated Fleisher's aggressive strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' said Irwin, who earned $400,000. ``I don't
know what his thinking was. I just felt like he was so far away
that awfully early in the day with a two-shot lead to try that
shot. It just brought trouble into play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't work this time; it may next time. But I dare say, I
bet if he was in the same position, he won't do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   The mistake amplified a significant difference between Irwin and
Fleisher.
</P>
<P>
   For all his excellence on the Senior Tour since he joined in
1999 _ 10 victories and nearly $4 million in earnings _ Fleisher
has yet to secure a major championship. Irwin, a three-time U.S.
Open winner, has been known as a player who performs best under the
most demanding pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks earlier, in the U.S. Open at Pebble Beach, Irwin
was the only player besides Tiger Woods to record two rounds in the
60s. He finished tied for 27th.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't go train for it, you don't go practice it,'' said
Irwin, referring to the matter of experience. ``You don't go buy
some at the store. It's immeasurable. Only way you get experience
is to be there and to make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Experience, however, wasn't the only factor that aided Irwin. He
also played extremely well, hitting one outstanding approach after
another on the front nine. All four of his birdies on the front
came in putts of 7 feet or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played super today,'' said Fleisher. ``There is nothing I
could have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody else was able to challenge Irwin. Tom Kite, who trailed
by just three strokes entering the day, made only three birdies,
shooting a 69 to finish five back, while Hubert Green and Allen
Doyle, both within range, failed to break 70. Only Raymond Floyd,
who shot a 67, made a move. He finished fourth, seven strokes
behind Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   For Irwin, the victory means a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``My career has been defined by USGA championships,'' said
Irwin, who automatically earns a trip to next year's U.S. Senior
Open in Tulsa, Okla. ``If there is a tournament to win on the
Senior Tour, this is it for me.''
</P>
<P>
   It also proves that Irwin, who takes over as the season's
leading money-winner with nearly $1.5 million, may be a long way
from the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is certainly a time period that you may be less
effective than you were before,'' said Irwin, who won his first
U.S. Senior Open in 1998 at Riviera Country Club in Pacific
Palisades, Calif. ``But if somebody is going to tell me at the age
of 55 you are not going to play golf anymore, I just don't buy into
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
