<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1370 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REFORM-BALLOT-NYT &LR;      07-02 0245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-BALLOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY TWO NAMES TO BE ON REFORM BALLOT  
 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When balloting begins Wednesday in the Reform Party presidential
primary, voters will have only two choices: Pat Buchanan, the
former conservative television commentator, and John Hagelin, a
physicist.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform presidential nominations committee has denied a
request by Ross Perot, the party founder _ who won a spot in the
primary through signature petitions _ that he be allowed to
substitute ``No Endorsement'' for his name on the ballot to let
voters protest the quality of the other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not consistent with the rules,'' said Michael Farris,
the committee chairman. ``We felt that his name would have to
appear on the ballot in some semblance of his legal name.
Otherwise, it would lead to confusion, and that was the long and
the short of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Farris said the committee also denied an appeal by the Buchanan
campaign to bar Hagelin from seeking the presidency under the
banner of another party if he lost to Buchanan. Hagelin was the
nominee of the Natural Law Party in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Farris said it was not within the province of the party's
leaders to tell Hagelin what he could or could not do if Buchanan
won the Reform nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to bring it up in the course of their campaign,
that's up to them,'' he said of Buchanan's supporters. ``We don't
feel we had the discretion to tell Hagelin what to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
