<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1478 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-SAIL-NYT &LR;      07-02 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COAST GUARD CHOREOGRAPHS HARBOR'S BIGGEST SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Precisely at 11 a.m. Saturday, the USS Nassau, an
amphibious-helicopter carrier, passed under the Verrazano-Narrows
Bridge into Upper New York Bay. The ship was headed for its turn at
the diesel ballet, a maneuver in which four tugboats nudge their
hulking gray partner into its appointed anchorage southwest of Red
Hook, Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The low-slung black tugs, engines thrumming and wakes bulging,
pushed and spun the 820-feet-long ship against a light breeze and
tide until it could tie down, one link at a time, to four buoys,
completing a procedure called a four-point mooring.
</P>
<P>
   The routine was repeated again Sunday with the aircraft carrier
John F. Kennedy, 990 feet long, and the USS Mount Whitney, a
620-feet-long command and control ship. The procedures,
particularly with such enormous ships in congested tidal waters,
required a degree of choreographic precision that makes young deck
officers pace.
</P>
<P>
   Far from this action, in a small room at Fort Wadsworth on
Staten Island, a team of Coast Guard men and women paced as well,
observing the maneuvers on television monitors and radar screens.
After years of Coast Guard preparation, the harbor traffic for
OpSail 2000 had begun, and the people in the Vessel Traffic Center,
as the room is known, were in the early stages of the most
demanding test in the center's history.
</P>
<P>
   The Vessel Traffic Center is one of four major command posts in
place for the OpSail celebrations on Independence Day. Others will
be at the command and control center inside One Police Plaza, the
City Office of Emergency Management's so-called bunker on the 23rd
floor of 7 World Trade Center and a temporary Navy center on Pier
94 on the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   Of all these command posts, the Coast Guard's is the only one
that functions at full strength all year, every hour. It is the
maritime counterpart of an airport air traffic control tower, a
place from which the comings and goings of all vessels in the Port
of New York are assisted, supervised and meticulously recorded. It
monitors harbor traffic by remote radar and live television cameras
mounted along the waterways, and keeps in touch with each vessel by
VHF radio or cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   The center's core purpose is to prevent nautical disasters like
the Exxon Valdez spill in Alaska in 1989 or the most notorious case
in recent decades in New York, the crash of a container ship, Sea
Witch, with the oil tanker Esso Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea Witch struck the tanker at night in the Narrows and the
two ships locked together, creating a drifting inferno that
eventually grounded in Gravesend Bay, Brooklyn. The collision
occurred in 1973, before the port's Vessel Traffic Center opened.
</P>
<P>
   The center was first used in 1976, and during the OpSail events
of the next few days, it will try to maintain order over what is
expected to be the largest number of ships and boats ever to gather
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   On a typical day, the operators help on about 750 port crossings
by large vessels as they pass through New York, serving as a sort
of information clearinghouse on events in the port. But that's a
typical day. As the OpSail celebration gains momentum, the Coast
Guard expects to see something unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty more naval vessels are to pass through the Narrows
Monday, as well as a number of tall sailing ships will also be
making their way into Upper New York Bay, and all these vessels
will be converging Tuesday with hundreds of security vessels and
tens of thousands of pleasure craft.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the radar signatures of the pleasure craft _
tiny white blips _ will overwhelm the center's radar monitors with
a solid field of interference. ``You'll have virtually complete
whiteout,'' said Lt. Cmdr. Christopher Nichols, the Vessel Traffic
Center's supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   To help maintain order, the Coast Guard will complement the
center with a strong presence on the water: more than 200 boats or
cutters, supervised by a command ship, the buoy tender Willow,
anchored just south of Governors Island. The Vessel Traffic Center
will also receive a video transmission from a blimp.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard also hopes that routine port traffic _ the
container ships, oil tankers and fuel barges _ will stay away until
the celebrations end. It has issued a 24-hour restriction against
commercial traffic, beginning at 6 a.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the center on Saturday, three operators peered at the
radar screens for a finely detailed overview of more than 40
nautical square miles, an area that includes New York City, Perth
Amboy, Newark and Elizabethport, and extends from Sandy Hook, N.J.,
to the Throgs Neck Bridge on the East River and to the Holland
Tunnel ventilators on the lower Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   On the screens, the outline of each segment of waterway glowed
brightly. The water showed up as black. Each of the dozens of
vessels traveling through the port was illuminated by its own
computerized icon, which, with a click, revealed the vessel's
course, speed and destination.
</P>
<P>
   The operators passed along all manner of nautical information in
quick, dispassionate bits: floating debris in this channel, proceed
with care; two vessels approaching Hell Gate, both will wait for
you to pass; and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Although similar to an air traffic control tower, the Vessel
Traffic Center has a key difference: it cannot ordinarily tell
vessels what to do. Ultimate responsibility for a ship and its
actions rests with each skipper and crew.
</P>
<P>
   As the Nassau wheeled slowly in the bay outside, Petty Officer
1st Class Matthew Starace watched the screens closely. He was
midway through a 12-hour shift, simultaneously monitoring and
talking with 13 ships and tugs traversing the East River, as well
as nine more at anchor.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, his clean screen will be a mass of white. Talking to
a tug-and-barge as it approached Hell Gate, he spoke into his
headset with the practiced composure of a mortician. It was a tone
of voice, Coast Guard officials say, they hope continues through
OpSail.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the secrets of this job,'' Starace said between
conversations with skippers out on the harbor, ``is just staying
calm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
