   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- July 2, 2000 -- OPSAIL-UNDERDOG-2 -- A
floating testament to either the indomitability of the human spirit
or the primacy of Murphy's Law, the Bat'kivshchyna, a 90-foot
metal-hulled former fishing trawler from the Ukraine dipped in
cement and topped with two masts, left Kiev on April 7. How it made
it across the Atlantic is still unclear. From running aground in
the Dnieper River a few days into the trip and losing a big chunk
of its keel, to storms in the Mediterranean shredding the mainsail,
to presumably getting lost somewhere in the somewhere in the
Atlantic, Dmytro Biriukovich, captain of the Bat'kivshchyna, never
lost faith that the ship would arrive for OpSail 2000. (Vincent
Laforet/The New York Times)
