   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- July 2, 2000 -- 6TH-GRADE-PRESSURES-2 --
On top of the timeless complications of being 12 years old, an age
of bubbling hormones and anti-authority stirrings, sixth-graders
today face a combination of pressures that their parents never
encountered. In this era of earlier and higher expectations, many
students say they are driven to excel by parents who had seized on
test scores and early college readiness as new benchmarks for
success. Max Mashore, a sixth grader at Sidwell Friends school in
Washington, D.C., wants to go to Duke University, his father's alma
mater. ``I don't want to go to some small college in the middle of
Maine or something,'' says Mashore. (Paul Hosefros/The New York
Times)
