and the Sorcerer's Stone.'' The newest ``Harry Potter,'' a 752-page
book, will be published simultaneously in the U.S. and Britain with
a first printing of 3.8 million copies in America, a record. Ben
Allen, 9, of Dallas, was worried that visiting New York would make
him miss the release of the new Harry Potter book on July 8, so Ben
and his mother went to Books of Wonder in Manhattan to reserve a
copy, Sunday. (Richard Perry/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) KFAR KILA, Lebanon -- July 2, 2000 -- LEBANON-TOURISTS --
Thousands of people have begun flocking to Lebanon's newest tourist
attraction: the barbed wire fence at the new official border with
Israel. Vendors have set up shop along Lebanon's border with
Israel, selling everything from Hezbollah T-shirts to key chains to
baseball caps. (Courtney Kealy/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) JERUSALEM -- July 2, 2000 -- ISRAEL-TREES-1 --
Tree-planting rituals, a deeply rooted phenomenon in the culture of
the Jewish diaspora, has also been an age-old ritual for Jewish
tourists. Now, an Israeli tabloid has created a commotion by
running an investigative article, ``The Great Tree Fraud,''
suggesting that Jewish National Fund (the tree-planting sponsoring
agency) workers cynically uproot the $10 pine saplings planted by
tourists. In fact, six of every 10 trees planted at the hilly,
arid, unirrigated site of Ein Kerem. Marvin Stabler of Richboro,
Pa., planting $10 pine saplings in the hills of Jerusalem. (Rina
Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- July 2, 2000 -- KOSOVO -- As the
``humane pillar'' of the United Nations administration in Kosovo
prepares to shut down, its director, Dennis McNamara, has some
advice for the next international mission to rebuild a country: Be
prepared to invest as much money and effort in winning the peace as
in fighting the war. McNamara, the U.N. special envoy for
humanitarian affairs, next to the bombed out ruins of the Serbian
Police building that lie behind his office in central Pristina.
(Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LONDON -- July 2, 2000 -- LONDON-AUCTIONS -- This season,
Christie's combined its Impressionist and Post-Impressionist
auction with its sale of 20th-century art in one evening, and both
areas of the market were strong. Its star painting was Cezanne's
``Still Life With Fruits and a Ginger Pot'' from 1895. Two
determined bidders vied for the painting, which ended up selling to
William Acquavella, the Manhattan dealer, for $18.1 million, just
at its high estimate. (Christie's Images Ltd./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- July 2, 2000 -- INDIA-WRITERS -- Jhumpa
Lahiri is among a slew of young Indian writers who are making a
literary splash in the West. Lahiri, a 33-year-old New Yorker and
the daughter of Bengali immigrants, won the Pulitzer Prize in April
for her first book, a collection of short stories titled
``Interpreter of Maladies.'' ``My connection with India is
fundamental,'' says Lahiri. ``But at the same time it is very
slippery and confusing. I would like to see myself as an American
writer, but when I was raised I was told not to think of myself as
an American.'' (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CHICAGO -- July 2, 2000 -- TV-LOCAL-NEWS-MEDIA -- A
no-gimmicks television news strategy is being studied across the
nation by news directors and station managers, who have sought ways
to stem the loss of viewers of their own local news programs, which
can account for as much as a third of a station's advertising
revenue. Pam Zekman, a reporter for Chicago's WBBM, interviewing J.
Terrence Brunner, executive director of the Better Government
Association. The station has revamped its 10 p.m. newscast by
devoting it to serious, no-frills journalism. (Steve Kagan/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
