<DOCNO> NYT20000702.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1482 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ELECTION03-2ND     07-02 1611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION03-2NDLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NDWITH HOPES FOR A CLEAN ELECTION, MEXICANS GO TO POLLS
 &HT;    Eds: Tops with Fox comments, editing in first 9 grafs.
 &HT;    930&AMP;add. With MEXICO-CARTER.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS and LESLIE MOORE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Opposition candidate Vicente Fox appeared headed
for a historic presidential election victory that could usher in a
new era for Mexico, exit polls indicated Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The surveys of voters leaving the polls are a new feature of
Mexican elections, and their reliability is uncertain. But if the
polls hold up, the 71-year reign of the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party (PRI) could be coming to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a towering and charismatic businessman who turned 58
Sunday, delivered a virtual victory speech at the headquarters of
his National Action Party (PAN).
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't yet confirm officially we've won the presidency of
the republic,'' Fox told cheering supporters. He said he would wait
until Mexico's Federal Elections Institute announced results of a
``quick count'' of the balloting.
</P>
<P>
   But he praised election officials and said, ``We're going
through a moment of transition to a new political state in a
peaceful and stable and tranquil manner. ... We have to
congratulate ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Significant voting returns were not available Sunday evening,
and Mexico's rural vote could swing votes toward the ruling party.
Turnout was high, and it may take days before all the votes can be
gathered and counted in this large and impoverished nation of 100
million people.
</P>
<P>
   PRI officials made no statement, but the streets of the capital
began to fill with Fox supporters celebrating his apparent victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe that the era of the dinosaurs is over,'' said
a jubilant Sonia Suarez, 26, an electrical engineer in Mexico City,
referring to the pejorative name often employed for the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   A Fox victory would end an era of one-party rule that is all
that a vast majority of Mexicans has ever known. The populist and
agrarian PRI would give way to a pro-business party that is
urban-oriented and inclined to let markets do more of what
government has done in the past.
</P>
<P>
   A nationwide poll for the leading Televisa television station
found Fox, of the National Action Party (PAN), with 44 percent to
38 percent for the PRI's Francisco Labastida. A third candidate,
leftist Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, had 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Polls by other television outlets and the Democracy Watch group
also showed Fox leading by six or more percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The exit polls also showed PAN winning governorships in two
states, Morelos and Guanajuato, and the leftist Democratic
Revolution Party holding on to the mayor's office in Mexico City's
federal district, the country's political heart.
</P>
<P>
   No polling results were available for the two houses of the
nation's Congress, also at stake Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   There were no immediate indications of widespread election
fraud. Though Mexico is notorious for electoral corruption, the PRI
had promised the vote would be free and fair.
</P>
<P>
   There were reports of angry would-be voters who didn't get to
cast ballots for president at special voting stations set up for
people who had recently moved or were in transit.
</P>
<P>
   Although election officials estimated that more than 99 percent
of all voting stations opened _ the best record ever for Mexico _
voters were enraged when special stations that could stock only a
limited number of ballots by law ran short.
</P>
<P>
   In the sprawling Mexico City working-class suburb of Ixtapaluca
in the state of Mexico, voters started shouting to cast votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't fair!'' said police officer Marco Hernandez, 23,
who was standing in a long line when officials said only 300
ballots were left out of 750 available for voters who had moved
since getting their voting credentials. Asked who he wanted to vote
for, Hernandez wrote on a piece of paper: ``I want change.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost 58 million people were eligible to vote in the election,
which followed the most hotly contested and passionate campaign
season in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida faced a strong challenge from Fox, running as the
candidate of the center-right Alliance for Change. Fox and
Labastida were neck-and-neck in many pre-election opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   Many voters said change was a prime motive for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election has been the most publicized in the history of
Mexico, and most of us want change,'' said street vendor Alfonso
Garrido, 53, who voted for Fox in Ecatepec, a city near the capital
where almost 1 million voters reside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always voted for the PRI before, but the truth is, I'm tired
of poverty and I hope that Fox, if he wins, will fulfill his
promises,'' said Garrido.
</P>
<P>
   But many other voters said they preferred to stick with the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to let Fox win. I don't like his pompous
attitude,'' said Patricia Arias, 36, an Ixtapaluca housewife who
voted for Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   But her sister, Edith Arias, 37, with whom she walked arm in
arm, voted for Cardenas because ``he cares about working people.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Ramirez, 67, also voted for Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think all three candidates put together can really
change much,'' he said. ``The PRI is part of society. It dominates
everything. The opposition could create problems.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same voting station, housewife Amapola Mendez voted with
her 2-year-old clinging to her leg. ``A lot of older people think
there will never be change,'' she said, explaining that she voted
for Fox. ``But many younger people are looking at other political
parties now.''
</P>
<P>
   Under an awning set up on Juarez Street in Ixtapaluca, people
crowded around tables stacked with color-coded ballots supervised
by a election officials and two people who counted votes and posted
results before shipping them to a district office.
</P>
<P>
   Each official was supposed to be selected by lottery and trained
by Mexico's independent Federal Elections Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Voters showed their photo ID voting credentials to these
officials, who matched them against a registration list that also
contained photos. Voters were given ballots to mark and instructed
to go into booths with curtains. Then they deposited the ballots in
color-coded boxes for federal elections and state and local races.
</P>
<P>
   Political parties were allowed to have two representatives per
table, but on Juarez Street, like other parts of the country, there
were complaints that too many PRI representatives wearing pins were
standing around or sitting at the tables.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, five women wearing PRI pins were crowded around
one table on Juarez Street, silently observing voters as they
approached to get their ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Manuel Solorzano, a PAN representative, said he was filing
a complaint because some PRI members had been substituted at the
last minute as vote counters at one table.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said, ``for the first time ever, we are seeing
an election where the government isn't sticking its hands in.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In the Valle de Chalco, another state of Mexico area where PRI
loyalty tends to run strong, people trickled into voting precincts
along with stray dogs.
</P>
<P>
   In early June, heavy rains flooded out hundreds from their
homes. Federal aid arrived and the government paid many families
almost $1,000 in disaster relief. But many said the help was
inadequate and slow to come.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many here were bent on backing the party of tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the party of my parents _ even my grandparents,'' said
housewife Rosa Maria Perez, 35. The ruling party ``gives us
security. I still don't have confidence in the other parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Voting PRI is family-bound duty, explained Patricia Sanchez
Pacheco, 37.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother got her papers to become a PRI activist 25 years
ago,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other parties don't have experience to govern a country,''
said her sister, Hortencia Sanchez Pacheco.
</P>
<P>
   The two sisters gave their votes to the PRI because it came
through in ways that count _ bags of cement, sand and aluminum
scrap for roofs for their neighborhood, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago we started receiving the help,'' said Hortencia
Sanchez, carefully minding her step on a street of rocks and
rubble.
</P>
<P>
   But even in this staunch PRI town, there was opposition _ and
indignation _ at the PRI's campaign classic campaign gifts for
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a bucket and a T-shirt, they want our vote? Forget it,''
said one voter who declined to give her name.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big gap between what the PRI says and what it
does,'' said electrician Juan Jesus Moreno, 43, who voted for
Cardenas, just as he did in 1994 and 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can Labastida talk about computers and English classes for
Mexicans (a campaign proposal) when we don't have enough to eat?''
he asked.
</P>
<P>
   A reliable den of PRI support, Valle de Chalco sports monuments
to former President Carlos Salinas de Gortari's government public
works project, Solidarity. The program paved roads, put in drainage
and electricity and built basketball courts in early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But the June sewage flood may have provoked a lower turnout for
the PRI than in previous elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems there was a bit of anger and apathy out there among
people for the way the government handled the disaster,'' said
Arturo Morales Torres, a local resident.
</P>
<P>
   Cox News researchers Julieta Gutierrez and Margarita Moreno
</P>
<P>
   contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Ferriss's e-mail address is susanf(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
