<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- July 2, 2000 -- OPSAIL-UNDERDOG-2 -- A
floating testament to either the indomitability of the human spirit
or the primacy of Murphy's Law, the Bat'kivshchyna, a 90-foot
metal-hulled former fishing trawler from the Ukraine dipped in
cement and topped with two masts, left Kiev on April 7. How it made
it across the Atlantic is still unclear. From running aground in
the Dnieper River a few days into the trip and losing a big chunk
of its keel, to storms in the Mediterranean shredding the mainsail,
to presumably getting lost somewhere in the somewhere in the
Atlantic, Dmytro Biriukovich, captain of the Bat'kivshchyna, never
lost faith that the ship would arrive for OpSail 2000. (Vincent
Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- July 2, 2000 -- OPSAIL-UNDERDOG-1 -- The
Bat'kivshchyna, a 90-foot metal-hulled former fishing trawler from
the Ukraine, will not be the largest ship in OpSail 2000, but it
may be the most persistent one. From running aground in the Dnieper
River a few days into the trip and losing a big chunk of its keel,
to storms in the Mediterranean shredding the mainsail, to
presumably getting lost somewhere in the somewhere in the Atlantic,
the Bat'kivshchyna is a floating testament to either the
indomitability of the human spirit or the primacy of Murphy's Law.
The Bat'kivshchyna in the waters of New York harbor, Sunday.
(Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) JERUSALEM -- July 2, 2000 -- ISRAEL-TREES-2 -- At Ein
Kerem in the hills of Jerusalem, Marvin Stabler, front, was among a
bunch of tourists on their way to plant $10 pine saplings in the
hills of Jerusalem, a deeply rooted phenomenon in the culture of
the Jewish diaspora. Though no agronomist, Stabler could look
around him and tell that the hillside area in Jerusalem was not the
most fertile ground. So it came as no shock to him to learn that
most of the saplings planted by his family would not survive. (Rina
Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- July 2, 2000 -- 6TH-GRADE-PRESSURES-2 --
On top of the timeless complications of being 12 years old, an age
of bubbling hormones and anti-authority stirrings, sixth-graders
today face a combination of pressures that their parents never
encountered. In this era of earlier and higher expectations, many
students say they are driven to excel by parents who had seized on
test scores and early college readiness as new benchmarks for
success. Max Mashore, a sixth grader at Sidwell Friends school in
Washington, D.C., wants to go to Duke University, his father's alma
mater. ``I don't want to go to some small college in the middle of
Maine or something,'' says Mashore. (Paul Hosefros/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- July 2, 2000 -- NY-OPSAIL-TWIN-TOWERS --
