<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1484 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MIAMI-NY-MOBSTERS-2TA     07-02 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-NY-MOBSTERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIES BINDING BROOKLYN AND MIAMI INCLUDE MOBSTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ One summer day in 1999, three men sat on the
sun-splashed deck of Shooters Restaurant in Miami Beach, flipping
through their menus and gazing at the lazy currents of the
Intracoastal Waterway.
</P>
<P>
   They had arrived that day, the authorities say, on the
glistening yacht of their host, Chris Paciello, a handsome South
Beach nightclub owner as famous for his sun-tanned biceps as for
his glamorous friendships with celebrities like Madonna. Throughout
the meal, his boat _ a bright, white 50-footer _ bobbed at its
berth in gentle waves.
</P>
<P>
   The scene, as described by an internal Miami Beach Police
Department memorandum, was so quintessentially South Florida, with
its idling power boat and alfresco lunch, that it could have been
photographed for a Dade County travel brochure. But through the
eyes of the investigators watching that day, it was all about a
place on the water farther up the coast: Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Paciello was soon to be charged with abetting murder as a member
of a vicious Bensonhurst Mafia crew. One of his guests that day was
Alphonse Persico, who the authorities say is the acting boss of the
Colombo crime family and keeps an apartment in Park Slope. The
second guest was yet another Brooklyn transplant: Andrew Dohler, an
undercover agent posing as a crooked Florida police officer, who
had started his career in, all of places, the 75th Precinct station
house in East New York.
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn mobsters _ and the officers who chase them _ have been
flocking to Miami ever since the first palm trees were planted here
on Ocean Drive. As anyone who has seen ``The Godfather'' knows, the
criminal link between the two locales has been tightly woven since
at least the 1950s, when Meyer Lansky established his illicit
beachhead on the Atlantic in hopes of cracking the Cuban gambling
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from Paciello and his friends, the authorities say there
are many notorious and recent examples of Brooklyn gangsters
heading south. In December 1996, Nicholas Corozzo, the heir to the
Gambino family throne, was arrested near a beach resort in Key
Biscayne in nothing more than his bathing trunks. And on June 22 of
this year, more than a dozen members of what is known as the South
Florida crew of the Colombo family were arrested in the Miami area
on charges of extortion, money laundering, illegal gambling, credit
card fraud and dealing in counterfeit drivers' licenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a gangster point of view, they just can't help themselves
_ they have to go,'' said Tom Cash, the former special agent in
charge of both the Miami and New York offices of the Drug
Enforcement Administration. ``Miami is everything Brooklyn is not.
It's sunny. The water is warm. The imported cannolis aren't as good
as on 18th Avenue in the old neighborhood, but, really, they're not
that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami has become such a destination for Brooklyn mobsters _
``it's their second stop after Bensonhurst,'' said one federal
prosecutor _ that it even has a local restaurant said to be favored
by New York wise guys and their retinues. According to former and
current mob investigators, gangsters vacationing or doing business
in Miami are likely to wind up at a velvet-roped, steak-and-lobster
place called the Forge.
</P>
<P>
   The Forge, which attracts what one investigator called ``men
with big cigars and women with tiny resumes,'' was opened in the
1950s by Alvin Malnick, a lawyer who worked closely with Lansky.
These days, the Forge is owned by Malnick's son, Shareef, who
appeared in federal court in Miami last year at a detention hearing
to show his support for his good friend Chris Paciello. Neither
Shareef Malnick nor his father returned telephone calls seeking
comment about the Forge.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday nights, in particular, the Forge is packed with
fleshy, older men in silk shirts or double-breasted suits who spend
good money buying drinks for the women who hover around them like
hummingbirds. On a recent night, after a couple of salsa numbers,
the disc jockey spun ``Volare.'' The big-screen television showed
the New York-Miami playoff basketball game. The customers cheered
for the Knicks each time they put one through the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Forge is sort of like Sparks Steak House South,'' Cash
said, referring to the New York mob landmark where Paul Castellano,
the Gambino family boss, was killed in 1986. ``It's been absolutely
infamous over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when the Brooklyn mob presence in Miami was
strictly La Cosa Nostra _ guys whose pinky rings clinked on their
daiquiri glasses _ but in recent years, Russian and Israeli
criminals with ties to neighborhoods like Brighton Beach and
Borough Park have also made the trip, investigators say. The faces
may be new, but the offenses they are said to commit _ money
laundering, cigarette and drug smuggling, extortion, promoting
prostitution _ have long been staples of organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   According to federal agents, a noted Russian mobster once
bragged that he had as many as 600 soldiers in southern Florida, a
great number of whom had passed through Brooklyn. Until two or
three years ago, according to a federal indictment, the point man
for the Russian Mafia in Miami was a onetime Brighton Beach
furniture store owner named Ludwig Fainberg.
</P>
<P>
   Court papers say that Fainberg, who moved from Brooklyn to
Florida in 1989, ran a remarkably eclectic criminal empire out of
two businesses he owned in Miami: a strip club near Miami
International Airport called Porky's and a borscht-and-blini
restaurant in North Miami Beach called Babushka.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 indictment charged Fainberg with drug trafficking,
money laundering, counterfeiting, even with trying to secure a
decommissioned Russian submarine for the drug lords of the Cali
cartel of Colombia. But while many of the crimes he is said to have
committed _ shipping bootleg cigarettes from Miami to New York, for
example _ are a testament to his roots in both places, the long
investigation that eventually led to his racketeering conviction in
1998 was the strongest evidence.
</P>
<P>
   When the government began to move against Fainberg in 1995,
there was no place better than New York to turn for help. To
infiltrate his cadre of Russian-speaking friends, investigators
recruited a Brooklyn informer named Gregory Roizis to work in
tandem with an undercover DEA agent, Alexander Yasevich, who also
hailed from Brighton Beach. As luck would have it, said Brent
Eaton, the agent who ran the investigation for the DEA, the two men
already knew each other from New York. As a child, Yasevich had
attended a summer camp that Roizis ran in Brighton Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks after the partners were reunited, the government sprang
its Brooklyn-based trap. Roizis was instructed to hang out in
Babushka, and on the appointed night, Yasevich walked in. Then, the
government says, as Fainberg watched, the two men greeted each
other in mock surprise. They bear-hugged, speaking Russian, and
loudly reminisced about Brighton Beach. Fainberg fell for the act
completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the perfect introduction,'' Eaton said.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli gangsters have also made their presence felt in Florida,
prosecutors and federal agents said. The Israelis are said to be
specialists in the illegal importation of the nightclub drug
Ecstasy and, according to a recent DEA intelligence brief, ``tend
to recruit couriers within their own ethnic and religious
communities,'' in neighborhoods like Williamsburg and Borough Park.
</P>
<P>
   In one recent case, two young Hasidic men, Shimon Levita, 19,
and Simcha Roth, 20, were found guilty of organizing a stable of
Hasidic couriers from Brooklyn for an Israeli man named Sean Erez,
who ran a ring that routinely shipped thousands of Ecstasy pills
from manufacturers in Amsterdam to distributors in Miami Beach. In
a similar but unrelated case being prosecuted in Brooklyn courts,
Israeli mobsters have been charged with using strippers from New
York bars like Scores and Tens to shuttle Ecstasy from Europe to
Miami and other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators suggest several reasons for the long-standing
criminal connection between Brooklyn and Miami. They say that
Miami, long an ``open city'' where no one criminal enterprise has
exercised complete control, is an easy place for out-of-towners to
set up shop. They say that the city's lucrative night life has long
attracted criminal types. And they say the police departments that
patrol the shore have a fractured and unfocused approach to
attacking organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   But the most persuasive reason may also be the simplest,
investigators say. New Yorkers _ from Donald Trump to everyone's
Aunt Frieda _ have always traveled to Miami in winter for a dose of
ultraviolet rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is heaven for these guys,'' said Diana Fernandez,
an assistant U.S. attorney in Miami, who prosecuted Fainberg.
``They consider their apartments in Miami to be like dachas. It has
palm trees and sand. It's like vacationland to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
