<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1490 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-PINS-MARTINEZ-NYT     07-02 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-PINS-MARTINEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS' MARTINEZ MIFFED AT TORRE FOR SUGGESTING A DAY OFF ;  ERDOS
REASSIGNED ;  TURNER MENDS , KNOBLAUCH SITS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla., _ Joe Torre thought about giving Tino
Martinez a day off Sunday, but Martinez was in the lineup against
the Devil Rays. Martinez had two hits Saturday, and Torre said he
wanted to give his first baseman _ who has struggled this season _
a chance to build on that success.
</P>
<P>
   But keeping Martinez on the field was probably an adept way of
addressing and perhaps defusing the comments Martinez made after
Saturday's game. Martinez bristled when reporters conveyed Torre's
opinion that the first baseman sometimes pushes himself too hard,
and that Saturday's performance might serve to ease some of that
self-imposed pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a sense of relief,'' Martinez said Saturday. ``I
expect it of myself. You're battling your own beliefs, and you're
battling your own manager. I never take a day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always, `I'm pressing.' It's never, `Let's work on your
swing.' Am I pressing? That's the easy way out.''
</P>
<P>
   When Martinez's comments were relayed to Torre before Sunday's
game, the manager said: ``I give my opinion. It looks to me like
he's fighting himself. It's not easy to follow up the years he's
had year in and year out. In that regard, I'm sure he's frustrated
with the fact that it's not happening for him. He's a very proud
individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez drove in 117 runs in 1996, 141 in 1997, 123 in 1998 and
105 last year.
</P>
<P>
   He went 0 for 4 in Sunday's 5-2 victory and, with 45 runs batted
in and seven home runs is on a pace to drive in 96 runs and hit 15
homers.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez began his professional career with Seattle, and the
Mariners place great emphasis on batting practice, on working
endlessly on hitting; he likes to go through extra rounds of
hitting, to go through repetitions with his swing.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' approach _ essentially dictated by Torre and the
hitting coach Chris Chambliss _ is more measured. When the team is
slumping offensively, Torre and Chambliss will sometimes give the
hitters a day off, in an effort to relax them.
</P>
<P>
   Teams don't uniformly take batting practice before most Sunday
games, but the Yankees did Sunday _ and the perception of other
players is that it was done to placate the likes of Martinez and
right fielder Paul O'Neill, who like to put in as much work as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Torre would not say whether Martinez has said the same thing to
him as he did to reporters. ``We talk,'' Torre said. ``I don't go
into things that we say behind closed doors. The only thing can do
is offer support where I can help, and basically, that's all I can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   YARNALL MIGHT START  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will play seven games in six days from July 4-9, and
they are unsure who will start two of those games. Ed Yarnall, who
had a poor spring and missed a chance to open the season in the
rotation, has a good chance of being promoted to pitch Thursday
against the Orioles. He was removed from Columbus' game Sunday
after throwing only 59 pitches against Toledo. Yarnall has pitched
much better for the Triple-A Clippers recently.
</P>
<P>
   If Yarnall does not start Thursday, Jason Grimsley, coming back
from an ear infection, could make that start, or be held back to
pitch in Saturday's day-night doubleheader against the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles' lineup is stocked with left-handed batters and
Grimsley has fared very well against lefties this year, limiting
them to a .217 batting average.
</P>
<P>
   ERDOS REASSIGNED
</P>
<P>
   To make room for Roger Clemens on the 25-man roster, the Yankees
designated pitcher Todd Erdos for assignment, a move debated at
length by the team's staff this morning. The Yankees could have
optioned Ben Ford or Craig Dingman to the minors without
complication, but Erdos is out of options and cannot be sent to
Triple-A without being passed through waivers.
</P>
<P>
   There is the possibility, then, that the Yankees will lose
Erdos. But the right-hander had been relegated to mop-up duty,
compiling a 5.04 earned run average in only 14 appearances; it had
become apparent that Torre was not going to trust Erdos more than
that.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, both Dingman and Ford have had impressive
outings in the last 10 days, and the consensus might have been that
either had more of a chance of succeeding in a crucial role than
Erdos. ``We feel right now that maybe the other guys can help us
better,'' said Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TURNER MENDS, KNOBLAUCH SITS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chris Turner, the Yankees' backup catcher, was nursing a stiff
shoulder Sunday, a problem that probably began in Saturday's brawl.
Turner was one of the players who wrestled Tampa Bay's Bobby Smith
away from Jorge Posada after those two started fighting. Turner
took some medication Sunday and believes he will be ready to play
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch, the second baseman, was not in the lineup for
the second consecutive day because of an ear infection, the same
problem that has plagued Grimsley. The air-conditioning was out in
most rooms in the Yankees' team hotel in Detroit last week, and for
that reason, Knoblauch stayed in Grimsley's room, where the
air-conditioning was freezing cold. Both got sick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
