<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1492 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-UNDECIDED-2     07-02 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-UNDECIDED-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH CHANGES TO NEW YORK SENATE RACE, VOTERS POSTPONING DECISIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This is the part of a series following a group of New York
voters from diverse backgrounds as they decide which candidate to
support for the U.S. Senate.) By JANE GROSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than a month into what is essentially a new race
for the U.S. Senate, Cathy Harrison and Dave Temkin, both party
stalwarts, have just about climbed off the fence of indecision and
chosen the candidate they will vote for in November, barring
scandal or surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison and Temkin _ she now set on Rep. Rick Lazio of Suffolk
County and he set on Hillary Rodham Clinton _ are part of a panel
of nine voters that The New York Times is following as they make
their decisions in this pivotal Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   They were culled from respondents to early New York Times/CBS
News Polls, back when Rudolph Giuliani was the Republican candidate
in the race, when the number of undecided voters was unusually
small and their indecision was based not on ignorance of the
candidates but rather on antipathy for them.
</P>
<P>
   All that has now changed, with Giuliani out of the contest
because of prostate cancer, and Clinton, in the eyes of these
voters, a less contentious figure than she was a year ago. But
except for Harrison and Temkin _ and Tom Beck, a Long Island
guidance counselor familiar with Lazio's record who embraced his
candidacy_ the six other voters continue to watch and wait.
</P>
<P>
   Tom and Barbara Smith, a struggling working-class couple from
Saugerties, say they still do not feel that they know enough about
the candidates, partly because they live in a part of the state
without the saturation news coverage of New York City, Albany,
Syracuse, Rochester or Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Charlene Clinton, a single mother in Buffalo who recently lost
her first job since leaving the welfare rolls, says she pays no
attention to politics, did not know Lazio had entered the race and
would make up her mind at the last minute, as she always does.
</P>
<P>
   Other voters on the panel have pet issues that will determine
their vote. Doug Taggart, vice president of a financial services
concern and a resident of Cortlandt Manor in Westchester, wants to
know how each candidate would spend the growing budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Schwartz, a computer consultant on Staten Island whose wife
is undergoing experimental cancer treatment, wants a senator who
cares about the disease, its causes and its cures.
</P>
<P>
   And Bob Harrison, a high school social studies teacher from
Amsterdam, who is Cathy Harrison's husband, wants to know how Lazio
and Clinton plan to invigorate the failing upstate economy.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Harrison, a nurse and a lifelong Republican, had a hard
time supporting Giuliani, despite party affiliation, because she
found him too harsh and autocratic, too focused on downstate
concerns and too indelicate in his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazio is another story, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I've been seeing and hearing, I like the family
feeling he gives off,'' Harrison said. ``He's a Republican
candidate and now I don't feel any need to cross over.''
</P>
<P>
   The choice is also simple now for Temkin, a telecommunications
expert from Flushing, Queens, and a lifelong Democrat. His
reservations about Clinton remain real, Temkin said. And he would
vote Republican if the candidate had the stature and courage to
cross his party when it was in the interest of New York state, as
Jacob Javits did when he was senator, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazio's defining act so far, in Temkin's mind, was deferring
to New York's Republican governor, George Pataki, by abandoning the
race in favor of Giuliani and then jumping back in on command.
``He's too loyal to the party,'' Temkin concluded.
</P>
<P>
   All these voters are learning about the candidates amid the din
of their daily lives, generally more compelling for them than
politics. There are gaps in what they know, and they have little
spare time to fill them.
</P>
<P>
   The Smiths, for instance, have been preoccupied with the birth
of a grandchild, the search for a new apartment and plans to paint
and hang bookshelves. Clinton, the single mother in Buffalo, lost a
job as a monitor at a school that was stripped of its
certification. She is back in the bureaucratic maze of welfare and
faced with a shut-off notice for an unpaid water bill. The
Harrisons just celebrated their son's high school graduation,
helped him choose a community college and left for a family
vacation in Hawaii, which took two years of savings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most of them are aware of certain policy announcements,
gaffes and tiffs. They agree that mudslinging, a word used by many,
has increased since Giuliani's withdrawal. They agree that Clinton
has been more visible in the metropolitan region and less visible
upstate, where she has less chance of winning with Lazio as her
opponent. They all are hoping for debates and better elaboration of
positions.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the sniping between the candidates is of no interest,
these voters said, except to irritate them. The accusations that
Lazio had inappropriately profited from a securities deal, for
instance, drew ridicule because equivalent accusations have been
made against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's posturing and pandering,'' Temkin said. ``It's like Dr.
Strangelove. They're afraid if the other guy does it and they
don't. We're not given enough credit for intelligence as voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith had a theory on why there was less negative campaigning
when the mayor was still in the race. ``Maybe she didn't feel as
threatened,'' he said of Clinton. ``Lazio is young and energetic
and he exploded out of the block. Maybe that shook her up.''
</P>
<P>
   These voters seem unmoved by the barrage of television
advertising. In nine interviews, only the Harrisons were able even
to describe a television commercial for a candidate _ one in which
Lazio is surrounded by his wife and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family values and such,'' Harrison said of the Lazio
commercials. ``Upstate, that's a plus.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Lazio's attractive family won over Harrison, her
husband, who comes from less conservative Republican family, says
he needs something more. ``On the economy, I haven't heard much
from either candidate,'' he said. ``That's an important issue up
here, to make sure New York state prospers. So I'm waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Taggart, who has been impressed with Lazio's energy, said he is
waiting to hear Lazio's plans, and Clinton's, for the national
budget surplus. Large tax cuts, a common Republican lure, would be
both foolish and selfish, in Taggart's view. First, cuts put very
little money in any individual's pocket, he said. And second,
prosperous times are an opportunity to be magnanimous.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the ways we define ourselves as a people,'' he said,
``is how we get through the best of times.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz, a former school teacher, is quick to acknowledge that
these days he has become a myopic voter, with only one thing on his
mind: his wife's non-Hodgkin's lymphoma. He has learned on the
Internet, from his lymphoma news group, that Lazio last year won
the Paul Tsongas Memorial Award from the Lymphoma Research
Foundation of America.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Normally a Democrat, and aware of Clinton's focus on health care
issues, he has offered the first lady a chance to weigh in, sending
an e-mail message to her campaign office that has not been
answered. ``I would like to get her viewpoint,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz is abashed to be so self-centered. ``I do understand
there are other issues for other people,'' he said. ``But for us,
this is life and death.'' In addition, he said concern about the
increased incidence of certain cancers ``branches into respect for
the environment and your position regarding corporate power and the
responsibility of big business for the mess they create.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlene Clinton, who said she has voted in all but one election
since she was eligible, has been consistently unaware of campaign
developments, including Giuliani's cancer diagnosis, the
announcement of his planned marital separation, his withdrawal from
the race and Lazio's entry.
</P>
<P>
   In elections past, she has relied on an elderly neighbor, an
avid newspaper reader, to keep her informed. Lately, that neighbor
has been ill. In addition, there has been a change of pastors at
the Cedar Grove Missionary Baptist Church. The former paster talked
a lot about politics, and the new one does not, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said she has never voted for a Republican, nor have her
parents, Clinton said. Yet she insisted that she remained
undecided. ``I'm not that into politics,'' she said. ``But issues
do concern me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-00 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
