<HEADLINE>
HASKELL COHEN, 86, PUBLICIST WHO CREATED NBA'S ALL-STAR GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   By RICHARD GOLDSTEIN 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Haskell Cohen, a longtime publicity director for the National
Basketball Association, who helped create the league's All-Star
Game _ a once-modest affair that has become an annual weekend
spectacle _ died June 28 at his home in Fort Lee, N.J. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   In the winter of 1951, when Cohen joined the NBA office, college
basketball was reeling from point-shaving scandals, giving the
professionals an opportunity to attract new fans. Cohen and NBA
Commissioner Maurice Podoloff, the league's two-man office, met
with Walter Brown, the Boston Celtics' owner, to think up a way to
gain attention.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen would recall suggesting: ``Why not an All-Star Game?
Baseball does it and people like it.'' Brown put the game in Boston
Garden, and on March 2, 1951, the first NBA All-Star Game drew
10,094 fans who saw the East defeat the West, 111-94.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Cohen played a supporting role in another
pioneering moment. With teams often content to dribble out the
clock, keeping scores low and games frequently tedious, Danny
Biasone, the owner of the Syracuse Nationals, proposed a 24-second
time limit for teams to attempt a shot.
</P>
<P>
   But when the idea was tried in an exhibition game at a Syracuse
gym in August 1954, a 24-second clock had not yet been devised.
Cohen kept his eye on the second hand of his wristwatch along the
sideline. Whenever 24 seconds had gone by without a shot, he would
shout, ``Time!''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen helped create the annual Stokes benefit game at Kutsher's
Country Club in Monticello, N.Y., in the Catskills. After Maurice
Stokes, the Cincinnati Royals' star, contracted encephalitis in
1958, Cohen joined with Jack Twyman, a teammate of Stokes', and
Milton Kutsher, the owner of the hotel, to stage a game each summer
featuring NBA stars to raise money for Stokes' medical bills and
for other former players in financial need.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, who was born in Worcester, Mass., and graduated from
Boston University, served as the NBA's publicist from 1951 to 1969.
He was a founder, in 1948, and later president of the United States
Committee Sports for Israel, the sponsor of U.S. participation in
the World Maccabiah Games in Israel, an Olympic-style competition
for Jewish athletes. As a contributing editor to Parade magazine,
he created its high school all-American teams in football,
basketball and soccer. He was also sports editor of the Jewish
Telegraphic Agency.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by two daughters, Irene Komet, of Fair Lawn,
N.J., and Evelyn Cohen, of Manhattan; three grandchildren; and five
great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Long after leaving the NBA, Cohen reminisced about that first
All-Star Game, telling of how he had suggested to Podoloff that the
league give the players gifts for participating.
</P>
<P>
   As Cohen remembered it:
</P>
<P>
   ``Podoloff said, `What do you have in mind?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Maybe a pin or a ring.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Whatever it is, don't spend more than $2.25 each.'''
</P>
<P>
   That was no way for a publicist to treat the dream teams of
their day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We later were able to cut a deal with a local store,'' Cohen
recalled, ``and each of the players received a television set.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
